P_HTM[942]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[943]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[944]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and liable to fall apart, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[945]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[946]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[947]="*“Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako cakkhusmimpi nibbindati, rūpesupi nibbindati, cakkhuviññāṇepi nibbindati, cakkhusamphassepi nibbindati.**“Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with the eye, sights, eye consciousness, and eye contact.*";
P_HTM[948]="*Yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tasmimpi nibbindati … pe …**And they grow disillusioned with the painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact.*";
P_HTM[949]="*jivhāyapi nibbindati, rasesupi nibbindati, jivhāviññāṇepi nibbindati, jivhāsamphassepi nibbindati, yampidaṃ jivhāsamphassapaccayā uppajjati … pe …**They grow disillusioned with the ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[950]="*manasmimpi nibbindati, dhammesupi nibbindati, manoviññāṇepi nibbindati, manosamphassepi nibbindati.**They grow disillusioned with the mind, thoughts, mind consciousness, and mind contact.*";
P_HTM[951]="*Yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tasmimpi nibbindati.**And they grow disillusioned with the painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact.*";
P_HTM[952]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati; vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[953]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[954]="*Ayaṃ kho, bhikkhave, sabbupādānapariyādānāya dhammo”ti.**This is the principle for depleting all fuel.”*";
P_HTM[955]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[956]="*Avijjāvaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[957]="*Avijjā saṃyojanā dve,* **";
P_HTM[958]="*āsavena duve vuttā;* **";
P_HTM[959]="*Anusayā apare dve,* **";
P_HTM[960]="*pariññā dve pariyādinnaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[961]="*Vaggo tena pavuccatīti.* **";
P_HTM[962]="*7. Migajālavaggo**With Migajāla*";
P_HTM[963]="*1. Paṭhamamigajālasuttaṃ**With Migajāla (1st)*";
P_HTM[964]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[965]="*Atha kho āyasmā migajālo yena bhagavā … pe …**Then Venerable Migajāla went up to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[966]="*ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā migajālo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**and said to him:*";
P_HTM[967]="*“‘ekavihārī, ekavihārī’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of one who lives alone.*";
P_HTM[968]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, ekavihārī hoti, kittāvatā ca pana sadutiyavihārī hotī”ti?**How is one who lives alone defined? And how is living with a partner defined?”*";
P_HTM[969]="*“Santi kho, migajāla, cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**“Migajāla, there are sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[970]="*Tañce bhikkhu abhinandati abhivadati ajjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**If a mendicant approves, welcomes, and keeps clinging to them,*";
P_HTM[971]="*Tassa taṃ abhinandato abhivadato ajjhosāya tiṭṭhato uppajjati nandī.**this gives rise to relishing.*";
P_HTM[972]="*Nandiyā sati sārāgo hoti;**When there’s relishing there’s lust.*";
P_HTM[973]="*sārāge sati saṃyogo hoti.**When there’s lust there is a fetter.*";
P_HTM[974]="*Nandisaṃyojanasaṃyutto kho, migajāla, bhikkhu sadutiyavihārīti vuccati.**A mendicant who is fettered by relishing is said to live with a partner.*";
P_HTM[975]="*… pe …**There are sounds … smells … tastes … touches …*";
P_HTM[976]="*Santi kho, migajāla, jivhāviññeyyā rasā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**There are thoughts known by the mind that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[977]="*Tañce bhikkhu abhinandati abhivadati ajjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**If a mendicant approves, welcomes, and keeps clinging to them,*";
P_HTM[978]="*Tassa taṃ abhinandato abhivadato ajjhosāya tiṭṭhato uppajjati nandī.**this gives rise to relishing.*";
P_HTM[979]="*Nandiyā sati sārāgo hoti;**When there’s relishing there’s lust.*";
P_HTM[980]="*sārāge sati saṃyogo hoti.**When there’s lust there is a fetter.*";
P_HTM[981]="*Nandisaṃyojanasaṃyutto kho, migajāla, bhikkhu sadutiyavihārīti vuccati.**A mendicant who is fettered by relishing is said to live with a partner.*";
P_HTM[982]="*Evaṃvihārī ca, migajāla, bhikkhu kiñcāpi araññavanapatthāni pantāni senāsanāni paṭisevati appasaddāni appanigghosāni vijanavātāni manussarāhasseyyakāni paṭisallānasāruppāni;**A mendicant who lives like this is said to live with a partner, even if they frequent remote lodgings in the wilderness and the forest that are quiet and still, far from the madding crowd, remote from human settlements, and fit for retreat.*";
P_HTM[983]="*atha kho sadutiyavihārīti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[984]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[985]="*Taṇhā hissa dutiyā, sāssa appahīnā.**For craving is their partner, and they haven’t given it up.*";
P_HTM[986]="*Tasmā ‘sadutiyavihārī’ti vuccati.**That’s why they’re said to live with a partner.*";
P_HTM[987]="*Santi ca kho, migajāla, cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**There are sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[988]="*Tañce bhikkhu nābhinandati nābhivadati nājjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**If a mendicant doesn’t approve, welcome, and keep clinging to them,*";
P_HTM[989]="*Tassa taṃ anabhinandato anabhivadato anajjhosāya tiṭṭhato nandī nirujjhati.**relishing ceases.*";
P_HTM[990]="*Nandiyā asati sārāgo na hoti;**When there’s no relishing there’s no lust.*";
P_HTM[991]="*sārāge asati saṃyogo na hoti.**When there’s no lust there’s no fetter.*";
P_HTM[992]="*Nandisaṃyojanavisaṃyutto kho, migajāla, bhikkhu ekavihārīti vuccati … pe …**A mendicant who is not fettered by relishing is said to live alone.*";
P_HTM[993]="*santi ca kho, migajāla, jivhāviññeyyā rasā … pe …**There are sounds … smells … tastes … touches …*";
P_HTM[994]="*santi ca kho, migajāla, manoviññeyyā dhammā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**There are thoughts known by the mind that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[995]="*Tañce bhikkhu nābhinandati nābhivadati nājjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**If a mendicant doesn’t approve, welcome, and keep clinging to them,*";
P_HTM[996]="*Tassa taṃ anabhinandato anabhivadato anajjhosāya tiṭṭhato nandī nirujjhati.**relishing ceases.*";
P_HTM[997]="*Nandiyā asati sārāgo na hoti;**When there’s no relishing there’s no lust.*";
P_HTM[998]="*sārāge asati saṃyogo na hoti.**When there’s no lust there’s no fetter.*";
P_HTM[999]="*Nandisaṃyojanavippayutto kho, migajāla, bhikkhu ekavihārīti vuccati.**A mendicant who is not fettered by relishing is said to live alone.*";
P_HTM[1000]="*Evaṃvihārī ca, migajāla, bhikkhu kiñcāpi gāmante viharati ākiṇṇo bhikkhūhi bhikkhunīhi upāsakehi upāsikāhi rājūhi rājamahāmattehi titthiyehi titthiyasāvakehi.**A mendicant who lives like this is said to live alone, even if they live in the neighborhood of a village crowded by monks, nuns, laymen, and laywomen; by rulers and their ministers, and teachers of other paths and their disciples.*";
P_HTM[1001]="*Atha kho ekavihārīti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[1002]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1003]="*Taṇhā hissa dutiyā, sāssa pahīnā.**For craving is their partner, and they have given it up.*";
P_HTM[1004]="*Tasmā ‘ekavihārī’ti vuccatī”ti.**That’s why they’re said to live alone.”*";
P_HTM[1005]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1006]="*2. Dutiyamigajālasuttaṃ**With Migajāla (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1007]="*Atha kho āyasmā migajālo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe …**Then Venerable Migajāla went up to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[1008]="*ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā migajālo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1009]="*“sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā saṅkhittena dhammaṃ desetu, yamahaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[1010]="*“Santi kho, migajāla, cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**“Migajāla, there are sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[1011]="*Tañce bhikkhu abhinandati abhivadati ajjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**If a mendicant approves, welcomes, and keep clinging to them,*";
P_HTM[1012]="*Tassa taṃ abhinandato abhivadato ajjhosāya tiṭṭhato uppajjati nandī.**this gives rise to relishing.*";
P_HTM[1013]="*Nandisamudayā dukkhasamudayo, migajālāti vadāmi … pe …**Relishing is the origin of suffering, I say.*";
P_HTM[1014]="*santi ca kho, migajāla, jivhāviññeyyā rasā … pe …**There are sounds … smells … tastes … touches …*";
P_HTM[1015]="*santi ca kho, migajāla, manoviññeyyā dhammā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**thoughts known by the mind that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[1016]="*Tañce bhikkhu abhinandati abhivadati ajjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**If a mendicant approves, welcomes, and keeps clinging to them,*";
P_HTM[1017]="*Tassa taṃ abhinandato abhivadato ajjhosāya tiṭṭhato uppajjati nandī.**this gives rise to relishing.*";
P_HTM[1018]="*Nandisamudayā dukkhasamudayo, migajālāti vadāmi.**Relishing is the origin of suffering, I say.*";
P_HTM[1019]="*Santi ca kho, migajāla, cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**There are sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[1020]="*Tañce bhikkhu nābhinandati nābhivadati nājjhosāya tiṭṭhati. Tassa taṃ anabhinandato anabhivadato anajjhosāya tiṭṭhato nandī nirujjhati.**If a mendicant doesn’t approve, welcome, and keep clinging to them, relishing ceases.*";
P_HTM[1021]="*Nandinirodhā dukkhanirodho, migajālāti vadāmi … pe …**When relishing ceases, suffering ceases, I say.*";
P_HTM[1022]="*santi ca kho, migajāla, jivhāviññeyyā rasā iṭṭhā kantā … pe …**There are sounds … smells … tastes … touches …*";
P_HTM[1023]="*santi ca kho, migajāla, manoviññeyyā dhammā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**thoughts known by the mind that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[1024]="*Tañce bhikkhu nābhinandati nābhivadati nājjhosāya tiṭṭhati. Tassa taṃ anabhinandato anabhivadato anajjhosāya tiṭṭhato nandī nirujjhati.**If a mendicant doesn’t approve, welcome, and keep clinging to them, relishing ceases.*";
P_HTM[1025]="*Nandinirodhā dukkhanirodho, migajālāti vadāmī”ti.**When relishing ceases, suffering ceases, I say.”*";
P_HTM[1026]="*Atha kho āyasmā migajālo bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**And then Venerable Migajāla approved and agreed with what the Buddha said. He got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[1027]="*Atha kho āyasmā migajālo eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharato nacirasseva—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihāsi.**Then Migajāla, living alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute, soon realized the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life. He lived having achieved with his own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[1028]="*“Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti abbhaññāsi.**He understood: “Rebirth is ended; the spiritual journey has been completed; what had to be done has been done; there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[1029]="*Aññataro ca panāyasmā migajālo arahataṃ ahosīti.**And Migajāla became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[1030]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1031]="*3. Paṭhamasamiddhimārapañhāsuttaṃ**Samiddhi’s Question About Māra*";
P_HTM[1032]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[1033]="*Atha kho āyasmā samiddhi yena bhagavā … pe …**Then Venerable Samiddhi went up to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[1034]="*bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1035]="*“‘māro, māro’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of this thing called ‘Māra’.*";
P_HTM[1036]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, māro vā assa mārapaññatti vā”ti?**How do we define Māra or what is known as Māra?”*";
P_HTM[1037]="*“Yattha kho, samiddhi, atthi cakkhu, atthi rūpā, atthi cakkhuviññāṇaṃ, atthi cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbā dhammā, atthi tattha māro vā mārapaññatti vā.**“Samiddhi, where there is the eye, sights, eye consciousness, and phenomena to be known by eye consciousness, there is Māra or what is known as Māra.*";
P_HTM[1038]="*Atthi sotaṃ, atthi saddā, atthi sotaviññāṇaṃ, atthi sotaviññāṇaviññātabbā dhammā, atthi tattha māro vā mārapaññatti vā.**Where there is the ear, sounds, ear consciousness, and phenomena to be known by ear consciousness, there is Māra or what is known as Māra.*";
P_HTM[1039]="*Atthi ghānaṃ, atthi gandhā, atthi ghānaviññāṇaṃ, atthi ghānaviññāṇaviññātabbā dhammā, atthi tattha māro vā mārapaññatti vā.**Where there is the nose, smells, nose consciousness, and phenomena to be known by nose consciousness, there is Māra or what is known as Māra.*";
P_HTM[1040]="*Atthi jivhā, atthi rasā, atthi jivhāviññāṇaṃ, atthi jivhāviññāṇaviññātabbā dhammā, atthi tattha māro vā mārapaññatti vā.**Where there is the tongue, tastes, tongue consciousness, and phenomena to be known by tongue consciousness, there is Māra or what is known as Māra.*";
P_HTM[1041]="*Atthi kāyo, atthi phoṭṭhabbā, atthi kāyaviññāṇaṃ, atthi kāyaviññāṇaviññātabbā dhammā, atthi tattha māro vā mārapaññatti vā.**Where there is the body, touches, body consciousness, and phenomena to be known by body consciousness, there is Māra or what is known as Māra.*";
P_HTM[1042]="*Atthi mano, atthi dhammā, atthi manoviññāṇaṃ, atthi manoviññāṇaviññātabbā dhammā, atthi tattha māro vā mārapaññatti vā.**Where there is the mind, thoughts, mind consciousness, and phenomena to be known by mind consciousness, there is Māra or what is known as Māra.*";
P_HTM[1043]="*Yattha ca kho, samiddhi, natthi cakkhu, natthi rūpā, natthi cakkhuviññāṇaṃ, natthi cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbā dhammā, natthi tattha māro vā mārapaññatti vā.**Where there is no eye, no sights, no eye consciousness, and no phenomena to be known by eye consciousness, there is no Māra or what is known as Māra.*";
P_HTM[1044]="*Natthi sotaṃ … pe …**Where there is no ear …*";
P_HTM[1045]="*natthi ghānaṃ … pe …**no nose …*";
P_HTM[1046]="*natthi jivhā, natthi rasā, natthi jivhāviññāṇaṃ, natthi jivhāviññāṇaviññātabbā dhammā, natthi tattha māro vā mārapaññatti vā.**no tongue …*";
P_HTM[1047]="*Natthi kāyo … pe ….**no body …*";
P_HTM[1048]="*Natthi mano, natthi dhammā, natthi manoviññāṇaṃ, natthi manoviññāṇaviññātabbā dhammā, natthi tattha māro vā mārapaññatti vā”ti.**Where there is no mind, no thoughts, no mind consciousness, and no phenomena to be known by mind consciousness, there is no Māra or what is known as Māra.”*";
P_HTM[1049]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1050]="*4. Samiddhisattapañhāsuttaṃ**Samiddhi’s Question About a Sentient Being*";
P_HTM[1051]="*“‘Satto, satto’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of this thing called a ‘sentient being’.*";
P_HTM[1052]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, satto vā assa sattapaññatti vā”ti … pe ….**How do we define a sentient being or what is known as a sentient being?” …*";
P_HTM[1053]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1054]="*5. Samiddhidukkhapañhāsuttaṃ**Samiddhi’s Question About Suffering*";
P_HTM[1055]="*“‘Dukkhaṃ, dukkhan’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of this thing called ‘suffering’.*";
P_HTM[1056]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, dukkhaṃ vā assa dukkhapaññatti vā”ti … pe ….**How do we define suffering or what is known as suffering?” …*";
P_HTM[1057]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1058]="*6. Samiddhilokapañhāsuttaṃ**Samiddhi’s Question About the World*";
P_HTM[1059]="*“‘Loko, loko’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of this thing called ‘the world’.*";
P_HTM[1060]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, loko vā assa lokapaññatti vā”ti?**How do we define the world or what is known as the world?”*";
P_HTM[1061]="*“Yattha kho, samiddhi, atthi cakkhu, atthi rūpā, atthi cakkhuviññāṇaṃ, atthi cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbā dhammā, atthi tattha loko vā lokapaññatti vāti … pe …**“Samiddhi, where there is the eye, sights, eye consciousness, and phenomena to be known by eye consciousness, there is the world or what is known as the world.*";
P_HTM[1062]="*atthi jivhā … pe …**Where there is the ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[1063]="*atthi mano, atthi dhammā, atthi manoviññāṇaṃ, atthi manoviññāṇaviññātabbā dhammā, atthi tattha loko vā lokapaññatti vā.**Where there is the mind, thoughts, mind consciousness, and phenomena to be known by mind consciousness, there is the world or what is known as the world.*";
P_HTM[1064]="*Yattha ca kho, samiddhi, natthi cakkhu, natthi rūpā, natthi cakkhuviññāṇaṃ, natthi cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbā dhammā, natthi tattha loko vā lokapaññatti vā … pe …**Where there is no eye, no sights, no eye consciousness, and no phenomena to be known by eye consciousness, there is no world or what is known as the world.*";
P_HTM[1065]="*natthi jivhā … pe …**Where there is no ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[1066]="*natthi mano, natthi dhammā, natthi manoviññāṇaṃ, natthi manoviññāṇaviññātabbā dhammā, natthi tattha loko vā lokapaññatti vā”ti.**Where there is no mind, no thoughts, no mind consciousness, and no phenomena to be known by mind consciousness, there is no world or what is known as the world.”*";
P_HTM[1067]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1068]="*7. Upasenaāsīvisasuttaṃ**Upasena and the Viper*";
P_HTM[1069]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā ca sāriputto āyasmā ca upaseno rājagahe viharanti sītavane sappasoṇḍikapabbhāre.**At one time the venerables Sāriputta and Upasena were staying near Rājagaha in the Cool Wood, under the Snake’s Hood Grotto.*";
P_HTM[1070]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmato upasenassa kāye āsīviso patito hoti.**Now at that time a viper fell on Upasena’s body,*";
P_HTM[1071]="*Atha kho āyasmā upaseno bhikkhū āmantesi:**and he addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[1072]="*“etha me, āvuso, imaṃ kāyaṃ mañcakaṃ āropetvā bahiddhā nīharatha.**“Come, reverends, lift this body onto a cot and carry it outside*";
P_HTM[1073]="*Purāyaṃ kāyo idheva vikirati;**before it’s scattered right here*";
P_HTM[1074]="*seyyathāpi bhusamuṭṭhī”ti.**like a handful of chaff.”*";
P_HTM[1075]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā sāriputto āyasmantaṃ upasenaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Sāriputta said to him,*";
P_HTM[1076]="*“na kho pana mayaṃ passāma āyasmato upasenassa kāyassa vā aññathattaṃ indriyānaṃ vā vipariṇāmaṃ.**“But we don’t see any impairment in your body or deterioration of your faculties.*";
P_HTM[1077]="*Atha ca panāyasmā upaseno evamāha:**Yet you say:*";
P_HTM[1078]="*‘etha me, āvuso, imaṃ kāyaṃ mañcakaṃ āropetvā bahiddhā nīharatha.**‘Come, reverends, lift this body onto a cot and carry it outside*";
P_HTM[1079]="*Purāyaṃ kāyo idheva vikirati;**before it’s scattered right here*";
P_HTM[1080]="*seyyathāpi bhusamuṭṭhī’”ti.**like a handful of chaff.’”*";
P_HTM[1081]="*“Yassa nūna, āvuso sāriputta, evamassa:**“Reverend Sāriputta, there may be an impairment in body or deterioration of faculties for someone who thinks:*";
P_HTM[1082]="*‘ahaṃ cakkhūti vā mama cakkhūti vā … pe …**‘I am the eye’ or ‘the eye is mine.’*";
P_HTM[1083]="*ahaṃ jivhāti vā mama jivhāti vā …**Or ‘I am the ear … nose … tongue … body …’*";
P_HTM[1084]="*ahaṃ manoti vā mama mano’ti vā.**Or ‘I am the mind’ or ‘the mind is mine.’*";
P_HTM[1085]="*Tassa, āvuso sāriputta, siyā kāyassa vā aññathattaṃ indriyānaṃ vā vipariṇāmo.* **";
P_HTM[1086]="*Mayhañca kho, āvuso sāriputta, na evaṃ hoti:**But I don’t think like that.*";
P_HTM[1087]="*‘ahaṃ cakkhūti vā mama cakkhūti vā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1088]="*ahaṃ jivhāti vā mama jivhāti vā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1089]="*ahaṃ manoti vā mama manoti vā’.* **";
P_HTM[1090]="*Tassa mayhañca kho, āvuso sāriputta, kiṃ kāyassa vā aññathattaṃ bhavissati, indriyānaṃ vā vipariṇāmo”ti.**So why would there be an impairment in my body or deterioration of my faculties?”*";
P_HTM[1091]="*Tathā hi panāyasmato upasenassa dīgharattaṃ ahaṅkāramamaṅkāramānānusayo susamūhato.**“That must be because Venerable Upasena has long ago totally eradicated ego, possessiveness, and the underlying tendency to conceit.*";
P_HTM[1092]="*Tasmā āyasmato upasenassa na evaṃ hoti:**That’s why it doesn’t occur to you:*";
P_HTM[1093]="*“‘ahaṃ cakkhūti vā mama cakkhūti vā … pe …**‘I am the eye’ or ‘the eye is mine.’ Or ‘I am the ear …*";
P_HTM[1094]="*ahaṃ jivhāti vā mama jivhāti vā … pe …**nose … tongue … body …’*";
P_HTM[1095]="*ahaṃ manoti vā mama mano’ti vā”ti.**Or ‘I am the mind’ or ‘the mind is mine.’”*";
P_HTM[1096]="*Atha kho te bhikkhū āyasmato upasenassa kāyaṃ mañcakaṃ āropetvā bahiddhā nīhariṃsu.**Then those mendicants lifted Upasena’s body onto a cot and carried it outside.*";
P_HTM[1097]="*Atha kho āyasmato upasenassa kāyo tattheva vikiri;**And his body was scattered right there*";
P_HTM[1098]="*seyyathāpi bhusamuṭṭhīti.**like a handful of chaff.*";
P_HTM[1099]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1100]="*8. Upavāṇasandiṭṭhikasuttaṃ**Upavāṇa on What is Visible in This Very Life*";
P_HTM[1101]="*Atha kho āyasmā upavāṇo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe …**Then Venerable Upavāṇa went up to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[1102]="*ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā upavāṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1103]="*“‘sandiṭṭhiko dhammo, sandiṭṭhiko dhammo’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of ‘a teaching visible in this very life’.*";
P_HTM[1104]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, sandiṭṭhiko dhammo hoti, akāliko ehipassiko opaneyyiko paccattaṃ veditabbo viññūhī”ti?**In what way is the teaching visible in this very life, immediately effective, inviting inspection, relevant, so that sensible people can know it for themselves?”*";
P_HTM[1105]="*“Idha pana, upavāṇa, bhikkhu cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā rūpappaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti rūparāgappaṭisaṃvedī ca.**“Upavāṇa, take a mendicant who sees a sight with their eyes. They experience both the sight and the desire for the sight.*";
P_HTM[1106]="*Santañca ajjhattaṃ rūpesu rāgaṃ ‘atthi me ajjhattaṃ rūpesu rāgo’ti pajānāti.**There is desire for sights in them, and they understand that.*";
P_HTM[1107]="*Yaṃ taṃ, upavāṇa, bhikkhu cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā rūpappaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti rūparāgappaṭisaṃvedī ca.**Since this is so,*";
P_HTM[1108]="*Santañca ajjhattaṃ rūpesu rāgaṃ ‘atthi me ajjhattaṃ rūpesu rāgo’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[1109]="*Evampi kho, upavāṇa, sandiṭṭhiko dhammo hoti akāliko ehipassiko opaneyyiko paccattaṃ veditabbo viññūhi … pe ….**this is how the teaching is visible in this very life, immediately effective, inviting inspection, relevant, so that sensible people can know it for themselves.*";
P_HTM[1110]="*Puna caparaṃ, upavāṇa, bhikkhu jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā rasappaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti rasarāgappaṭisaṃvedī ca.**Next, take a mendicant who hears … smells … tastes … touches …*";
P_HTM[1111]="*Santañca ajjhattaṃ rasesu rāgaṃ ‘atthi me ajjhattaṃ rasesu rāgo’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[1112]="*Yaṃ taṃ, upavāṇa, bhikkhu jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā rasappaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti rasarāgappaṭisaṃvedī ca.* **";
P_HTM[1113]="*Santañca ajjhattaṃ rasesu rāgaṃ ‘atthi me ajjhattaṃ rasesu rāgo’ti pajānāti. Evampi kho, upavāṇa, sandiṭṭhiko dhammo hoti akāliko ehipassiko opaneyyiko paccattaṃ veditabbo viññūhi … pe ….* **";
P_HTM[1114]="*Puna caparaṃ, upavāṇa, bhikkhu manasā dhammaṃ viññāya dhammappaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti dhammarāgappaṭisaṃvedī ca.**Next, take a mendicant who knows a thought with their mind. They experience both the thought and the desire for the thought.*";
P_HTM[1115]="*Santañca ajjhattaṃ dhammesu rāgaṃ ‘atthi me ajjhattaṃ dhammesu rāgo’ti pajānāti.**There is desire for thoughts in them, and they understand that.*";
P_HTM[1116]="*Yaṃ taṃ, upavāṇa, bhikkhu manasā dhammaṃ viññāya dhammappaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti dhammarāgappaṭisaṃvedī ca.**Since this is so,*";
P_HTM[1117]="*Santañca ajjhattaṃ dhammesu rāgaṃ ‘atthi me ajjhattaṃ dhammesu rāgo’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[1118]="*Evampi kho, upavāṇa, sandiṭṭhiko dhammo hoti … pe … paccattaṃ veditabbo viññūhi … pe ….**this is how the teaching is visible in this very life, immediately effective, inviting inspection, relevant, so that sensible people can know it for themselves.*";
P_HTM[1119]="*Idha pana, upavāṇa, bhikkhu cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā rūpappaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti, no ca rūparāgappaṭisaṃvedī.**Take a mendicant who sees a sight with their eyes. They experience the sight but no desire for the sight.*";
P_HTM[1120]="*Asantañca ajjhattaṃ rūpesu rāgaṃ ‘natthi me ajjhattaṃ rūpesu rāgo’ti pajānāti.**There is no desire for sights in them, and they understand that.*";
P_HTM[1121]="*Yaṃ taṃ, upavāṇa, bhikkhu cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā rūpappaṭisaṃvedīhi kho hoti, no ca rūparāgappaṭisaṃvedī.**Since this is so,*";
P_HTM[1122]="*Asantañca ajjhattaṃ rūpesu rāgaṃ ‘natthi me ajjhattaṃ rūpesu rāgo’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[1123]="*Evampi kho, upavāṇa, sandiṭṭhiko dhammo hoti, akāliko ehipassiko opaneyyiko paccattaṃ veditabbo viññūhi … pe ….**this is how the teaching is visible in this very life, immediately effective, inviting inspection, relevant, so that sensible people can know it for themselves.*";
P_HTM[1124]="*Puna caparaṃ, upavāṇa, bhikkhu jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā rasappaṭisaṃvedīhi kho hoti, no ca rasarāgappaṭisaṃvedī. Asantañca ajjhattaṃ rasesu rāgaṃ ‘natthi me ajjhattaṃ rasesu rāgo’ti pajānāti … pe ….**Next, take a mendicant who hears … smells … tastes … touches …*";
P_HTM[1125]="*Puna caparaṃ, upavāṇa, bhikkhu manasā dhammaṃ viññāya dhammappaṭisaṃvedīhi kho hoti, no ca dhammarāgappaṭisaṃvedī.* **";
P_HTM[1126]="*Asantañca ajjhattaṃ dhammesu rāgaṃ ‘natthi me ajjhattaṃ dhammesu rāgo’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[1127]="*Yaṃ taṃ, upavāṇa, bhikkhu manasā dhammaṃ viññāya dhammappaṭisaṃvedīhi kho hoti, no ca dhammarāgappaṭisaṃvedī.**Next, take a mendicant who knows a thought with their mind. They experience the thought but no desire for the thought.*";
P_HTM[1128]="*Asantañca ajjhattaṃ dhammesu rāgaṃ ‘natthi me ajjhattaṃ dhammesu rāgo’ti pajānāti.**There is no desire for thoughts in them, and they understand that.*";
P_HTM[1129]="*Evampi kho, upavāṇa, sandiṭṭhiko dhammo hoti, akāliko ehipassiko opaneyyiko paccattaṃ veditabbo viññūhī”ti.**Since this is so, this is how the teaching is visible in this very life, immediately effective, inviting inspection, relevant, so that sensible people can know it for themselves.”*";
P_HTM[1130]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1131]="*9. Paṭhamachaphassāyatanasuttaṃ**Six Fields of Contact (1st)*";
P_HTM[1132]="*“Yo hi koci, bhikkhave, bhikkhu channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**“Mendicants, anyone who doesn’t truly understand the six fields of contacts’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape*";
P_HTM[1133]="*Avusitaṃ tena brahmacariyaṃ, ārakā so imasmā dhammavinayā”ti.**has not completed the spiritual journey and is far from this teaching and training.”*";
P_HTM[1134]="*Evaṃ vutte, aññataro bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, one of the mendicants said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1135]="*“etthāhaṃ, bhante, anassasaṃ.**“Here, sir, I’m lost.*";
P_HTM[1136]="*Ahañhi, bhante, channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāmī”ti.**For I don’t truly understand the six fields of contacts’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.”*";
P_HTM[1137]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, bhikkhu,**“What do you think, mendicant?*";
P_HTM[1138]="*cakkhuṃ ‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’ti samanupassasī”ti?**Do you regard the eye like this: ‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1139]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1140]="*“Sādhu, bhikkhu, ettha ca te, bhikkhu, cakkhu ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya sudiṭṭhaṃ bhavissati.**“Good, mendicant! And regarding the eye, you will truly see clearly with right wisdom that: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1141]="*Esevanto dukkhassa … pe …**Just this is the end of suffering.*";
P_HTM[1142]="*jivhaṃ ‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’ti samanupassasī”ti?**Do you regard the ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[1143]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[1144]="*“Sādhu, bhikkhu, ettha ca te, bhikkhu, jivhā ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya sudiṭṭhaṃ bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[1145]="*Esevanto dukkhassa … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1146]="*manaṃ ‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’ti samanupassasī”ti?**Do you regard the mind like this: ‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1147]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1148]="*“Sādhu, bhikkhu, ettha ca te, bhikkhu, mano ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya sudiṭṭhaṃ bhavissati.**“Good, mendicant! And regarding the mind, you will truly see clearly with right wisdom that: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1149]="*Esevanto dukkhassā”ti.**Just this is the end of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[1150]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1151]="*10. Dutiyachaphassāyatanasuttaṃ**Six Fields of Contact (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1152]="*“Yo hi koci, bhikkhave, bhikkhu channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**“Mendicants, anyone who doesn’t truly understand the six fields of contacts’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape*";
P_HTM[1153]="*Avusitaṃ tena brahmacariyaṃ, ārakā so imasmā dhammavinayā”ti.**has not completed the spiritual journey and is far from this teaching and training.”*";
P_HTM[1154]="*Evaṃ vutte, aññataro bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, one of the mendicants said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1155]="*“etthāhaṃ, bhante, anassasaṃ panassasaṃ.**“Here, sir, I’m lost, truly lost.*";
P_HTM[1156]="*Ahañhi, bhante, channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāmī”ti.**For I don’t truly understand the six fields of contacts’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.”*";
P_HTM[1157]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, bhikkhu,**“What do you think, mendicant?*";
P_HTM[1158]="*cakkhuṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassasī”ti?**Do you regard the eye like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1159]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1160]="*“Sādhu, bhikkhu, ettha ca te, bhikkhu, cakkhu ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya sudiṭṭhaṃ bhavissati.**“Good, mendicant! And regarding the eye, you will truly see clearly with right wisdom that: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1161]="*Evaṃ te etaṃ paṭhamaṃ phassāyatanaṃ pahīnaṃ bhavissati āyatiṃ apunabbhavāya … pe ….**In this way you will give up the first field of contact, so that there are no more future lives.*";
P_HTM[1162]="*“Jivhaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassasī”ti?**Do you regard the ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[1163]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[1164]="*“Sādhu, bhikkhu, ettha ca te, bhikkhu, jivhā ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya sudiṭṭhaṃ bhavissati. Evaṃ te etaṃ catutthaṃ phassāyatanaṃ pahīnaṃ bhavissati āyatiṃ apunabbhavāya … pe ….* **";
P_HTM[1165]="*“Manaṃ ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassasī”ti?**Do you regard the mind like this: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1166]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1167]="*“Sādhu, bhikkhu, ettha ca te, bhikkhu, mano ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti evametaṃ yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya sudiṭṭhaṃ bhavissati.**“Good, mendicant! And regarding the mind, you will truly see clearly with right wisdom that: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1168]="*Evaṃ te etaṃ chaṭṭhaṃ phassāyatanaṃ pahīnaṃ bhavissati āyatiṃ apunabbhavāyā”ti.**In this way you will give up the sixth field of contact, so that there are no more future lives.”*";
P_HTM[1169]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1170]="*11. Tatiyachaphassāyatanasuttaṃ**Six Fields of Contact (3rd)*";
P_HTM[1171]="*“Yo hi koci, bhikkhave, bhikkhu channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**“Mendicants, anyone who doesn’t truly understand the six fields of contacts’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape*";
P_HTM[1172]="*Avusitaṃ tena brahmacariyaṃ, ārakā so imasmā dhammavinayā”ti.**has not completed the spiritual journey and is far from this teaching and training.”*";
P_HTM[1173]="*Evaṃ vutte, aññataro bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, one of the mendicants said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1174]="*“etthāhaṃ, bhante, anassasaṃ panassasaṃ.**“Here, sir, I’m lost, truly lost.*";
P_HTM[1175]="*Ahañhi, bhante, channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāmī”ti.**For I don’t truly understand the six fields of contacts’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.”*";
P_HTM[1176]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, bhikkhu,**“What do you think, mendicant?*";
P_HTM[1177]="*cakkhu niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is the eye permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1178]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1179]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[1180]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1181]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and liable to fall apart, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[1182]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1183]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1184]="*“Sotaṃ …**“Is the ear …*";
P_HTM[1185]="*ghānaṃ …**nose …*";
P_HTM[1186]="*jivhā …**tongue …*";
P_HTM[1187]="*kāyo …**body …*";
P_HTM[1188]="*mano nicco vā anicco vā”ti?**mind permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1189]="*“Anicco, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1190]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[1191]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1192]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and liable to fall apart, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[1193]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1194]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1195]="*“Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhu, sutavā ariyasāvako cakkhusmimpi nibbindati, sotasmimpi nibbindati, ghānasmimpi nibbindati, jivhāyapi nibbindati, kāyasmimpi nibbindati, manasmimpi nibbindati.**“Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[1196]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati; vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[1197]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[1198]="*Ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1199]="*Migajālavaggo dutiyo.* **";
P_HTM[1200]="*Migajālena dve vuttā,* **";
P_HTM[1201]="*Cattāro ca samiddhinā;* **";
P_HTM[1202]="*Upaseno upavāṇo,* **";
P_HTM[1203]="*Chaphassāyatanikā tayoti.* **";
P_HTM[1204]="*8. Gilānavaggo**Sick*";
P_HTM[1205]="*1. Paṭhamagilānasuttaṃ**Sick (1st)*";
P_HTM[1206]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1207]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1208]="*“amukasmiṃ, bhante, vihāre aññataro bhikkhu navo appaññāto ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**“Sir, in such and such a monastery there’s a mendicant who is junior and not well-known. He’s sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[1209]="*Sādhu, bhante, bhagavā yena so bhikkhu tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.**Please go to him out of compassion.”*";
P_HTM[1210]="*Atha kho bhagavā navavādañca sutvā gilānavādañca, “appaññāto bhikkhū”ti iti viditvā yena so bhikkhu tenupasaṅkami.**When the Buddha heard that the mendicant was junior and ill, understanding that he was not well-known, he went to him.*";
P_HTM[1211]="*Addasā kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ dūratova āgacchantaṃ.**That mendicant saw the Buddha coming off in the distance*";
P_HTM[1212]="*Disvāna mañcake samadhosi.**and tried to rise on his cot.*";
P_HTM[1213]="*Atha kho bhagavā taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavoca:**The Buddha said to that monk,*";
P_HTM[1214]="*“alaṃ, bhikkhu, mā tvaṃ mañcake samadhosi.**“It’s all right, mendicant, don’t get up.*";
P_HTM[1215]="*Santimāni āsanāni paññattāni, tatthāhaṃ nisīdissāmī”ti.**There are some seats spread out, I will sit there.”*";
P_HTM[1216]="*Nisīdi bhagavā paññatte āsane.**He sat on the seat spread out*";
P_HTM[1217]="*Nisajja kho bhagavā taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavoca:**and said to the mendicant,*";
P_HTM[1218]="*“kacci te, bhikkhu, khamanīyaṃ, kacci yāpanīyaṃ, kacci dukkhā vedanā paṭikkamanti no abhikkamanti, paṭikkamosānaṃ paññāyati no abhikkamo”ti?**“I hope you’re keeping well, mendicant; I hope you’re alright. I hope that your pain is fading, not growing, that its fading is evident, not its growing.”*";
P_HTM[1219]="*“Na me, bhante, khamanīyaṃ, na yāpanīyaṃ, bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti no paṭikkamanti, abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati no paṭikkamo”ti.**“Sir, I’m not keeping well, I’m not alright. The pain is terrible and growing, not fading; its growing is evident, not its fading.”*";
P_HTM[1220]="*“Kacci te, bhikkhu, na kiñci kukkuccaṃ, na koci vippaṭisāro”ti?**“I hope you don’t have any remorse or regret?”*";
P_HTM[1221]="*“Taggha me, bhante, anappakaṃ kukkuccaṃ, anappako vippaṭisāro”ti.**“Indeed, sir, I have no little remorse and regret.”*";
P_HTM[1222]="*“Kacci pana taṃ, bhikkhu, attā sīlato upavadatī”ti?**“I hope you have no reason to blame yourself when it comes to ethical conduct?”*";
P_HTM[1223]="*“Na kho maṃ, bhante, attā sīlato upavadatī”ti.**“No sir, I have no reason to blame myself when it comes to ethical conduct.”*";
P_HTM[1224]="*“No ce kira te, bhikkhu, attā sīlato upavadati, atha kiñca te kukkuccaṃ ko ca vippaṭisāro”ti?**“In that case, mendicant, why do you have remorse and regret?”*";
P_HTM[1225]="*“Na khvāhaṃ, bhante, sīlavisuddhatthaṃ bhagavatā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāmī”ti.**“Because I understand that the Buddha has not taught the Dhamma merely for the sake of ethical purity.”*";
P_HTM[1226]="*“No ce kira tvaṃ, bhikkhu, sīlavisuddhatthaṃ mayā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāsi, atha kimatthaṃ carahi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, mayā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāsī”ti?**“If that is so, what exactly do you understand to be the purpose of teaching the Dhamma?”*";
P_HTM[1227]="*“Rāgavirāgatthaṃ khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāmī”ti.**“I understand that the Buddha has taught the Dhamma for the purpose of the fading away of greed.”*";
P_HTM[1228]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhikkhu.**“Good, good, mendicant!*";
P_HTM[1229]="*Sādhu kho tvaṃ, bhikkhu, rāgavirāgatthaṃ mayā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāsi.**It’s good that you understand that I’ve taught the Dhamma for the purpose of the fading away of greed.*";
P_HTM[1230]="*Rāgavirāgattho hi, bhikkhu, mayā dhammo desito.**For that is indeed the purpose.*";
P_HTM[1231]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, bhikkhu,**What do you think, mendicant?*";
P_HTM[1232]="*cakkhu niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is the eye permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1233]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.” …*";
P_HTM[1234]="*“… pe …* **";
P_HTM[1235]="*Sotaṃ …**“Is the ear …*";
P_HTM[1236]="*ghānaṃ …**nose …*";
P_HTM[1237]="*jivhā …**tongue …*";
P_HTM[1238]="*kāyo …**body …*";
P_HTM[1239]="*mano nicco vā anicco vā”ti?**mind permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1240]="*“Anicco, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1241]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[1242]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1243]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and liable to fall apart, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[1244]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1245]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1246]="*“Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhu, sutavā ariyasāvako cakkhusmimpi nibbindati, sotasmimpi nibbindati … pe … manasmimpi nibbindati.**“Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[1247]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati; vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[1248]="*‘Khīṇā jāti … pe … nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended … there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[1249]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1250]="*Attamano so bhikkhu bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandi.**Satisfied, that mendicant was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1251]="*Imasmiñca pana veyyākaraṇasmiṃ bhaññamāne tassa bhikkhuno virajaṃ vītamalaṃ dhammacakkhuṃ udapādi:**And while this discourse was being spoken, the stainless, immaculate vision of the Dhamma arose in that mendicant:*";
P_HTM[1252]="*“yaṃ kiñci samudayadhammaṃ sabbaṃ taṃ nirodhadhamman”ti.**“Everything that has a beginning has an end.”*";
P_HTM[1253]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1254]="*2. Dutiyagilānasuttaṃ**Sick (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1255]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu … pe … bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha … and asked him,*";
P_HTM[1256]="*“amukasmiṃ, bhante, vihāre aññataro bhikkhu navo appaññāto ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**“Sir, in such and such a monastery there’s a mendicant who is junior and not well-known. He’s sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[1257]="*Sādhu, bhante, bhagavā yena so bhikkhu tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.**Please go to him out of compassion.”*";
P_HTM[1258]="*Atha kho bhagavā navavādañca sutvā gilānavādañca, “appaññāto bhikkhū”ti iti viditvā yena so bhikkhu tenupasaṅkami.**When the Buddha heard that the mendicant was junior and ill, understanding that he was not well-known, he went to him.*";
P_HTM[1259]="*Addasā kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ dūratova āgacchantaṃ.**That mendicant saw the Buddha coming off in the distance*";
P_HTM[1260]="*Disvāna mañcake samadhosi.**and tried to rise on his cot.*";
P_HTM[1261]="*Atha kho bhagavā taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavoca:**Then the Buddha said to that monk,*";
P_HTM[1262]="*“alaṃ, bhikkhu, mā tvaṃ mañcake samadhosi.**“It’s all right, mendicant, don’t get up.*";
P_HTM[1263]="*Santimāni āsanāni paññattāni, tatthāhaṃ nisīdissāmī”ti.**There are some seats spread out, I will sit there.”*";
P_HTM[1264]="*Nisīdi bhagavā paññatte āsane. Nisajja kho bhagavā taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavoca:**He sat on the seat spread out and said to the mendicant,*";
P_HTM[1265]="*“kacci te, bhikkhu, khamanīyaṃ, kacci yāpanīyaṃ, kacci dukkhā vedanā paṭikkamanti no abhikkamanti, paṭikkamosānaṃ paññāyati no abhikkamo”ti?**“I hope you’re keeping well, mendicant; I hope you’re alright. I hope that your pain is fading, not growing, that its fading is evident, not its growing.”*";
P_HTM[1266]="*“Na me, bhante, khamanīyaṃ, na yāpanīyaṃ … pe …**“Sir, I’m not keeping well, I’m not alright. …*";
P_HTM[1267]="*na kho maṃ, bhante, attā sīlato upavadatī”ti.**I have no reason to blame myself when it comes to ethical conduct.”*";
P_HTM[1268]="*“No ce kira te, bhikkhu, attā sīlato upavadati, atha kiñca te kukkuccaṃ ko ca vippaṭisāro”ti?**“In that case, mendicant, why do you have remorse and regret?”*";
P_HTM[1269]="*“Na khvāhaṃ, bhante, sīlavisuddhatthaṃ bhagavatā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāmī”ti.**“Because I understand that the Buddha has not taught the Dhamma merely for the sake of ethical purity.”*";
P_HTM[1270]="*“No ce kira tvaṃ, bhikkhu, sīlavisuddhatthaṃ mayā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāsi, atha kimatthaṃ carahi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, mayā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāsī”ti?**“If that is so, what exactly do you understand to be the purpose of teaching the Dhamma?”*";
P_HTM[1271]="*“Anupādāparinibbānatthaṃ khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāmī”ti.**“I understand that the Buddha has taught the Dhamma for the purpose of complete extinguishment by not grasping.”*";
P_HTM[1272]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhikkhu.**“Good, good, mendicant!*";
P_HTM[1273]="*Sādhu kho tvaṃ, bhikkhu, anupādāparinibbānatthaṃ mayā dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāsi.**It’s good that you understand that I’ve taught the Dhamma for the purpose of complete extinguishment by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[1274]="*Anupādāparinibbānattho hi, bhikkhu, mayā dhammo desito.**For that is indeed the purpose.*";
P_HTM[1275]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, bhikkhu,**“What do you think, mendicant?*";
P_HTM[1276]="*cakkhu niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is the eye permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1277]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.” …*";
P_HTM[1278]="*“… pe …* **";
P_HTM[1279]="*Sotaṃ …**“Is the ear …*";
P_HTM[1280]="*ghānaṃ …**nose …*";
P_HTM[1281]="*jivhā …**tongue …*";
P_HTM[1282]="*kāyo …**body …*";
P_HTM[1283]="*mano …**mind …*";
P_HTM[1284]="*manoviññāṇaṃ …**mind consciousness …*";
P_HTM[1285]="*manosamphasso …**mind contact …*";
P_HTM[1286]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact: is that permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1287]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1288]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[1289]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1290]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and liable to fall apart, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[1291]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1292]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1293]="*“Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhu, sutavā ariyasāvako cakkhusmimpi nibbindati … pe …**“Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with the eye … ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[1294]="*manasmimpi …**mind …*";
P_HTM[1295]="*manoviññāṇepi …**mind consciousness …*";
P_HTM[1296]="*manosamphassepi nibbindati.**mind contact …*";
P_HTM[1297]="*Yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tasmimpi nibbindati.**They grow disillusioned with the painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact.*";
P_HTM[1298]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati; vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[1299]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[1300]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1301]="*Attamano so bhikkhu bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandi.**Satisfied, that mendicant was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1302]="*Imasmiñca pana veyyākaraṇasmiṃ bhaññamāne tassa bhikkhussa anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimuccīti.**And while this discourse was being spoken, the mind of that mendicant was freed from defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[1303]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1304]="*3. Rādhaaniccasuttaṃ**With Rādha on Impermanence*";
P_HTM[1305]="*Atha kho āyasmā rādho … pe …**The Venerable Rādha went up to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[1306]="*ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā rādho bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1307]="*“sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā saṃkhittena dhammaṃ desetu, yamahaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[1308]="*“Yaṃ kho, rādha, aniccaṃ tatra te chando pahātabbo.**“Rādha, you should give up desire for what is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[1309]="*Kiñca, rādha, aniccaṃ tatra te chando pahātabbo?**And what is impermanent?*";
P_HTM[1310]="*Cakkhu aniccaṃ, rūpā aniccā, cakkhuviññāṇaṃ …**The eye, sights, eye consciousness,*";
P_HTM[1311]="*cakkhusamphasso …**and eye contact are impermanent.*";
P_HTM[1312]="*yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccaṃ. Tatra te chando pahātabbo … pe …**And the pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact is also impermanent. You should give up desire for it.*";
P_HTM[1313]="*jivhā …**The ear … nose … tongue …*";
P_HTM[1314]="*kāyo …**body …*";
P_HTM[1315]="*mano anicco. Tatra te chando pahātabbo.**The mind,*";
P_HTM[1316]="*Dhammā …**thoughts,*";
P_HTM[1317]="*manoviññāṇaṃ …**mind consciousness,*";
P_HTM[1318]="*manosamphasso …**and mind contact are impermanent.*";
P_HTM[1319]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccaṃ. Tatra te chando pahātabbo.**And the pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact is also impermanent. You should give up desire for it.*";
P_HTM[1320]="*Yaṃ kho, rādha, aniccaṃ tatra te chando pahātabbo”ti.**You should give up desire for what is impermanent.”*";
P_HTM[1321]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1322]="*4. Rādhadukkhasuttaṃ**With Rādha on Suffering*";
P_HTM[1323]="*“Yaṃ kho, rādha, dukkhaṃ tatra te chando pahātabbo.**“Rādha, you should give up desire for what is suffering. …”*";
P_HTM[1324]="*Kiñca, rādha, dukkhaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[1325]="*Cakkhu kho, rādha, dukkhaṃ. Tatra te chando pahātabbo.* **";
P_HTM[1326]="*Rūpā …* **";
P_HTM[1327]="*cakkhuviññāṇaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[1328]="*cakkhusamphasso …* **";
P_HTM[1329]="*yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassa … pe … adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi dukkhaṃ. Tatra te chando pahātabbo … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1330]="*mano dukkho …* **";
P_HTM[1331]="*dhammā …* **";
P_HTM[1332]="*manoviññāṇaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[1333]="*manosamphasso …* **";
P_HTM[1334]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi dukkhaṃ. Tatra te chando pahātabbo.* **";
P_HTM[1335]="*Yaṃ kho, rādha, dukkhaṃ tatra te chando pahātabbo”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1336]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1337]="*5. Rādhaanattasuttaṃ**With Rādha on Not*";
P_HTM[1338]="*“Yo kho, rādha, anattā tatra te chando pahātabbo.**“Rādha, you should give up desire for what is not-self. …”*";
P_HTM[1339]="*Ko ca, rādha, anattā?* **";
P_HTM[1340]="*Cakkhu kho, rādha, anattā. Tatra te chando pahātabbo.* **";
P_HTM[1341]="*Rūpā …* **";
P_HTM[1342]="*cakkhuviññāṇaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[1343]="*cakkhusamphasso …* **";
P_HTM[1344]="*yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1345]="*mano anattā …* **";
P_HTM[1346]="*dhammā …* **";
P_HTM[1347]="*manoviññāṇaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[1348]="*manosamphasso …* **";
P_HTM[1349]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi anattā. Tatra te chando pahātabbo.* **";
P_HTM[1350]="*Yo kho, rādha, anattā tatra te chando pahātabbo”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1351]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1352]="*6. Paṭhamaavijjāpahānasuttaṃ**Giving Up Ignorance (1st)*";
P_HTM[1353]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe …**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[1354]="*ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1355]="*“atthi nu kho, bhante, eko dhammo yassa pahānā bhikkhuno avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjatī”ti?**“Sir, is there one thing such that by giving it up a mendicant gives up ignorance and gives rise to knowledge?”*";
P_HTM[1356]="*“Atthi kho, bhikkhu, eko dhammo yassa pahānā bhikkhuno avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjatī”ti.**“There is, mendicant.”*";
P_HTM[1357]="*“Katamo pana, bhante, eko dhammo yassa pahānā bhikkhuno avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjatī”ti?**“But what is that one thing?”*";
P_HTM[1358]="*“Avijjā kho, bhikkhu, eko dhammo yassa pahānā bhikkhuno avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjatī”ti.**“Ignorance is one thing such that by giving it up a mendicant gives up ignorance and gives rise to knowledge.”*";
P_HTM[1359]="*“Kathaṃ pana, bhante, jānato, kathaṃ passato bhikkhuno avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjatī”ti?**“But how does a mendicant know and see so as to give up ignorance and give rise to knowledge?”*";
P_HTM[1360]="*“Cakkhuṃ kho, bhikkhu, aniccato jānato passato bhikkhuno avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjati. Rūpe … cakkhuviññāṇaṃ … cakkhusamphassaṃ …**“When a mendicant knows and sees the eye, sights, eye consciousness, and eye contact as impermanent, ignorance is given up and knowledge arises.*";
P_HTM[1361]="*yampidaṃ, cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccato jānato passato bhikkhuno avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjati … pe …**And also knowing and seeing the pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact as impermanent, ignorance is given up and knowledge arises. …*";
P_HTM[1362]="*manaṃ aniccato jānato passato bhikkhuno avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjati. Dhamme … manoviññāṇaṃ … manosamphassaṃ …**Knowing and seeing the mind, thoughts, mind consciousness, and mind contact as impermanent, ignorance is given up and knowledge arises.*";
P_HTM[1363]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccato jānato passato bhikkhuno avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjati.**And also knowing and seeing the pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact as impermanent, ignorance is given up and knowledge arises.*";
P_HTM[1364]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, jānato evaṃ passato bhikkhuno avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjatī”ti.**That’s how a mendicant knows and sees so as to give up ignorance and give rise to knowledge.”*";
P_HTM[1365]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1366]="*7. Dutiyaavijjāpahānasuttaṃ**Giving Up Ignorance (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1367]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu … pe … etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha … and asked him,*";
P_HTM[1368]="*“atthi nu kho, bhante, eko dhammo yassa pahānā bhikkhuno avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjatī”ti?**“Sir, is there one thing such that by giving it up a mendicant gives up ignorance and gives rise to knowledge?”*";
P_HTM[1369]="*“Atthi kho, bhikkhu, eko dhammo yassa pahānā bhikkhuno avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjatī”ti.**“There is, mendicant.”*";
P_HTM[1370]="*“Katamo pana, bhante, eko dhammo yassa pahānā bhikkhuno avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjatī”ti?**“But what is that one thing?”*";
P_HTM[1371]="*“Avijjā kho, bhikkhu, eko dhammo yassa pahānā bhikkhuno avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjatī”ti.**“Ignorance is one thing such that by giving it up a mendicant gives up ignorance and gives rise to knowledge.”*";
P_HTM[1372]="*“Kathaṃ pana, bhante, jānato, kathaṃ passato avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjatī”ti?**“But how does a mendicant know and see so as to give up ignorance and give rise to knowledge?”*";
P_HTM[1373]="*“Idha, bhikkhu, bhikkhuno sutaṃ hoti:**“It’s when a mendicant has heard:*";
P_HTM[1374]="*‘sabbe dhammā nālaṃ abhinivesāyā’ti.**‘Nothing is worth clinging on to.’*";
P_HTM[1375]="*Evañcetaṃ, bhikkhu, bhikkhuno sutaṃ hoti:**When a mendicant has heard that*";
P_HTM[1376]="*‘sabbe dhammā nālaṃ abhinivesāyā’ti.**nothing is worth clinging on to,*";
P_HTM[1377]="*So sabbaṃ dhammaṃ abhijānāti, sabbaṃ dhammaṃ abhiññāya sabbaṃ dhammaṃ parijānāti, sabbaṃ dhammaṃ pariññāya sabbanimittāni aññato passati, cakkhuṃ aññato passati, rūpe …**they directly know all things. Directly knowing all things, they completely understand all things. Completely understanding all things, they see all signs as other. They see the eye, sights,*";
P_HTM[1378]="*cakkhuviññāṇaṃ …**eye consciousness,*";
P_HTM[1379]="*cakkhusamphassaṃ …**and eye contact as other.*";
P_HTM[1380]="*yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aññato passati … pe …**And they also see the pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact as other. …*";
P_HTM[1381]="*manaṃ aññato passati, dhamme …**They see the mind, thoughts,*";
P_HTM[1382]="*manoviññāṇaṃ …**mind consciousness,*";
P_HTM[1383]="*manosamphassaṃ …**and mind contact as other.*";
P_HTM[1384]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aññato passati.**And they also see the pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact as other.*";
P_HTM[1385]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, jānato evaṃ passato bhikkhuno avijjā pahīyati, vijjā uppajjatī”ti.**That’s how a mendicant knows and sees so as to give up ignorance and give rise to knowledge.”*";
P_HTM[1386]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1387]="*8. Sambahulabhikkhusuttaṃ**Several Mendicants*";
P_HTM[1388]="*Atha kho sambahulā bhikkhū yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then several mendicants went up to the Buddha … and asked him,*";
P_HTM[1389]="*“idha no, bhante, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā amhe evaṃ pucchanti:**“Sir, sometimes wanderers who follow other paths ask us:*";
P_HTM[1390]="*‘kimatthiyaṃ, āvuso, samaṇe gotame brahmacariyaṃ vussatī’ti?**‘Reverends, what’s the purpose of living the spiritual life with the ascetic Gotama?’*";
P_HTM[1391]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhā mayaṃ, bhante, tesaṃ aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ evaṃ byākaroma:**We answer them like this:*";
P_HTM[1392]="*‘dukkhassa kho, āvuso, pariññatthaṃ bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ vussatī’ti.**‘The purpose of living the spiritual life under the Buddha is to completely understand suffering.’*";
P_HTM[1393]="*Kacci mayaṃ, bhante, evaṃ puṭṭhā evaṃ byākaramānā vuttavādino ceva bhagavato homa, na ca bhagavantaṃ abhūtena abbhācikkhāma, dhammassa cānudhammaṃ byākaroma, na ca koci sahadhammiko vādānuvādo gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgacchatī”ti?**Answering this way, we trust that we repeat what the Buddha has said, and don’t misrepresent him with an untruth. We trust our explanation is in line with the teaching, and that there are no legitimate grounds for rebuke or criticism.”*";
P_HTM[1394]="*“Taggha tumhe, bhikkhave, evaṃ puṭṭhā evaṃ byākaramānā vuttavādino ceva me hotha, na ca maṃ abhūtena abbhācikkhatha, dhammassa cānudhammaṃ byākarotha, na ca koci sahadhammiko vādānuvādo gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgacchati.**“Indeed, in answering this way you repeat what I’ve said, and don’t misrepresent me with an untruth. Your explanation is in line with the teaching, and there are no legitimate grounds for rebuke or criticism.*";
P_HTM[1395]="*Dukkhassa hi, bhikkhave, pariññatthaṃ mayi brahmacariyaṃ vussati.**For the purpose of living the spiritual life under me is to completely understand suffering.*";
P_HTM[1396]="*Sace pana vo, bhikkhave, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**If wanderers who follow other paths were to ask you:*";
P_HTM[1397]="*‘katamaṃ pana taṃ, āvuso, dukkhaṃ, yassa pariññāya samaṇe gotame brahmacariyaṃ vussatī’ti?**‘Reverends, what is that suffering?’*";
P_HTM[1398]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhā tumhe, bhikkhave, tesaṃ aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ evaṃ byākareyyātha:**You should answer them:*";
P_HTM[1399]="*‘cakkhu kho, āvuso, dukkhaṃ, tassa pariññāya bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ vussati.**‘Reverends, the eye is suffering. The purpose of living the spiritual life under the Buddha is to completely understand this.*";
P_HTM[1400]="*Rūpā … pe …**Sights … Eye consciousness … Eye contact …*";
P_HTM[1401]="*yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi dukkhaṃ.**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact is also suffering.*";
P_HTM[1402]="*Tassa pariññāya bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ vussati … pe …**The purpose of living the spiritual life under the Buddha is to completely understand this.*";
P_HTM[1403]="*mano dukkho … pe …**Ear … Nose … Tongue … Body … Mind …*";
P_HTM[1404]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi dukkhaṃ.**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact is also suffering.*";
P_HTM[1405]="*Tassa pariññāya bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ vussati.**The purpose of living the spiritual life under the Buddha is to completely understand this.*";
P_HTM[1406]="*Idaṃ kho taṃ, āvuso, dukkhaṃ, tassa pariññāya bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ vussatī’ti.**This is that suffering. The purpose of living the spiritual life under the Buddha is to completely understand this.’*";
P_HTM[1407]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhā tumhe, bhikkhave, tesaṃ aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ evaṃ byākareyyāthā”ti.**When questioned by wanderers who follow other paths, that’s how you should answer them.”*";
P_HTM[1408]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1409]="*9. Lokapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question On the World*";
P_HTM[1410]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha … and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1411]="*“‘Loko, loko’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of this thing called ‘the world’.*";
P_HTM[1412]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, lokoti vuccatī”ti?**How is the world defined?”*";
P_HTM[1413]="*“‘Lujjatī’ti kho, bhikkhu, tasmā lokoti vuccati.**“It wears away, mendicant, that’s why it’s called ‘the world’.*";
P_HTM[1414]="*Kiñca lujjati?**And what is wearing away?*";
P_HTM[1415]="*Cakkhu kho, bhikkhu, lujjati.**The eye is wearing away.*";
P_HTM[1416]="*Rūpā lujjanti, cakkhuviññāṇaṃ lujjati, cakkhusamphasso lujjati, yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi lujjati … pe …**Sights … eye consciousness … eye contact is wearing away. The painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact is also wearing away.*";
P_HTM[1417]="*jivhā lujjati … pe …**The ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[1418]="*mano lujjati, dhammā lujjanti, manoviññāṇaṃ lujjati, manosamphasso lujjati, yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi lujjati.**The mind … thoughts … mind consciousness … mind contact is wearing away. The painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact is also wearing away.*";
P_HTM[1419]="*Lujjatīti kho, bhikkhu, tasmā lokoti vuccatī”ti.**It wears away, mendicant, that’s why it’s called ‘the world’.”*";
P_HTM[1420]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1421]="*10. Phaggunapañhāsuttaṃ**Phagguna’s Question*";
P_HTM[1422]="*Atha kho āyasmā phagguno … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā phagguno bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**And then Venerable Phagguna went up to the Buddha … and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1423]="*“Atthi nu kho, bhante, taṃ cakkhu, yena cakkhunā atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivaṭṭe paññāpayamāno paññāpeyya … pe …**“Sir, suppose someone were to describe the Buddhas of the past who have become completely extinguished, cut off proliferation, cut off the track, finished off the cycle, and transcended suffering. Does the eye exist by which they could be described?*";
P_HTM[1424]="*atthi nu kho, bhante, sā jivhā, yāya jivhāya atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivaṭṭe paññāpayamāno paññāpeyya … pe …**Does the ear … nose … tongue … body exist …?*";
P_HTM[1425]="*atthi nu kho so, bhante, mano, yena manena atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivaṭṭe paññāpayamāno paññāpeyyā”ti?**Does the mind exist by which they could be described?”*";
P_HTM[1426]="*“Natthi kho taṃ, phagguna, cakkhu, yena cakkhunā atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivaṭṭe paññāpayamāno paññāpeyya … pe …**“Phagguna, suppose someone were to describe the Buddhas of the past who have become completely extinguished, cut off proliferation, cut off the track, finished off the cycle, and transcended suffering. The eye does not exist by which they could be described.*";
P_HTM[1427]="*natthi kho sā, phagguna, jivhā, yāya jivhāya atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivaṭṭe paññāpayamāno paññāpeyya … pe …**The ear … nose … tongue … body does not exist …*";
P_HTM[1428]="*natthi kho so, phagguna, mano, yena manena atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivaṭṭe paññāpayamāno paññāpeyyā”ti.**The mind does not exist by which they could be described.”*";
P_HTM[1429]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1430]="*Gilānavaggo tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[1431]="*Gilānena duve vuttā,* **";
P_HTM[1432]="*rādhena apare tayo;* **";
P_HTM[1433]="*Avijjāya ca dve vuttā,* **";
P_HTM[1434]="*bhikkhu loko ca phaggunoti.* **";
P_HTM[1435]="*9. Channavaggo**With Channa*";
P_HTM[1436]="*1. Palokadhammasuttaṃ**Wearing Out*";
P_HTM[1437]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1438]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Ānanda went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1439]="*“‘Loko, loko’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of this thing called ‘the world’.*";
P_HTM[1440]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, lokoti vuccatī”ti?**How is the world defined?”*";
P_HTM[1441]="*“Yaṃ kho, ānanda, palokadhammaṃ, ayaṃ vuccati ariyassa vinaye loko.**“Ānanda, that which wears out is called the world in the training of the noble one.*";
P_HTM[1442]="*Kiñca, ānanda, palokadhammaṃ?**And what wears out?*";
P_HTM[1443]="*Cakkhu kho, ānanda, palokadhammaṃ, rūpā palokadhammā, cakkhuviññāṇaṃ palokadhammaṃ, cakkhusamphasso palokadhammo, yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā … pe … tampi palokadhammaṃ … pe …**The eye wears out. Sights … eye consciousness … eye contact wears out. The painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact also wears out.*";
P_HTM[1444]="*jivhā palokadhammā, rasā palokadhammā, jivhāviññāṇaṃ palokadhammaṃ, jivhāsamphasso palokadhammo, yampidaṃ jivhāsamphassapaccayā … pe … tampi palokadhammaṃ … pe …**The ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[1445]="*mano palokadhammo, dhammā palokadhammā, manoviññāṇaṃ palokadhammaṃ, manosamphasso palokadhammo, yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi palokadhammaṃ.**The mind … thoughts … mind consciousness … mind contact wears out. The painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact also wears out.*";
P_HTM[1446]="*Yaṃ kho, ānanda, palokadhammaṃ, ayaṃ vuccati ariyassa vinaye loko”ti.**That which wears out is called the world in the training of the noble one.”*";
P_HTM[1447]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1448]="*2. Suññatalokasuttaṃ**The World is Empty*";
P_HTM[1449]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando … pe … bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**And then Venerable Ānanda … said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1450]="*“‘suñño loko, suñño loko’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they say that ‘the world is empty’.*";
P_HTM[1451]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, suñño lokoti vuccatī”ti?**What does the saying ‘the world is empty’ refer to?”*";
P_HTM[1452]="*“Yasmā ca kho, ānanda, suññaṃ attena vā attaniyena vā tasmā suñño lokoti vuccati.**“Ānanda, they say that ‘the world is empty’ because it’s empty of self or what belongs to self.*";
P_HTM[1453]="*Kiñca, ānanda, suññaṃ attena vā attaniyena vā?**And what is empty of self or what belongs to self?*";
P_HTM[1454]="*Cakkhu kho, ānanda, suññaṃ attena vā attaniyena vā.**The eye,*";
P_HTM[1455]="*Rūpā suññā attena vā attaniyena vā, cakkhuviññāṇaṃ suññaṃ attena vā attaniyena vā, cakkhusamphasso suñño attena vā attaniyena vā … pe …**sights, eye consciousness, and eye contact are empty of self or what belongs to self. …*";
P_HTM[1456]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi suññaṃ attena vā attaniyena vā.**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact is also empty of self or what belongs to self.*";
P_HTM[1457]="*Yasmā ca kho, ānanda, suññaṃ attena vā attaniyena vā, tasmā suñño lokoti vuccatī”ti.**They say that ‘the world is empty’ because it’s empty of self or what belongs to self.”*";
P_HTM[1458]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1459]="*3. Saṃkhittadhammasuttaṃ**A Teaching In Brief*";
P_HTM[1460]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Seated to one side, Venerable Ānanda said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1461]="*“sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā saṃkhittena dhammaṃ desetu, yamahaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[1462]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ānanda,**“What do you think, Ānanda?*";
P_HTM[1463]="*cakkhu niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is the eye permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1464]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1465]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[1466]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1467]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and liable to fall apart, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[1468]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1469]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1470]="*“Rūpā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?**“Are sights …*";
P_HTM[1471]="*“Aniccā, bhante” … pe ….* **";
P_HTM[1472]="*“Cakkhuviññāṇaṃ … pe …**eye consciousness … eye contact …*";
P_HTM[1473]="*yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact: is that permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1474]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1475]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[1476]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1477]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and liable to fall apart, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[1478]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1479]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante” … pe ….**“No, sir.” …*";
P_HTM[1480]="*“Jivhā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?**“Is the ear … nose … tongue … body … mind …*";
P_HTM[1481]="*“Aniccā, bhante” … pe ….* **";
P_HTM[1482]="*“Jivhāviññāṇaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[1483]="*jivhāsamphasso … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1484]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact: is that permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1485]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1486]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[1487]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1488]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and liable to fall apart, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[1489]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1490]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1491]="*“Evaṃ passaṃ, ānanda, sutavā ariyasāvako cakkhusmimpi nibbindati … pe … cakkhusamphassepi nibbindati … pe …**“Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with the eye, sights, eye consciousness, and eye contact. And they grow disillusioned with the painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact.*";
P_HTM[1492]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tasmimpi nibbindati.**They grow disillusioned with the ear … nose … tongue … body … mind … painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact.*";
P_HTM[1493]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati; vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[1494]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[1495]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1496]="*4. Channasuttaṃ**With Channa*";
P_HTM[1497]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[1498]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā ca sāriputto āyasmā ca mahācundo āyasmā ca channo gijjhakūṭe pabbate viharanti.**Now at that time the venerables Sāriputta, Mahācunda, and Channa were staying on the Vulture’s Peak Mountain.*";
P_HTM[1499]="*Tena kho pana samayena yena āyasmā channo ābādhiko hoti dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**Now at that time Venerable Channa was sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[1500]="*Atha kho āyasmā sāriputto sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yenāyasmā mahācundo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ mahācundaṃ etadavoca:**Then in the late afternoon, Venerable Sāriputta came out of retreat, went to Venerable Mahācunda and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1501]="*“āyāmāvuso cunda, yenāyasmā channo tenupasaṅkamissāma gilānapucchakā”ti.**“Come, Reverend Cunda, let’s go to see Venerable Channa and ask about his illness.”*";
P_HTM[1502]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho āyasmā mahācundo āyasmato sāriputtassa paccassosi.**“Yes, reverend,” replied Mahācunda.*";
P_HTM[1503]="*Atha kho āyasmā ca sāriputto āyasmā ca mahācundo yenāyasmā channo tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdiṃsu. Nisajja kho āyasmā sāriputto āyasmantaṃ channaṃ etadavoca:**And then Sāriputta and Mahācunda went to see Channa and sat down on the seats spread out. Sāriputta said to Channa:*";
P_HTM[1504]="*“kacci te, āvuso channa, khamanīyaṃ, kacci yāpanīyaṃ, kacci dukkhā vedanā paṭikkamanti no abhikkamanti, paṭikkamosānaṃ paññāyati no abhikkamo”ti?**“I hope you’re keeping well, Reverend Channa; I hope you’re alright. I hope that your pain is fading, not growing, that its fading is evident, not its growing.”*";
P_HTM[1505]="*“Na me, āvuso sāriputta, khamanīyaṃ na yāpanīyaṃ, bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti no paṭikkamanti, abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati no paṭikkamo.**“Reverend Sāriputta, I’m not keeping well, I’m not alright. The pain is terrible and growing, not fading; its growing is evident, not its fading.*";
P_HTM[1506]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso, balavā puriso tiṇhena sikharena muddhani abhimattheyya; evameva kho, āvuso, adhimattā vātā muddhani ūhananti.**The winds piercing my head are so severe, it feels like a strong man drilling into my head with a sharp point.*";
P_HTM[1507]="*Na me, āvuso, khamanīyaṃ, na yāpanīyaṃ … pe … no paṭikkamo.* **";
P_HTM[1508]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso, balavā puriso daḷhena varattakkhaṇḍena sīse sīsaveṭhaṃ dadeyya; evameva kho, āvuso, adhimattā sīse sīsavedanā.**The pain in my head is so severe, it feels like a strong man tightening a tough leather strap around my head.*";
P_HTM[1509]="*Na me, āvuso, khamanīyaṃ, na yāpanīyaṃ … pe … no paṭikkamo.* **";
P_HTM[1510]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso, dakkho goghātako vā goghātakantevāsī vā tiṇhena govikantanena kucchiṃ parikanteyya; evameva kho adhimattā vātā kucchiṃ parikantanti.**The winds piercing my belly are so severe, it feels like a deft butcher or their apprentice is slicing my belly open with a meat cleaver.*";
P_HTM[1511]="*Na me, āvuso, khamanīyaṃ, na yāpanīyaṃ … pe … no paṭikkamo.* **";
P_HTM[1512]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso, dve balavanto purisā dubbalataraṃ purisaṃ nānābāhāsu gahetvā aṅgārakāsuyā santāpeyyuṃ samparitāpeyyuṃ; evameva kho, āvuso, adhimatto kāyasmiṃ ḍāho.**The burning in my body is so severe, it feels like two strong men grabbing a weaker man by the arms to burn and scorch him on a pit of glowing coals.*";
P_HTM[1513]="*Na me, āvuso, khamanīyaṃ, na yāpanīyaṃ, bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti no paṭikkamanti, abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati no paṭikkamo.**I’m not keeping well, I’m not alright. The pain is terrible and growing, not fading; its growing is evident, not its fading.*";
P_HTM[1514]="*Satthaṃ, āvuso sāriputta, āharissāmi, nāvakaṅkhāmi jīvitan”ti.**Reverend Sāriputta, I will slit my wrists. I don’t wish to live.”*";
P_HTM[1515]="*“Mā āyasmā channo satthaṃ āharesi.**“Please don’t slit your wrists!*";
P_HTM[1516]="*Yāpetāyasmā channo, yāpentaṃ mayaṃ āyasmantaṃ channaṃ icchāma.**Venerable Channa, keep going! We want you to keep going.*";
P_HTM[1517]="*Sace āyasmato channassa natthi sappāyāni bhojanāni, ahaṃ āyasmato channassa sappāyāni bhojanāni pariyesissāmi.**If you don’t have any suitable food, we’ll find it for you.*";
P_HTM[1518]="*Sace āyasmato channassa natthi sappāyāni bhesajjāni, ahaṃ āyasmato channassa sappāyāni bhesajjāni pariyesissāmi.**If you don’t have suitable medicine, we’ll find it for you.*";
P_HTM[1519]="*Sace āyasmato channassa natthi patirūpā upaṭṭhākā, ahaṃ āyasmantaṃ channaṃ upaṭṭhahissāmi.**If you don’t have a capable carer, we’ll find one for you.*";
P_HTM[1520]="*Mā āyasmā channo satthaṃ āharesi.**Please don’t slit your wrists!*";
P_HTM[1521]="*Yāpetāyasmā channo, yāpentaṃ mayaṃ āyasmantaṃ channaṃ icchāmā”ti.**Venerable Channa, keep going! We want you to keep going.”*";
P_HTM[1522]="*“Na me, āvuso sāriputta, natthi sappāyāni bhojanāni;**“Reverend Sāriputta, it’s not that I don’t have suitable food;*";
P_HTM[1523]="*atthi me sappāyāni bhojanāni.**I do have suitable food.*";
P_HTM[1524]="*Napi me natthi sappāyāni bhesajjāni;**It’s not that I don’t have suitable medicine;*";
P_HTM[1525]="*atthi me sappāyāni bhesajjāni.**I do have suitable medicine.*";
P_HTM[1526]="*Napi me natthi patirūpā upaṭṭhākā;**It’s not that I don’t have a capable carer;*";
P_HTM[1527]="*atthi me patirūpā upaṭṭhākā.**I do have a capable carer.*";
P_HTM[1528]="*Api ca me, āvuso, satthā pariciṇṇo dīgharattaṃ manāpeneva, no amanāpena.**Moreover, for a long time now I have served the Teacher with love, not without love.*";
P_HTM[1529]="*Etañhi, āvuso, sāvakassa patirūpaṃ yaṃ satthāraṃ paricareyya manāpeneva, no amanāpena.**For it is proper for a disciple to serve the Teacher with love, not without love.*";
P_HTM[1530]="*‘Anupavajjaṃ channo bhikkhu satthaṃ āharissatī’ti—evametaṃ, āvuso sāriputta, dhārehī”ti.**You should remember this: ‘The mendicant Channa slit his wrists blamelessly.’”*";
P_HTM[1531]="*“Puccheyyāma mayaṃ āyasmantaṃ channaṃ kañcideva desaṃ, sace āyasmā channo okāsaṃ karoti pañhassa veyyākaraṇāyā”ti.**“I’d like to ask Venerable Channa about a certain point, if you’d take the time to answer.”*";
P_HTM[1532]="*“Pucchāvuso sāriputta, sutvā vedissāmā”ti.**“Ask, Reverend Sāriputta. When I’ve heard it I’ll know.”*";
P_HTM[1533]="*“Cakkhuṃ, āvuso channa, cakkhuviññāṇaṃ cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’ti samanupassasi … pe …**“Reverend Channa, do you regard the eye, eye consciousness, and things knowable by eye consciousness in this way: ‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?*";
P_HTM[1534]="*jivhaṃ, āvuso channa, jivhāviññāṇaṃ jivhāviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’ti samanupassasi … pe …**Do you regard the ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[1535]="*manaṃ, āvuso channa, manoviññāṇaṃ manoviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’ti samanupassasī”ti?**mind, mind consciousness, and things knowable by mind consciousness in this way: ‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1536]="*“Cakkhuṃ, āvuso sāriputta, cakkhuviññāṇaṃ cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassāmi … pe …**“Reverend Sāriputta, I regard the eye, eye consciousness, and things knowable by eye consciousness in this way: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self.’*";
P_HTM[1537]="*jivhaṃ, āvuso sāriputta, jivhāviññāṇaṃ jivhāviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassāmi … pe …**I regard the ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[1538]="*manaṃ, āvuso sāriputta, manoviññāṇaṃ manoviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassāmī”ti.**mind, mind consciousness, and things knowable by mind consciousness in this way: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self’.”*";
P_HTM[1539]="*“Cakkhusmiṃ, āvuso channa, cakkhuviññāṇe cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbesu dhammesu kiṃ disvā kiṃ abhiññāya cakkhuṃ cakkhuviññāṇaṃ cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassasi …**“Reverend Channa, what have you seen, what have you directly known in these things that you regard them in this way: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1540]="*jivhāya, āvuso channa, jivhāviññāṇe jivhāviññāṇaviññātabbesu dhammesu kiṃ disvā kiṃ abhiññāya jivhaṃ jivhāviññāṇaṃ jivhāviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassasi …* **";
P_HTM[1541]="*manasmiṃ, āvuso channa, manoviññāṇe manoviññāṇaviññātabbesu dhammesu kiṃ disvā kiṃ abhiññāya manaṃ manoviññāṇaṃ manoviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassasī”ti?* **";
P_HTM[1542]="*“Cakkhusmiṃ, āvuso sāriputta, cakkhuviññāṇe cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbesu dhammesu nirodhaṃ disvā nirodhaṃ abhiññāya cakkhuṃ cakkhuviññāṇaṃ cakkhuviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassāmi … pe …**“Reverend Sāriputta, after seeing cessation, after directly knowing cessation in these things I regard them in this way: ‘This is not mine, I am not this, this is not my self’.”*";
P_HTM[1543]="*jivhāya, āvuso sāriputta, jivhāviññāṇe jivhāviññāṇaviññātabbesu dhammesu nirodhaṃ disvā nirodhaṃ abhiññāya jivhaṃ jivhāviññāṇaṃ jivhāviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassāmi … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1544]="*manasmiṃ, āvuso sāriputta, manoviññāṇe manoviññāṇaviññātabbesu dhammesu nirodhaṃ disvā nirodhaṃ abhiññāya manaṃ manoviññāṇaṃ manoviññāṇaviññātabbe dhamme ‘netaṃ mama, nesohamasmi, na meso attā’ti samanupassāmī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1545]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā mahācundo āyasmantaṃ channaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Venerable Mahācunda said to Venerable Channa,*";
P_HTM[1546]="*“tasmātiha, āvuso channa, idampi tassa bhagavato sāsanaṃ niccakappaṃ sādhukaṃ manasi kātabbaṃ:**“So, Reverend Channa, you should pay close attention to this instruction of the Buddha whenever you can:*";
P_HTM[1547]="*‘nissitassa calitaṃ, anissitassa calitaṃ natthi.**‘For the dependent there is agitation. For the independent there’s no agitation.*";
P_HTM[1548]="*Calite asati passaddhi hoti.**When there’s no agitation there is tranquility.*";
P_HTM[1549]="*Passaddhiyā sati nati na hoti.**When there’s tranquility there’s no inclination.*";
P_HTM[1550]="*Natiyā asati āgatigati na hoti.**When there’s no inclination, there’s no coming and going.*";
P_HTM[1551]="*Āgatigatiyā asati cutūpapāto na hoti.**When there’s no coming and going, there’s no passing away and reappearing.*";
P_HTM[1552]="*Cutūpapāte asati nevidha na huraṃ na ubhayamantarena.**When there’s no passing away and reappearing, there’s no this world or world beyond or between the two.*";
P_HTM[1553]="*Esevanto dukkhassā’”ti.**Just this is the end of suffering.’”*";
P_HTM[1554]="*Atha kho āyasmā ca sāriputto āyasmā ca mahācundo āyasmantaṃ channaṃ iminā ovādena ovaditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkamiṃsu.**And when the venerables Sāriputta and Mahācunda had given Venerable Channa this advice they got up from their seat and left.*";
P_HTM[1555]="*Atha kho āyasmā channo acirapakkantesu tesu āyasmantesu satthaṃ āharesi.**Not long after those venerables had left, Venerable Channa slit his wrists.*";
P_HTM[1556]="*Atha kho āyasmā sāriputto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā sāriputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Sāriputta went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1557]="*“āyasmatā, bhante, channena satthaṃ āharitaṃ.**“Sir, Venerable Channa has slit his wrists.*";
P_HTM[1558]="*Tassa kā gati ko abhisamparāyo”ti?**Where has he been reborn in his next life?”*";
P_HTM[1559]="*“Nanu te, sāriputta, channena bhikkhunā sammukhāyeva anupavajjatā byākatā”ti?**“Sāriputta, didn’t the mendicant Channa declare his blamelessness to you personally?”*";
P_HTM[1560]="*“Atthi, bhante, pubbavijjanaṃ nāma vajjigāmo.**“Sir, there is a Vajjian village named Pubbavijjhana*";
P_HTM[1561]="*Tatthāyasmato channassa mittakulāni suhajjakulāni upavajjakulānī”ti.**where Channa had families with whom he was friendly, intimate, and familiar.”*";
P_HTM[1562]="*“Honti hete, sāriputta, channassa bhikkhuno mittakulāni suhajjakulāni upavajjakulāni.**“The mendicant Channa did indeed have such families.*";
P_HTM[1563]="*Na kho panāhaṃ, sāriputta, ettāvatā saupavajjoti vadāmi.**But this is not enough for me to call someone ‘blameworthy’.*";
P_HTM[1564]="*Yo kho, sāriputta, tañca kāyaṃ nikkhipati, aññañca kāyaṃ upādiyati, tamahaṃ saupavajjoti vadāmi.**When someone lays down this body and takes up another body, I call them ‘blameworthy’.*";
P_HTM[1565]="*Taṃ channassa bhikkhuno natthi.**But the mendicant Channa did no such thing.*";
P_HTM[1566]="*‘Anupavajjaṃ channena bhikkhunā satthaṃ āharitan’ti—**You should remember this: ‘The mendicant Channa slit his wrists blamelessly.’”*";
P_HTM[1567]="*evametaṃ, sāriputta, dhārehī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1568]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1569]="*5. Puṇṇasuttaṃ**With Puṇṇa*";
P_HTM[1570]="*Atha kho āyasmā puṇṇo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā puṇṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**And then Venerable Puṇṇa went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1571]="*“sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā saṃkhittena dhammaṃ desetu, yamahaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[1572]="*“Santi kho, puṇṇa, cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**“Puṇṇa, there are sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[1573]="*Tañce bhikkhu abhinandati abhivadati ajjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**If a mendicant approves, welcomes, and keeps clinging to them,*";
P_HTM[1574]="*Tassa taṃ abhinandato abhivadato ajjhosāya tiṭṭhato uppajjati nandī.**this gives rise to relishing.*";
P_HTM[1575]="*‘Nandisamudayā dukkhasamudayo, puṇṇā’ti vadāmi … pe …**Relishing is the origin of suffering, I say.*";
P_HTM[1576]="*santi kho, puṇṇa, jivhāviññeyyā rasā … pe …**There are sounds … smells … tastes … touches …*";
P_HTM[1577]="*santi kho, puṇṇa, manoviññeyyā dhammā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**There are thoughts known by the mind that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[1578]="*Tañce bhikkhu abhinandati abhivadati ajjhosāya tiṭṭhati.**If a mendicant approves, welcomes, and keeps clinging to them,*";
P_HTM[1579]="*Tassa taṃ abhinandato abhivadato ajjhosāya tiṭṭhato uppajjati nandī.**this gives rise to relishing.*";
P_HTM[1580]="*‘Nandisamudayā dukkhasamudayo, puṇṇā’ti vadāmi.**Relishing is the origin of suffering, I say.*";
P_HTM[1581]="*Santi kho, puṇṇa, cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**There are sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[1582]="*Tañce bhikkhu nābhinandati nābhivadati nājjhosāya tiṭṭhati, tassa taṃ anabhinandato anabhivadato anajjhosāya tiṭṭhato nirujjhati nandī.**If a mendicant doesn’t approve, welcome, and keep clinging to them, relishing ceases.*";
P_HTM[1583]="*‘Nandinirodhā dukkhanirodho, puṇṇā’ti vadāmi … pe …**When relishing ceases, suffering ceases, I say. …*";
P_HTM[1584]="*santi kho, puṇṇa, manoviññeyyā dhammā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**There are thoughts known by the mind that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[1585]="*Tañce bhikkhu nābhinandati nābhivadati nājjhosāya tiṭṭhati, tassa taṃ anabhinandato anabhivadato anajjhosāya tiṭṭhato nirujjhati nandī.**If a mendicant doesn’t approve, welcome, and keep clinging to them, relishing ceases.*";
P_HTM[1586]="*‘Nandinirodhā dukkhanirodho, puṇṇā’ti vadāmi.**When relishing ceases, suffering ceases, I say.*";
P_HTM[1587]="*Iminā tvaṃ, puṇṇa, mayā saṃkhittena ovādena ovadito katamasmiṃ janapade viharissasī”ti?**Puṇṇa, now that I’ve given you this brief advice, what country will you live in?”*";
P_HTM[1588]="*“Atthi, bhante, sunāparanto nāma janapado, tatthāhaṃ viharissāmī”ti.**“Sir, there’s a country called Sunāparanta; I will live there.”*";
P_HTM[1589]="*“Caṇḍā kho, puṇṇa, sunāparantakā manussā;**“The people of Sunāparanta are wild and rough, Puṇṇa.*";
P_HTM[1590]="*pharusā kho, puṇṇa, sunāparantakā manussā.* **";
P_HTM[1591]="*Sace taṃ, puṇṇa, sunāparantakā manussā akkosissanti paribhāsissanti, tatra te, puṇṇa, kinti bhavissatī”ti?**If they abuse and insult you, what will you think of them?”*";
P_HTM[1592]="*“Sace maṃ, bhante, sunāparantakā manussā akkosissanti paribhāsissanti, tatra me evaṃ bhavissati:**“If they abuse and insult me, I will think:*";
P_HTM[1593]="*‘bhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, subhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, yaṃ me nayime pāṇinā pahāraṃ dentī’ti.**‘These people of Sunāparanta are gracious, truly gracious, since they don’t hit me with their fists.’*";
P_HTM[1594]="*Evamettha, bhagavā, bhavissati;**That’s what I’ll think, Blessed One.*";
P_HTM[1595]="*evamettha, sugata, bhavissatī”ti.**That’s what I’ll think, Holy One.”*";
P_HTM[1596]="*“Sace pana te, puṇṇa, sunāparantakā manussā pāṇinā pahāraṃ dassanti, tatra pana te, puṇṇa, kinti bhavissatī”ti?**“But if they do hit you with their fists, what will you think of them then?”*";
P_HTM[1597]="*“Sace me, bhante, sunāparantakā manussā pāṇinā pahāraṃ dassanti, tatra me evaṃ bhavissati:**“If they hit me with their fists, I’ll think:*";
P_HTM[1598]="*‘bhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, subhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, yaṃ me nayime leḍḍunā pahāraṃ dentī’ti.**‘These people of Sunāparanta are gracious, truly gracious, since they don’t throw stones at me.’*";
P_HTM[1599]="*Evamettha, bhagavā, bhavissati;**That’s what I’ll think, Blessed One.*";
P_HTM[1600]="*evamettha, sugata, bhavissatī”ti.**That’s what I’ll think, Holy One.”*";
P_HTM[1601]="*“Sace pana te, puṇṇa, sunāparantakā manussā leḍḍunā pahāraṃ dassanti, tatra pana te, puṇṇa, kinti bhavissatī”ti?**“But if they do throw stones at you, what will you think of them then?”*";
P_HTM[1602]="*“Sace me, bhante, sunāparantakā manussā leḍḍunā pahāraṃ dassanti, tatra me evaṃ bhavissati:**“If they throw stones at me, I’ll think:*";
P_HTM[1603]="*‘bhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, subhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, yaṃ me nayime daṇḍena pahāraṃ dentī’ti.**‘These people of Sunāparanta are gracious, truly gracious, since they don’t beat me with a club.’*";
P_HTM[1604]="*Evamettha, bhagavā, bhavissati;**That’s what I’ll think, Blessed One.*";
P_HTM[1605]="*evamettha, sugata, bhavissatī”ti.**That’s what I’ll think, Holy One.”*";
P_HTM[1606]="*“Sace pana puṇṇa, sunāparantakā manussā daṇḍena pahāraṃ dassanti, tatra pana te, puṇṇa, kinti bhavissatī”ti?**“But if they do beat you with a club, what will you think of them then?”*";
P_HTM[1607]="*“Sace me, bhante, sunāparantakā manussā daṇḍena pahāraṃ dassanti, tatra me evaṃ bhavissati:**“If they beat me with a club, I’ll think:*";
P_HTM[1608]="*‘bhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, subhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, yaṃ me nayime satthena pahāraṃ dentī’ti.**‘These people of Sunāparanta are gracious, truly gracious, since they don’t stab me with a knife.’*";
P_HTM[1609]="*Evamettha, bhagavā, bhavissati;**That’s what I’ll think, Blessed One.*";
P_HTM[1610]="*evamettha, sugata, bhavissatī”ti.**That’s what I’ll think, Holy One.”*";
P_HTM[1611]="*“Sace pana te, puṇṇa, sunāparantakā manussā satthena pahāraṃ dassanti, tatra pana te, puṇṇa, kinti bhavissatī”ti?**“But if they do stab you with a knife, what will you think of them then?”*";
P_HTM[1612]="*“Sace me, bhante, sunāparantakā manussā satthena pahāraṃ dassanti, tatra me evaṃ bhavissati:**“If they stab me with a knife, I’ll think:*";
P_HTM[1613]="*‘bhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, subhaddakā vatime sunāparantakā manussā, yaṃ maṃ nayime tiṇhena satthena jīvitā voropentī’ti.**‘These people of Sunāparanta are gracious, truly gracious, since they don’t take my life with a sharp knife.’*";
P_HTM[1614]="*Evamettha, bhagavā, bhavissati;**That’s what I’ll think, Blessed One.*";
P_HTM[1615]="*evamettha, sugata, bhavissatī”ti.**That’s what I’ll think, Holy One.”*";
P_HTM[1616]="*“Sace pana taṃ, puṇṇa, sunāparantakā manussā tiṇhena satthena jīvitā voropessanti, tatra pana te, puṇṇa, kinti bhavissatī”ti?**“But if they do take your life with a sharp knife, what will you think of them then?”*";
P_HTM[1617]="*“Sace maṃ, bhante, sunāparantakā manussā tiṇhena satthena jīvitā voropessanti, tatra me evaṃ bhavissati:**“If they take my life with a sharp knife, I’ll think:*";
P_HTM[1618]="*‘santi kho tassa bhagavato sāvakā kāyena ca jīvitena ca aṭṭīyamānā harāyamānā jigucchamānā satthahārakaṃ pariyesanti, taṃ me idaṃ apariyiṭṭhaññeva satthahārakaṃ laddhan’ti.**‘There are disciples of the Buddha who looked for someone to assist with slitting their wrists because they were horrified, repelled, and disgusted with the body and with life. And I have found this without looking!’*";
P_HTM[1619]="*Evamettha, bhagavā, bhavissati;**That’s what I’ll think, Blessed One.*";
P_HTM[1620]="*evamettha, sugata, bhavissatī”ti.**That’s what I’ll think, Holy One.”*";
P_HTM[1621]="*“Sādhu sādhu, puṇṇa.**“Good, good Puṇṇa!*";
P_HTM[1622]="*Sakkhissasi kho tvaṃ, puṇṇa, iminā damūpasamena samannāgato sunāparantasmiṃ janapade vatthuṃ.**Having such self-control and peacefulness, you will be quite capable of living in Sunāparanta.*";
P_HTM[1623]="*Yassadāni tvaṃ, puṇṇa, kālaṃ maññasī”ti.**Now, Puṇṇa, go at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[1624]="*Atha kho āyasmā puṇṇo bhagavato vacanaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā senāsanaṃ saṃsāmetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena sunāparanto janapado tena cārikaṃ pakkāmi.**And then Puṇṇa welcomed and agreed with the Buddha’s words. He got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right. Then he set his lodgings in order and, taking his bowl and robe, set out for Sunāparanta.*";
P_HTM[1625]="*Anupubbena cārikaṃ caramāno yena sunāparanto janapado tadavasari.**Traveling stage by stage, he arrived at Sunāparanta,*";
P_HTM[1626]="*Tatra sudaṃ āyasmā puṇṇo sunāparantasmiṃ janapade viharati.**and stayed there.*";
P_HTM[1627]="*Atha kho āyasmā puṇṇo tenevantaravassena pañcamattāni upāsakasatāni paṭivedesi.**Within that rainy season he confirmed around five hundred male and five hundred female lay followers. And within that same rainy season he realized the three knowledges.*";
P_HTM[1628]="*Tenevantaravassena pañcamattāni upāsikāsatāni paṭivedesi.* **";
P_HTM[1629]="*Tenevantaravassena tisso vijjā sacchākāsi.* **";
P_HTM[1630]="*Tenevantaravassena parinibbāyi.**And within that same rainy season he became completely extinguished.*";
P_HTM[1631]="*Atha kho sambahulā bhikkhū yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then several mendicants went up to the Buddha … and asked him,*";
P_HTM[1632]="*“yo so, bhante, puṇṇo nāma kulaputto bhagavatā saṅkhittena ovādena ovadito, so kālaṅkato.**“Sir, the gentleman named Puṇṇa, who was advised in brief by the Buddha, has passed away.*";
P_HTM[1633]="*Tassa kā gati ko abhisamparāyo”ti?**Where has he been reborn in his next life?”*";
P_HTM[1634]="*“Paṇḍito, bhikkhave, puṇṇo kulaputto, paccapādi dhammassānudhammaṃ, na ca maṃ dhammādhikaraṇaṃ vihesesi.**“Mendicants, Puṇṇa was astute. He practiced in line with the teachings, and did not trouble me about the teachings.*";
P_HTM[1635]="*Parinibbuto, bhikkhave, puṇṇo kulaputto”ti.**Puṇṇa has become completely extinguished.”*";
P_HTM[1636]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1637]="*6. Bāhiyasuttaṃ**With Bāhiya*";
P_HTM[1638]="*Atha kho āyasmā bāhiyo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā bāhiyo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Bāhiya went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1639]="*“sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā saṅkhittena dhammaṃ desetu, yamahaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[1640]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, bāhiya,**“What do you think, Bāhiya?*";
P_HTM[1641]="*cakkhu niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is the eye permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1642]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1643]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[1644]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1645]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and liable to fall apart, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[1646]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1647]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1648]="*“Rūpā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?**“Are sights …*";
P_HTM[1649]="*“Aniccā, bhante” … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1650]="*cakkhuviññāṇaṃ … pe …**eye consciousness …*";
P_HTM[1651]="*cakkhusamphasso … pe …**eye contact …*";
P_HTM[1652]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact: is that permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[1653]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1654]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[1655]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1656]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and liable to fall apart, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[1657]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[1658]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1659]="*“Evaṃ passaṃ, bāhiya, sutavā ariyasāvako cakkhusmimpi nibbindati, rūpesupi nibbindati, cakkhuviññāṇepi nibbindati, cakkhusamphassepi nibbindati … pe …**“Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with the eye, sights, eye consciousness, and eye contact. And they grow disillusioned with the painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact.*";
P_HTM[1660]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tasmimpi nibbindati.**They grow disillusioned with the ear … nose … tongue … body … mind … painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact.*";
P_HTM[1661]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati; vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[1662]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[1663]="*Atha kho āyasmā bāhiyo bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**And then Venerable Bāhiya approved and agreed with what the Buddha said. He got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[1664]="*Atha kho āyasmā bāhiyo eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto nacirasseva—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihāsi.**Then Bāhiya, living alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute, soon realized the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life. He lived having achieved with his own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[1665]="*“Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti abbhaññāsi.**He understood: “Rebirth is ended; the spiritual journey has been completed; what had to be done has been done; there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[1666]="*Aññataro ca panāyasmā bāhiyo arahataṃ ahosīti.**And Venerable Bāhiya became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[1667]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1668]="*7. Paṭhamaejāsuttaṃ**Turbulence (1st)*";
P_HTM[1669]="*“Ejā, bhikkhave, rogo, ejā gaṇḍo, ejā sallaṃ.**“Mendicants, turbulence is a disease, turbulence is a boil, turbulence is a dart.*";
P_HTM[1670]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, tathāgato anejo viharati vītasallo.**That’s why the Realized One lives unperturbed, with dart drawn out.*";
P_HTM[1671]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cepi ākaṅkheyya ‘anejo vihareyyaṃ vītasallo’ti,**Now, a mendicant might wish: ‘May I live unperturbed, with dart drawn out.’*";
P_HTM[1672]="*cakkhuṃ na maññeyya, cakkhusmiṃ na maññeyya, cakkhuto na maññeyya, cakkhu meti na maññeyya;**So let them not identify with the eye, let them not identify regarding the eye, let them not identify as the eye, let them not identify ‘the eye is mine.’*";
P_HTM[1673]="*rūpe na maññeyya, rūpesu na maññeyya, rūpato na maññeyya, rūpā meti na maññeyya;**Let them not identify sights …*";
P_HTM[1674]="*cakkhuviññāṇaṃ na maññeyya, cakkhuviññāṇasmiṃ na maññeyya, cakkhuviññāṇato na maññeyya, cakkhuviññāṇaṃ meti na maññeyya;**eye consciousness …*";
P_HTM[1675]="*cakkhusamphassaṃ na maññeyya, cakkhusamphassasmiṃ na maññeyya, cakkhusamphassato na maññeyya, cakkhusamphasso meti na maññeyya.**eye contact …*";
P_HTM[1676]="*Yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi na maññeyya, tasmimpi na maññeyya, tatopi na maññeyya, taṃ meti na maññeyya.**Let them not identify with the pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact. Let them not identify regarding that, let them not identify as that, and let them not identify ‘that is mine.’*";
P_HTM[1677]="*Sotaṃ na maññeyya … pe …**Let them not identify the ear …*";
P_HTM[1678]="*ghānaṃ na maññeyya … pe …**nose …*";
P_HTM[1679]="*jivhaṃ na maññeyya, jivhāya na maññeyya, jivhāto na maññeyya, jivhā meti na maññeyya;**tongue …*";
P_HTM[1680]="*rase na maññeyya … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1681]="*jivhāviññāṇaṃ na maññeyya … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1682]="*jivhāsamphassaṃ na maññeyya … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1683]="*yampidaṃ jivhāsamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi na maññeyya, tasmimpi na maññeyya, tatopi na maññeyya, taṃ meti na maññeyya.* **";
P_HTM[1684]="*Kāyaṃ na maññeyya … pe …**body …*";
P_HTM[1685]="*manaṃ na maññeyya, manasmiṃ na maññeyya, manato na maññeyya, mano meti na maññeyya;**mind …*";
P_HTM[1686]="*dhamme na maññeyya … pe …**thoughts …*";
P_HTM[1687]="*mano viññāṇaṃ … pe …**mind consciousness …*";
P_HTM[1688]="*manosamphassaṃ … pe …**mind contact …*";
P_HTM[1689]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi na maññeyya, tasmimpi na maññeyya, tatopi na maññeyya, taṃ meti na maññeyya;**Let them not identify with the pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact. Let them not identify regarding that, let them not identify as that, and let them not identify ‘that is mine.’*";
P_HTM[1690]="*sabbaṃ na maññeyya, sabbasmiṃ na maññeyya, sabbato na maññeyya, sabbaṃ meti na maññeyya.**Let them not identify with all, let them not identify regarding all, let them not identify as all, let them not identify ‘all is mine’.*";
P_HTM[1691]="*So evaṃ amaññamāno na kiñcipi loke upādiyati.**Not identifying, they don’t grasp at anything in the world.*";
P_HTM[1692]="*Anupādiyaṃ na paritassati. Aparitassaṃ paccattaññeva parinibbāyati.**Not grasping, they’re not anxious. Not being anxious, they personally become extinguished.*";
P_HTM[1693]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[1694]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1695]="*8. Dutiyaejāsuttaṃ**Turbulence (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1696]="*“Ejā, bhikkhave, rogo, ejā gaṇḍo, ejā sallaṃ.**“Mendicants, turbulence is a disease, turbulence is a boil, turbulence is a dart.*";
P_HTM[1697]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, tathāgato anejo viharati vītasallo.**That’s why the Realized One lives unperturbed, with dart drawn out.*";
P_HTM[1698]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cepi ākaṅkheyya ‘anejo vihareyyaṃ vītasallo’ti,**Now, a mendicant might wish: ‘May I live unperturbed, with dart drawn out.’*";
P_HTM[1699]="*cakkhuṃ na maññeyya, cakkhusmiṃ na maññeyya, cakkhuto na maññeyya, cakkhu meti na maññeyya;**So let them not identify with the eye, let them not identify in the eye, let them not identify from the eye, let them not identify: ‘The eye is mine.’*";
P_HTM[1700]="*rūpe na maññeyya …**Let them not identify with sights …*";
P_HTM[1701]="*cakkhuviññāṇaṃ …**eye consciousness …*";
P_HTM[1702]="*cakkhusamphassaṃ …**eye contact …*";
P_HTM[1703]="*yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi na maññeyya, tasmimpi na maññeyya, tatopi na maññeyya, taṃ meti na maññeyya.**Let them not identify with the pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact. Let them not identify in that, let them not identify from that, and let them not identify: ‘That is mine.’*";
P_HTM[1704]="*Yañhi, bhikkhave, maññati, yasmiṃ maññati, yato maññati, yaṃ meti maññati, tato taṃ hoti aññathā.**For whatever you identify with, whatever you identify in, whatever you identify as, and whatever you identify to be ‘mine’: that becomes something else.*";
P_HTM[1705]="*Aññathābhāvī bhavasatto loko bhavameva abhinandati … pe ….**The world is attached to being, taking pleasure only in being, yet it becomes something else.*";
P_HTM[1706]="*Jivhaṃ na maññeyya, jivhāya na maññeyya, jivhāto na maññeyya, jivhā meti na maññeyya;**Let them not identify with the ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[1707]="*rase na maññeyya …* **";
P_HTM[1708]="*jivhāviññāṇaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[1709]="*jivhāsamphassaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[1710]="*yampidaṃ jivhāsamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi na maññeyya, tasmimpi na maññeyya, tatopi na maññeyya, taṃ meti na maññeyya.* **";
P_HTM[1711]="*Yañhi, bhikkhave, maññati, yasmiṃ maññati, yato maññati, yaṃ meti maññati, tato taṃ hoti aññathā. Aññathābhāvī bhavasatto loko bhavameva abhinandati … pe ….* **";
P_HTM[1712]="*Manaṃ na maññeyya, manasmiṃ na maññeyya, manato na maññeyya, mano meti na maññeyya …**Let them not identify with the mind …*";
P_HTM[1713]="*manoviññāṇaṃ …**mind consciousness …*";
P_HTM[1714]="*manosamphassaṃ …**mind contact …*";
P_HTM[1715]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi na maññeyya, tasmimpi na maññeyya, tatopi na maññeyya, taṃ meti na maññeyya.**Let them not identify with the pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact. Let them not identify in that, let them not identify as that, and let them not identify: ‘That is mine.’*";
P_HTM[1716]="*Yañhi, bhikkhave, maññati, yasmiṃ maññati, yato maññati, yaṃ meti maññati, tato taṃ hoti aññathā.**For whatever you identify with, whatever you identify in, whatever you identify as, and whatever you identify to be ‘mine’: that becomes something else.*";
P_HTM[1717]="*Aññathābhāvī bhavasatto loko bhavameva abhinandati.**The world is attached to being, taking pleasure only in being, yet it becomes something else.*";
P_HTM[1718]="*Yāvatā, bhikkhave, khandhadhātuāyatanā tampi na maññeyya, tasmimpi na maññeyya, tatopi na maññeyya, taṃ meti na maññeyya.**As far as the aggregates, elements, and sense fields extend, they don’t identify with that, they don’t identify in that, they don’t identify as that, and they don’t identify: ‘That is mine.’*";
P_HTM[1719]="*So evaṃ amaññamāno na kiñci loke upādiyati.**Not identifying, they don’t grasp at anything in the world.*";
P_HTM[1720]="*Anupādiyaṃ na paritassati. Aparitassaṃ paccattaññeva parinibbāyati.**Not grasping, they’re not anxious. Not being anxious, they personally become extinguished.*";
P_HTM[1721]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[1722]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1723]="*9. Paṭhamadvayasuttaṃ**A Duality (1st)*";
P_HTM[1724]="*“Dvayaṃ vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi.**“Mendicants, I will teach you a duality.*";
P_HTM[1725]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[1726]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, dvayaṃ?**And what is a duality?*";
P_HTM[1727]="*Cakkhuñceva rūpā ca, sotañceva saddā ca, ghānañceva gandhā ca, jivhā ceva rasā ca, kāyo ceva phoṭṭhabbā ca, mano ceva dhammā ca—**It’s just the eye and sights, the ear and sounds, the nose and smells, the tongue and tastes, the body and touches, and the mind and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[1728]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, dvayaṃ.**This is called a duality.*";
P_HTM[1729]="*Yo, bhikkhave, evaṃ vadeyya:**Mendicants, suppose someone was to say:*";
P_HTM[1730]="*‘ahametaṃ dvayaṃ paccakkhāya aññaṃ dvayaṃ paññapessāmī’ti, tassa vācāvatthukamevassa.**‘I’ll reject this duality and describe another duality.’ They’d have no grounds for that,*";
P_HTM[1731]="*Puṭṭho ca na sampāyeyya.**they’d be stumped by questions, and, in addition, they’d get frustrated.*";
P_HTM[1732]="*Uttariñca vighātaṃ āpajjeyya.* **";
P_HTM[1733]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1734]="*Yathā taṃ, bhikkhave, avisayasmin”ti.**Because they’re out of their element.”*";
P_HTM[1735]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1736]="*10. Dutiyadvayasuttaṃ**A Duality (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1737]="*“Dvayaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭicca viññāṇaṃ sambhoti.**“Mendicants, consciousness exists dependent on a duality.*";
P_HTM[1738]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, dvayaṃ paṭicca viññāṇaṃ sambhoti?**And what is that duality?*";
P_HTM[1739]="*Cakkhuñca paṭicca rūpe ca uppajjati cakkhuviññāṇaṃ.**Eye consciousness arises dependent on the eye and sights.*";
P_HTM[1740]="*Cakkhu aniccaṃ vipariṇāmi aññathābhāvi.**The eye is impermanent, perishing, and changing.*";
P_HTM[1741]="*Rūpā aniccā vipariṇāmino aññathābhāvino.**Sights are impermanent, perishing, and changing.*";
P_HTM[1742]="*Itthetaṃ dvayaṃ calañceva byathañca aniccaṃ vipariṇāmi aññathābhāvi.**So this duality is tottering and toppling; it’s impermanent, perishing, and changing.*";
P_HTM[1743]="*Cakkhuviññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ vipariṇāmi aññathābhāvi.**Eye consciousness is impermanent, perishing, and changing.*";
P_HTM[1744]="*Yopi hetu yopi paccayo cakkhuviññāṇassa uppādāya, sopi hetu sopi paccayo anicco vipariṇāmī aññathābhāvī.**And the causes and conditions that give rise to eye consciousness are also impermanent, perishing, and changing.*";
P_HTM[1745]="*Aniccaṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, paccayaṃ paṭicca uppannaṃ cakkhuviññāṇaṃ kuto niccaṃ bhavissati.**But since eye consciousness has arisen dependent on conditions that are impermanent, how could it be permanent?*";
P_HTM[1746]="*Yā kho, bhikkhave, imesaṃ tiṇṇaṃ dhammānaṃ saṅgati sannipāto samavāyo, ayaṃ vuccati cakkhusamphasso.**The meeting, coming together, and joining together of these three things is called eye contact.*";
P_HTM[1747]="*Cakkhusamphassopi anicco vipariṇāmī aññathābhāvī.**Eye contact is also impermanent, perishing, and changing.*";
P_HTM[1748]="*Yopi hetu yopi paccayo cakkhusamphassassa uppādāya, sopi hetu sopi paccayo anicco vipariṇāmī aññathābhāvī.**And the causes and conditions that give rise to eye contact are also impermanent, perishing, and changing.*";
P_HTM[1749]="*Aniccaṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, paccayaṃ paṭicca uppanno cakkhusamphasso kuto nicco bhavissati.**But since eye contact has arisen dependent on conditions that are impermanent, how could it be permanent?*";
P_HTM[1750]="*Phuṭṭho, bhikkhave, vedeti, phuṭṭho ceteti, phuṭṭho sañjānāti.**Contacted, one feels, intends, and perceives.*";
P_HTM[1751]="*Itthetepi dhammā calā ceva byathā ca aniccā vipariṇāmino aññathābhāvino … pe …**So these things are tottering and toppling; they’re impermanent, perishing, and changing.*";
P_HTM[1752]="*Jivhañca paṭicca rase ca uppajjati jivhāviññāṇaṃ.**Ear consciousness … Nose consciousness … Tongue consciousness … Body consciousness …*";
P_HTM[1753]="*Jivhā aniccā vipariṇāmī aññathābhāvī.* **";
P_HTM[1754]="*Rasā aniccā vipariṇāmino aññathābhāvino.* **";
P_HTM[1755]="*Itthetaṃ dvayaṃ calañceva byathañca aniccaṃ vipariṇāmi aññathābhāvi.* **";
P_HTM[1756]="*Jivhāviññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ vipariṇāmi aññathābhāvi.* **";
P_HTM[1757]="*Yopi hetu yopi paccayo jivhāviññāṇassa uppādāya, sopi hetu sopi paccayo anicco vipariṇāmī aññathābhāvī.* **";
P_HTM[1758]="*Aniccaṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, paccayaṃ paṭicca uppannaṃ jivhāviññāṇaṃ, kuto niccaṃ bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[1759]="*Yā kho, bhikkhave, imesaṃ tiṇṇaṃ dhammānaṃ saṅgati sannipāto samavāyo, ayaṃ vuccati jivhāsamphasso.* **";
P_HTM[1760]="*Jivhāsamphassopi anicco vipariṇāmī aññathābhāvī.* **";
P_HTM[1761]="*Yopi hetu yopi paccayo jivhāsamphassassa uppādāya, sopi hetu sopi paccayo anicco vipariṇāmī aññathābhāvī.* **";
P_HTM[1762]="*Aniccaṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, paccayaṃ paṭicca uppanno jivhāsamphasso, kuto nicco bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[1763]="*Phuṭṭho, bhikkhave, vedeti, phuṭṭho ceteti, phuṭṭho sañjānāti.* **";
P_HTM[1764]="*Itthetepi dhammā calā ceva byathā ca aniccā vipariṇāmino aññathābhāvino … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1765]="*Manañca paṭicca dhamme ca uppajjati manoviññāṇaṃ.**Mind consciousness arises dependent on the mind and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[1766]="*Mano anicco vipariṇāmī aññathābhāvī.**The mind is impermanent, perishing, and changing.*";
P_HTM[1767]="*Dhammā aniccā vipariṇāmino aññathābhāvino.**Thoughts are impermanent, perishing, and changing.*";
P_HTM[1768]="*Itthetaṃ dvayaṃ calañceva byathañca aniccaṃ vipariṇāmi aññathābhāvi.**So this duality is tottering and toppling; it’s impermanent, perishing, and changing.*";
P_HTM[1769]="*Manoviññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ vipariṇāmi aññathābhāvi.**Mind consciousness is impermanent, perishing, and changing.*";
P_HTM[1770]="*Yopi hetu yopi paccayo manoviññāṇassa uppādāya, sopi hetu sopi paccayo anicco vipariṇāmī aññathābhāvī.**And the causes and conditions that give rise to mind consciousness are also impermanent, perishing, and changing.*";
P_HTM[1771]="*Aniccaṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, paccayaṃ paṭicca uppannaṃ manoviññāṇaṃ, kuto niccaṃ bhavissati.**But since mind consciousness has arisen dependent on conditions that are impermanent, how could it be permanent?*";
P_HTM[1772]="*Yā kho, bhikkhave, imesaṃ tiṇṇaṃ dhammānaṃ saṅgati sannipāto samavāyo, ayaṃ vuccati manosamphasso.**The meeting, coming together, and joining together of these three things is called mind contact.*";
P_HTM[1773]="*Manosamphassopi anicco vipariṇāmī aññathābhāvī.**Mind contact is also impermanent, perishing, and changing.*";
P_HTM[1774]="*Yopi hetu yopi paccayo manosamphassassa uppādāya, sopi hetu sopi paccayo anicco vipariṇāmī aññathābhāvī.**And the causes and conditions that give rise to mind contact are also impermanent, perishing, and changing.*";
P_HTM[1775]="*Aniccaṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, paccayaṃ paṭicca uppanno manosamphasso, kuto nicco bhavissati.**But since mind contact has arisen dependent on conditions that are impermanent, how could it be permanent?*";
P_HTM[1776]="*Phuṭṭho, bhikkhave, vedeti, phuṭṭho ceteti, phuṭṭho sañjānāti.**Contacted, one feels, intends, and perceives.*";
P_HTM[1777]="*Itthetepi dhammā calā ceva byathā ca aniccā vipariṇāmino aññathābhāvino.**So these things are tottering and toppling; they’re impermanent, perishing, and changing.*";
P_HTM[1778]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, dvayaṃ paṭicca viññāṇaṃ sambhotī”ti.**This is how consciousness exists dependent on a duality.”*";
P_HTM[1779]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1780]="*Channavaggo catuttho.* **";
P_HTM[1781]="*Palokasuññā saṅkhittaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[1782]="*channo puṇṇo ca bāhiyo;* **";
P_HTM[1783]="*Ejena ca duve vuttā,* **";
P_HTM[1784]="*dvayehi apare duveti.* **";
P_HTM[1785]="*10. Saḷavaggo**The Sixes*";
P_HTM[1786]="*1. Adantaaguttasuttaṃ**Untamed, Unguarded*";
P_HTM[1787]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1788]="*“Chayime, bhikkhave, phassāyatanā adantā aguttā arakkhitā asaṃvutā dukkhādhivāhā honti.**“Mendicants, these six fields of contact bring suffering when they’re untamed, unguarded, unprotected, and unrestrained.*";
P_HTM[1789]="*Katame cha?**What six?*";
P_HTM[1790]="*Cakkhu, bhikkhave, phassāyatanaṃ adantaṃ aguttaṃ arakkhitaṃ asaṃvutaṃ dukkhādhivāhaṃ hoti … pe …**The field of eye contact brings suffering when it’s untamed, unguarded, unprotected, and unrestrained.*";
P_HTM[1791]="*jivhā, bhikkhave, phassāyatanaṃ adantaṃ aguttaṃ arakkhitaṃ asaṃvutaṃ dukkhādhivāhaṃ hoti … pe …**The field of ear contact … nose contact … tongue contact … body contact …*";
P_HTM[1792]="*mano, bhikkhave, phassāyatanaṃ adantaṃ aguttaṃ arakkhitaṃ asaṃvutaṃ dukkhādhivāhaṃ hoti.**The field of mind contact brings suffering when it’s untamed, unguarded, unprotected, and unrestrained.*";
P_HTM[1793]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cha phassāyatanā adantā aguttā arakkhitā asaṃvutā dukkhādhivāhā honti”.**These six fields of contact bring suffering when they’re untamed, unguarded, unprotected, and unrestrained.*";
P_HTM[1794]="*Chayime, bhikkhave, phassāyatanā sudantā suguttā surakkhitā susaṃvutā sukhādhivāhā honti.**These six fields of contact bring happiness when they’re well tamed, well guarded, well protected, and well restrained.*";
P_HTM[1795]="*Katame cha?**What six?*";
P_HTM[1796]="*Cakkhu, bhikkhave, phassāyatanaṃ sudantaṃ suguttaṃ surakkhitaṃ susaṃvutaṃ sukhādhivāhaṃ hoti … pe …**The field of eye contact brings happiness when it’s well tamed, well guarded, well protected, and well restrained.*";
P_HTM[1797]="*jivhā, bhikkhave, phassāyatanaṃ sudantaṃ suguttaṃ surakkhitaṃ susaṃvutaṃ sukhādhivāhaṃ hoti … pe …**The field of ear contact … nose contact … tongue contact … body contact …*";
P_HTM[1798]="*mano, bhikkhave, phassāyatanaṃ sudantaṃ suguttaṃ surakkhitaṃ susaṃvutaṃ sukhādhivāhaṃ hoti.**The field of mind contact brings happiness when it’s well tamed, well guarded, well protected, and well restrained.*";
P_HTM[1799]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cha phassāyatanā sudantā suguttā surakkhitā susaṃvutā sukhādhivāhā hontī”ti.**These six fields of contact bring happiness when they’re well tamed, well guarded, well protected, and well restrained.”*";
P_HTM[1800]="*Idamavoca bhagavā … pe …**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1801]="*etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[1802]="*“Saḷeva phassāyatanāni bhikkhavo,**“Mendicants, it’s just the six fields of contact*";
P_HTM[1803]="*Asaṃvuto yattha dukkhaṃ nigacchati;**that lead the unrestrained to suffering.*";
P_HTM[1804]="*Tesañca ye saṃvaraṇaṃ avedisuṃ,**Those who understand how to restrain them*";
P_HTM[1805]="*Saddhādutiyā viharantānavassutā.**live with faith as partner, uncorrupted.*";
P_HTM[1806]="*Disvāna rūpāni manoramāni,**When you’ve seen pleasant sights*";
P_HTM[1807]="*Athopi disvāna amanoramāni;**and unpleasant ones, too,*";
P_HTM[1808]="*Manorame rāgapathaṃ vinodaye,**get rid of desire for the pleasant,*";
P_HTM[1809]="*Na cāppiyaṃ meti manaṃ padosaye.**without hating what you don’t like.*";
P_HTM[1810]="*Saddañca sutvā dubhayaṃ piyāppiyaṃ,**When you’ve heard sounds both liked and disliked,*";
P_HTM[1811]="*Piyamhi sadde na samucchito siyā;**don’t fall under the thrall of sounds you like,*";
P_HTM[1812]="*Athoppiye dosagataṃ vinodaye,**get rid of hate for the unliked,*";
P_HTM[1813]="*Na cāppiyaṃ meti manaṃ padosaye.**and don’t hurt your mind by thinking of what you don’t like.*";
P_HTM[1814]="*Gandhañca ghatvā surabhiṃ manoramaṃ,**When you’ve smelled a pleasant, fragrant scent,*";
P_HTM[1815]="*Athopi ghatvā asuciṃ akantiyaṃ;**and one that’s foul and unpleasant,*";
P_HTM[1816]="*Akantiyasmiṃ paṭighaṃ vinodaye,**get rid of aversion for the unpleasant,*";
P_HTM[1817]="*Chandānunīto na ca kantiye siyā.**while not yielding to desire for the pleasant.*";
P_HTM[1818]="*Rasañca bhotvāna asāditañca sāduṃ,**When you’ve enjoyed a sweet, delicious taste,*";
P_HTM[1819]="*Athopi bhotvāna asādumekadā;**and sometimes those that are bitter,*";
P_HTM[1820]="*Sāduṃ rasaṃ nājjhosāya bhuñje,**don’t be attached to enjoying sweet tastes,*";
P_HTM[1821]="*Virodhamāsādusu nopadaṃsaye.**and don’t despise the bitter.*";
P_HTM[1822]="*Phassena phuṭṭho na sukhena majje,**Don’t be intoxicated by a pleasant touch,*";
P_HTM[1823]="*Dukkhena phuṭṭhopi na sampavedhe;**and don’t tremble at a painful touch.*";
P_HTM[1824]="*Phassadvayaṃ sukhadukkhe upekkhe,**Look with equanimity at the duality of pleasant and painful contacts,*";
P_HTM[1825]="*Anānuruddho aviruddha kenaci.**without favoring or opposing anything.*";
P_HTM[1826]="*Papañcasaññā itarītarā narā,**People generally let their perceptions proliferate;*";
P_HTM[1827]="*Papañcayantā upayanti saññino;**perceiving and proliferating, they are attracted.*";
P_HTM[1828]="*Manomayaṃ gehasitañca sabbaṃ,**When you’ve dispelled all thoughts of the lay life,*";
P_HTM[1829]="*Panujja nekkhammasitaṃ irīyati.**wander intent on renunciation.*";
P_HTM[1830]="*Evaṃ mano chassu yadā subhāvito,**When the mind is well developed like this regarding the six,*";
P_HTM[1831]="*Phuṭṭhassa cittaṃ na vikampate kvaci;**it doesn’t waver at contacts at all.*";
P_HTM[1832]="*Te rāgadose abhibhuyya bhikkhavo,**Mendicants, those who have mastered greed and hate*";
P_HTM[1833]="*Bhavattha jātimaraṇassa pāragā”ti.**go beyond birth and death.”*";
P_HTM[1834]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1835]="*2. Mālukyaputtasuttaṃ**Māluṅkyaputta*";
P_HTM[1836]="*Atha kho āyasmā mālukyaputto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā mālukyaputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Māluṅkyaputta went up to the Buddha … and asked him,*";
P_HTM[1837]="*“sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā saṃkhittena dhammaṃ desetu, yamahaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[1838]="*“Ettha dāni, mālukyaputta, kiṃ dahare bhikkhū vakkhāma.**“Well now, Māluṅkyaputta, what are we to say to the young monks,*";
P_HTM[1839]="*Yatra hi nāma tvaṃ, bhikkhu, jiṇṇo vuddho mahallako addhagato vayoanuppatto saṅkhittena ovādaṃ yācasī”ti.**when even an old man like you, elderly and senior, advanced in years, having reached the final stage of life, asks the Realized One for brief advice?”*";
P_HTM[1840]="*“Kiñcāpāhaṃ, bhante, jiṇṇo vuddho mahallako addhagato vayoanuppatto.**“Sir, even though I’m an old man, elderly and senior,*";
P_HTM[1841]="*Desetu me, bhante, bhagavā saṅkhittena dhammaṃ, desetu sugato saṅkhittena dhammaṃ, appeva nāmāhaṃ bhagavato bhāsitassa atthaṃ ājāneyyaṃ. Appeva nāmāhaṃ bhagavato bhāsitassa dāyādo assan”ti.**may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief! May the Holy one please teach me in brief! Hopefully I can understand the meaning of what the Buddha says. Hopefully I can be an heir of the Buddha’s teaching!”*";
P_HTM[1842]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, mālukyaputta,**“What do you think, Māluṅkyaputta?*";
P_HTM[1843]="*ye te cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā adiṭṭhā adiṭṭhapubbā, na ca passasi, na ca te hoti passeyyanti? Atthi te tattha chando vā rāgo vā pemaṃ vā”ti?**Do you have any desire or greed or fondness for sights known by the eye that you haven’t seen, you’ve never seen before, you don’t see, and you don’t think would be seen?”*";
P_HTM[1844]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1845]="*“Ye te sotaviññeyyā saddā assutā assutapubbā, na ca suṇāsi, na ca te hoti suṇeyyanti? Atthi te tattha chando vā rāgo vā pemaṃ vā”ti?**“Do you have any desire or greed or affection for sounds known by the ear …*";
P_HTM[1846]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[1847]="*“Ye te ghānaviññeyyā gandhā aghāyitā aghāyitapubbā, na ca ghāyasi, na ca te hoti ghāyeyyanti? Atthi te tattha chando vā rāgo vā pemaṃ vā”ti?**smells known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[1848]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[1849]="*“Ye te jivhāviññeyyā rasā asāyitā asāyitapubbā, na ca sāyasi, na ca te hoti sāyeyyanti? Atthi te tattha chando vā rāgo vā pemaṃ vā”ti?**tastes known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[1850]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[1851]="*“Ye te kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā asamphuṭṭhā asamphuṭṭhapubbā, na ca phusasi, na ca te hoti phuseyyanti? Atthi te tattha chando vā rāgo vā pemaṃ vā”ti?**touches known by the body …*";
P_HTM[1852]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[1853]="*“Ye te manoviññeyyā dhammā aviññātā aviññātapubbā, na ca vijānāsi, na ca te hoti vijāneyyanti? Atthi te tattha chando vā rāgo vā pemaṃ vā”ti?**thoughts known by the mind that you haven’t known, you’ve never known before, you don’t know, and you don’t think would be known?”*";
P_HTM[1854]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1855]="*“Ettha ca te, mālukyaputta, diṭṭhasutamutaviññātabbesu dhammesu diṭṭhe diṭṭhamattaṃ bhavissati, sute sutamattaṃ bhavissati, mute mutamattaṃ bhavissati, viññāte viññātamattaṃ bhavissati.**“In that case, when it comes to things that are to be seen, heard, thought, and known: in the seen will be merely the seen; in the heard will be merely the heard; in the thought will be merely the thought; in the known will be merely the known.*";
P_HTM[1856]="*Yato kho te, mālukyaputta, diṭṭhasutamutaviññātabbesu dhammesu diṭṭhe diṭṭhamattaṃ bhavissati, sute sutamattaṃ bhavissati, mute mutamattaṃ bhavissati, viññāte viññātamattaṃ bhavissati;**When this is the case,*";
P_HTM[1857]="*tato tvaṃ, mālukyaputta, na tena.**you won’t be ‘by that’.*";
P_HTM[1858]="*Yato tvaṃ, mālukyaputta, na tena;**When you’re not ‘by that’,*";
P_HTM[1859]="*tato tvaṃ, mālukyaputta, na tattha.**you won’t be ‘in that’.*";
P_HTM[1860]="*Yato tvaṃ, mālukyaputta, na tattha;**When you’re not ‘in that’,*";
P_HTM[1861]="*tato tvaṃ, mālukyaputta, nevidha, na huraṃ, na ubhayamantarena.**you won’t be in this world or the world beyond or in between the two.*";
P_HTM[1862]="*Esevanto dukkhassā”ti.**Just this is the end of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[1863]="*“Imassa khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmi:**“This is how I understand the detailed meaning of the Buddha’s brief statement:*";
P_HTM[1864]="*‘Rūpaṃ disvā sati muṭṭhā,**‘When you see a sight, mindfulness is lost*";
P_HTM[1865]="*Piyaṃ nimittaṃ manasi karoto;**as attention latches on a pleasant feature.*";
P_HTM[1866]="*Sārattacitto vedeti,**Experiencing it with a mind full of desire,*";
P_HTM[1867]="*Tañca ajjhosa tiṭṭhati.**you keep clinging to it.*";
