P_HTM[2009]="*Atha kho āyasmā mālukyaputto bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**And then Venerable Māluṅkyaputta approved and agreed with what the Buddha said. He got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[2010]="*Atha kho āyasmā mālukyaputto eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto nacirasseva—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihāsi.**Then Māluṅkyaputta, living alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute, soon realized the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life. He lived having achieved with his own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[2011]="*“Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti abbhaññāsi.**He understood: “Rebirth is ended; the spiritual journey has been completed; what had to be done has been done; there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[2012]="*Aññataro ca panāyasmā mālukyaputto arahataṃ ahosīti.**And Venerable Māluṅkyaputta became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[2013]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2014]="*3. Parihānadhammasuttaṃ**Liable to Decline*";
P_HTM[2015]="*“Parihānadhammañca vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi aparihānadhammañca cha ca abhibhāyatanāni.**“Mendicants, I will teach you who is liable to decline, who is not liable to decline, and the six fields of mastery.*";
P_HTM[2016]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[2017]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, parihānadhammo hoti?**And how is someone liable to decline?*";
P_HTM[2018]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā sarasaṅkappā saṃyojaniyā.**When a mendicant sees a sight with the eye, bad, unskillful phenomena arise: memories and thoughts prone to fetters.*";
P_HTM[2019]="*Tañce bhikkhu adhivāseti nappajahati na vinodeti na byantīkaroti na anabhāvaṃ gameti, veditabbametaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā:**Suppose that mendicant tolerates them and doesn’t give them up, get rid of them, eliminate them, and obliterate them. They should understand:*";
P_HTM[2020]="*‘parihāyāmi kusalehi dhammehi’.**‘My skillful qualities are declining.*";
P_HTM[2021]="*Parihānañhetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatāti … pe ….**For this is what the Buddha calls decline.’*";
P_HTM[2022]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā uppajjanti … pe …**Furthermore, when a mendicant hears a sound … smells an odor … tastes a flavor … feels a touch …*";
P_HTM[2023]="*puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno manasā dhammaṃ viññāya uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā sarasaṅkappā saṃyojaniyā.**knows a thought with the mind, bad, unskillful phenomena arise: memories and thoughts prone to fetters.*";
P_HTM[2024]="*Tañce bhikkhu adhivāseti nappajahati na vinodeti na byantīkaroti na anabhāvaṃ gameti, veditabbametaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā:**If that mendicant tolerates them and doesn’t give them up, get rid of them, eliminate them, and obliterate them, they should understand:*";
P_HTM[2025]="*‘parihāyāmi kusalehi dhammehi’.**‘My skillful qualities are declining.*";
P_HTM[2026]="*Parihānañhetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatāti.**For this is what the Buddha calls decline.’*";
P_HTM[2027]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, parihānadhammo hoti.**That’s how someone is liable to decline.*";
P_HTM[2028]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, aparihānadhammo hoti?**And how is someone not liable to decline?*";
P_HTM[2029]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā sarasaṅkappā saṃyojaniyā.**When a mendicant sees a sight with the eye, bad, unskillful phenomena arise: memories and thoughts prone to fetters.*";
P_HTM[2030]="*Tañce bhikkhu nādhivāseti pajahati vinodeti byantīkaroti anabhāvaṃ gameti, veditabbametaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā:**Suppose that mendicant doesn’t tolerate them but gives them up, gets rid of them, eliminates them, and obliterates them. They should understand:*";
P_HTM[2031]="*‘na parihāyāmi kusalehi dhammehi’.**‘My skillful qualities are not declining.*";
P_HTM[2032]="*Aparihānañhetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatāti … pe ….**For this is what the Buddha calls non-decline.’*";
P_HTM[2033]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā uppajjanti … pe …**Furthermore, when a mendicant hears a sound … smells an odor … tastes a flavor … feels a touch …*";
P_HTM[2034]="*puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno manasā dhammaṃ viññāya uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā sarasaṅkappā saṃyojaniyā.**knows a thought with the mind, bad, unskillful phenomena arise: memories and thoughts prone to fetters.*";
P_HTM[2035]="*Tañce bhikkhu nādhivāseti pajahati vinodeti byantīkaroti anabhāvaṃ gameti, veditabbametaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā:**Suppose that mendicant doesn’t tolerate them but gives them up, gets rid of them, eliminates them, and obliterates them. They should understand:*";
P_HTM[2036]="*‘na parihāyāmi kusalehi dhammehi’.**‘My skillful qualities are not declining.*";
P_HTM[2037]="*Aparihānañhetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatāti.**For this is what the Buddha calls non-decline.’*";
P_HTM[2038]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, aparihānadhammo hoti.**That’s how someone is not liable to decline.*";
P_HTM[2039]="*Katamāni ca, bhikkhave, cha abhibhāyatanāni?**And what are the six fields of mastery?*";
P_HTM[2040]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā nuppajjanti pāpakā akusalā sarasaṅkappā saṃyojaniyā.**When a mendicant sees a sight with the eye, bad, unskillful phenomena don’t arise: memories and thoughts prone to fetters.*";
P_HTM[2041]="*Veditabbametaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā:**They should understand:*";
P_HTM[2042]="*‘abhibhūtametaṃ āyatanaṃ’.**‘This sense field has been mastered.*";
P_HTM[2043]="*Abhibhāyatanañhetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatāti … pe …**For this is what the Buddha calls a field of mastery.’ …*";
P_HTM[2044]="*puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno manasā dhammaṃ viññāya nuppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā sarasaṅkappā saṃyojaniyā.**Furthermore, when a mendicant knows a thought with the mind, bad, unskillful phenomena don’t arise: memories and thoughts prone to fetters.*";
P_HTM[2045]="*Veditabbametaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā:**They should understand:*";
P_HTM[2046]="*‘abhibhūtametaṃ āyatanaṃ’.**‘This sense field has been mastered.*";
P_HTM[2047]="*Abhibhāyatanañhetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatāti.**For this is what the Buddha calls a field of mastery.’*";
P_HTM[2048]="*Imāni vuccanti, bhikkhave, cha abhibhāyatanānī”ti.**These are the six fields of mastery.”*";
P_HTM[2049]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2050]="*4. Pamādavihārīsuttaṃ**One Who Lives Negligently*";
P_HTM[2051]="*“Pamādavihāriñca vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi appamādavihāriñca.**“Mendicants, I will teach you who lives negligently and who lives diligently.*";
P_HTM[2052]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[2053]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, pamādavihārī hoti?**And how does someone live negligently?*";
P_HTM[2054]="*Cakkhundriyaṃ asaṃvutassa, bhikkhave, viharato cittaṃ byāsiñcati cakkhuviññeyyesu rūpesu.**When you live with the eye faculty unrestrained, your mind becomes polluted when it comes to sights known by the eye.*";
P_HTM[2055]="*tassa byāsittacittassa pāmojjaṃ na hoti.**When the mind is polluted, there’s no joy.*";
P_HTM[2056]="*Pāmojje asati pīti na hoti.**When there’s no joy, there’s no rapture.*";
P_HTM[2057]="*Pītiyā asati passaddhi na hoti.**When there’s no rapture, there’s no tranquility.*";
P_HTM[2058]="*Passaddhiyā asati dukkhaṃ hoti.**When there’s no tranquility, there’s suffering.*";
P_HTM[2059]="*Dukkhino cittaṃ na samādhiyati.**When one is suffering, the mind does not become immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[2060]="*Asamāhite citte dhammā na pātubhavanti.**When the mind is not immersed in samādhi, principles do not become clear.*";
P_HTM[2061]="*Dhammānaṃ apātubhāvā pamādavihārītveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati … pe …**Because principles have not become clear, you’re considered to live negligently.*";
P_HTM[2062]="*jivhindriyaṃ asaṃvutassa, bhikkhave, viharato cittaṃ byāsiñcati jivhāviññeyyesu rasesu,**When you live with the ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[2063]="*tassa byāsittacittassa … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2064]="*pamādavihārītveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2065]="*manindriyaṃ asaṃvutassa, bhikkhave, viharato cittaṃ byāsiñcati manoviññeyyesu dhammesu,**mind faculty unrestrained, your mind becomes polluted when it comes to thoughts known by the mind.*";
P_HTM[2066]="*tassa byāsittacittassa pāmojjaṃ na hoti.**When the mind is polluted, there’s no joy.*";
P_HTM[2067]="*Pāmojje asati pīti na hoti.**When there’s no joy, there’s no rapture.*";
P_HTM[2068]="*Pītiyā asati passaddhi na hoti.**When there’s no rapture, there’s no tranquility.*";
P_HTM[2069]="*Passaddhiyā asati dukkhaṃ hoti.**When there’s no tranquility, there’s suffering.*";
P_HTM[2070]="*Dukkhino cittaṃ na samādhiyati.**When one is suffering, the mind does not become immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[2071]="*Asamāhite citte dhammā na pātubhavanti.**When the mind is not immersed in samādhi, principles do not become clear.*";
P_HTM[2072]="*Dhammānaṃ apātubhāvā pamādavihārītveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**Because principles have not become clear, you’re considered to live negligently.*";
P_HTM[2073]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pamādavihārī hoti.**That’s how someone lives negligently.*";
P_HTM[2074]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, appamādavihārī hoti?**And how does someone live diligently?*";
P_HTM[2075]="*Cakkhundriyaṃ saṃvutassa, bhikkhave, viharato cittaṃ na byāsiñcati cakkhuviññeyyesu rūpesu,**When you live with the eye faculty restrained, your mind doesn’t become polluted when it comes to sights known by the eye.*";
P_HTM[2076]="*tassa abyāsittacittassa pāmojjaṃ jāyati.**When the mind isn’t polluted, joy springs up.*";
P_HTM[2077]="*Pamuditassa pīti jāyati.**Being joyful, rapture springs up.*";
P_HTM[2078]="*Pītimanassa kāyo passambhati.**When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil.*";
P_HTM[2079]="*Passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ viharati.**When the body is tranquil, one feels bliss.*";
P_HTM[2080]="*Sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[2081]="*Samāhite citte dhammā pātubhavanti.**When the mind is immersed in samādhi, principles become clear.*";
P_HTM[2082]="*Dhammānaṃ pātubhāvā appamādavihārītveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati … pe …**Because principles have become clear, you’re considered to live diligently.*";
P_HTM[2083]="*jivhindriyaṃ saṃvutassa, bhikkhave, viharato cittaṃ na byāsiñcati … pe …**When you live with the ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[2084]="*appamādavihārītveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati.* **";
P_HTM[2085]="*Manindriyaṃ saṃvutassa, bhikkhave, viharato cittaṃ na byāsiñcati, manoviññeyyesu dhammesu,**mind faculty restrained, your mind doesn’t become polluted when it comes to thoughts known by the mind.*";
P_HTM[2086]="*tassa abyāsittacittassa pāmojjaṃ jāyati.**When the mind isn’t polluted, joy springs up.*";
P_HTM[2087]="*Pamuditassa pīti jāyati.**Being joyful, rapture springs up.*";
P_HTM[2088]="*Pītimanassa kāyo passambhati.**When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil.*";
P_HTM[2089]="*Passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ viharati.**When the body is tranquil, one feels bliss.*";
P_HTM[2090]="*Sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[2091]="*Samāhite citte dhammā pātubhavanti.**When the mind is immersed in samādhi, principles become clear.*";
P_HTM[2092]="*Dhammānaṃ pātubhāvā appamādavihārītveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**Because principles have become clear, you’re considered to live diligently.*";
P_HTM[2093]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, appamādavihārī hotī”ti.**That’s how someone lives diligently.”*";
P_HTM[2094]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2095]="*5. Saṃvarasuttaṃ**Restraint*";
P_HTM[2096]="*“Saṃvarañca vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi, asaṃvarañca.**“Mendicants, I will teach you who is restrained and who is unrestrained.*";
P_HTM[2097]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[2098]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, asaṃvaro hoti?**And how is someone unrestrained?*";
P_HTM[2099]="*Santi, bhikkhave, cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**There are sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[2100]="*Tañce bhikkhu abhinandati abhivadati ajjhosāya tiṭṭhati, veditabbametaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā:**If a mendicant approves, welcomes, and keeps clinging to them, they should understand:*";
P_HTM[2101]="*‘parihāyāmi kusalehi dhammehi.**‘My skillful qualities are declining.*";
P_HTM[2102]="*Parihānañhetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā’ti … pe …**For this is what the Buddha calls decline.’*";
P_HTM[2103]="*santi, bhikkhave, jivhāviññeyyā rasā … pe …**There are sounds … smells … tastes … touches …*";
P_HTM[2104]="*santi, bhikkhave, manoviññeyyā dhammā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**thoughts known by the mind that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[2105]="*Tañce bhikkhu abhinandati abhivadati ajjhosāya tiṭṭhati, veditabbametaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā:**If a mendicant approves, welcomes, and keeps clinging to them, they should understand:*";
P_HTM[2106]="*‘parihāyāmi kusalehi dhammehi.**‘My skillful qualities are declining.*";
P_HTM[2107]="*Parihānañhetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā’ti.**For this is what the Buddha calls decline.’*";
P_HTM[2108]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, asaṃvaro hoti.**This is how someone is unrestrained.*";
P_HTM[2109]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, saṃvaro hoti?**And how is someone restrained?*";
P_HTM[2110]="*Santi, bhikkhave, cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**There are sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[2111]="*Tañce bhikkhu nābhinandati nābhivadati nājjhosāya tiṭṭhati, veditabbametaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhunā:**If a mendicant doesn’t approve, welcome, and keep clinging to them, they should understand:*";
P_HTM[2112]="*‘na parihāyāmi kusalehi dhammehi.**‘My skillful qualities are not declining.*";
P_HTM[2113]="*Aparihānañhetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā’ti … pe …**For this is what the Buddha calls non-decline.’*";
P_HTM[2114]="*santi, bhikkhave, jivhāviññeyyā rasā … pe …**There are sounds … smells … tastes … touches …*";
P_HTM[2115]="*santi, bhikkhave, manoviññeyyā dhammā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**thoughts known by the mind that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[2116]="*Tañce bhikkhu nābhinandati nābhivadati nājjhosāya tiṭṭhati, veditabbametaṃ bhikkhunā:**If a mendicant doesn’t approve, welcome, and keep clinging to them, they should understand:*";
P_HTM[2117]="*‘na parihāyāmi kusalehi dhammehi.**‘My skillful qualities are not declining.*";
P_HTM[2118]="*Aparihānañhetaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā’ti.**For this is what the Buddha calls non-decline.’*";
P_HTM[2119]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, saṃvaro hotī”ti.**This is how someone is restrained.”*";
P_HTM[2120]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2121]="*6. Samādhisuttaṃ**Immersion*";
P_HTM[2122]="*“Samādhiṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvetha.**“Mendicants, develop immersion.*";
P_HTM[2123]="*Samāhito, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**A mendicant who has immersion truly understands.*";
P_HTM[2124]="*Kiñca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti?**What do they truly understand?*";
P_HTM[2125]="*‘Cakkhu aniccan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**They truly understand that the eye is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[2126]="*‘rūpā aniccā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**They truly understand that sights …*";
P_HTM[2127]="*‘cakkhuviññāṇaṃ aniccan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**eye consciousness …*";
P_HTM[2128]="*‘cakkhusamphasso anicco’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**eye contact …*";
P_HTM[2129]="*‘Yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti … pe …**the pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact is impermanent. …*";
P_HTM[2130]="*‘mano aniccan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand that the mind is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[2131]="*Dhammā …**They truly understand that thoughts …*";
P_HTM[2132]="*manoviññāṇaṃ …**mind consciousness …*";
P_HTM[2133]="*manosamphasso …**mind contact …*";
P_HTM[2134]="*‘yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**the pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[2135]="*Samādhiṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvetha.**Mendicants, develop immersion.*";
P_HTM[2136]="*Samāhito, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yathābhūtaṃ pajānātī”ti.**A mendicant who has immersion truly understands.”*";
P_HTM[2137]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2138]="*7. Paṭisallānasuttaṃ**Retreat*";
P_HTM[2139]="*“Paṭisallāne, bhikkhave, yogamāpajjatha.**“Mendicants, meditate in retreat.*";
P_HTM[2140]="*Paṭisallīno, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**A mendicant in retreat truly understands.*";
P_HTM[2141]="*Kiñca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti?**What do they truly understand?*";
P_HTM[2142]="*‘Cakkhu aniccan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**They truly understand that the eye is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[2143]="*‘rūpā aniccā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**They truly understand that sights …*";
P_HTM[2144]="*‘cakkhuviññāṇaṃ aniccan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**eye consciousness …*";
P_HTM[2145]="*‘cakkhusamphasso anicco’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti … pe …**eye contact …*";
P_HTM[2146]="*‘yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**the pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[2147]="*Paṭisallāne, bhikkhave, yogamāpajjatha.**Mendicants, meditate in retreat.*";
P_HTM[2148]="*Paṭisallīno, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yathābhūtaṃ pajānātī”ti.**A mendicant in retreat truly understands.”*";
P_HTM[2149]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2150]="*8. Paṭhamanatumhākaṃsuttaṃ**It’s Not Yours (1st)*";
P_HTM[2151]="*“Yaṃ, bhikkhave, na tumhākaṃ, taṃ pajahatha.**“Mendicants, give up what’s not yours.*";
P_HTM[2152]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[2153]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, na tumhākaṃ?**And what isn’t yours?*";
P_HTM[2154]="*Cakkhu, bhikkhave, na tumhākaṃ.**The eye isn’t yours: give it up.*";
P_HTM[2155]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2156]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[2157]="*Rūpā na tumhākaṃ.**Sights …*";
P_HTM[2158]="*Te pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2159]="*Te vo pahīnā hitāya sukhāya bhavissanti.* **";
P_HTM[2160]="*Cakkhuviññāṇaṃ na tumhākaṃ.**Eye consciousness …*";
P_HTM[2161]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2162]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[2163]="*Cakkhusamphasso na tumhākaṃ.**Eye contact …*";
P_HTM[2164]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2165]="*So vo pahīno hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[2166]="*Yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi na tumhākaṃ.**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact isn’t yours: give it up.*";
P_HTM[2167]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2168]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[2169]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[2170]="*Jivhā na tumhākaṃ.**The ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[2171]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2172]="*Sā vo pahīnā hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[2173]="*Rasā na tumhākaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2174]="*Te pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2175]="*Te vo pahīnā hitāya sukhāya bhavissanti.* **";
P_HTM[2176]="*Jivhāviññāṇaṃ na tumhākaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2177]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2178]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[2179]="*Jivhāsamphasso na tumhākaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2180]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2181]="*So vo pahīno hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[2182]="*Yampidaṃ jivhāsamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi na tumhākaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2183]="*Taṃ pajahatha. Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati … pe ….* **";
P_HTM[2184]="*Mano na tumhākaṃ.**The mind isn’t yours: give it up.*";
P_HTM[2185]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2186]="*So vo pahīno hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[2187]="*Dhammā na tumhākaṃ.**Thoughts …*";
P_HTM[2188]="*Te pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2189]="*Te vo pahīnā hitāya sukhāya bhavissanti.* **";
P_HTM[2190]="*Manoviññāṇaṃ na tumhākaṃ.**Mind consciousness …*";
P_HTM[2191]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2192]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[2193]="*Manosamphasso na tumhākaṃ.**Mind contact …*";
P_HTM[2194]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2195]="*So vo pahīno hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[2196]="*Yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi na tumhākaṃ.**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact isn’t yours: give it up.*";
P_HTM[2197]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2198]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[2199]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, yaṃ imasmiṃ jetavane tiṇakaṭṭhasākhāpalāsaṃ taṃ jano hareyya vā ḍaheyya vā yathāpaccayaṃ vā kareyya,**Suppose a person was to carry off the grass, sticks, branches, and leaves in this Jeta’s Grove, or burn them, or do what they want with them.*";
P_HTM[2200]="*api nu tumhākaṃ evamassa:**Would you think:*";
P_HTM[2201]="*‘amhe jano harati vā ḍahati vā yathāpaccayaṃ vā karotī’”ti?**‘This person is carrying us off, burning us, or doing what they want with us?’”*";
P_HTM[2202]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[2203]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[2204]="*“Na hi no etaṃ, bhante, attā vā attaniyaṃ vā”ti.**Because that’s neither self nor belonging to self.”*";
P_HTM[2205]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, cakkhu na tumhākaṃ.**“In the same way, the eye isn’t yours: give it up.*";
P_HTM[2206]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2207]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness. …*";
P_HTM[2208]="*Rūpā na tumhākaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[2209]="*cakkhuviññāṇaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[2210]="*cakkhusamphasso … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2211]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi na tumhākaṃ.**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact isn’t yours: give it up.*";
P_HTM[2212]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2213]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissatī”ti.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.”*";
P_HTM[2214]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2215]="*9. Dutiyanatumhākaṃsuttaṃ**It’s Not Yours (2nd)*";
P_HTM[2216]="*“Yaṃ, bhikkhave, na tumhākaṃ taṃ pajahatha.**“Mendicants, give up what’s not yours.*";
P_HTM[2217]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[2218]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, na tumhākaṃ?**And what isn’t yours?*";
P_HTM[2219]="*Cakkhu, bhikkhave, na tumhākaṃ.**The eye isn’t yours: give it up.*";
P_HTM[2220]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2221]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[2222]="*Rūpā na tumhākaṃ.**Sights …*";
P_HTM[2223]="*Te pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2224]="*Te vo pahīnā hitāya sukhāya bhavissanti.* **";
P_HTM[2225]="*Cakkhuviññāṇaṃ na tumhākaṃ.**Eye consciousness …*";
P_HTM[2226]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2227]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[2228]="*Cakkhusamphasso na tumhākaṃ.**Eye contact …*";
P_HTM[2229]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2230]="*So vo pahīno hitāya sukhāya bhavissati … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2231]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi na tumhākaṃ.**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact isn’t yours: give it up.*";
P_HTM[2232]="*Taṃ pajahatha.* **";
P_HTM[2233]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissati.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[2234]="*Yampi, bhikkhave, na tumhākaṃ, taṃ pajahatha.**Give up what’s not yours.*";
P_HTM[2235]="*Taṃ vo pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya bhavissatī”ti.**Giving it up will be for your welfare and happiness.”*";
P_HTM[2236]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2237]="*10. Udakasuttaṃ**About Uddaka*";
P_HTM[2238]="*“Udako sudaṃ, bhikkhave, rāmaputto evaṃ vācaṃ bhāsati:**“Mendicants, Uddaka, son of Rāma, used to say:*";
P_HTM[2239]="*‘idaṃ jātu vedagū, idaṃ jātu sabbajī, idaṃ jātu apalikhataṃ gaṇḍamūlaṃ palikhaṇin’ti.**‘This for sure is the knowledge master! This for sure is the conqueror of all! This for sure is the boil’s root dug out, never dug out before!’*";
P_HTM[2240]="*Taṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhave, udako rāmaputto avedagūyeva samāno ‘vedagūsmī’ti bhāsati, asabbajīyeva samāno ‘sabbajīsmī’ti bhāsati, apalikhataṃyeva gaṇḍamūlaṃ palikhataṃ me ‘gaṇḍamūlan’ti bhāsati.**Even though Uddaka, son of Rāma, was no knowledge master, he said ‘I’m a knowledge master.’ Though he was no conqueror of all, he said ‘I’m conqueror of all.’ And though the boil’s root was not dug out, he said ‘I’ve dug out the boil’s root.’*";
P_HTM[2241]="*Idha kho taṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**Here’s how a mendicant would rightly say:*";
P_HTM[2242]="*‘idaṃ jātu vedagū, idaṃ jātu sabbajī, idaṃ jātu apalikhataṃ gaṇḍamūlaṃ palikhaṇin’ti.**‘Here’s the thing: the knowledge master! Here’s the thing: the conqueror of all! Here’s the thing: the boil’s root has been dug out, which was never dug out before!’*";
P_HTM[2243]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, vedagū hoti?**And how is someone a knowledge master?*";
P_HTM[2244]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**It’s when a mendicant truly understands the six fields of contact’s origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[2245]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vedagū hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is a knowledge master.*";
P_HTM[2246]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sabbajī hoti?**And how is a mendicant a conqueror of all?*";
P_HTM[2247]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimutto hoti;**It’s when a mendicant comes to be freed by not grasping after truly understanding these six sense fields’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[2248]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sabbajī hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is a conqueror of all.*";
P_HTM[2249]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno apalikhataṃ gaṇḍamūlaṃ palikhataṃ hoti?**And how has a mendicant dug out the boil’s root, which was never dug out before?*";
P_HTM[2250]="*Gaṇḍoti kho, bhikkhave, imassetaṃ cātumahābhūtikassa kāyassa adhivacanaṃ mātāpettikasambhavassa odanakummāsūpacayassa aniccucchādanaparimaddanabhedanaviddhaṃsanadhammassa.**‘Boil’ is a term for this body made up of the four primary elements, produced by mother and father, built up from rice and porridge, liable to impermanence, to wearing away and erosion, to breaking up and destruction.*";
P_HTM[2251]="*Gaṇḍamūlanti kho, bhikkhave, taṇhāyetaṃ adhivacanaṃ.**‘Boil’s root’ is a term for craving.*";
P_HTM[2252]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno taṇhā pahīnā hoti ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā;**It’s when a mendicant has given up craving, cut it off at the root, made it like a palm stump, obliterated it, so it’s unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[2253]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno apalikhataṃ gaṇḍamūlaṃ palikhataṃ hoti.**That’s how a mendicant has dug out the boil’s root, which was never dug out before.*";
P_HTM[2254]="*Udako sudaṃ, bhikkhave, rāmaputto evaṃ vācaṃ bhāsati:**Uddaka, son of Rāma, used to say:*";
P_HTM[2255]="*‘idaṃ jātu vedagū, idaṃ jātu sabbajī, idaṃ jātu apalikhataṃ gaṇḍamūlaṃ palikhaṇin’ti.**‘This for sure is the knowledge master! This for sure is the conqueror of all! This for sure is the boil’s root dug out, never dug out before!’*";
P_HTM[2256]="*Taṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhave, udako rāmaputto avedagūyeva samāno ‘vedagūsmī’ti bhāsati, asabbajīyeva samāno ‘sabbajīsmī’ti bhāsati;**Even though Uddaka, son of Rāma, was no knowledge master, he said ‘I’m a knowledge master.’ Though he was no conqueror of all, he said ‘I’m conqueror of all.’ And though the boil’s root was not dug out, he said ‘I’ve dug out the boil’s root.’*";
P_HTM[2257]="*apalikhataṃyeva gaṇḍamūlaṃ ‘palikhataṃ me gaṇḍamūlan’ti bhāsati.* **";
P_HTM[2258]="*Idha kho taṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**But that’s how a mendicant would rightly say:*";
P_HTM[2259]="*‘idaṃ jātu vedagū, idaṃ jātu sabbajī, idaṃ jātu apalikhataṃ gaṇḍamūlaṃ palikhaṇin’”ti.**‘This for sure is the knowledge master! This for sure is the conqueror of all! This for sure is the boil’s root dug out, never dug out before!’”*";
P_HTM[2260]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2261]="*Saḷavaggo pañcamo.* **";
P_HTM[2262]="*Dve saṅgayhā parihānaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[2263]="*Pamādavihārī ca saṃvaro;* **";
P_HTM[2264]="*Samādhi paṭisallānaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[2265]="*Dve natumhākena uddakoti.* **";
P_HTM[2266]="*Saḷāyatanavagge dutiyapaṇṇāsako samatto.* **";
P_HTM[2267]="*Avijjā migajālañca,* **";
P_HTM[2268]="*Gilānaṃ channaṃ catutthakaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[2269]="*Saḷavaggena paññāsaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[2270]="*Dutiyo paṇṇāsako ayanti.* **";
P_HTM[2271]="*Paṭhamasatakaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2272]="*11. Yogakkhemivaggo**Sanctuary*";
P_HTM[2273]="*1. Yogakkhemisuttaṃ**Sanctuary*";
P_HTM[2274]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[2275]="*“Yogakkhemipariyāyaṃ vo, bhikkhave, dhammapariyāyaṃ desessāmi.**“Mendicants, I will teach you an exposition of the teaching, an explanation of one who has reached sanctuary.*";
P_HTM[2276]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[2277]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, yogakkhemipariyāyo dhammapariyāyo?**And what is an exposition of the teaching, an explanation of one who has reached sanctuary?*";
P_HTM[2278]="*Santi, bhikkhave, cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**There are sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[2279]="*Te tathāgatassa pahīnā ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.**The Realized One has given these up, cut them off at the root, made them like a palm stump, and obliterated them, so they are unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[2280]="*Tesañca pahānāya akkhāsi yogaṃ, tasmā tathāgato ‘yogakkhemī’ti vuccati … pe …**He teaches meditation for giving them up. That’s why the Realized One is called one who has reached sanctuary. …*";
P_HTM[2281]="*santi, bhikkhave, manoviññeyyā dhammā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**There are thoughts known by the mind that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[2282]="*Te tathāgatassa pahīnā ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.**The Realized One has given these up, cut them off at the root, made them like a palm stump, and obliterated them, so they are unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[2283]="*Tesañca pahānāya akkhāsi yogaṃ, tasmā tathāgato ‘yogakkhemī’ti vuccati.**He teaches meditation for giving them up. That’s why the Realized One is called one who has reached sanctuary.*";
P_HTM[2284]="*Ayaṃ kho, bhikkhave, yogakkhemipariyāyo dhammapariyāyo”ti.**This is an exposition of the teaching, an explanation of one who has reached sanctuary.”*";
P_HTM[2285]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2286]="*2. Upādāyasuttaṃ**Because of Grasping*";
P_HTM[2287]="*“Kismiṃ nu kho, bhikkhave, sati kiṃ upādāya uppajjati ajjhattaṃ sukhaṃ dukkhan”ti?**“Mendicants, when what exists, because of grasping what, do pleasure and pain arise in oneself?”*";
P_HTM[2288]="*“Bhagavaṃmūlakā no, bhante, dhammā … pe ….**“Our teachings are rooted in the Buddha. …”*";
P_HTM[2289]="*“Cakkhusmiṃ kho, bhikkhave, sati cakkhuṃ upādāya uppajjati ajjhattaṃ sukhaṃ dukkhaṃ … pe …**“Mendicants, when there’s an eye, because of grasping the eye, pleasure and pain arise in oneself. …*";
P_HTM[2290]="*manasmiṃ sati manaṃ upādāya uppajjati ajjhattaṃ sukhaṃ dukkhaṃ.**When there’s a mind, because of grasping the mind, pleasure and pain arise in oneself.*";
P_HTM[2291]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[2292]="*cakkhu niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is the eye permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[2293]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2294]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[2295]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2296]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, api nu taṃ anupādāya uppajjeyya ajjhattaṃ sukhaṃ dukkhan”ti?**“But by not grasping what’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, would pleasure and pain arise in oneself?”*";
P_HTM[2297]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante” … pe ….**“No, sir.” …*";
P_HTM[2298]="*“Jivhā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?**“Is the ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[2299]="*“Aniccā, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[2300]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[2301]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[2302]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, api nu taṃ anupādāya uppajjeyya ajjhattaṃ sukhaṃ dukkhan”ti?* **";
P_HTM[2303]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante” … pe ….* **";
P_HTM[2304]="*“Mano nicco vā anicco vā”ti?**mind permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[2305]="*“Anicco, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2306]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[2307]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2308]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, api nu taṃ anupādāya uppajjeyya ajjhattaṃ sukhaṃ dukkhan”ti?**“But by not grasping what’s impermanent, suffering, and perishable, would pleasure and pain arise in oneself?”*";
P_HTM[2309]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[2310]="*“Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako cakkhusmimpi nibbindati … pe … manasmimpi nibbindati.**“Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[2311]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati; vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[2312]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[2313]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2314]="*3. Dukkhasamudayasuttaṃ**The Origin of Suffering*";
P_HTM[2315]="*“Dukkhassa, bhikkhave, samudayañca atthaṅgamañca desessāmi.**“Mendicants, I will teach you the origin and ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[2316]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[2317]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, dukkhassa samudayo?**And what, mendicants, is the origin of suffering?*";
P_HTM[2318]="*Cakkhuñca paṭicca rūpe ca uppajjati cakkhuviññāṇaṃ. Tiṇṇaṃ saṅgati phasso.**Eye consciousness arises dependent on the eye and sights. The meeting of the three is contact.*";
P_HTM[2319]="*Phassapaccayā vedanā;**Contact is a condition for feeling.*";
P_HTM[2320]="*vedanāpaccayā taṇhā.**Feeling is a condition for craving.*";
P_HTM[2321]="*Ayaṃ dukkhassa samudayo … pe …**This is the origin of suffering …*";
P_HTM[2322]="*jivhañca paṭicca rase ca uppajjati jivhāviññāṇaṃ. Tiṇṇaṃ saṅgati phasso.* **";
P_HTM[2323]="*Phassapaccayā vedanā;* **";
P_HTM[2324]="*vedanāpaccayā taṇhā.* **";
P_HTM[2325]="*Ayaṃ dukkhassa samudayo … pe … manañca paṭicca dhamme ca uppajjati manoviññāṇaṃ.**Mind consciousness arises dependent on the mind and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[2326]="*Tiṇṇaṃ saṅgati phasso.**The meeting of the three is contact.*";
P_HTM[2327]="*Phassapaccayā vedanā;**Contact is a condition for feeling.*";
P_HTM[2328]="*vedanāpaccayā taṇhā.**Feeling is a condition for craving.*";
P_HTM[2329]="*Ayaṃ kho, bhikkhave, dukkhassa samudayo.**This is the origin of suffering.*";
P_HTM[2330]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, dukkhassa atthaṅgamo?**And what is the ending of suffering?*";
P_HTM[2331]="*Cakkhuñca paṭicca rūpe ca uppajjati cakkhuviññāṇaṃ. Tiṇṇaṃ saṅgati phasso.**Eye consciousness arises dependent on the eye and sights. The meeting of the three is contact.*";
P_HTM[2332]="*Phassapaccayā vedanā;**Contact is a condition for feeling.*";
P_HTM[2333]="*vedanāpaccayā taṇhā.**Feeling is a condition for craving.*";
P_HTM[2334]="*Tassāyeva taṇhāya asesavirāganirodhā upādānanirodho;**When that craving fades away and ceases with nothing left over, grasping ceases.*";
P_HTM[2335]="*upādānanirodhā bhavanirodho;**When grasping ceases, continued existence ceases.*";
P_HTM[2336]="*bhavanirodhā jātinirodho;**When continued existence ceases, rebirth ceases.*";
P_HTM[2337]="*jātinirodhā jarāmaraṇaṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā nirujjhanti.**When rebirth ceases, old age and death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress cease.*";
P_HTM[2338]="*Evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa nirodho hoti.**That is how this entire mass of suffering ceases.*";
P_HTM[2339]="*Ayaṃ dukkhassa atthaṅgamo … pe …**This is the ending of suffering. …*";
P_HTM[2340]="*jivhañca paṭicca rase ca uppajjati jivhāviññāṇaṃ … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2341]="*manañca paṭicca dhamme ca uppajjati manoviññāṇaṃ. Tiṇṇaṃ saṅgati phasso.**Mind consciousness arises dependent on the mind and thoughts. The meeting of the three is contact.*";
P_HTM[2342]="*Phassapaccayā vedanā;**Contact is a condition for feeling.*";
P_HTM[2343]="*vedanāpaccayā taṇhā.**Feeling is a condition for craving.*";
P_HTM[2344]="*Tassāyeva taṇhāya asesavirāganirodhā upādānanirodho;**When that craving fades away and ceases with nothing left over, grasping ceases.*";
P_HTM[2345]="*upādānanirodhā bhavanirodho;**When grasping ceases, continued existence ceases.*";
P_HTM[2346]="*bhavanirodhā jātinirodho;**When continued existence ceases, rebirth ceases.*";
P_HTM[2347]="*jātinirodhā jarāmaraṇaṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā nirujjhanti.**When rebirth ceases, old age and death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress cease.*";
P_HTM[2348]="*Evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa nirodho hoti.**That is how this entire mass of suffering ceases.*";
P_HTM[2349]="*Ayaṃ kho, bhikkhave, dukkhassa atthaṅgamo”ti.**This is the ending of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[2350]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2351]="*4. Lokasamudayasuttaṃ**The Origin of the World*";
P_HTM[2352]="*“Lokassa, bhikkhave, samudayañca atthaṅgamañca desessāmi.**“Mendicants, I will teach you the origin and ending of the world.*";
P_HTM[2353]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[2354]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, lokassa samudayo?**And what, mendicants, is the origin of the world?*";
P_HTM[2355]="*Cakkhuñca paṭicca rūpe ca uppajjati cakkhuviññāṇaṃ. Tiṇṇaṃ saṅgati phasso.**Eye consciousness arises dependent on the eye and sights. The meeting of the three is contact.*";
P_HTM[2356]="*Phassapaccayā vedanā;**Contact is a condition for feeling.*";
P_HTM[2357]="*vedanāpaccayā taṇhā;**Feeling is a condition for craving.*";
P_HTM[2358]="*taṇhāpaccayā upādānaṃ;**Craving is a condition for grasping.*";
P_HTM[2359]="*upādānapaccayā bhavo;**Grasping is a condition for continued existence.*";
P_HTM[2360]="*bhavapaccayā jāti;**Continued existence is a condition for rebirth.*";
