P_HTM[3422]="*Anattasambhūtā, bhikkhave, rūpā kuto attā bhavissanti.**Since sights are produced by what is not-self, how could they be self?*";
P_HTM[3423]="*Saddā …**Sounds …*";
P_HTM[3424]="*gandhā …**Smells …*";
P_HTM[3425]="*rasā …**Tastes …*";
P_HTM[3426]="*phoṭṭhabbā …**Touches …*";
P_HTM[3427]="*dhammā anattā.**Thoughts are not-self.*";
P_HTM[3428]="*Yopi hetu, yopi paccayo dhammānaṃ uppādāya, sopi anattā.**The cause and condition that gives rise to thoughts is also not-self.*";
P_HTM[3429]="*Anattasambhūtā, bhikkhave, dhammā kuto attā bhavissanti.**Since thoughts are produced by what is not-self, how could they be self?*";
P_HTM[3430]="*Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako rūpesupi nibbindati, saddesupi … gandhesupi … rasesupi … phoṭṭhabbesupi … dhammesupi nibbindati.**Seeing this …*";
P_HTM[3431]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati; vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[3432]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’”*";
P_HTM[3433]="*Dvādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3434]="*Devadahavaggo catuttho.* **";
P_HTM[3435]="*Devadaho khaṇo rūpā,* **";
P_HTM[3436]="*dve natumhākameva ca;* **";
P_HTM[3437]="*Hetunāpi tayo vuttā,* **";
P_HTM[3438]="*duve ajjhattabāhirāti.* **";
P_HTM[3439]="*15. Navapurāṇavaggo**The Old and the New*";
P_HTM[3440]="*1. Kammanirodhasuttaṃ**The Cessation of Action*";
P_HTM[3441]="*“Navapurāṇāni, bhikkhave, kammāni desessāmi kammanirodhaṃ kammanirodhagāminiñca paṭipadaṃ.**“Mendicants, I will teach you old action, new action, the cessation of action, and the practice that leads to the cessation of action.*";
P_HTM[3442]="*Taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmīti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak. …*";
P_HTM[3443]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, purāṇakammaṃ?**And what is old action?*";
P_HTM[3444]="*Cakkhu, bhikkhave, purāṇakammaṃ abhisaṅkhataṃ abhisañcetayitaṃ vedaniyaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ … pe …**The eye is old action. It should be seen as produced by choices and intentions, as something to be felt.*";
P_HTM[3445]="*jivhā purāṇakammā abhisaṅkhatā abhisañcetayitā vedaniyā daṭṭhabbā … pe …**The ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[3446]="*mano purāṇakammo abhisaṅkhato abhisañcetayito vedaniyo daṭṭhabbo.**mind is old action. It should be seen as produced by choices and intentions, as something to be felt.*";
P_HTM[3447]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, purāṇakammaṃ.**This is called old action.*";
P_HTM[3448]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, navakammaṃ?**And what is new action?*";
P_HTM[3449]="*Yaṃ kho, bhikkhave, etarahi kammaṃ karoti kāyena vācāya manasā,**The deeds you currently perform by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[3450]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, navakammaṃ.**This is called new action.*";
P_HTM[3451]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, kammanirodho?**And what is the cessation of action?*";
P_HTM[3452]="*Yo kho, bhikkhave, kāyakammavacīkammamanokammassa nirodhā vimuttiṃ phusati,**When you experience freedom due to the cessation of deeds by body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[3453]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, kammanirodho.**This is called the cessation of action.*";
P_HTM[3454]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, kammanirodhagāminī paṭipadā?**And what’s the practice that leads to the cessation of action?*";
P_HTM[3455]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, seyyathidaṃ—**It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[3456]="*sammādiṭṭhi, sammāsaṅkappo, sammāvācā, sammākammanto, sammāājīvo, sammāvāyāmo, sammāsati, sammāsamādhi—**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[3457]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, kammanirodhagāminī paṭipadā.**This is called the practice that leads to the cessation of action.*";
P_HTM[3458]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, desitaṃ mayā purāṇakammaṃ, desitaṃ navakammaṃ, desito kammanirodho, desitā kammanirodhagāminī paṭipadā.**So, mendicants, I’ve taught you old action, new action, the cessation of action, and the practice that leads to the cessation of action.*";
P_HTM[3459]="*Yaṃ kho, bhikkhave, satthārā karaṇīyaṃ sāvakānaṃ hitesinā anukampakena anukampaṃ upādāya, kataṃ vo taṃ mayā.**Out of compassion, I’ve done what a teacher should do who wants what’s best for their disciples.*";
P_HTM[3460]="*Etāni, bhikkhave, rukkhamūlāni, etāni suññāgārāni. Jhāyatha, bhikkhave, mā pamādattha; mā pacchāvippaṭisārino ahuvattha. Ayaṃ vo amhākaṃ anusāsanī”ti.**Here are these roots of trees, and here are these empty huts. Practice absorption, mendicants! Don’t be negligent! Don’t regret it later! This is my instruction to you.”*";
P_HTM[3461]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3462]="*2. Aniccanibbānasappāyasuttaṃ**The Impermanent as Conducive to Extinguishment*";
P_HTM[3463]="*“Nibbānasappāyaṃ vo, bhikkhave, paṭipadaṃ desessāmi.**“Mendicants, I will teach you a practice that’s conducive to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[3464]="*Taṃ suṇātha … pe …**Listen …*";
P_HTM[3465]="*katamā ca sā, bhikkhave, nibbānasappāyā paṭipadā?**And what is that practice that’s conducive to extinguishment?*";
P_HTM[3466]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cakkhuṃ aniccanti passati, rūpā aniccāti passati, cakkhuviññāṇaṃ aniccanti passati, cakkhusamphasso aniccoti passati. Yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccanti passati … pe …**It’s when a mendicant sees that the eye, sights, eye consciousness, and eye contact are impermanent. And they see that the painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact is also impermanent.*";
P_HTM[3467]="*jivhā aniccāti passati, rasā aniccāti passati, jivhāviññāṇaṃ aniccanti passati, jivhāsamphasso aniccoti passati, yampidaṃ jivhāsamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccanti passati … pe …**They see that the ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[3468]="*mano aniccoti passati, dhammā aniccāti passati, manoviññāṇaṃ aniccanti passati, manosamphasso aniccoti passati, yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccanti passati.**mind, thoughts, mind-consciousness, and mind contact are impermanent. And they see that the painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact is also impermanent.*";
P_HTM[3469]="*Ayaṃ kho sā, bhikkhave, nibbānasappāyā paṭipadā”ti.**This is that practice that’s conducive to extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[3470]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3471]="*3. Dukkhanibbānasappāyasuttaṃ**The Suffering as Conducive to Extinguishment*";
P_HTM[3472]="*“Nibbānasappāyaṃ vo, bhikkhave, paṭipadaṃ desessāmi.**“Mendicants, I will teach you a practice that’s conducive to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[3473]="*Taṃ suṇātha … pe …**Listen …*";
P_HTM[3474]="*katamā ca sā, bhikkhave, nibbānasappāyā paṭipadā?**And what is that practice that’s conducive to extinguishment?*";
P_HTM[3475]="*Idha, bhikkhave, cakkhuṃ dukkhanti passati, rūpā dukkhāti passati, cakkhuviññāṇaṃ dukkhanti passati, cakkhusamphasso dukkhoti passati, yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi dukkhanti passati … pe …**It’s when a mendicant sees that the eye, sights, eye consciousness, and eye contact are suffering. And they see that the painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact is also suffering.*";
P_HTM[3476]="*jivhā dukkhāti passati … pe …**They see that the ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[3477]="*mano dukkhoti passati, dhammā dukkhāti passati, manoviññāṇaṃ dukkhanti passati, manosamphasso dukkhoti passati, yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi dukkhanti passati.**mind, thoughts, mind-consciousness, and mind contact are suffering. And they see that the painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact is also suffering.*";
P_HTM[3478]="*Ayaṃ kho sā, bhikkhave, nibbānasappāyā paṭipadā”ti.**This is that practice that’s conducive to extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[3479]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3480]="*4. Anattanibbānasappāyasuttaṃ**Not*";
P_HTM[3481]="*“Nibbānasappāyaṃ vo, bhikkhave, paṭipadaṃ desessāmi.**“Mendicants, I will teach you a practice that’s conducive to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[3482]="*Taṃ suṇātha … pe …**Listen …*";
P_HTM[3483]="*katamā ca sā, bhikkhave, nibbānasappāyā paṭipadā?**And what is that practice that’s conducive to extinguishment?*";
P_HTM[3484]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cakkhuṃ anattāti passati, rūpā anattāti passati, cakkhuviññāṇaṃ anattāti passati, cakkhusamphasso anattāti passati, yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi anattāti passati … pe …**It’s when a mendicant sees that the eye, sights, eye consciousness, and eye contact are not-self. And they see that the painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact is also not-self.*";
P_HTM[3485]="*mano anattāti passati, dhammā anattāti passati, manoviññāṇaṃ anattāti passati, manosamphasso anattāti passati, yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi anattāti passati.**They see that the ear … nose … tongue … body … mind, thoughts, mind-consciousness, and mind contact are not-self. And they see that the painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact is also not-self.*";
P_HTM[3486]="*Ayaṃ kho sā, bhikkhave, nibbānasappāyā paṭipadā”ti.**This is that practice that’s conducive to extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[3487]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3488]="*5. Nibbānasappāyapaṭipadāsuttaṃ**A Practice Conducive to Extinguishment*";
P_HTM[3489]="*“Nibbānasappāyaṃ vo, bhikkhave, paṭipadaṃ desessāmi.**“Mendicants, I will teach you a practice that’s conducive to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[3490]="*Taṃ suṇātha … pe …**Listen …*";
P_HTM[3491]="*katamā ca sā, bhikkhave, nibbānasappāyā paṭipadā?**And what is that practice that’s conducive to extinguishment?*";
P_HTM[3492]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[3493]="*cakkhu niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**Is the eye permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[3494]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3495]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[3496]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3497]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and liable to fall apart, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[3498]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[3499]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3500]="*“Rūpā niccā vā aniccā vā”ti?**“Are sights …*";
P_HTM[3501]="*“Aniccā, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[3502]="*“Cakkhuviññāṇaṃ …**eye consciousness …*";
P_HTM[3503]="*cakkhusamphasso … pe …**eye contact …*";
P_HTM[3504]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi niccaṃ vā aniccaṃ vā”ti?**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact: is that permanent or impermanent?”*";
P_HTM[3505]="*“Aniccaṃ, bhante”.**“Impermanent, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3506]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vā taṃ sukhaṃ vā”ti?**“But if it’s impermanent, is it suffering or happiness?”*";
P_HTM[3507]="*“Dukkhaṃ, bhante”.**“Suffering, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3508]="*“Yaṃ panāniccaṃ dukkhaṃ vipariṇāmadhammaṃ, kallaṃ nu taṃ samanupassituṃ:**“But if it’s impermanent, suffering, and liable to fall apart, is it fit to be regarded thus:*";
P_HTM[3509]="*‘etaṃ mama, esohamasmi, eso me attā’”ti?**‘This is mine, I am this, this is my self’?”*";
P_HTM[3510]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3511]="*“Evaṃ passaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavā ariyasāvako cakkhusmimpi nibbindati, rūpesupi nibbindati, cakkhuviññāṇepi nibbindati, cakkhusamphassepi nibbindati … pe …**Seeing this, a learned noble disciple grows disillusioned with the eye, sights, eye consciousness, and eye contact. And they grow disillusioned with the painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact.*";
P_HTM[3512]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tasmimpi nibbindati.**They grow disillusioned with the ear … nose … tongue … body … mind … painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact.*";
P_HTM[3513]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati; virāgā vimuccati … pe …**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away they’re freed. …*";
P_HTM[3514]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[3515]="*Ayaṃ kho sā, bhikkhave, nibbānasappāyā paṭipadā”ti.**This is that practice that’s conducive to extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[3516]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3517]="*6. Antevāsikasuttaṃ**A Student*";
P_HTM[3518]="*“Anantevāsikamidaṃ, bhikkhave, brahmacariyaṃ vussati anācariyakaṃ.**“Mendicants, this spiritual life is lived without a resident student and without a teaching master.*";
P_HTM[3519]="*Santevāsiko, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sācariyako dukkhaṃ na phāsu viharati.**A mendicant who lives with a resident student and a teaching master lives in suffering and discomfort.*";
P_HTM[3520]="*Anantevāsiko, bhikkhave, bhikkhu anācariyako sukhaṃ phāsu viharati.**A mendicant who lives without a resident student and a teaching master lives in happiness and comfort.*";
P_HTM[3521]="*Kathañca, bhikkhu, santevāsiko sācariyako dukkhaṃ na phāsu viharati?**And how does a mendicant who lives with a resident student and a teaching master live in suffering and discomfort?*";
P_HTM[3522]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā sarasaṅkappā saṃyojaniyā.**When a mendicant sees a sight with the eye, bad, unskillful phenomena arise: memories and thoughts prone to fetters.*";
P_HTM[3523]="*Tyāssa anto vasanti, antassa vasanti pāpakā akusalā dhammāti.**Those qualities reside within. Since they have bad unskillful qualities residing within,*";
P_HTM[3524]="*Tasmā santevāsikoti vuccati.**they’re said to have a resident student.*";
P_HTM[3525]="*Te naṃ samudācaranti, samudācaranti naṃ pāpakā akusalā dhammāti.**Those qualities master them. Since they’re mastered by bad unskillful qualities,*";
P_HTM[3526]="*Tasmā sācariyakoti vuccati … pe ….**they’re said to have a teaching master.*";
P_HTM[3527]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā sarasaṅkappā saṃyojaniyā.**Furthermore, when a mendicant hears … smells … tastes … touches …*";
P_HTM[3528]="*Tyāssa anto vasanti, antassa vasanti pāpakā akusalā dhammāti.* **";
P_HTM[3529]="*Tasmā santevāsikoti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[3530]="*Te naṃ samudācaranti, samudācaranti naṃ pāpakā akusalā dhammāti. Tasmā sācariyakoti vuccati … pe ….* **";
P_HTM[3531]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno manasā dhammaṃ viññāya uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā sarasaṅkappā saṃyojaniyā.**knows a thought with the mind, bad, unskillful phenomena arise: memories and thoughts prone to fetters.*";
P_HTM[3532]="*Tyāssa anto vasanti, antassa vasanti pāpakā akusalā dhammāti.**Those qualities reside within. Since they have bad unskillful qualities residing within,*";
P_HTM[3533]="*Tasmā santevāsikoti vuccati.**they’re said to have a resident student.*";
P_HTM[3534]="*Te naṃ samudācaranti, samudācaranti naṃ pāpakā akusalā dhammāti.**Those qualities master them. Since they’re mastered by bad unskillful qualities,*";
P_HTM[3535]="*Tasmā sācariyakoti vuccati.**they’re said to have a teaching master.*";
P_HTM[3536]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu santevāsiko sācariyako dukkhaṃ, na phāsu viharati.**That’s how a mendicant who lives with a resident student and a teaching master lives in suffering and discomfort.*";
P_HTM[3537]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu anantevāsiko anācariyako sukhaṃ phāsu viharati?**And how does a mendicant who lives without a resident student and a teaching master live in happiness and comfort?*";
P_HTM[3538]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā na uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā sarasaṅkappā saṃyojaniyā.**When a mendicant sees a sight with the eye, bad, unskillful phenomena don’t arise: memories and thoughts prone to fetters.*";
P_HTM[3539]="*Tyāssa na anto vasanti, nāssa anto vasanti pāpakā akusalā dhammāti.**Those qualities don’t reside within. Since they don’t have bad unskillful qualities residing within,*";
P_HTM[3540]="*Tasmā anantevāsikoti vuccati.**they’re said to not have a resident student.*";
P_HTM[3541]="*Te naṃ na samudācaranti, na samudācaranti naṃ pāpakā akusalā dhammāti.**Those qualities don’t master them. Since they’re not mastered by bad unskillful qualities,*";
P_HTM[3542]="*Tasmā anācariyakoti vuccati … pe ….**they’re said to not have a teaching master.*";
P_HTM[3543]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā na uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā sarasaṅkappā saṃyojaniyā.**Furthermore, when a mendicant hears … smells … tastes … touches …*";
P_HTM[3544]="*Tyāssa na anto vasanti, nāssa anto vasanti pāpakā akusalā dhammāti.* **";
P_HTM[3545]="*Tasmā anantevāsikoti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[3546]="*Te naṃ na samudācaranti, na samudācaranti naṃ pāpakā akusalā dhammāti. Tasmā anācariyakoti vuccati … pe ….* **";
P_HTM[3547]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno manasā dhammaṃ viññāya na uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā sarasaṅkappā saṃyojaniyā.**knows a thought with the mind, bad, unskillful phenomena don’t arise: memories and thoughts prone to fetters.*";
P_HTM[3548]="*Tyāssa na anto vasanti, nāssa anto vasanti pāpakā akusalā dhammāti.**Those qualities don’t reside within. Since they don’t have bad unskillful qualities residing within,*";
P_HTM[3549]="*Tasmā anantevāsikoti vuccati.**they’re said to not have a resident student.*";
P_HTM[3550]="*Te naṃ na samudācaranti, na samudācaranti naṃ pāpakā akusalā dhammāti.**Those qualities don’t master them. Since they’re not mastered by bad unskillful qualities,*";
P_HTM[3551]="*Tasmā anācariyakoti vuccati.**they’re said to not have a teaching master.*";
P_HTM[3552]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu anantevāsiko anācariyako sukhaṃ phāsu viharati.**That’s how a mendicant who lives without a resident student and a teaching master lives in happiness and comfort.*";
P_HTM[3553]="*Anantevāsikamidaṃ, bhikkhave, brahmacariyaṃ vussati.**This spiritual life is lived without a resident student and without a teaching master.*";
P_HTM[3554]="*Anācariyakaṃ santevāsiko, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sācariyako dukkhaṃ, na phāsu viharati.**A mendicant who lives with a resident student and a teaching master lives in suffering and discomfort.*";
P_HTM[3555]="*Anantevāsiko, bhikkhave, bhikkhu anācariyako sukhaṃ phāsu viharatī”ti.**A mendicant who lives without a resident student and a teaching master lives in happiness and comfort.”*";
P_HTM[3556]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3557]="*7. Kimatthiyabrahmacariyasuttaṃ**What’s the Purpose of the Spiritual Life?*";
P_HTM[3558]="*“Sace vo, bhikkhave, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**“Mendicants, if wanderers who follow another path were to ask you:*";
P_HTM[3559]="*‘kimatthiyaṃ, āvuso, samaṇe gotame brahmacariyaṃ vussatī’ti?**‘Reverends, what’s the purpose of living the spiritual life with the ascetic Gotama?’*";
P_HTM[3560]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhā tumhe, bhikkhave, tesaṃ aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ evaṃ byākareyyātha:**You should answer them:*";
P_HTM[3561]="*‘dukkhassa kho, āvuso, pariññāya bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ vussatī’ti.**‘The purpose of living the spiritual life under the Buddha is to completely understand suffering.’*";
P_HTM[3562]="*Sace pana vo, bhikkhave, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**If wanderers who follow other paths were to ask you:*";
P_HTM[3563]="*‘katamaṃ panāvuso, dukkhaṃ, yassa pariññāya samaṇe gotame brahmacariyaṃ vussatī’ti?**‘Reverends, what is that suffering?’*";
P_HTM[3564]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhā tumhe, bhikkhave, tesaṃ aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ evaṃ byākareyyātha:**You should answer them:*";
P_HTM[3565]="*‘Cakkhu kho, āvuso, dukkhaṃ;**‘The eye is suffering.*";
P_HTM[3566]="*tassa pariññāya bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ vussati.**The purpose of living the spiritual life under the Buddha is to completely understand this.*";
P_HTM[3567]="*Rūpā dukkhā;**Sights …*";
P_HTM[3568]="*tesaṃ pariññāya bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ vussati.* **";
P_HTM[3569]="*Cakkhuviññāṇaṃ dukkhaṃ;**Eye consciousness …*";
P_HTM[3570]="*tassa pariññāya bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ vussati.* **";
P_HTM[3571]="*Cakkhusamphasso dukkho;**Eye contact …*";
P_HTM[3572]="*tassa pariññāya bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ vussati.* **";
P_HTM[3573]="*Yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi dukkhaṃ;**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact is also suffering.*";
P_HTM[3574]="*tassa pariññāya bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ vussati … pe …**The purpose of living the spiritual life under the Buddha is to completely understand this.*";
P_HTM[3575]="*jivhā dukkhā …**The ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[3576]="*mano dukkho;**mind …*";
P_HTM[3577]="*tassa pariññāya bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ vussati …* **";
P_HTM[3578]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi dukkhaṃ;**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact is also suffering.*";
P_HTM[3579]="*tassa pariññāya bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ vussati.**The purpose of living the spiritual life under the Buddha is to completely understand this.*";
P_HTM[3580]="*Idaṃ kho, āvuso, dukkhaṃ;**This is that suffering.*";
P_HTM[3581]="*yassa pariññāya bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ vussatī’ti.**The purpose of living the spiritual life under the Buddha is to completely understand this.’*";
P_HTM[3582]="*Evaṃ puṭṭhā tumhe, bhikkhave, tesaṃ aññatitthiyānaṃ paribbājakānaṃ evaṃ byākareyyāthā”ti.**When questioned by wanderers who follow other paths, that’s how you should answer them.”*";
P_HTM[3583]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3584]="*8. Atthinukhopariyāyasuttaṃ**Is There a Method?*";
P_HTM[3585]="*“Atthi nu kho, bhikkhave, pariyāyo yaṃ pariyāyaṃ āgamma bhikkhu aññatreva saddhāya, aññatra ruciyā, aññatra anussavā, aññatra ākāraparivitakkā, aññatra diṭṭhinijjhānakkhantiyā aññaṃ byākareyya:**“Mendicants, is there a method—apart from faith, preference, oral tradition, reasoned contemplation, or acceptance of a view after consideration—that a mendicant can rely on to declare their enlightenment? That is:*";
P_HTM[3586]="*‘khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāmī”ti?**‘I understand: “Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.”’”*";
P_HTM[3587]="*“Bhagavaṃmūlakā no, bhante, dhammā, bhagavaṃnettikā bhagavaṃpaṭisaraṇā. Sādhu vata, bhante, bhagavantaṃyeva paṭibhātu etassa bhāsitassa attho. Bhagavato sutvā bhikkhū dhāressantī”ti.**“Our teachings are rooted in the Buddha. He is our guide and our refuge. Sir, may the Buddha himself please clarify the meaning of this. The mendicants will listen and remember it.”*";
P_HTM[3588]="*“Tena hi, bhikkhave, suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, mendicants, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[3589]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[3590]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[3591]="*“atthi, bhikkhave, pariyāyo yaṃ pariyāyaṃ āgamma bhikkhu aññatreva saddhāya, aññatra ruciyā, aññatra anussavā, aññatra ākāraparivitakkā, aññatra diṭṭhinijjhānakkhantiyā aññaṃ byākareyya:**“There is a method—apart from faith, preference, oral tradition, reasoned contemplation, or acceptance of a view after consideration—that a mendicant can rely on to declare their enlightenment. That is:*";
P_HTM[3592]="*‘“khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti pajānāmī’ti.**‘I understand: “Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.”’*";
P_HTM[3593]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, pariyāyo, yaṃ pariyāyaṃ āgamma bhikkhu aññatreva saddhāya … pe … aññatra diṭṭhinijjhānakkhantiyā aññaṃ byākaroti: ‘khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāmī’ti?**And what is that method?*";
P_HTM[3594]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā santaṃ vā ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohaṃ, atthi me ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohoti pajānāti;**Take a mendicant who sees a sight with the eye. When they have greed, hate, and delusion in them, they understand ‘I have greed, hate, and delusion in me.’*";
P_HTM[3595]="*asantaṃ vā ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohaṃ, natthi me ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohoti pajānāti.**When they don’t have greed, hate, and delusion in them, they understand ‘I don’t have greed, hate, and delusion in me.’*";
P_HTM[3596]="*Yaṃ taṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā santaṃ vā ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohaṃ, atthi me ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohoti pajānāti; asantaṃ vā ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohaṃ, natthi me ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohoti pajānāti. Api nu me, bhikkhave, dhammā saddhāya vā veditabbā, ruciyā vā veditabbā, anussavena vā veditabbā, ākāraparivitakkena vā veditabbā, diṭṭhinijjhānakkhantiyā vā veditabbā”ti?**Since this is so, are these things understood by faith, preference, oral tradition, reasoned contemplation, or acceptance of a view after consideration?”*";
P_HTM[3597]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3598]="*“Nanume, bhikkhave, dhammā paññāya disvā veditabbā”ti?**“Aren’t they understood by seeing them with wisdom?”*";
P_HTM[3599]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3600]="*“Ayaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pariyāyo yaṃ pariyāyaṃ āgamma bhikkhu aññatreva saddhāya, aññatra ruciyā, aññatra anussavā, aññatra ākāraparivitakkā, aññatra diṭṭhinijjhānakkhantiyā aññaṃ byākaroti:**“This is a method—apart from faith, preference, oral tradition, reasoned contemplation, or acceptance of a view after consideration—that a mendicant can rely on to declare their enlightenment. That is:*";
P_HTM[3601]="*‘“khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti pajānāmī’ti … pe ….**‘I understand: “Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.”’*";
P_HTM[3602]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā santaṃ vā ajjhattaṃ … pe … rāgadosamohoti pajānāti; asantaṃ vā ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohaṃ, natthi me ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohoti pajānāti.**Furthermore, a mendicant hears a sound … smells an odor … tastes a flavor … feels a touch …*";
P_HTM[3603]="*Yaṃ taṃ, bhikkhave, jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā santaṃ vā ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohaṃ, atthi me ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohoti pajānāti; asantaṃ vā ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohaṃ, natthi me ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohoti pajānāti; api nu me, bhikkhave, dhammā saddhāya vā veditabbā, ruciyā vā veditabbā, anussavena vā veditabbā, ākāraparivitakkena vā veditabbā, diṭṭhinijjhānakkhantiyā vā veditabbā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[3604]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[3605]="*“Nanume, bhikkhave, dhammā paññāya disvā veditabbā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[3606]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[3607]="*“Ayampi kho, bhikkhave, pariyāyo yaṃ pariyāyaṃ āgamma bhikkhu aññatreva saddhāya, aññatra ruciyā, aññatra anussavā, aññatra ākāraparivitakkā, aññatra diṭṭhinijjhānakkhantiyā aññaṃ byākaroti: ‘“khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti pajānāmī’ti … pe ….* **";
P_HTM[3608]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu manasā dhammaṃ viññāya santaṃ vā ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohaṃ, atthi me ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohoti pajānāti;**knows a thought with the mind. When they have greed, hate, and delusion in them, they understand ‘I have greed, hate, and delusion in me.’*";
P_HTM[3609]="*asantaṃ vā ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohaṃ, natthi me ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohoti pajānāti.**When they don’t have greed, hate, and delusion in them, they understand ‘I don’t have greed, hate, and delusion in me.’*";
P_HTM[3610]="*Yaṃ taṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu manasā dhammaṃ viññāya santaṃ vā ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohaṃ, atthi me ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohoti pajānāti; asantaṃ vā ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohaṃ, natthi me ajjhattaṃ rāgadosamohoti pajānāti; api nu me, bhikkhave, dhammā saddhāya vā veditabbā, ruciyā vā veditabbā, anussavena vā veditabbā, ākāraparivitakkena vā veditabbā, diṭṭhinijjhānakkhantiyā vā veditabbā”ti?**Since this is so, are these things understood by faith, preference, oral tradition, reasoned contemplation, or acceptance of a view after consideration?”*";
P_HTM[3611]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3612]="*“Nanume, bhikkhave, dhammā paññāya disvā veditabbā”ti?**“Aren’t they understood by seeing them with wisdom?”*";
P_HTM[3613]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3614]="*“Ayampi kho, bhikkhave, pariyāyo yaṃ pariyāyaṃ āgamma bhikkhu aññatreva saddhāya, aññatra ruciyā, aññatra anussavā, aññatra ākāraparivitakkā, aññatra diṭṭhinijjhānakkhantiyā aññaṃ byākaroti:**“This too is a method—apart from faith, preference, oral tradition, reasoned contemplation, or acceptance of a view after consideration—that a mendicant can rely on to declare their enlightenment. That is:*";
P_HTM[3615]="*‘“khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti pajānāmī’ti.**‘I understand: “Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.”’”*";
P_HTM[3616]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3617]="*9. Indriyasampannasuttaṃ**Endowed With Faculties*";
P_HTM[3618]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha … and asked him,*";
P_HTM[3619]="*“‘indriyasampanno, indriyasampanno’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of someone who is ‘accomplished regarding the faculties’.*";
P_HTM[3620]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, indriyasampanno hotī”ti?**How is someone accomplished regarding the faculties defined?”*";
P_HTM[3621]="*“Cakkhundriye ce, bhikkhu, udayabbayānupassī viharanto cakkhundriye nibbindati … pe …**“Mendicant, if someone meditates observing rise and fall in the eye faculty, they grow disillusioned with the eye faculty.*";
P_HTM[3622]="*jivhindriye ce, bhikkhu, udayabbayānupassī viharanto jivhindriye nibbindati … pe …**If they meditate observing rise and fall in the ear faculty … nose faculty … tongue faculty … body faculty …*";
P_HTM[3623]="*manindriye ce, bhikkhu, udayabbayānupassī viharanto manindriye nibbindati.**mind faculty, they grow disillusioned with the mind faculty.*";
P_HTM[3624]="*Nibbindaṃ virajjati … pe … vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**Being disillusioned, desire fades away. … When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[3625]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[3626]="*Ettāvatā kho, bhikkhu, indriyasampanno hotī”ti.**This is how someone who is accomplished regarding the faculties is defined.”*";
P_HTM[3627]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3628]="*10. Dhammakathikapucchasuttaṃ**A Dhamma Speaker*";
P_HTM[3629]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha … and asked him,*";
P_HTM[3630]="*“‘dhammakathiko, dhammakathiko’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of a ‘Dhamma speaker’.*";
P_HTM[3631]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, dhammakathiko hotī”ti?**How is a Dhamma speaker defined?”*";
P_HTM[3632]="*“Cakkhussa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya dhammaṃ deseti, ‘dhammakathiko bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāya.**“If a mendicant teaches Dhamma for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding the eye, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who speaks on Dhamma’.*";
P_HTM[3633]="*Cakkhussa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hoti, ‘dhammānudhammappaṭipanno bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāya.**If they practice for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding the eye, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who practices in line with the teaching’.*";
P_HTM[3634]="*Cakkhussa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidā virāgā nirodhā anupādāvimutto hoti, ‘diṭṭhadhammanibbānappatto bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāya … pe …**If they’re freed by not grasping by disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding the eye, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who has attained extinguishment in this very life’.*";
P_HTM[3635]="*jivhāya ce, bhikkhu, nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya dhammaṃ deseti, ‘dhammakathiko bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāya … pe …**If a mendicant teaches Dhamma for disillusionment with the ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[3636]="*manassa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya dhammaṃ deseti, ‘dhammakathiko bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāya.**mind, for its fading away and cessation, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who speaks on Dhamma’.*";
P_HTM[3637]="*Manassa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hoti, ‘dhammānudhammappaṭipanno bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāya.**If they practice for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding the mind, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who practices in line with the teaching’.*";
P_HTM[3638]="*Manassa ce, bhikkhu, nibbidā virāgā nirodhā anupādāvimutto hoti, ‘diṭṭhadhammanibbānappatto bhikkhū’ti alaṃvacanāyā”ti.**If they’re freed by not grasping by disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding the mind, they’re qualified to be called a ‘mendicant who has attained extinguishment in this very life’.”*";
P_HTM[3639]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3640]="*Navapurāṇavaggo pañcamo.* **";
P_HTM[3641]="*Kammaṃ cattāri sappāyā,* **";
P_HTM[3642]="*anantevāsi kimatthiyā;* **";
P_HTM[3643]="*Atthi nu kho pariyāyo,* **";
P_HTM[3644]="*indriyakathikena cāti.* **";
P_HTM[3645]="*Saḷāyatanavagge tatiyapaṇṇāsako samatto.* **";
P_HTM[3646]="*Yogakkhemi ca loko ca,* **";
P_HTM[3647]="*Gahapati devadahena ca;* **";
P_HTM[3648]="*Navapurāṇena paṇṇāso,* **";
P_HTM[3649]="*Tatiyo tena vuccatīti.* **";
P_HTM[3650]="*16. Nandikkhayavaggo**The End of Relishing*";
P_HTM[3651]="*1. Ajjhattanandikkhayasuttaṃ**The Interior and the End of Relishing*";
P_HTM[3652]="*“Aniccaṃyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cakkhuṃ aniccanti passati, sāssa hoti sammādiṭṭhi.**“Mendicants, the eye really is impermanent. A mendicant sees that it is impermanent: that’s their right view.*";
P_HTM[3653]="*Sammā passaṃ nibbindati.**Seeing rightly, they grow disillusioned.*";
P_HTM[3654]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo;**When relishing ends, greed ends. When greed ends, relishing ends.*";
P_HTM[3655]="*rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.* **";
P_HTM[3656]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ suvimuttanti vuccati … pe …**When relishing and greed end, the mind is said to be well freed.*";
P_HTM[3657]="*aniccaṃyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhu jivhaṃ aniccanti passati, sāssa hoti sammādiṭṭhi.**The ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[3658]="*Sammā passaṃ nibbindati.* **";
P_HTM[3659]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo;* **";
P_HTM[3660]="*rāgakkhayā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3661]="*cittaṃ suvimuttanti vuccati … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3662]="*aniccaṃyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhu manaṃ aniccanti passati, sāssa hoti sammādiṭṭhi.**mind really is impermanent. A mendicant sees that it is impermanent: that’s their right view.*";
P_HTM[3663]="*Sammā passaṃ nibbindati.**Seeing rightly, they grow disillusioned.*";
P_HTM[3664]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo;**When relishing ends, greed ends. When greed ends, relishing ends.*";
P_HTM[3665]="*rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.* **";
P_HTM[3666]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ suvimuttanti vuccatī”ti.**When relishing and greed end, the mind is said to be well freed.”*";
P_HTM[3667]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3668]="*2. Bāhiranandikkhayasuttaṃ**The Exterior and the End of Relishing*";
P_HTM[3669]="*“Anicceyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhu rūpe aniccāti passati, sāssa hoti sammādiṭṭhi.**“Mendicants, sights really are impermanent. A mendicant sees that they are impermanent: that’s their right view.*";
P_HTM[3670]="*Sammā passaṃ nibbindati.**Seeing rightly, they grow disillusioned.*";
P_HTM[3671]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo;**When relishing ends, greed ends. When greed ends, relishing ends.*";
P_HTM[3672]="*rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.* **";
P_HTM[3673]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ suvimuttanti vuccati.**When relishing and greed end, the mind is said to be well freed.*";
P_HTM[3674]="*Anicceyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sadde …**Sounds …*";
P_HTM[3675]="*gandhe …**Smells …*";
P_HTM[3676]="*rase …**Tastes …*";
P_HTM[3677]="*phoṭṭhabbe …**Touches …*";
P_HTM[3678]="*dhamme aniccāti passati, sāssa hoti sammādiṭṭhi.**Thoughts really are impermanent. A mendicant sees that they are impermanent: that’s their right view.*";
P_HTM[3679]="*Sammā passaṃ nibbindati.**Seeing rightly, they grow disillusioned.*";
P_HTM[3680]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo;**When relishing ends, greed ends. When greed ends, relishing ends.*";
P_HTM[3681]="*rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.* **";
P_HTM[3682]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ suvimuttanti vuccatī”ti.**When relishing and greed end, the mind is said to be well freed.”*";
P_HTM[3683]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3684]="*3. Ajjhattaaniccanandikkhayasuttaṃ**Focus, the Interior, and the End of Relishing*";
P_HTM[3685]="*“Cakkhuṃ, bhikkhave, yoniso manasi karotha, cakkhāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassatha.**“Mendicants, properly attend to the eye. Truly see the impermanence of the eye.*";
P_HTM[3686]="*Cakkhuṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yoniso manasikaronto, cakkhāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassanto cakkhusmimpi nibbindati.**When a mendicant does this, they grow disillusioned with the eye.*";
P_HTM[3687]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo;**When relishing ends, greed ends. When greed ends, relishing ends.*";
P_HTM[3688]="*rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.* **";
P_HTM[3689]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ suvimuttanti vuccati.**When relishing and greed end, the mind is said to be well freed.*";
P_HTM[3690]="*Sotaṃ, bhikkhave, yoniso manasi karotha …**Properly attend to the ear …*";
P_HTM[3691]="*ghānaṃ …**nose …*";
P_HTM[3692]="*jivhaṃ, bhikkhave, yoniso manasi karotha, jivhāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassatha.**tongue …*";
P_HTM[3693]="*Jivhaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yoniso manasikaronto, jivhāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassanto jivhāyapi nibbindati.* **";
P_HTM[3694]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo;* **";
P_HTM[3695]="*rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.* **";
P_HTM[3696]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ suvimuttanti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[3697]="*Kāyaṃ …**body …*";
P_HTM[3698]="*manaṃ, bhikkhave, yoniso manasi karotha, manāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassatha.**mind. Truly see the impermanence of the mind.*";
P_HTM[3699]="*Manaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yoniso manasikaronto, manāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassanto manasmimpi nibbindati.**When a mendicant does this, they grow disillusioned with the mind.*";
P_HTM[3700]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo;**When relishing ends, greed ends. When greed ends, relishing ends.*";
P_HTM[3701]="*rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.* **";
P_HTM[3702]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ suvimuttanti vuccatī”ti.**When relishing and greed end, the mind is said to be well freed.”*";
P_HTM[3703]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3704]="*4. Bāhiraaniccanandikkhayasuttaṃ**Focus, the Exterior, and the End of Relishing*";
P_HTM[3705]="*“Rūpe, bhikkhave, yoniso manasi karotha, rūpāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassatha.**“Mendicants, properly attend to sights. Truly see the impermanence of sights.*";
P_HTM[3706]="*Rūpe, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yoniso manasikaronto, rūpāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassanto rūpesupi nibbindati.**When a mendicant does this, they grow disillusioned with sights.*";
P_HTM[3707]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo;**When relishing ends, greed ends. When greed ends, relishing ends.*";
P_HTM[3708]="*rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.* **";
P_HTM[3709]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ suvimuttanti vuccati.**When relishing and greed end, the mind is said to be well freed.*";
P_HTM[3710]="*Sadde …**Properly attend to sounds …*";
P_HTM[3711]="*gandhe …**smells …*";
P_HTM[3712]="*rase …**tastes …*";
P_HTM[3713]="*phoṭṭhabbe …**touches …*";
P_HTM[3714]="*dhamme, bhikkhave, yoniso manasi karotha, dhammāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassatha.**thoughts. Truly see the impermanence of thoughts.*";
P_HTM[3715]="*Dhamme, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yoniso manasikaronto, dhammāniccatañca yathābhūtaṃ samanupassanto dhammesupi nibbindati.**When a mendicant does this, they grow disillusioned with thoughts.*";
P_HTM[3716]="*Nandikkhayā rāgakkhayo;**When relishing ends, greed ends.*";
P_HTM[3717]="*rāgakkhayā nandikkhayo.**When greed ends, relishing ends.*";
P_HTM[3718]="*Nandirāgakkhayā cittaṃ suvimuttanti vuccatī”ti.**When relishing and greed end, the mind is said to be well freed.”*";
P_HTM[3719]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3720]="*5. Jīvakambavanasamādhisuttaṃ**On Immersion at Jīvaka’s Mango Grove*";
P_HTM[3721]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati jīvakambavane.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha in Jīvaka’s Mango Grove.*";
P_HTM[3722]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[3723]="*“bhikkhavo”ti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3724]="*“samādhiṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvetha.**“Mendicants, develop immersion.*";
P_HTM[3725]="*Samāhitassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati.**For a mendicant with immersion, things become truly clear.*";
P_HTM[3726]="*Kiñca yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati?**And what becomes truly clear?*";
P_HTM[3727]="*Cakkhuṃ aniccanti yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati, rūpā aniccāti yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati, cakkhuviññāṇaṃ aniccanti yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati, cakkhusamphasso aniccoti yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati, yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccanti yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati … pe …**It becomes truly clear that the eye, sights, eye consciousness, and eye contact are impermanent. And it also becomes truly clear that the painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[3728]="*jivhā aniccāti yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati … pe …**It becomes truly clear that the ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[3729]="*mano aniccoti yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati, dhammā aniccāti yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati … pe …**mind, thoughts, mind consciousness, and mind contact are impermanent.*";
P_HTM[3730]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccanti yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati.**And it also becomes truly clear that the painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[3731]="*Samādhiṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvetha.**Mendicants, develop immersion.*";
P_HTM[3732]="*Samāhitassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyatī”ti.**For a mendicant with immersion, things become truly clear.”*";
P_HTM[3733]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3734]="*6. Jīvakambavanapaṭisallānasuttaṃ**On Retreat at Jīvaka’s Mango Grove*";
P_HTM[3735]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati jīvakambavane.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha in Jīvaka’s Mango Grove.*";
P_HTM[3736]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi … pe …**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[3737]="*“paṭisallāne, bhikkhave, yogamāpajjatha.**“Mendicants, meditate in retreat.*";
P_HTM[3738]="*Paṭisallīnassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati.**For a mendicant who meditates in retreat, things become truly clear.*";
P_HTM[3739]="*Kiñca yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati?**And what becomes truly clear?*";
P_HTM[3740]="*Cakkhuṃ aniccanti yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati, rūpā aniccāti yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati, cakkhuviññāṇaṃ aniccanti yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati, cakkhusamphasso aniccoti yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati, yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccanti yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati … pe …**It becomes truly clear that the eye, sights, eye consciousness, and eye contact are impermanent. And it also becomes truly clear that the painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact is impermanent. …*";
P_HTM[3741]="*mano aniccoti yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati, dhammā …**It becomes truly clear that the mind, thoughts, mind consciousness, and mind contact are impermanent.*";
P_HTM[3742]="*manoviññāṇaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[3743]="*manosamphasso …* **";
P_HTM[3744]="*yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccanti yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyati.**And it also becomes truly clear that the painful, pleasant, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[3745]="*Paṭisallāne, bhikkhave, yogamāpajjatha.**Mendicants, meditate in retreat.*";
P_HTM[3746]="*Paṭisallīnassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno yathābhūtaṃ okkhāyatī”ti.**For a mendicant who meditates in retreat, things become truly clear.”*";
P_HTM[3747]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3748]="*7. Koṭṭhikaaniccasuttaṃ**With Koṭṭhita on Impermanence*";
P_HTM[3749]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahākoṭṭhiko yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā koṭṭhiko bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Mahākoṭṭhita went up to the Buddha … and asked him,*";
P_HTM[3750]="*“sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā saṃkhittena dhammaṃ desetu, yamahaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[3751]="*“Yaṃ kho, koṭṭhika, aniccaṃ tatra te chando pahātabbo.**“Koṭṭhita, you should give up desire for what is impermanent.*";
P_HTM[3752]="*Kiñca, koṭṭhika, aniccaṃ?**And what is impermanent?*";
P_HTM[3753]="*Cakkhu kho, koṭṭhika, aniccaṃ; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**The eye,*";
P_HTM[3754]="*Rūpā aniccā; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**sights,*";
P_HTM[3755]="*Cakkhuviññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**eye consciousness,*";
P_HTM[3756]="*Cakkhusamphasso anicco; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**and eye contact are impermanent: you should give up desire for them.*";
P_HTM[3757]="*Yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccaṃ; tatra te chando pahātabbo … pe …**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact is also impermanent: you should give up desire for it.*";
P_HTM[3758]="*jivhā aniccā; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**The ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[3759]="*Rasā aniccā; tatra te chando pahātabbo.* **";
P_HTM[3760]="*Jivhāviññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ; tatra te chando pahātabbo.* **";
P_HTM[3761]="*Jivhāsamphasso anicco; tatra te chando pahātabbo.* **";
P_HTM[3762]="*Yampidaṃ jivhāsamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccaṃ; tatra te chando pahātabbo … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3763]="*mano anicco; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**The mind,*";
P_HTM[3764]="*Dhammā aniccā; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**thoughts,*";
P_HTM[3765]="*Manoviññāṇaṃ aniccaṃ; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**mind consciousness,*";
P_HTM[3766]="*Manosamphasso anicco; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**and mind contact are impermanent: you should give up desire for them.*";
P_HTM[3767]="*Yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi aniccaṃ; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact is also impermanent: you should give up desire for it.*";
P_HTM[3768]="*Yaṃ kho, koṭṭhika, aniccaṃ tatra te chando pahātabbo”ti.**Koṭṭhita, you should give up desire for what is impermanent.”*";
P_HTM[3769]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3770]="*8. Koṭṭhikadukkhasuttaṃ**With Koṭṭhita on Suffering*";
P_HTM[3771]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahākoṭṭhiko … pe … bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Mahākoṭṭhita … said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3772]="*“sādhu me, bhante … pe … vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[3773]="*“Yaṃ kho, koṭṭhika, dukkhaṃ tatra te chando pahātabbo.**“Koṭṭhita, you should give up desire for what is suffering.*";
P_HTM[3774]="*Kiñca, koṭṭhika, dukkhaṃ?**And what is suffering?*";
P_HTM[3775]="*Cakkhu kho, koṭṭhika, dukkhaṃ; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**The eye,*";
P_HTM[3776]="*Rūpā dukkhā; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**sights,*";
P_HTM[3777]="*Cakkhuviññāṇaṃ dukkhaṃ; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**eye consciousness,*";
P_HTM[3778]="*Cakkhusamphasso dukkho; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**and eye contact are suffering: you should give up desire for them.*";
P_HTM[3779]="*Yampidaṃ cakkhusamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi dukkhaṃ; tatra te chando pahātabbo … pe …**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by eye contact is also suffering; you should give up desire for it.*";
P_HTM[3780]="*jivhā dukkhā; tatra te chando pahātabbo … pe …**The ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[3781]="*mano dukkho; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**The mind,*";
P_HTM[3782]="*Dhammā dukkhā; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**thoughts,*";
P_HTM[3783]="*Manoviññāṇaṃ dukkhaṃ; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**mind consciousness,*";
P_HTM[3784]="*Manosamphasso dukkho; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**and mind contact are suffering: you should give up desire for them.*";
P_HTM[3785]="*Yampidaṃ manosamphassapaccayā uppajjati vedayitaṃ sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā tampi dukkhaṃ; tatra te chando pahātabbo.**The pleasant, painful, or neutral feeling that arises conditioned by mind contact is also suffering: you should give up desire for it.*";
P_HTM[3786]="*Yaṃ kho, koṭṭhika, dukkhaṃ tatra te chando pahātabbo”ti.**Koṭṭhita, you should give up desire for what is suffering.”*";
