P_HTM[5240]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, telañca paṭicca vaṭṭiñca paṭicca telappadīpo jhāyeyya,**Suppose an oil lamp depended on oil and a wick to burn.*";
P_HTM[5241]="*tasseva telassa ca vaṭṭiyā ca pariyādānā anāhāro nibbāyeyya;**As the oil and the wick are used up, it would be extinguished due to lack of fuel.*";
P_HTM[5242]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāyapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayamāno ‘kāyapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayāmī’ti pajānāti. Jīvitapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayamāno ‘jīvitapariyantikaṃ vedanaṃ vedayāmī’ti pajānāti.**In the same way, feeling the end of the body approaching, a mendicant understands: ‘I feel the end of the body approaching.’ Feeling the end of life approaching, they understand: ‘I feel the end of life approaching.’*";
P_HTM[5243]="*‘Kāyassa bhedā uddhaṃ jīvitapariyādānā idheva sabbavedayitāni anabhinanditāni sītībhavissantī’ti pajānātī”ti.**They understand: ‘When my body breaks up and my life is over, everything that’s felt, since I no longer take pleasure in it, will become cool right here.’”*";
P_HTM[5244]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5245]="*9. Aniccasuttaṃ**Impermanent*";
P_HTM[5246]="*“Tisso imā, bhikkhave, vedanā aniccā saṅkhatā paṭiccasamuppannā khayadhammā vayadhammā virāgadhammā nirodhadhammā.**“Mendicants, these three feelings are impermanent, conditioned, dependently originated, liable to end, vanish, fade away, and cease.*";
P_HTM[5247]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[5248]="*Sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā—**Pleasant, painful, and neutral feeling.*";
P_HTM[5249]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, tisso vedanā aniccā saṅkhatā paṭiccasamuppannā khayadhammā vayadhammā virāgadhammā nirodhadhammā”ti.**These are the three feelings that are impermanent, conditioned, dependently originated, liable to end, vanish, fade away, and cease.”*";
P_HTM[5250]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5251]="*10. Phassamūlakasuttaṃ**Rooted in Contact*";
P_HTM[5252]="*“Tisso imā, bhikkhave, vedanā phassajā phassamūlakā phassanidānā phassapaccayā.**“Mendicants, these three feelings are born, rooted, sourced, and conditioned by contact.*";
P_HTM[5253]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[5254]="*Sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā.**Pleasant, painful, and neutral feeling.*";
P_HTM[5255]="*Sukhavedaniyaṃ, bhikkhave, phassaṃ paṭicca uppajjati sukhā vedanā.**Pleasant feeling arises dependent on a contact to be experienced as pleasant.*";
P_HTM[5256]="*Tasseva sukhavedaniyassa phassassa nirodhā, yaṃ tajjaṃ vedayitaṃ sukhavedaniyaṃ phassaṃ paṭicca uppannā sukhā vedanā, sā nirujjhati, sā vūpasammati.**With the cessation of that contact to be experienced as pleasant, the corresponding pleasant feeling ceases and stops.*";
P_HTM[5257]="*Dukkhavedaniyaṃ, bhikkhave, phassaṃ paṭicca uppajjati dukkhā vedanā.**Painful feeling arises dependent on a contact to be experienced as painful.*";
P_HTM[5258]="*Tasseva dukkhavedaniyassa phassassa nirodhā, yaṃ tajjaṃ vedayitaṃ dukkhavedaniyaṃ phassaṃ paṭicca uppannā dukkhā vedanā, sā nirujjhati, sā vūpasammati.**With the cessation of that contact to be experienced as painful, the corresponding painful feeling ceases and stops.*";
P_HTM[5259]="*Adukkhamasukhavedaniyaṃ, bhikkhave, phassaṃ paṭicca uppajjati adukkhamasukhā vedanā.**Neutral feeling arises dependent on a contact to be experienced as neutral.*";
P_HTM[5260]="*Tasseva adukkhamasukhavedaniyassa phassassa nirodhā, yaṃ tajjaṃ vedayitaṃ adukkhamasukhavedaniyaṃ phassaṃ paṭicca uppannā adukkhamasukhā vedanā, sā nirujjhati, sā vūpasammati.**With the cessation of that contact to be experienced as neutral, the corresponding neutral feeling ceases and stops.*";
P_HTM[5261]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, dvinnaṃ kaṭṭhānaṃ saṅghaṭṭanasamodhānā usmā jāyati, tejo abhinibbattati. Tesaṃyeva kaṭṭhānaṃ nānābhāvā vinikkhepā, yā tajjā usmā, sā nirujjhati, sā vūpasammati.**When you rub two sticks together, heat is generated and fire is produced. But when you part the sticks and lay them aside, any corresponding heat ceases and stops.*";
P_HTM[5262]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, imā tisso vedanā phassajā phassamūlakā phassanidānā phassapaccayā.**In the same way, these three feelings are born, rooted, sourced, and conditioned by contact.*";
P_HTM[5263]="*Tajjaṃ phassaṃ paṭicca tajjā vedanā uppajjanti.**The appropriate feeling arises dependent on the corresponding contact.*";
P_HTM[5264]="*Tajjassa phassassa nirodhā tajjā vedanā nirujjhantī”ti.**When the corresponding contact ceases, the appropriate feeling ceases.”*";
P_HTM[5265]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5266]="*Vedanāsaṃyuttassa sagāthāvaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[5267]="*Samādhi sukhaṃ pahānena,* **";
P_HTM[5268]="*pātālaṃ daṭṭhabbena ca;* **";
P_HTM[5269]="*Sallena ceva gelaññā,* **";
P_HTM[5270]="*anicca phassamūlakāti.* **";
P_HTM[5271]="*2. Yamakavaggo**In Private*";
P_HTM[5272]="*1. Rahogatasuttaṃ**In Private*";
P_HTM[5273]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[5274]="*“idha mayhaṃ, bhante, rahogatassa paṭisallīnassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi—**“Just now, sir, as I was in private retreat this thought came to mind.*";
P_HTM[5275]="*tisso vedanā vuttā bhagavatā.**The Buddha has spoken of three feelings.*";
P_HTM[5276]="*Sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā—**Pleasant, painful, and neutral feeling.*";
P_HTM[5277]="*imā tisso vedanā vuttā bhagavatā.**These are the three feelings the Buddha has spoken of.*";
P_HTM[5278]="*Vuttaṃ kho panetaṃ bhagavatā:**But the Buddha has also said:*";
P_HTM[5279]="*‘yaṃ kiñci vedayitaṃ taṃ dukkhasmin’ti.**‘Suffering includes whatever is felt.’*";
P_HTM[5280]="*Kiṃ nu kho etaṃ bhagavatā sandhāya bhāsitaṃ:**What was the Buddha referring to when he said this?”*";
P_HTM[5281]="*‘yaṃ kiñci vedayitaṃ taṃ dukkhasmin’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[5282]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhikkhu.**“Good, good, mendicant!*";
P_HTM[5283]="*Tisso imā, bhikkhu, vedanā vuttā mayā.**I have spoken of these three feelings.*";
P_HTM[5284]="*Sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā—**Pleasant, painful, and neutral feeling.*";
P_HTM[5285]="*imā tisso vedanā vuttā mayā.**These are the three feelings I have spoken of.*";
P_HTM[5286]="*Vuttaṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhu, mayā:**But I have also said:*";
P_HTM[5287]="*‘yaṃ kiñci vedayitaṃ, taṃ dukkhasmin’ti.**‘Suffering includes whatever is felt.’*";
P_HTM[5288]="*Taṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhu, mayā saṅkhārānaṃyeva aniccataṃ sandhāya bhāsitaṃ:**When I said this I was referring to the impermanence of conditions, to the fact that conditions are*";
P_HTM[5289]="*‘yaṃ kiñci vedayitaṃ taṃ dukkhasmin’ti.* **";
P_HTM[5290]="*Taṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhu, mayā saṅkhārānaṃyeva khayadhammataṃ … pe …**liable to end,*";
P_HTM[5291]="*vayadhammataṃ … pe …**vanish,*";
P_HTM[5292]="*virāgadhammataṃ … pe …**fade away,*";
P_HTM[5293]="*nirodhadhammataṃ … pe …**cease,*";
P_HTM[5294]="*vipariṇāmadhammataṃ sandhāya bhāsitaṃ:**and perish.*";
P_HTM[5295]="*‘yaṃ kiñci vedayitaṃ taṃ dukkhasmin’ti.* **";
P_HTM[5296]="*Atha kho pana, bhikkhu, mayā anupubbasaṅkhārānaṃ nirodho akkhāto.**But I have also explained the progressive cessation of conditions.*";
P_HTM[5297]="*Paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa vācā niruddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the first absorption, speech has ceased.*";
P_HTM[5298]="*Dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa vitakkavicārā niruddhā honti.**For someone who has attained the second absorption, the placing of the mind and keeping it connected have ceased.*";
P_HTM[5299]="*Tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa pīti niruddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the third absorption, rapture has ceased.*";
P_HTM[5300]="*Catutthaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa assāsapassāsā niruddhā honti.**For someone who has attained the fourth absorption, breathing has ceased.*";
P_HTM[5301]="*Ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samāpannassa rūpasaññā niruddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the dimension of infinite space, the perception of form has ceased.*";
P_HTM[5302]="*Viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samāpannassa ākāsānañcāyatanasaññā niruddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the dimension of infinite consciousness, the perception of the dimension of infinite space has ceased.*";
P_HTM[5303]="*Ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samāpannassa viññāṇañcāyatanasaññā niruddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the dimension of nothingness, the perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness has ceased.*";
P_HTM[5304]="*Nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samāpannassa ākiñcaññāyatanasaññā niruddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, the perception of the dimension of nothingness has ceased.*";
P_HTM[5305]="*Saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpannassa saññā ca vedanā ca niruddhā honti.**For someone who has attained the cessation of perception and feeling, perception and feeling have ceased.*";
P_HTM[5306]="*Khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno rāgo niruddho hoti, doso niruddho hoti, moho niruddho hoti.**For a mendicant who has ended the defilements, greed, hate, and delusion have ceased.*";
P_HTM[5307]="*Atha kho, bhikkhu, mayā anupubbasaṅkhārānaṃ vūpasamo akkhāto.**And I have also explained the progressive stilling of conditions.*";
P_HTM[5308]="*Paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa vācā vūpasantā hoti.**For someone who has attained the first absorption, speech has stilled.*";
P_HTM[5309]="*Dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa vitakkavicārā vūpasantā honti … pe …**For someone who has attained the second absorption, the placing of the mind and keeping it connected have stilled. …*";
P_HTM[5310]="*saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpannassa saññā ca vedanā ca vūpasantā honti.**For someone who has attained the cessation of perception and feeling, perception and feeling have stilled.*";
P_HTM[5311]="*Khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno rāgo vūpasanto hoti, doso vūpasanto hoti, moho vūpasanto hoti.**For a mendicant who has ended the defilements, greed, hate, and delusion have stilled.*";
P_HTM[5312]="*Chayimā, bhikkhu, passaddhiyo.**There are these six levels of tranquility.*";
P_HTM[5313]="*Paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa vācā paṭippassaddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the first absorption, speech has been tranquilized.*";
P_HTM[5314]="*Dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa vitakkavicārā paṭippassaddhā honti.**For someone who has attained the second absorption, the placing of the mind and keeping it connected have been tranquilized.*";
P_HTM[5315]="*Tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa pīti paṭippassaddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the third absorption, rapture has been tranquilized.*";
P_HTM[5316]="*Catutthaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa assāsapassāsā paṭippassaddhā honti.**For someone who has attained the fourth absorption, breathing has been tranquilized.*";
P_HTM[5317]="*Saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpannassa saññā ca vedanā ca paṭippassaddhā honti.**For someone who has attained the cessation of perception and feeling, perception and feeling have been tranquilized.*";
P_HTM[5318]="*Khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno rāgo paṭippassaddho hoti, doso paṭippassaddho hoti, moho paṭippassaddho hotī”ti.**For a mendicant who has ended the defilements, greed, hate, and delusion have been tranquilized.”*";
P_HTM[5319]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5320]="*2. Paṭhamaākāsasuttaṃ**In the Sky (1st)*";
P_HTM[5321]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ākāse vividhā vātā vāyanti.**“Mendicants, various winds blow in the sky.*";
P_HTM[5322]="*Puratthimāpi vātā vāyanti, pacchimāpi vātā vāyanti, uttarāpi vātā vāyanti, dakkhiṇāpi vātā vāyanti, sarajāpi vātā vāyanti, arajāpi vātā vāyanti, sītāpi vātā vāyanti, uṇhāpi vātā vāyanti, parittāpi vātā vāyanti, adhimattāpi vātā vāyanti.**Winds blow from the east, the west, the north, and the south. There are winds that are dusty and dustless, cool and warm, weak and strong.*";
P_HTM[5323]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, imasmiṃ kāyasmiṃ vividhā vedanā uppajjanti, sukhāpi vedanā uppajjati, dukkhāpi vedanā uppajjati, adukkhamasukhāpi vedanā uppajjatīti.**In the same way, various feelings arise in this body: pleasant, painful, and neutral feelings.*";
P_HTM[5324]="*Yathāpi vātā ākāse,**There are many and various*";
P_HTM[5325]="*vāyanti vividhā puthū;**winds that blow in the sky.*";
P_HTM[5326]="*Puratthimā pacchimā cāpi,**From the east they come, also the west,*";
P_HTM[5327]="*uttarā atha dakkhiṇā.**the north, and then the south.*";
P_HTM[5328]="*Sarajā arajā capi,**They are dusty and dustless,*";
P_HTM[5329]="*sītā uṇhā ca ekadā;**cool and sometimes warm,*";
P_HTM[5330]="*Adhimattā parittā ca,**strong and weak;*";
P_HTM[5331]="*puthū vāyanti mālutā.**these are the different breezes that blow.*";
P_HTM[5332]="*Tathevimasmiṃ kāyasmiṃ,**So too, in this body*";
P_HTM[5333]="*samuppajjanti vedanā;**feelings arise,*";
P_HTM[5334]="*Sukhadukkhasamuppatti,**pleasant and painful,*";
P_HTM[5335]="*adukkhamasukhā ca yā.**and those that are neutral.*";
P_HTM[5336]="*Yato ca bhikkhu ātāpī,**But when a mendicant is keen,*";
P_HTM[5337]="*sampajaññaṃ na riñcati;**not neglecting situational awareness,*";
P_HTM[5338]="*Tato so vedanā sabbā,**that astute person*";
P_HTM[5339]="*parijānāti paṇḍito.**understands all feelings.*";
P_HTM[5340]="*So vedanā pariññāya,**Completely understanding feelings,*";
P_HTM[5341]="*diṭṭhe dhamme anāsavo;**they’re without defilements in this very life.*";
P_HTM[5342]="*Kāyassa bhedā dhammaṭṭho,**That knowledge-master is grounded in the teaching;*";
P_HTM[5343]="*saṅkhyaṃ nopeti vedagū”ti.**when their body breaks up, they can’t be reckoned.”*";
P_HTM[5344]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5345]="*3. Dutiyaākāsasuttaṃ**In the Sky (2nd)*";
P_HTM[5346]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ākāse vividhā vātā vāyanti.**“Mendicants, various winds blow in the sky.*";
P_HTM[5347]="*Puratthimāpi vātā vāyanti … pe … adhimattāpi vātā vāyanti.**Winds blow from the east, the west, the north, and the south. There are winds that are dusty and dustless, cool and warm, weak and strong.*";
P_HTM[5348]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, imasmiṃ kāyasmiṃ vividhā vedanā uppajjanti, sukhāpi vedanā uppajjati, dukkhāpi vedanā uppajjati, adukkhamasukhāpi vedanā uppajjatī”ti.**In the same way, various feelings arise in this body: pleasant, painful, and neutral feelings.”*";
P_HTM[5349]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5350]="*4. Agārasuttaṃ**A Guest House*";
P_HTM[5351]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, āgantukāgāraṃ. Tattha puratthimāyapi disāya āgantvā vāsaṃ kappenti, pacchimāyapi disāya āgantvā vāsaṃ kappenti, uttarāyapi disāya āgantvā vāsaṃ kappenti, dakkhiṇāyapi disāya āgantvā vāsaṃ kappenti. Khattiyāpi āgantvā vāsaṃ kappenti, brāhmaṇāpi āgantvā vāsaṃ kappenti, vessāpi āgantvā vāsaṃ kappenti, suddāpi āgantvā vāsaṃ kappenti.**“Mendicants, suppose there was a guest house. Lodgers come from the east, west, north, and south. Aristocrats, brahmins, merchants, and workers all stay there.*";
P_HTM[5352]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, imasmiṃ kāyasmiṃ vividhā vedanā uppajjanti. Sukhāpi vedanā uppajjati, dukkhāpi vedanā uppajjati, adukkhamasukhāpi vedanā uppajjati.**In the same way, various feelings arise in this body: pleasant, painful, and neutral feelings.*";
P_HTM[5353]="*Sāmisāpi sukhā vedanā uppajjati, sāmisāpi dukkhā vedanā uppajjati, sāmisāpi adukkhamasukhā vedanā uppajjati.**Also material pleasant, painful, and neutral feelings arise.*";
P_HTM[5354]="*Nirāmisāpi sukhā vedanā uppajjati, nirāmisāpi dukkhā vedanā uppajjati, nirāmisāpi adukkhamasukhā vedanā uppajjatī”ti.**Also spiritual pleasant, painful, and neutral feelings arise.”*";
P_HTM[5355]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5356]="*5. Paṭhamaānandasuttaṃ**With Ānanda (1st)*";
P_HTM[5357]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi, ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Ānanda went up to the Buddha … sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[5358]="*“katamā nu kho, bhante, vedanā, katamo vedanāsamudayo, katamo vedanānirodho, katamā vedanānirodhagāminī paṭipadā?**“Sir, what is feeling? What’s the origin of feeling? What’s the cessation of feeling? What’s the practice that leads to the cessation of feeling?*";
P_HTM[5359]="*Ko vedanāya assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇan”ti?**And what is feeling’s gratification, drawback, and escape?”*";
P_HTM[5360]="*“Tisso imā, ānanda, vedanā—**“Ānanda, there are these three feelings:*";
P_HTM[5361]="*sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā—**pleasant, painful, and neutral.*";
P_HTM[5362]="*imā vuccanti, ānanda, vedanā.**These are called feeling.*";
P_HTM[5363]="*Phassasamudayā vedanāsamudayo;**Feeling originates from contact.*";
P_HTM[5364]="*phassanirodhā vedanānirodho.**When contact ceases, feeling ceases.*";
P_HTM[5365]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo vedanānirodhagāminī paṭipadā, seyyathidaṃ—**The practice that leads to the cessation of feelings is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[5366]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[5367]="*Yaṃ vedanaṃ paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ, ayaṃ vedanāya assādo.**The pleasure and happiness that arise from feeling: this is its gratification.*";
P_HTM[5368]="*Yaṃ vedanā aniccā dukkhā vipariṇāmadhammā, ayaṃ vedanāya ādīnavo.**That feeling is impermanent, suffering, and perishable: this is its drawback.*";
P_HTM[5369]="*Yo vedanāya chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ, idaṃ vedanāya nissaraṇaṃ.**Removing and giving up desire and greed for feeling: this is its escape.*";
P_HTM[5370]="*Atha kho panānanda, mayā anupubbasaṅkhārānaṃ nirodho akkhāto.**But I have also explained the progressive cessation of conditions.*";
P_HTM[5371]="*Paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa vācā niruddhā hoti … pe …**For someone who has attained the first absorption, speech has ceased. …*";
P_HTM[5372]="*saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpannassa saññā ca vedanā ca niruddhā honti.**For someone who has attained the cessation of perception and feeling, perception and feeling have ceased.*";
P_HTM[5373]="*Khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno rāgo niruddho hoti, doso niruddho hoti, moho niruddho hoti.**For a mendicant who has ended the defilements, greed, hate, and delusion have ceased.*";
P_HTM[5374]="*Atha kho panānanda, mayā anupubbasaṅkhārānaṃ vūpasamo akkhāto.**And I have also explained the progressive stilling of conditions.*";
P_HTM[5375]="*Paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa vācā vūpasantā hoti … pe …**For someone who has attained the first absorption, speech has stilled. …*";
P_HTM[5376]="*saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpannassa saññā ca vedanā ca vūpasantā honti.**For someone who has attained the cessation of perception and feeling, perception and feeling have stilled.*";
P_HTM[5377]="*Khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno rāgo vūpasanto hoti, doso vūpasanto hoti, moho vūpasanto hoti.**For a mendicant who has ended the defilements, greed, hate, and delusion have stilled.*";
P_HTM[5378]="*Atha kho panānanda, mayā anupubbasaṅkhārānaṃ paṭippassaddhi akkhātā.**And I have also explained the progressive tranquilizing of conditions.*";
P_HTM[5379]="*Paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa vācā paṭippassaddhā hoti … pe …**For someone who has attained the first absorption, speech has been tranquilized. …*";
P_HTM[5380]="*ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samāpannassa rūpasaññā paṭippassaddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the dimension of infinite space, the perception of form has been tranquilized.*";
P_HTM[5381]="*Viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samāpannassa ākāsānañcāyatanasaññā paṭippassaddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the dimension of infinite consciousness, the perception of the dimension of infinite space has been tranquilized.*";
P_HTM[5382]="*Ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samāpannassa viññāṇañcāyatanasaññā paṭippassaddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the dimension of nothingness, the perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness has been tranquilized.*";
P_HTM[5383]="*Nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samāpannassa ākiñcaññāyatanasaññā paṭippassaddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, the perception of the dimension of nothingness has been tranquilized.*";
P_HTM[5384]="*Saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpannassa saññā ca vedanā ca paṭippassaddhā honti.**For someone who has attained the cessation of perception and feeling, perception and feeling have been tranquilized.*";
P_HTM[5385]="*Khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno rāgo paṭippassaddho hoti, doso paṭippassaddho hoti, moho paṭippassaddho hotī”ti.**For a mendicant who has ended the defilements, greed, hate, and delusion have been tranquilized.”*";
P_HTM[5386]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5387]="*6. Dutiyaānandasuttaṃ**With Ānanda (2nd)*";
P_HTM[5388]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**Then Venerable Ānanda went up to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side. The Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[5389]="*“katamā nu kho, ānanda, vedanā, katamo vedanāsamudayo, katamo vedanānirodho, katamā vedanānirodhagāminī paṭipadā?**“Ānanda, what is feeling? What’s the origin of feeling? What’s the cessation of feeling? What’s the practice that leads to the cessation of feeling?*";
P_HTM[5390]="*Ko vedanāya assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇan”ti?**And what is feeling’s gratification, drawback, and escape?”*";
P_HTM[5391]="*“Bhagavaṃmūlakā no, bhante, dhammā bhagavaṃnettikā bhagavaṃpaṭisaraṇā. Sādhu, bhante, bhagavantaññeva paṭibhātu etassa bhāsitassa attho. Bhagavato sutvā bhikkhū dhāressantī”ti.**“Our teachings are rooted in the Buddha. He is our guide and our refuge. Sir, may the Buddha himself please clarify the meaning of this. The mendicants will listen and remember it.”*";
P_HTM[5392]="*“Tena hi, ānanda, suṇohi, sādhukaṃ manasi karohi; bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, Ānanda, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[5393]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[5394]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[5395]="*“tisso imā, ānanda, vedanā—**“Ānanda, there are these three feelings:*";
P_HTM[5396]="*sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā—**pleasant, painful, and neutral.*";
P_HTM[5397]="*imā vuccanti, ānanda, vedanā … pe …**These are called feeling. …*";
P_HTM[5398]="*phassasamudayā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5399]="*khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno rāgo paṭippassaddho hoti, doso paṭippassaddho hoti, moho paṭippassaddho hotī”ti.**For a mendicant who has ended the defilements, greed, hate, and delusion have been tranquilized.”*";
P_HTM[5400]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5401]="*7. Paṭhamasambahulasuttaṃ**With Several Mendicants (1st)*";
P_HTM[5402]="*Atha kho sambahulā bhikkhū yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then several mendicants went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[5403]="*“katamā nu kho, bhante, vedanā, katamo vedanāsamudayo, katamo vedanānirodho, katamā vedanānirodhagāminī paṭipadā?**“Sir, what is feeling? What’s the origin of feeling? What’s the cessation of feeling? What’s the practice that leads to the cessation of feeling?*";
P_HTM[5404]="*Ko vedanāya assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇan”ti?**And what is feeling’s gratification, drawback, and escape?”*";
P_HTM[5405]="*“Tisso imā, bhikkhave, vedanā—**“Mendicants, there are these three feelings:*";
P_HTM[5406]="*sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā—**pleasant, painful, and neutral.*";
P_HTM[5407]="*imā vuccanti, bhikkhave, vedanā.**These are called feeling.*";
P_HTM[5408]="*Phassasamudayā vedanāsamudayo;**Feeling originates from contact.*";
P_HTM[5409]="*phassanirodhā vedanānirodho.**When contact ceases, feeling ceases.*";
P_HTM[5410]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo vedanānirodhagāminī paṭipadā, seyyathidaṃ—**The practice that leads to the cessation of feelings is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[5411]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[5412]="*Yaṃ vedanaṃ paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ, ayaṃ vedanāya assādo.**The pleasure and happiness that arise from feeling: this is its gratification.*";
P_HTM[5413]="*Yaṃ vedanā aniccā dukkhā vipariṇāmadhammā, ayaṃ vedanāya ādīnavo.**That feeling is impermanent, suffering, and perishable: this is its drawback.*";
P_HTM[5414]="*Yo vedanāya chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ, idaṃ vedanāya nissaraṇaṃ.**Removing and giving up desire and greed for feeling: this is its escape.*";
P_HTM[5415]="*Atha kho pana, bhikkhave, mayā anupubbasaṅkhārānaṃ nirodho akkhāto.**But I have also explained the progressive cessation of conditions. …*";
P_HTM[5416]="*Paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa vācā niruddhā hoti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5417]="*khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno rāgo niruddho hoti, doso niruddho hoti, moho niruddho hoti.* **";
P_HTM[5418]="*Atha kho pana, bhikkhave, mayā anupubbasaṅkhārānaṃ vūpasamo akkhāto.* **";
P_HTM[5419]="*Paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa vācā vūpasantā hoti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5420]="*khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno rāgo vūpasanto hoti, doso vūpasanto hoti, moho vūpasanto hoti.* **";
P_HTM[5421]="*Chayimā, bhikkhave, passaddhiyo.* **";
P_HTM[5422]="*Paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa vācā paṭippassaddhā hoti.* **";
P_HTM[5423]="*Dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa vitakkavicārā paṭippassaddhā honti.* **";
P_HTM[5424]="*Tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa pīti paṭippassaddhā hoti.* **";
P_HTM[5425]="*Catutthaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa assāsapassāsā paṭippassaddhā honti.* **";
P_HTM[5426]="*Saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpannassa saññā ca vedanā ca paṭippassaddhā honti.* **";
P_HTM[5427]="*Khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno rāgo paṭippassaddho hoti, doso paṭippassaddho hoti, moho paṭippassaddho hotī”ti.**For a mendicant who has ended the defilements, greed, hate, and delusion have been tranquilized.”*";
P_HTM[5428]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5429]="*8. Dutiyasambahulasuttaṃ**With Several Mendicants (2nd)*";
P_HTM[5430]="*Atha kho sambahulā bhikkhū yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu … pe …**Then several mendicants went up to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[5431]="*ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said to them:*";
P_HTM[5432]="*“katamā nu kho, bhikkhave, vedanā, katamo vedanāsamudayo, katamo vedanānirodho, katamā vedanānirodhagāminī paṭipadā?**“Mendicants, what is feeling? What’s the origin of feeling? What’s the cessation of feeling? What’s the practice that leads to the cessation of feeling?*";
P_HTM[5433]="*Ko vedanāya assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇan”ti?**And what is feeling’s gratification, drawback, and escape?”*";
P_HTM[5434]="*“Bhagavaṃmūlakā no, bhante, dhammā … pe …”**“Our teachings are rooted in the Buddha. …”*";
P_HTM[5435]="*“tisso imā, bhikkhave, vedanā—**“Mendicants, there are these three feelings:*";
P_HTM[5436]="*sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā—**pleasant, painful, and neutral.*";
P_HTM[5437]="*imā vuccanti, bhikkhave, vedanā … pe … phassasamudayā … pe ….**These are called feeling. …”*";
P_HTM[5438]="*(Yathā purimasuttante, tathā vitthāretabbo.)**(This should be told in full as in the previous discourse.)*";
P_HTM[5439]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5440]="*9. Pañcakaṅgasuttaṃ**With Pañcakaṅga*";
P_HTM[5441]="*Atha kho pañcakaṅgo thapati yenāyasmā udāyī tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ udāyiṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho pañcakaṅgo thapati āyasmantaṃ udāyiṃ etadavoca:**Then the master builder Pañcakaṅga went up to Venerable Udāyī, bowed, sat down to one side, and asked him,*";
P_HTM[5442]="*“kati nu kho, bhante udāyi, vedanā vuttā bhagavatā”ti?**“Sir, how many feelings has the Buddha spoken of?”*";
P_HTM[5443]="*“Tisso kho, thapati, vedanā vuttā bhagavatā.**“Master builder, the Buddha has spoken of three feelings:*";
P_HTM[5444]="*Sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā—**pleasant, painful, and neutral.*";
P_HTM[5445]="*imā kho, thapati, tisso vedanā vuttā bhagavatā”ti.**The Buddha has spoken of these three feelings.”*";
P_HTM[5446]="*Evaṃ vutte, pañcakaṅgo thapati āyasmantaṃ udāyiṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Pañcakaṅga said to Udāyī,*";
P_HTM[5447]="*“na kho, bhante udāyi, tisso vedanā vuttā bhagavatā.**“Sir, Udāyī, the Buddha hasn’t spoken of three feelings.*";
P_HTM[5448]="*Dve vedanā vuttā bhagavatā—**He’s spoken of two feelings:*";
P_HTM[5449]="*sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā.**pleasant and painful.*";
P_HTM[5450]="*Yāyaṃ, bhante, adukkhamasukhā vedanā, santasmiṃ esā paṇīte sukhe vuttā bhagavatā”ti.**The Buddha said that neutral feeling is included as a peaceful and subtle kind of pleasure.”*";
P_HTM[5451]="*Dutiyampi kho āyasmā udāyī pañcakaṅgaṃ thapatiṃ etadavoca:**For a second time, Udāyī said to him,*";
P_HTM[5452]="*“na kho, thapati, dve vedanā vuttā bhagavatā.**“The Buddha hasn’t spoken of two feelings,*";
P_HTM[5453]="*Tisso vedanā vuttā bhagavatā.**he’s spoken of three.”*";
P_HTM[5454]="*Sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā—* **";
P_HTM[5455]="*imā tisso vedanā vuttā bhagavatā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5456]="*Dutiyampi kho pañcakaṅgo thapati āyasmantaṃ udāyiṃ etadavoca:**For a second time, Pañcakaṅga said to Udāyī,*";
P_HTM[5457]="*“na kho, bhante udāyi, tisso vedanā vuttā bhagavatā.**“The Buddha hasn’t spoken of three feelings,*";
P_HTM[5458]="*Dve vedanā vuttā bhagavatā—**he’s spoken of two.”*";
P_HTM[5459]="*sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā.* **";
P_HTM[5460]="*Yāyaṃ, bhante, adukkhamasukhā vedanā, santasmiṃ esā paṇīte sukhe vuttā bhagavatā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5461]="*Tatiyampi kho āyasmā udāyī pañcakaṅgaṃ thapatiṃ etadavoca:**And for a third time, Udāyī said to him,*";
P_HTM[5462]="*“na kho, thapati, dve vedanā vuttā bhagavatā.**“The Buddha hasn’t spoken of two feelings,*";
P_HTM[5463]="*Tisso vedanā vuttā bhagavatā.**he’s spoken of three.”*";
P_HTM[5464]="*Sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā—* **";
P_HTM[5465]="*imā tisso vedanā vuttā bhagavatā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5466]="*Tatiyampi kho pañcakaṅgo thapati āyasmantaṃ udāyiṃ etadavoca:**And for a third time, Pañcakaṅga said to Udāyī,*";
P_HTM[5467]="*“na kho, bhante udāyi, tisso vedanā vuttā bhagavatā.**“The Buddha hasn’t spoken of three feelings,*";
P_HTM[5468]="*Dve vedanā vuttā bhagavatā—**he’s spoken of two.”*";
P_HTM[5469]="*sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā.* **";
P_HTM[5470]="*Yāyaṃ, bhante, adukkhamasukhā vedanā, santasmiṃ esā paṇīte sukhe vuttā bhagavatā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5471]="*Neva sakkhi āyasmā udāyī pañcakaṅgaṃ thapatiṃ saññāpetuṃ, na panāsakkhi pañcakaṅgo thapati āyasmantaṃ udāyiṃ saññāpetuṃ.**But neither was able to persuade the other.*";
P_HTM[5472]="*Assosi kho āyasmā ānando āyasmato udāyissa pañcakaṅgena thapatinā saddhiṃ imaṃ kathāsallāpaṃ.**Venerable Ānanda heard this discussion between Udāyī and Pañcakaṅga.*";
P_HTM[5473]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**He went to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side,*";
P_HTM[5474]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando yāvatako āyasmato udāyissa pañcakaṅgena thapatinā saddhiṃ ahosi kathāsallāpo taṃ sabbaṃ bhagavato ārocesi.**and informed the Buddha of all they had discussed.*";
P_HTM[5475]="*“Santameva, ānanda, pariyāyaṃ pañcakaṅgo thapati udāyissa bhikkhuno nābbhanumodi;**“Ānanda, the explanation by the mendicant Udāyī, which the master builder Pañcakaṅga didn’t agree with, was quite correct.*";
P_HTM[5476]="*santañca panānanda, pariyāyaṃ udāyī bhikkhu pañcakaṅgassa thapatino nābbhanumodi.**But the explanation by Pañcakaṅga, which Udāyī didn’t agree with, was also quite correct.*";
P_HTM[5477]="*Dvepi mayā, ānanda, vedanā vuttā pariyāyena.**In one explanation I’ve spoken of two feelings. In another explanation I’ve spoken of three feelings, or five, six, eighteen, thirty-six, or a hundred and eight feelings.*";
P_HTM[5478]="*Tissopi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena.* **";
P_HTM[5479]="*Pañcapi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena.* **";
P_HTM[5480]="*Chapi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena.* **";
P_HTM[5481]="*Aṭṭhārasāpi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena.* **";
P_HTM[5482]="*Chattiṃsāpi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena.* **";
P_HTM[5483]="*Aṭṭhasatampi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena.* **";
P_HTM[5484]="*Evaṃ pariyāyadesito kho, ānanda, mayā dhammo.**I’ve explained the teaching in all these different ways.*";
P_HTM[5485]="*Evaṃ pariyāyadesite kho, ānanda, mayā dhamme ye aññamaññassa subhāsitaṃ sulapitaṃ, na samanumaññissanti, na samanujānissanti, na samanumodissanti, tesaṃ etaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ—bhaṇḍanajātā kalahajātā vivādāpannā aññamaññaṃ mukhasattīhi vitudantā viharissantīti.**This being so, you can expect that those who don’t concede, approve, or agree with what has been well spoken will argue, quarrel, and fight, continually wounding each other with barbed words.*";
P_HTM[5486]="*Evaṃ pariyāyadesito kho, ānanda, mayā dhammo.**I’ve explained the teaching in all these different ways.*";
P_HTM[5487]="*Evaṃ pariyāyadesite kho, ānanda, mayā dhamme ye aññamaññassa subhāsitaṃ sulapitaṃ samanumaññissanti samanujānissanti samanumodissanti, tesaṃ etaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ—samaggā sammodamānā avivadamānā khīrodakībhūtā aññamaññaṃ piyacakkhūhi sampassantā viharissantīti.**This being so, you can expect that those who do concede, approve, or agree with what has been well spoken will live in harmony, appreciating each other, without quarreling, blending like milk and water, and regarding each other with kindly eyes.*";
P_HTM[5488]="*Pañcime, ānanda, kāmaguṇā.**There are these five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[5489]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[5490]="*Cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā … pe …**Sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing. …*";
P_HTM[5491]="*kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**Touches known by the body that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[5492]="*Ime kho, ānanda, pañca kāmaguṇā.**These are the five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[5493]="*Yaṃ kho, ānanda, ime pañca kāmaguṇe paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ—**The pleasure and happiness that arise from these five kinds of sensual stimulation is called sensual pleasure.*";
P_HTM[5494]="*idaṃ vuccati kāmasukhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5495]="*Ye kho, ānanda, evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**There are those who would say*";
P_HTM[5496]="*‘etapparamaṃ santaṃ sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedentī’ti—**that this is the highest pleasure and happiness that sentient beings experience.*";
P_HTM[5497]="*idaṃ nesāhaṃ nānujānāmi.**But I don’t acknowledge that.*";
P_HTM[5498]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[5499]="*Atthānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**Because there is another pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5500]="*Katamañcānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca?**And what is that pleasure?*";
P_HTM[5501]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[5502]="*Idaṃ kho, ānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This is a pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5503]="*Ye kho, ānanda, evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**There are those who would say*";
P_HTM[5504]="*‘etapparamaṃ santaṃ sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedentī’ti—**that this is the highest pleasure and happiness that sentient beings experience.*";
P_HTM[5505]="*idaṃ nesāhaṃ nānujānāmi.**But I don’t acknowledge that.*";
P_HTM[5506]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[5507]="*Atthānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**Because there is another pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5508]="*Katamañcānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca?**And what is that pleasure?*";
P_HTM[5509]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu, vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when, as the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, a mendicant enters and remains in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[5510]="*Idaṃ kho, ānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This is a pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5511]="*Ye kho, ānanda, evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**There are those who would say*";
P_HTM[5512]="*‘etapparamaṃ santaṃ sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedentī’ti—**that this is the highest pleasure and happiness that sentient beings experience.*";
P_HTM[5513]="*idaṃ nesāhaṃ nānujānāmi.**But I don’t acknowledge that.*";
P_HTM[5514]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[5515]="*Atthānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**Because there is another pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5516]="*Katamañcānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca?**And what is that pleasure?*";
P_HTM[5517]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati sato ca sampajāno, sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedeti, yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti: ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when, with the fading away of rapture, a mendicant enters and remains in the third absorption, where they meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[5518]="*Idaṃ kho, ānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This is a pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5519]="*Ye kho, ānanda, evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**There are those who would say*";
P_HTM[5520]="*‘etapparamaṃ santaṃ sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedentī’ti—**that this is the highest pleasure and happiness that sentient beings experience.*";
P_HTM[5521]="*idaṃ nesāhaṃ nānujānāmi.**But I don’t acknowledge that.*";
P_HTM[5522]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[5523]="*Atthānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**Because there is another pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5524]="*Katamañcānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca?**And what is that pleasure?*";
P_HTM[5525]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when, giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, a mendicant enters and remains in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[5526]="*Idaṃ kho, ānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This is a pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5527]="*Ye kho, ānanda, evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**There are those who would say*";
P_HTM[5528]="*‘etapparamaṃ santaṃ sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedentī’ti—**that this is the highest pleasure and happiness that sentient beings experience.*";
P_HTM[5529]="*idaṃ nesāhaṃ nānujānāmi.**But I don’t acknowledge that.*";
P_HTM[5530]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[5531]="*Atthānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**Because there is another pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5532]="*Katamañcānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca?**And what is that pleasure?*";
P_HTM[5533]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā, paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā, nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā, ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant—going totally beyond perceptions of form, with the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity—aware that ‘space is infinite’, enters and remains in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[5534]="*Idaṃ kho, ānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This is a pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5535]="*Ye kho, ānanda, evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**There are those who would say*";
P_HTM[5536]="*‘etapparamaṃ santaṃ sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedentī’ti—**that this is the highest pleasure and happiness that sentient beings experience.*";
P_HTM[5537]="*idaṃ nesāhaṃ nānujānāmi.**But I don’t acknowledge that.*";
P_HTM[5538]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[5539]="*Atthānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**Because there is another pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5540]="*Katamañcānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca?**And what is that pleasure?*";
P_HTM[5541]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma, ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant, going totally beyond the dimension of infinite space, aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, enters and remains in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5542]="*Idaṃ kho, ānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This is a pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5543]="*Ye kho, ānanda, evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**There are those who would say*";
P_HTM[5544]="*‘etapparamaṃ santaṃ sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedentī’ti—**that this is the highest pleasure and happiness that sentient beings experience.*";
P_HTM[5545]="*idaṃ nesāhaṃ nānujānāmi.**But I don’t acknowledge that.*";
P_HTM[5546]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[5547]="*Atthānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**Because there is another pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5548]="*Katamañcānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca?**And what is that pleasure?*";
P_HTM[5549]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma, ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant, going totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness, aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, enters and remains in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[5550]="*Idaṃ kho, ānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This is a pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5551]="*Ye kho, ānanda, evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**There are those who would say*";
P_HTM[5552]="*‘etapparamaṃ santaṃ sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedentī’ti—**that this is the highest pleasure and happiness that sentient beings experience.*";
P_HTM[5553]="*idaṃ nesāhaṃ nānujānāmi.**But I don’t acknowledge that.*";
P_HTM[5554]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[5555]="*Atthānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**Because there is another pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5556]="*Katamañcānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca?**And what is that pleasure?*";
P_HTM[5557]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant, going totally beyond the dimension of nothingness, enters and remains in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[5558]="*Idaṃ kho, ānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This is a pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5559]="*Ye kho, ānanda, evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**There are those who would say*";
P_HTM[5560]="*‘etapparamaṃ santaṃ sukhaṃ somanassaṃ paṭisaṃvedentī’ti—**that this is the highest pleasure and happiness that sentient beings experience.*";
P_HTM[5561]="*idaṃ nesāhaṃ nānujānāmi.**But I don’t acknowledge that.*";
P_HTM[5562]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[5563]="*Atthānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**Because there is another pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5564]="*Katamañcānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca?**And what is that pleasure?*";
P_HTM[5565]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant, going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, enters and remains in the cessation of perception and feeling.*";
P_HTM[5566]="*Idaṃ kho, ānanda, etamhā sukhā aññaṃ sukhaṃ abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This is a pleasure that is finer than that.*";
P_HTM[5567]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, ānanda, vijjati yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that wanderers who follow other paths might say:*";
P_HTM[5568]="*‘saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samaṇo gotamo āha, tañca sukhasmiṃ paññapeti.**‘The ascetic Gotama spoke of the cessation of perception and feeling, and he includes it in happiness.*";
P_HTM[5569]="*Tayidaṃ kiṃsu, tayidaṃ kathaṃsū’ti?**What’s up with that?’*";
P_HTM[5570]="*Evaṃvādino, ānanda, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evamassu vacanīyā:**When wanderers who follow other paths say this, you should say to them:*";
P_HTM[5571]="*‘na kho, āvuso, bhagavā sukhaññeva vedanaṃ sandhāya sukhasmiṃ paññapeti.**‘Reverends, when the Buddha describes what’s included in happiness, he’s not just referring to pleasant feeling.*";
P_HTM[5572]="*Yattha yattha, āvuso, sukhaṃ upalabbhati, yahiṃ yahiṃ, taṃ taṃ tathāgato sukhasmiṃ paññapetī’”ti.**The Realized One describes pleasure as included in happiness wherever it’s found, and in whatever context.’”*";
P_HTM[5573]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5574]="*10. Bhikkhusuttaṃ**A Mendicant*";
P_HTM[5575]="*“Dvepi mayā, bhikkhave, vedanā vuttā pariyāyena, tissopi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena, pañcapi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena, chapi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena, aṭṭhārasāpi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena, chattiṃsāpi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena, aṭṭhasatampi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena.**“Mendicants, in one explanation I’ve spoken of two feelings. In another explanation I’ve spoken of three feelings, or five, six, eighteen, thirty-six, or a hundred and eight feelings.*";
P_HTM[5576]="*Evaṃ pariyāyadesito, bhikkhave, mayā dhammo.**I’ve taught the Dhamma with all these explanations.*";
P_HTM[5577]="*Evaṃ pariyāyadesite kho, bhikkhave, mayā dhamme ye aññamaññassa subhāsitaṃ sulapitaṃ na samanumaññissanti, na samanujānissanti, na samanumodissanti, tesaṃ etaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ—bhaṇḍanajātā kalahajātā vivādāpannā aññamaññaṃ mukhasattīhi vitudantā viharissantīti.**This being so, you can expect that those who don’t concede, approve, or agree with what has been well spoken will argue, quarrel, and fight, continually wounding each other with barbed words.*";
P_HTM[5578]="*Evaṃ pariyāyadesito, bhikkhave, mayā dhammo.**I’ve taught the Dhamma with all these explanations.*";
P_HTM[5579]="*Evaṃ pariyāyadesite kho, bhikkhave, mayā dhamme ye aññamaññassa subhāsitaṃ sulapitaṃ samanumaññissanti samanujānissanti samanumodissanti, tesaṃ etaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ—samaggā sammodamānā avivadamānā khīrodakībhūtā aññamaññaṃ piyacakkhūhi sampassantā viharissantīti.**This being so, you can expect that those who do concede, approve, or agree with what has been well spoken will live in harmony, appreciating each other, without quarreling, blending like milk and water, and regarding each other with kindly eyes.*";
P_HTM[5580]="*Pañcime, bhikkhave, kāmaguṇā … pe …**There are these five kinds of sensual stimulation. …*";
P_HTM[5581]="*ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhave, vijjati yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that wanderers who follow other paths might say:*";
P_HTM[5582]="*‘saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samaṇo gotamo āha, tañca sukhasmiṃ paññapeti.**‘The ascetic Gotama spoke of the cessation of perception and feeling, and he includes it in happiness.*";
P_HTM[5583]="*Tayidaṃ kiṃsu, tayidaṃ kathaṃsū’ti?**What’s up with that?’*";
P_HTM[5584]="*Evaṃvādino, bhikkhave, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evamassu vacanīyā:**Mendicants, when wanderers who follow other paths say this, you should say to them:*";
P_HTM[5585]="*‘na kho, āvuso, bhagavā sukhaññeva vedanaṃ sandhāya sukhasmiṃ paññapeti.**‘Reverends, when the Buddha describes what’s included in happiness, he’s not just referring to pleasant feeling.*";
P_HTM[5586]="*Yattha yattha, āvuso, sukhaṃ upalabbhati yahiṃ yahiṃ, taṃ taṃ tathāgato sukhasmiṃ paññapetī’”ti.**The Realized One describes pleasure as included in happiness wherever it’s found, and in whatever context.’”*";
P_HTM[5587]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5588]="*Rahogatavaggo dutiyo.* **";
P_HTM[5589]="*Rahogataṃ dve ākāsaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5590]="*agāraṃ dve ca ānandā;* **";
P_HTM[5591]="*Sambahulā duve vuttā,* **";
P_HTM[5592]="*pañcakaṅgo ca bhikkhunāti.* **";
P_HTM[5593]="*3. Sabbavaggo**The Explanation of the Hundred and Eight*";
P_HTM[5594]="*1. Sīvakasuttaṃ**With Sīvaka*";
P_HTM[5595]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[5596]="*Atha kho moḷiyasīvako paribbājako yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then the wanderer Moḷiyasīvaka went up to the Buddha and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[5597]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho moḷiyasīvako paribbājako bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[5598]="*“santi, bho gotama, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**“Master Gotama, there are some ascetics and brahmins who have this doctrine and view:*";
P_HTM[5599]="*‘yaṃ kiñcāyaṃ purisapuggalo paṭisaṃvedeti sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā sabbaṃ taṃ pubbekatahetū’ti.**‘Everything this individual experiences—pleasurable, painful, or neutral—is because of past deeds.’*";
P_HTM[5600]="*Idha bhavaṃ gotamo kimāhā”ti?**What does Master Gotama say about this?”*";
P_HTM[5601]="*“Pittasamuṭṭhānānipi kho, sīvaka, idhekaccāni vedayitāni uppajjanti.**“Sīvaka, some feelings stem from bile disorders.*";
P_HTM[5602]="*Sāmampi kho etaṃ, sīvaka, veditabbaṃ yathā pittasamuṭṭhānānipi idhekaccāni vedayitāni uppajjanti.**You can know this from your own personal experience,*";
P_HTM[5603]="*Lokassapi kho etaṃ, sīvaka, saccasammataṃ yathā pittasamuṭṭhānānipi idhekaccāni vedayitāni uppajjanti.**and it is generally agreed to be true.*";
P_HTM[5604]="*Tatra, sīvaka, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**Since this is so, the ascetics and brahmins whose view is that*";
P_HTM[5605]="*‘yaṃ kiñcāyaṃ purisapuggalo paṭisaṃvedeti sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā sabbaṃ taṃ pubbekatahetū’ti.**everything an individual experiences is because of past deeds*";
P_HTM[5606]="*Yañca sāmaṃ ñātaṃ tañca atidhāvanti, yañca loke saccasammataṃ tañca atidhāvanti.**go beyond personal experience and beyond what is generally agreed to be true.*";
P_HTM[5607]="*Tasmā tesaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ micchāti vadāmi.**So those ascetics and brahmins are wrong, I say.*";
P_HTM[5608]="*Semhasamuṭṭhānānipi kho, sīvaka … pe …**Some feelings stem from phlegm disorders …*";
P_HTM[5609]="*vātasamuṭṭhānānipi kho, sīvaka … pe …**wind disorders …*";
P_HTM[5610]="*sannipātikānipi kho, sīvaka … pe …**their conjunction …*";
P_HTM[5611]="*utupariṇāmajānipi kho, sīvaka … pe …**change in weather …*";
P_HTM[5612]="*visamaparihārajānipi kho, sīvaka … pe …**not taking care of yourself …*";
P_HTM[5613]="*opakkamikānipi kho, sīvaka … pe …**overexertion …*";
P_HTM[5614]="*kammavipākajānipi kho, sīvaka, idhekaccāni vedayitāni uppajjanti.**Some feelings are the result of past deeds.*";
P_HTM[5615]="*Sāmampi kho etaṃ, sīvaka, veditabbaṃ.**You can know this from your own personal experience,*";
P_HTM[5616]="*Yathā kammavipākajānipi idhekaccāni vedayitāni uppajjanti;* **";
P_HTM[5617]="*lokassapi kho etaṃ, sīvaka, saccasammataṃ.**and it is generally agreed to be true.*";
P_HTM[5618]="*Yathā kammavipākajānipi idhekaccāni vedayitāni uppajjanti;* **";
P_HTM[5619]="*tatra, sīvaka, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**Since this is so, the ascetics and brahmins whose view is that*";
P_HTM[5620]="*‘yaṃ kiñcāyaṃ purisapuggalo paṭisaṃvedeti sukhaṃ vā dukkhaṃ vā adukkhamasukhaṃ vā sabbaṃ taṃ pubbekatahetū’ti.**everything an individual experiences is because of past deeds*";
P_HTM[5621]="*Yañca sāmaṃ ñātaṃ tañca atidhāvanti yañca loke saccasammataṃ tañca atidhāvanti.**go beyond personal experience and beyond what is generally agreed to be true.*";
P_HTM[5622]="*Tasmā ‘tesaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ micchā’ti vadāmī”ti.**So those ascetics and brahmins are wrong, I say.”*";
P_HTM[5623]="*Evaṃ vutte, moḷiyasīvako paribbājako bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, the wanderer Moḷiyasīvaka said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[5624]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama, abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama … pe …**“Excellent, Master Gotama! Excellent! …*";
P_HTM[5625]="*upāsakaṃ maṃ bhavaṃ gotamo dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may Master Gotama remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[5626]="*“Pittaṃ semhañca vāto ca,**“Bile, phlegm, and wind,*";
P_HTM[5627]="*Sannipātā utūni ca;**their conjunction, and the weather,*";
P_HTM[5628]="*Visamaṃ opakkamikaṃ,**not taking care of yourself, overexertion,*";
P_HTM[5629]="*Kammavipākena aṭṭhamī”ti.**and the result of deeds is the eighth.”*";
P_HTM[5630]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5631]="*2. Aṭṭhasatasuttaṃ**The Explanation of the Hundred and Eight*";
P_HTM[5632]="*“Aṭṭhasatapariyāyaṃ vo, bhikkhave, dhammapariyāyaṃ desessāmi.**“Mendicants, I will teach you an exposition of the teaching on the hundred and eight.*";
P_HTM[5633]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[5634]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, aṭṭhasatapariyāyo, dhammapariyāyo?**And what is the exposition of the teaching on the hundred and eight?*";
P_HTM[5635]="*Dvepi mayā, bhikkhave, vedanā vuttā pariyāyena;**Mendicants, in one explanation I’ve spoken of two feelings. In another explanation I’ve spoken of three feelings, or five, six, eighteen, thirty-six, or a hundred and eight feelings.*";
P_HTM[5636]="*tissopi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena;* **";
P_HTM[5637]="*pañcapi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena;* **";
P_HTM[5638]="*chapi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena;* **";
P_HTM[5639]="*aṭṭhārasāpi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena;* **";
P_HTM[5640]="*chattiṃsāpi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena;* **";
P_HTM[5641]="*aṭṭhasatampi mayā vedanā vuttā pariyāyena.* **";
P_HTM[5642]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, dve vedanā?**And what are the two feelings?*";
P_HTM[5643]="*Kāyikā ca cetasikā ca—**Physical and mental.*";
P_HTM[5644]="*imā vuccanti, bhikkhave, dve vedanā.**These are called the two feelings.*";
P_HTM[5645]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, tisso vedanā?**And what are the three feelings?*";
P_HTM[5646]="*Sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā—**Pleasant, painful, and neutral feelings. …*";
P_HTM[5647]="*imā vuccanti, bhikkhave, tisso vedanā.* **";
P_HTM[5648]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, pañca vedanā?**And what are the five feelings?*";
P_HTM[5649]="*Sukhindriyaṃ, dukkhindriyaṃ, somanassindriyaṃ, domanassindriyaṃ, upekkhindriyaṃ—**The faculties of pleasure, pain, happiness, sadness, and equanimity. …*";
P_HTM[5650]="*imā vuccanti, bhikkhave, pañca vedanā.* **";
P_HTM[5651]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, cha vedanā?**And what are the six feelings?*";
P_HTM[5652]="*Cakkhusamphassajā vedanā … pe …**Feeling born of eye contact … ear contact … nose contact … tongue contact … body contact …*";
P_HTM[5653]="*manosamphassajā vedanā—**mind contact. …*";
P_HTM[5654]="*imā vuccanti, bhikkhave, cha vedanā.* **";
P_HTM[5655]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, aṭṭhārasa vedanā?**And what are the eighteen feelings?*";
P_HTM[5656]="*Cha somanassūpavicārā, cha domanassūpavicārā, cha upekkhūpavicārā—**There are six preoccupations with happiness, six preoccupations with sadness, and six preoccupations with equanimity. …*";
P_HTM[5657]="*imā vuccanti, bhikkhave, aṭṭhārasa vedanā.* **";
P_HTM[5658]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, chattiṃsa vedanā?**And what are the thirty-six feelings?*";
P_HTM[5659]="*Cha gehasitāni somanassāni, cha nekkhammasitāni somanassāni, cha gehasitāni domanassāni, cha nekkhammasitāni domanassāni, cha gehasitā upekkhā, cha nekkhammasitā upekkhā—**Six kinds of lay happiness and six kinds of renunciate happiness. Six kinds of lay sadness and six kinds of renunciate sadness. Six kinds of lay equanimity and six kinds of renunciate equanimity. …*";
P_HTM[5660]="*imā vuccanti, bhikkhave, chattiṃsa vedanā.* **";
P_HTM[5661]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, aṭṭhasataṃ vedanā?**And what are the hundred and eight feelings?*";
P_HTM[5662]="*Atītā chattiṃsa vedanā, anāgatā chattiṃsa vedanā, paccuppannā chattiṃsa vedanā—**Thirty six feelings in the past, future, and present.*";
P_HTM[5663]="*imā vuccanti, bhikkhave, aṭṭhasataṃ vedanā.**These are called the hundred and eight feelings.*";
P_HTM[5664]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, aṭṭhasatapariyāyo dhammapariyāyo”ti.**This is the exposition of the teaching on the hundred and eight.”*";
P_HTM[5665]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5666]="*3. Aññatarabhikkhusuttaṃ**With a Mendicant*";
P_HTM[5667]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[5668]="*“katamā nu kho, bhante, vedanā, katamo vedanāsamudayo, katamā vedanāsamudayagāminī paṭipadā?**“Sir, what is feeling? What’s the origin of feeling? What’s the practice that leads to the origin of feeling?*";
P_HTM[5669]="*Katamo vedanānirodho, katamā vedanānirodhagāminī paṭipadā?**What’s the cessation of feeling? What’s the practice that leads to the cessation of feeling?*";
P_HTM[5670]="*Ko vedanāya assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇan”ti?**And what is feeling’s gratification, drawback, and escape?”*";
P_HTM[5671]="*“Tisso imā, bhikkhu, vedanā—**“Mendicant, there are these three feelings:*";
P_HTM[5672]="*sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā.**pleasant, painful, and neutral.*";
P_HTM[5673]="*Imā vuccanti, bhikkhu, vedanā.**These are called feeling.*";
P_HTM[5674]="*Phassasamudayā vedanāsamudayo.**Feeling originates from contact.*";
P_HTM[5675]="*Taṇhā vedanāsamudayagāminī paṭipadā.**Craving is the practice that leads to the origin of feeling.*";
P_HTM[5676]="*Phassanirodhā vedanānirodho.**When contact ceases, feeling ceases.*";
P_HTM[5677]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo vedanānirodhagāminī paṭipadā, seyyathidaṃ—**The practice that leads to the cessation of feelings is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[5678]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[5679]="*Yaṃ vedanaṃ paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ, ayaṃ vedanāya assādo;**The pleasure and happiness that arise from feeling: this is its gratification.*";
P_HTM[5680]="*yaṃ vedanā aniccā dukkhā vipariṇāmadhammā, ayaṃ vedanāya ādīnavo;**That feeling is impermanent, suffering, and perishable: this is its drawback.*";
P_HTM[5681]="*yo vedanāya chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ, idaṃ vedanāya nissaraṇan”ti.**Removing and giving up desire and greed for feeling: this is its escape.”*";
P_HTM[5682]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5683]="*4. Pubbasuttaṃ**Before*";
P_HTM[5684]="*“Pubbeva me, bhikkhave, sambodhā anabhisambuddhassa bodhisattasseva sato etadahosi:**“Mendicants, before my awakening—when I was still unawakened but intent on awakening—I thought:*";
P_HTM[5685]="*‘katamā nu kho vedanā, katamo vedanāsamudayo, katamā vedanāsamudayagāminī paṭipadā, katamo vedanānirodho, katamā vedanānirodhagāminī paṭipadā?**‘What is feeling? What’s the origin of feeling? What’s the practice that leads to the origin of feeling? What’s the cessation of feeling? What’s the practice that leads to the cessation of feeling?*";
P_HTM[5686]="*Ko vedanāya assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇan’ti?**And what is feeling’s gratification, drawback, and escape?’*";
P_HTM[5687]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhave, etadahosi:**Then it occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[5688]="*‘tisso imā vedanā—**‘There are these three feelings:*";
P_HTM[5689]="*sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā.**pleasant, painful, and neutral.*";
P_HTM[5690]="*Imā vuccanti vedanā.**These are called feeling.*";
P_HTM[5691]="*Phassasamudayā vedanāsamudayo.**Feeling originates from contact.*";
P_HTM[5692]="*Taṇhā vedanāsamudayagāminī paṭipadā … pe …**Craving is the practice that leads to the origin of feeling …*";
P_HTM[5693]="*yo vedanāya chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ. Idaṃ vedanāya nissaraṇan’”ti.**Removing and giving up desire and greed for feeling: this is its escape.’”*";
P_HTM[5694]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5695]="*5. Ñāṇasuttaṃ**Knowledge*";
P_HTM[5696]="*“‘Imā vedanā’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**“‘These are the feelings.’ Such was the vision, knowledge, wisdom, realization, and light that arose in me regarding teachings not learned before from another.*";
P_HTM[5697]="*‘Ayaṃ vedanāsamudayo’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi … pe … āloko udapādi.**‘This is the origin of feeling.’ …*";
P_HTM[5698]="*‘Ayaṃ vedanāsamudayagāminī paṭipadā’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi … pe …**‘This is the practice that leads to the origin of feeling.’ …*";
P_HTM[5699]="*‘ayaṃ vedanānirodho’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi … pe …**‘This is the cessation of feeling.’ …*";
P_HTM[5700]="*‘ayaṃ vedanānirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi … pe …**‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of feeling.’ …*";
P_HTM[5701]="*‘ayaṃ vedanāya assādo’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu … pe …**‘This is the gratification of feeling.’ …*";
P_HTM[5702]="*‘ayaṃ vedanāya ādīnavo’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu … pe …**‘This is the drawback of feeling.’ …*";
P_HTM[5703]="*‘idaṃ kho nissaraṇan’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādī”ti.**‘This is the escape from feeling.’ Such was the vision, knowledge, wisdom, realization, and light that arose in me regarding teachings not learned before from another.”*";
P_HTM[5704]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5705]="*6. Sambahulabhikkhusuttaṃ**With Several Mendicants*";
P_HTM[5706]="*Atha kho sambahulā bhikkhū yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then several mendicants went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[5707]="*“katamā nu kho, bhante, vedanā, katamo vedanāsamudayo, katamā vedanāsamudayagāminī paṭipadā?**“Sir, what is feeling? What’s the origin of feeling? What’s the practice that leads to the origin of feeling?*";
P_HTM[5708]="*Katamo vedanānirodho, katamā vedanānirodhagāminī paṭipadā?**What’s the cessation of feeling? What’s the practice that leads to the cessation of feeling?*";
P_HTM[5709]="*Ko vedanāya assādo, ko ādīnavo, kiṃ nissaraṇan”ti?**And what is feeling’s gratification, drawback, and escape?”*";
P_HTM[5710]="*“Tisso imā, bhikkhave, vedanā—**“Mendicants, there are these three feelings.*";
P_HTM[5711]="*sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā.**pleasant, painful, and neutral.*";
P_HTM[5712]="*Imā vuccanti, bhikkhave, vedanā.**These are called feeling.*";
P_HTM[5713]="*Phassasamudayā vedanāsamudayo.**Feeling originates from contact.*";
P_HTM[5714]="*Taṇhā vedanāsamudayagāminī paṭipadā.**Craving is the practice that leads to the origin of feeling.*";
P_HTM[5715]="*Phassanirodhā … pe …**When contact ceases, feeling ceases. …*";
P_HTM[5716]="*yo vedanāya chandarāgavinayo chandarāgappahānaṃ. Idaṃ vedanāya nissaraṇan”ti.**Removing and giving up desire and greed for feeling: this is its escape.”*";
P_HTM[5717]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5718]="*7. Paṭhamasamaṇabrāhmaṇasuttaṃ**Ascetics and Brahmins (1st)*";
P_HTM[5719]="*“Tisso imā, bhikkhave, vedanā.**“Mendicants, there are these three feelings.*";
P_HTM[5720]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[5721]="*Sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā.**Pleasant, painful, and neutral feeling.*";
P_HTM[5722]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā imāsaṃ tissannaṃ vedanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti.**There are ascetics and brahmins who don’t truly understand these three feelings’ gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[5723]="*Na me te, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu vā samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu vā brāhmaṇasammatā, na ca pana te āyasmanto sāmaññatthaṃ vā brahmaññatthaṃ vā diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharanti.**I don’t regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables don’t realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and don’t live having realized it with their own insight.*";
P_HTM[5724]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā imāsaṃ tissannaṃ vedanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti.**There are ascetics and brahmins who do truly understand these three feelings’ gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[5725]="*Te kho me, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu ceva samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu ca brāhmaṇasammatā. Te ca panāyasmanto sāmaññatthañca brahmaññatthañca, diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharantī”ti.**I regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and live having realized it with their own insight.”*";
P_HTM[5726]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5727]="*8. Dutiyasamaṇabrāhmaṇasuttaṃ**Ascetics and Brahmins (2nd)*";
P_HTM[5728]="*“Tisso imā, bhikkhave, vedanā.**“Mendicants, there are these three feelings.*";
P_HTM[5729]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[5730]="*Sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā.**Pleasant, painful, and neutral feeling.*";
P_HTM[5731]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā imāsaṃ tissannaṃ vedanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti … pe …**There are ascetics and brahmins who don’t truly understand these three feelings’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape. …*";
P_HTM[5732]="*pajānanti … pe … sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharantī”ti.**There are ascetics and brahmins who do truly understand …”*";
P_HTM[5733]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5734]="*9. Tatiyasamaṇabrāhmaṇasuttaṃ**Ascetics and Brahmins (3rd)*";
P_HTM[5735]="*“Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā vedanaṃ nappajānanti, vedanāsamudayaṃ nappajānanti, vedanānirodhaṃ nappajānanti, vedanānirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ nappajānanti … pe …**“Mendicants, there are ascetics and brahmins who don’t understand feeling, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation. …*";
P_HTM[5736]="*pajānanti … pe … sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharantī”ti.**There are ascetics and brahmins who do understand …”*";
P_HTM[5737]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5738]="*10. Suddhikasuttaṃ**Plain Version*";
P_HTM[5739]="*“Tisso imā, bhikkhave, vedanā.**“Mendicants, there are these three feelings.*";
P_HTM[5740]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[5741]="*Sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā—**Pleasant, painful, and neutral feelings.*";
P_HTM[5742]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, tisso vedanā”ti.**These are the three feelings.”*";
P_HTM[5743]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5744]="*11. Nirāmisasuttaṃ**Spiritual*";
P_HTM[5745]="*“Atthi, bhikkhave, sāmisā pīti, atthi nirāmisā pīti, atthi nirāmisā nirāmisatarā pīti;**“Mendicants, there is material rapture, spiritual rapture, and even more spiritual rapture.*";
P_HTM[5746]="*atthi sāmisaṃ sukhaṃ, atthi nirāmisaṃ sukhaṃ, atthi nirāmisā nirāmisataraṃ sukhaṃ;**There is material pleasure, spiritual pleasure, and even more spiritual pleasure.*";
P_HTM[5747]="*atthi sāmisā upekkhā, atthi nirāmisā upekkhā, atthi nirāmisā nirāmisatarā upekkhā;**There is material equanimity, spiritual equanimity, and even more spiritual equanimity.*";
P_HTM[5748]="*atthi sāmiso vimokkho, atthi nirāmiso vimokkho, atthi nirāmisā nirāmisataro vimokkho.**There is material liberation, spiritual liberation, and even more spiritual liberation.*";
P_HTM[5749]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, sāmisā pīti?**And what is material rapture?*";
P_HTM[5750]="*Pañcime, bhikkhave, kāmaguṇā.**There are these five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[5751]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[5752]="*Cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā … pe …**Sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing. Sounds … Smells … Tastes …*";
P_HTM[5753]="*kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**Touches known by the body that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[5754]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca kāmaguṇā.**These are the five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[5755]="*Yā kho, bhikkhave, ime pañca kāmaguṇe paṭicca uppajjati pīti, ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sāmisā pīti.**The rapture that arises from these five kinds of sensual stimulation is called material rapture.*";
P_HTM[5756]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, nirāmisā pīti?**And what is spiritual rapture?*";
P_HTM[5757]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[5758]="*Vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**As the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, they enter and remain in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[5759]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, nirāmisā pīti.**This is called spiritual rapture.*";
P_HTM[5760]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, nirāmisā nirāmisatarā pīti?**And what is even more spiritual rapture?*";
P_HTM[5761]="*Yā kho, bhikkhave, khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno rāgā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ paccavekkhato, dosā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ paccavekkhato, mohā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ paccavekkhato uppajjati pīti, ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, nirāmisā nirāmisatarā pīti.**When a mendicant who has ended the defilements reviews their mind free from greed, hate, and delusion, rapture arises. This is called even more spiritual rapture.*";
P_HTM[5762]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, sāmisaṃ sukhaṃ?**And what is material pleasure?*";
P_HTM[5763]="*Pañcime, bhikkhave, kāmaguṇā.**Mendicants, there are these five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[5764]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[5765]="*Cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā … pe …**Sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing. Sounds … Smells … Tastes …*";
P_HTM[5766]="*kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**Touches known by the body that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[5767]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca kāmaguṇā.**These are the five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[5768]="*Yaṃ kho, bhikkhave, ime pañca kāmaguṇe paṭicca uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ, idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sāmisaṃ sukhaṃ.**The pleasure and happiness that arise from these five kinds of sensual stimulation is called material pleasure.*";
P_HTM[5769]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, nirāmisaṃ sukhaṃ?**And what is spiritual pleasure?*";
P_HTM[5770]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[5771]="*Vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**As the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, they enter and remain in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[5772]="*Pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati sato ca sampajāno sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedeti, yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti: ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**And with the fading away of rapture, they enter and remain in the third absorption, where they meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[5773]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, nirāmisaṃ sukhaṃ.**This is called spiritual pleasure.*";
P_HTM[5774]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, nirāmisā nirāmisataraṃ sukhaṃ?**And what is even more spiritual pleasure?*";
P_HTM[5775]="*Yaṃ kho, bhikkhave, khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno rāgā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ paccavekkhato, dosā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ paccavekkhato, mohā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ paccavekkhato uppajjati sukhaṃ somanassaṃ, idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, nirāmisā nirāmisataraṃ sukhaṃ.**When a mendicant who has ended the defilements reviews their mind free from greed, hate, and delusion, pleasure and happiness arises. This is called even more spiritual pleasure.*";
P_HTM[5776]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, sāmisā upekkhā?**And what is material equanimity?*";
P_HTM[5777]="*Pañcime, bhikkhave, kāmaguṇā.**There are these five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[5778]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[5779]="*Cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā … pe …**Sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing. Sounds … Smells … Tastes …*";
P_HTM[5780]="*kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**Touches known by the body that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[5781]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca kāmaguṇā.**These are the five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[5782]="*Yā kho, bhikkhave, ime pañca kāmaguṇe paṭicca uppajjati upekkhā, ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sāmisā upekkhā.**The equanimity that arises from these five kinds of sensual stimulation is called material equanimity.*";
P_HTM[5783]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, nirāmisā upekkhā?**And what is spiritual equanimity?*";
P_HTM[5784]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā, dukkhassa ca pahānā, pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā, adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when, giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, a mendicant enters and remains in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[5785]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, nirāmisā upekkhā.**This is called spiritual equanimity.*";
P_HTM[5786]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, nirāmisā nirāmisatarā upekkhā?**And what is even more spiritual equanimity?*";
P_HTM[5787]="*Yā kho, bhikkhave, khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno rāgā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ paccavekkhato, dosā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ paccavekkhato, mohā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ paccavekkhato uppajjati upekkhā, ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, nirāmisā nirāmisatarā upekkhā.**When a mendicant who has ended the defilements reviews their mind free from greed, hate, and delusion, equanimity arises. This is called even more spiritual equanimity.*";
P_HTM[5788]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, sāmiso vimokkho?**And what is material liberation?*";
P_HTM[5789]="*Rūpappaṭisaṃyutto vimokkho sāmiso vimokkho.**Liberation connected with form is material.*";
P_HTM[5790]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, nirāmiso vimokkho?**And what is spiritual liberation?*";
P_HTM[5791]="*Arūpappaṭisaṃyutto vimokkho nirāmiso vimokkho.**Liberation connected with the formless is spiritual.*";
P_HTM[5792]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, nirāmisā nirāmisataro vimokkho?**And what is even more spiritual liberation?*";
P_HTM[5793]="*Yo kho, bhikkhave, khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno rāgā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ paccavekkhato, dosā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ paccavekkhato, mohā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ paccavekkhato uppajjati vimokkho, ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, nirāmisā nirāmisataro vimokkho”ti.**When a mendicant who has ended the defilements reviews their mind free from greed, hate, and delusion, liberation arises. This is called even more spiritual liberation.”*";
P_HTM[5794]="*Ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5795]="*Aṭṭhasatapariyāyavaggo tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[5796]="*Sīvakaaṭṭhasataṃ bhikkhu,* **";
P_HTM[5797]="*pubbe ñāṇañca bhikkhunā;* **";
P_HTM[5798]="*Samaṇabrāhmaṇā tīṇi,* **";
P_HTM[5799]="*suddhikañca nirāmisanti.* **";
P_HTM[5800]="*Vedanāsaṃyuttaṃ samattaṃ.**The Linked Discourses on feeling are complete.*";
P_HTM[5801]="*37. Mātugāmasaṃyuttaṃ* **";
P_HTM[5802]="*1. Aniccavaggo**Abbreviated Texts*";
P_HTM[5803]="*1. Mātugāmasuttaṃ**A Female*";
P_HTM[5804]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, aṅgehi samannāgato mātugāmo ekantaamanāpo hoti purisassa.**“Mendicants, when a female has five factors she is extremely undesirable to a man.*";
P_HTM[5805]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[5806]="*Na ca rūpavā hoti, na ca bhogavā hoti, na ca sīlavā hoti, alaso ca hoti, pajañcassa na labhati—**She’s not attractive, wealthy, or ethical; she’s idle, and she doesn’t beget children.*";
P_HTM[5807]="*imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi aṅgehi samannāgato mātugāmo ekantaamanāpo hoti purisassa.**When a female has these five factors she is extremely undesirable to a man.*";
P_HTM[5808]="*Pañcahi, bhikkhave, aṅgehi samannāgato mātugāmo ekantamanāpo hoti purisassa.**When a female has five factors she is extremely desirable to a man.*";
P_HTM[5809]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[5810]="*Rūpavā ca hoti, bhogavā ca hoti, sīlavā ca hoti, dakkho ca hoti analaso, pajañcassa labhati—**She’s attractive, wealthy, and ethical; she’s skillful and tireless, and she begets children.*";
P_HTM[5811]="*imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi aṅgehi samannāgato mātugāmo ekantamanāpo hoti purisassā”ti.**When a female has these five factors she is extremely desirable to a man.”*";
P_HTM[5812]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5813]="*2. Purisasuttaṃ**A Man*";
P_HTM[5814]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, aṅgehi samannāgato puriso ekantaamanāpo hoti mātugāmassa.**“Mendicants, when a man has five factors he is extremely undesirable to a female.*";
P_HTM[5815]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[5816]="*Na ca rūpavā hoti, na ca bhogavā hoti, na ca sīlavā hoti, alaso ca hoti, pajañcassa na labhati—**He’s not attractive, wealthy, or ethical; he’s idle, and he doesn’t beget children.*";
P_HTM[5817]="*imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi aṅgehi samannāgato puriso ekantaamanāpo hoti mātugāmassa.**When a man has these five factors he is extremely undesirable to a female.*";
P_HTM[5818]="*Pañcahi, bhikkhave, aṅgehi samannāgato puriso ekantamanāpo hoti mātugāmassa.**When a man has five factors he is extremely desirable to a female.*";
P_HTM[5819]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[5820]="*Rūpavā ca hoti, bhogavā ca hoti, sīlavā ca hoti, dakkho ca hoti analaso, pajañcassa labhati—**He’s attractive, wealthy, and ethical; he’s skillful and tireless, and he begets children.*";
P_HTM[5821]="*imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi aṅgehi samannāgato puriso ekantamanāpo hoti mātugāmassā”ti.**When a man has these five factors he is extremely desirable to a female.”*";
P_HTM[5822]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5823]="*3. Āveṇikadukkhasuttaṃ**Particular Suffering*";
P_HTM[5824]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, mātugāmassa āveṇikāni dukkhāni, yāni mātugāmo paccanubhoti, aññatreva purisehi.**“Mendicants, there are these five kinds of suffering that particularly apply to females. They’re undergone by females and not by men.*";
P_HTM[5825]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[5826]="*Idha, bhikkhave, mātugāmo daharova samāno patikulaṃ gacchati, ñātakehi vinā hoti.**Firstly, a female, while still young, goes to live with her husband’s family and is separated from her relatives.*";
P_HTM[5827]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, mātugāmassa paṭhamaṃ āveṇikaṃ dukkhaṃ, yaṃ mātugāmo paccanubhoti, aññatreva purisehi.**This is the first kind of suffering that particularly applies to females.*";
P_HTM[5828]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, mātugāmo utunī hoti.**Furthermore, a female undergoes the menstrual cycle.*";
P_HTM[5829]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, mātugāmassa dutiyaṃ āveṇikaṃ dukkhaṃ, yaṃ mātugāmo paccanubhoti, aññatreva purisehi.**This is the second kind of suffering that particularly applies to females.*";
P_HTM[5830]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, mātugāmo gabbhinī hoti.**Furthermore, a female undergoes pregnancy.*";
P_HTM[5831]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, mātugāmassa tatiyaṃ āveṇikaṃ dukkhaṃ, yaṃ mātugāmo paccanubhoti, aññatreva purisehi.**This is the third kind of suffering that particularly applies to females.*";
P_HTM[5832]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, mātugāmo vijāyati.**Furthermore, a female gives birth.*";
P_HTM[5833]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, mātugāmassa catutthaṃ āveṇikaṃ dukkhaṃ, yaṃ mātugāmo paccanubhoti, aññatreva purisehi.**This is the fourth kind of suffering that particularly applies to females.*";
P_HTM[5834]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, mātugāmo purisassa pāricariyaṃ upeti.**Furthermore, a female provides services for a man.*";
P_HTM[5835]="*Idaṃ kho, bhikkhave, mātugāmassa pañcamaṃ āveṇikaṃ dukkhaṃ, yaṃ mātugāmo paccanubhoti, aññatreva purisehi.**This is the fifth kind of suffering that particularly applies to females.*";
P_HTM[5836]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca mātugāmassa āveṇikāni dukkhāni, yāni mātugāmo paccanubhoti, aññatreva purisehī”ti.**These are the five kinds of suffering that particularly apply to females. They’re undergone by females and not by men.”*";
P_HTM[5837]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5838]="*4. Tīhidhammehisuttaṃ**Three Qualities*";
P_HTM[5839]="*“Tīhi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo yebhuyyena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**“Mendicants, when females have three qualities, when their body breaks up, after death, they are mostly reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[5840]="*Katamehi tīhi?**What three?*";
P_HTM[5841]="*Idha, bhikkhave, mātugāmo pubbaṇhasamayaṃ maccheramalapariyuṭṭhitena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati.**A female lives at home with a heart full of the stain of stinginess in the morning, jealousy in the afternoon, and sexual desire in the evening.*";
P_HTM[5842]="*Majjhanhikasamayaṃ issāpariyuṭṭhitena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati.* **";
P_HTM[5843]="*Sāyanhasamayaṃ kāmarāgapariyuṭṭhitena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati.* **";
P_HTM[5844]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, tīhi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo yebhuyyena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjatī”ti.**When females have these three qualities, when their body breaks up, after death, they are mostly reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.”*";
P_HTM[5845]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5846]="*()* **";
P_HTM[5847]="*5. Kodhanasuttaṃ**Irritable*";
P_HTM[5848]="*Atha kho āyasmā anuruddho yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā anuruddho bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Anuruddha went up to the Buddha, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[5849]="*“idhāhaṃ, bhante, mātugāmaṃ passāmi dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjantaṃ.**“Sometimes, sir, with my clairvoyance that’s purified and superhuman, I see that a female—when her body breaks up, after death—is reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[5850]="*Katīhi nu kho, bhante, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjatī”ti?**How many qualities do females have so that they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell?”*";
P_HTM[5851]="*“Pañcahi kho, anuruddha, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**“Anuruddha, when females have five qualities, when their body breaks up, after death, they are reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[5852]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[5853]="*Assaddho ca hoti, ahiriko ca hoti, anottappī ca hoti, kodhano ca hoti, duppañño ca hoti—**They’re faithless, shameless, imprudent, irritable, and witless.*";
P_HTM[5854]="*imehi kho, anuruddha, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjatī”ti.**When females have these five qualities, when their body breaks up, after death, they are reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.”*";
P_HTM[5855]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5856]="*6. Upanāhīsuttaṃ**Hostility*";
P_HTM[5857]="*“Pañcahi, anuruddha, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.* **";
P_HTM[5858]="*Katamehi pañcahi?* **";
P_HTM[5859]="*Assaddho ca hoti, ahiriko ca hoti, anottappī ca hoti, upanāhī ca hoti, duppañño ca hoti—**“… They’re faithless, shameless, imprudent, hostile, and witless. …”*";
P_HTM[5860]="*imehi kho, anuruddha, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5861]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5862]="*7. Issukīsuttaṃ**Jealous*";
P_HTM[5863]="*“Pañcahi, anuruddha, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.* **";
P_HTM[5864]="*Katamehi pañcahi?* **";
P_HTM[5865]="*Assaddho ca hoti, ahiriko ca hoti, anottappī ca hoti, issukī ca hoti, duppañño ca hoti—**“… They’re faithless, shameless, imprudent, jealous, and witless. …”*";
P_HTM[5866]="*imehi kho, anuruddha, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5867]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5868]="*8. Maccharīsuttaṃ**Stingy*";
P_HTM[5869]="*“Pañcahi, anuruddha, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.* **";
P_HTM[5870]="*Katamehi pañcahi?* **";
P_HTM[5871]="*Assaddho ca hoti, ahiriko ca hoti, anottappī ca hoti, maccharī ca hoti, duppañño ca hoti—**“… They’re faithless, shameless, imprudent, stingy, and witless. …”*";
P_HTM[5872]="*imehi kho, anuruddha, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5873]="*apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5874]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5875]="*9. Aticārīsuttaṃ**Adultery*";
P_HTM[5876]="*“Pañcahi, anuruddha, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo … pe … apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.* **";
P_HTM[5877]="*Katamehi pañcahi?* **";
P_HTM[5878]="*Assaddho ca hoti, ahiriko ca hoti, anottappī ca hoti, aticārī ca hoti, duppañño ca hoti—**“… They’re faithless, shameless, imprudent, adulterous, and witless. …”*";
P_HTM[5879]="*imehi kho, anuruddha, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo … pe … upapajjatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5880]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5881]="*10. Dussīlasuttaṃ**Unethical*";
P_HTM[5882]="*“Pañcahi, anuruddha, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo … pe … nirayaṃ upapajjati.* **";
P_HTM[5883]="*Katamehi pañcahi?* **";
P_HTM[5884]="*Assaddho ca hoti, ahiriko ca hoti, anottappī ca hoti, dussīlo ca hoti, duppañño ca hoti—**“… They’re faithless, shameless, imprudent, unethical, and witless. …”*";
P_HTM[5885]="*imehi kho, anuruddha, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo … pe … nirayaṃ upapajjatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5886]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5887]="*11. Appassutasuttaṃ**Uneducated*";
P_HTM[5888]="*“Pañcahi, anuruddha, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo … pe … nirayaṃ upapajjati.* **";
P_HTM[5889]="*Katamehi pañcahi?* **";
P_HTM[5890]="*Assaddho ca hoti, ahiriko ca hoti, anottappī ca hoti, appassuto ca hoti, duppañño ca hoti—**“… They’re faithless, shameless, imprudent, uneducated, and witless. …”*";
P_HTM[5891]="*imehi kho, anuruddha, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo … pe … nirayaṃ upapajjatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5892]="*Ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5893]="*12. Kusītasuttaṃ**Lazy*";
P_HTM[5894]="*“Pañcahi, anuruddha, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo … pe … nirayaṃ upapajjati.* **";
P_HTM[5895]="*Katamehi pañcahi?* **";
P_HTM[5896]="*Assaddho ca hoti, ahiriko ca hoti, anottappī ca hoti, kusīto ca hoti, duppañño ca hoti—**“… They’re faithless, shameless, imprudent, lazy, and witless. …”*";
P_HTM[5897]="*imehi kho, anuruddha, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo … pe … apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5898]="*Dvādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5899]="*13. Muṭṭhassatisuttaṃ**Unmindful*";
P_HTM[5900]="*“Pañcahi, anuruddha, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo … pe … nirayaṃ upapajjati.* **";
P_HTM[5901]="*Katamehi pañcahi?* **";
P_HTM[5902]="*Assaddho ca hoti, ahiriko ca hoti, anottappī ca hoti, muṭṭhassati ca hoti, duppañño ca hoti—**“… They’re faithless, shameless, imprudent, unmindful, and witless. …”*";
P_HTM[5903]="*imehi kho, anuruddha, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo … pe … nirayaṃ upapajjatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5904]="*Terasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5905]="*14. Pañcaverasuttaṃ**Five Threats*";
P_HTM[5906]="*“Pañcahi, anuruddha, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo … pe … nirayaṃ upapajjati.**“Anuruddha, when females have five qualities, when their body breaks up, after death, they are reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[5907]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[5908]="*Pāṇātipātī ca hoti, adinnādāyī ca hoti, kāmesumicchācārī ca hoti, musāvādī ca hoti, surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhāyī ca hoti—**They kill living creatures, steal, commit sexual misconduct, lie, and consume alcoholic drinks that cause negligence.*";
P_HTM[5909]="*imehi kho, anuruddha, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjatī”ti.**When females have these five qualities, when their body breaks up, after death, they are reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.”*";
P_HTM[5910]="*Cuddasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5911]="*Paṭhamapeyyālavaggo.* **";
P_HTM[5912]="*Mātugāmo puriso ca,* **";
P_HTM[5913]="*āveṇikā tidhammo ca;* **";
P_HTM[5914]="*Kodhano upanāhī ca,* **";
P_HTM[5915]="*issukī maccharena ca;* **";
P_HTM[5916]="*Aticārī ca dussīlo,* **";
P_HTM[5917]="*appassuto ca kusīto;* **";
P_HTM[5918]="*Muṭṭhassati pañcaveraṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5919]="*kaṇhapakkhe pakāsito.* **";
P_HTM[5920]="*2. Yamakavaggo**Abbreviated Texts*";
P_HTM[5921]="*1. Akkodhanasuttaṃ**Loving*";
P_HTM[5922]="*Atha kho āyasmā anuruddho yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā anuruddho bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Anuruddha went up to the Buddha … and asked him,*";
P_HTM[5923]="*“idhāhaṃ, bhante, mātugāmaṃ passāmi dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjantaṃ.**“Sometimes, sir, with my clairvoyance that’s purified and superhuman, I see that a female—when her body breaks up, after death—is reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[5924]="*Katīhi nu kho, bhante, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjatī”ti?**How many qualities do females have so that they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm?”*";
P_HTM[5925]="*“Pañcahi kho, anuruddha, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**“Anuruddha, when females have five qualities, when their body breaks up, after death, they are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[5926]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[5927]="*Saddho ca hoti, hirimā ca hoti, ottappī ca hoti, akkodhano ca hoti, paññavā ca hoti—**They’re faithful, conscientious, prudent, loving, and wise.*";
P_HTM[5928]="*imehi kho, anuruddha, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjatī”ti.**When females have these five qualities, when their body breaks up, after death, they are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.”*";
P_HTM[5929]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5930]="*2. Anupanāhīsuttaṃ**Free of Hostility*";
P_HTM[5931]="*“Pañcahi, anuruddha, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.* **";
P_HTM[5932]="*Katamehi pañcahi?* **";
P_HTM[5933]="*Saddho ca hoti, hirimā ca hoti, ottappī ca hoti, anupanāhī ca hoti, paññavā ca hoti—**“… They’re faithful, conscientious, prudent, free of hostility, and wise. …”*";
P_HTM[5934]="*imehi kho, anuruddha, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5935]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5936]="*3. Anissukīsuttaṃ**Free of Jealousy*";
P_HTM[5937]="*“Pañcahi, anuruddha, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.* **";
P_HTM[5938]="*Katamehi pañcahi?* **";
P_HTM[5939]="*Saddho ca hoti, hirimā ca hoti, ottappī ca hoti, anissukī ca hoti, paññavā ca hoti … pe ….**“… They’re faithful, conscientious, prudent, free of jealousy, and wise. …”*";
P_HTM[5940]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5941]="*4. Amaccharīsuttaṃ**Free of Stinginess*";
P_HTM[5942]="*“Amaccharī ca hoti, paññavā ca hoti … pe ….**“… They’re faithful, conscientious, prudent, free of stinginess, and wise. …”*";
P_HTM[5943]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5944]="*5. Anaticārīsuttaṃ**Not Adulterous*";
P_HTM[5945]="*“Anaticārī ca hoti, paññavā ca hoti … pe ….**“… They’re faithful, conscientious, prudent, not adulterous, and wise. …”*";
P_HTM[5946]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5947]="*6. Susīlasuttaṃ**Ethical*";
P_HTM[5948]="*“Sīlavā ca hoti, paññavā ca hoti … pe ….**“… They’re faithful, conscientious, prudent, ethical, and wise. …”*";
P_HTM[5949]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5950]="*7. Bahussutasuttaṃ**Educated*";
P_HTM[5951]="*“Bahussuto ca hoti, paññavā ca hoti … pe ….**“… They’re faithful, conscientious, prudent, educated, and wise. …”*";
P_HTM[5952]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5953]="*8. Āraddhavīriyasuttaṃ**Energetic*";
P_HTM[5954]="*“Āraddhavīriyo ca hoti, paññavā ca hoti … pe ….**“… They’re faithful, conscientious, prudent, energetic, and wise. …”*";
P_HTM[5955]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5956]="*9. Upaṭṭhitassatisuttaṃ**Mindful*";
P_HTM[5957]="*“Upaṭṭhitassati ca hoti, paññavā ca hoti … pe …**“… They’re faithful, conscientious, prudent, mindful, and wise. …”*";
P_HTM[5958]="*imehi kho, anuruddha, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[5959]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5960]="*Ime aṭṭha suttantasaṅkhepā.* **";
P_HTM[5961]="*10. Pañcasīlasuttaṃ**Five Precepts*";
P_HTM[5962]="*“Pañcahi, anuruddha, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**“Anuruddha, when females have five qualities, when their body breaks up, after death, they are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[5963]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[5964]="*Pāṇātipātā paṭivirato ca hoti, adinnādānā paṭivirato ca hoti, kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato ca hoti, musāvādā paṭivirato ca hoti, surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānā paṭivirato ca hoti—**They don’t kill living creatures, steal, commit sexual misconduct, lie, or consume alcoholic drinks that cause negligence.*";
P_HTM[5965]="*imehi kho, anuruddha, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjatī”ti.**When females have these five qualities, when their body breaks up, after death, they are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.”*";
P_HTM[5966]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5967]="*Dutiyapeyyālavaggo.* **";
P_HTM[5968]="*Dutiye ca akkodhano,* **";
P_HTM[5969]="*anupanāhī anissukī;* **";
P_HTM[5970]="*Amaccharī anaticārī,* **";
P_HTM[5971]="*sīlavā ca bahussuto;* **";
P_HTM[5972]="*Vīriyaṃ sati sīlañca,* **";
P_HTM[5973]="*sukkapakkhe pakāsito.* **";
P_HTM[5974]="*3. Sabbavaggo**Powers*";
P_HTM[5975]="*1. Visāradasuttaṃ**Assured*";
P_HTM[5976]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, mātugāmassa balāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five powers of a female.*";
P_HTM[5977]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[5978]="*Rūpabalaṃ, bhogabalaṃ, ñātibalaṃ, puttabalaṃ, sīlabalaṃ—**Attractiveness, wealth, relatives, children, and ethical behavior.*";
P_HTM[5979]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca mātugāmassa balāni.**These are the five powers of a female.*";
P_HTM[5980]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi balehi samannāgato mātugāmo visārado agāraṃ ajjhāvasatī”ti.**A female living at home with these five qualities is self-assured.”*";
P_HTM[5981]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5982]="*2. Pasayhasuttaṃ**Under Her Thumb*";
P_HTM[5983]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, mātugāmassa balāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five powers of a female.*";
P_HTM[5984]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[5985]="*Rūpabalaṃ, bhogabalaṃ, ñātibalaṃ, puttabalaṃ, sīlabalaṃ—**Attractiveness, wealth, relatives, children, and ethical behavior.*";
P_HTM[5986]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca mātugāmassa balāni.**These are the five powers of a female.*";
P_HTM[5987]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi balehi samannāgato mātugāmo sāmikaṃ pasayha agāraṃ ajjhāvasatī”ti.**A female living at home with these five powers has her husband under her thumb.”*";
P_HTM[5988]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5989]="*3. Abhibhuyyasuttaṃ**Mastered*";
P_HTM[5990]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, mātugāmassa balāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five powers of a female.*";
P_HTM[5991]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[5992]="*Rūpabalaṃ, bhogabalaṃ, ñātibalaṃ, puttabalaṃ, sīlabalaṃ—**Attractiveness, wealth, relatives, children, and ethical behavior.*";
P_HTM[5993]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca mātugāmassa balāni.**These are the five powers of a female.*";
P_HTM[5994]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi balehi samannāgato mātugāmo sāmikaṃ abhibhuyya vattatī”ti.**A female living at home with these five powers has her husband under her mastery.”*";
P_HTM[5995]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5996]="*4. Ekasuttaṃ**One*";
P_HTM[5997]="*“Ekena ca kho, bhikkhave, balena samannāgato puriso mātugāmaṃ abhibhuyya vattati.**“Mendicants, when a man has one power he has a female under his mastery.*";
P_HTM[5998]="*Katamena ekena balena?**What one power?*";
P_HTM[5999]="*Issariyabalena abhibhūtaṃ mātugāmaṃ neva rūpabalaṃ tāyati, na bhogabalaṃ tāyati, na ñātibalaṃ tāyati, na puttabalaṃ tāyati, na sīlabalaṃ tāyatī”ti.**The power of authority. Mastered by this, a female’s powers of attractiveness, wealth, relatives, children, and ethical behavior do not avail her.”*";
P_HTM[6000]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6001]="*5. Aṅgasuttaṃ**In That Respect*";
P_HTM[6002]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, mātugāmassa balāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five powers of a female.*";
P_HTM[6003]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[6004]="*Rūpabalaṃ, bhogabalaṃ, ñātibalaṃ, puttabalaṃ, sīlabalaṃ.**Attractiveness, wealth, relatives, children, and ethical behavior.*";
P_HTM[6005]="*Rūpabalena ca, bhikkhave, mātugāmo samannāgato hoti, na ca bhogabalena—**A female who has the power of attractiveness but not the power of wealth*";
P_HTM[6006]="*evaṃ so tenaṅgena aparipūro hoti.**is incomplete in that respect.*";
P_HTM[6007]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, mātugāmo rūpabalena ca samannāgato hoti, bhogabalena ca—**But when she has the power of attractiveness and the power of wealth*";
P_HTM[6008]="*evaṃ so tenaṅgena paripūro hoti.**she’s complete in that respect.*";
P_HTM[6009]="*Rūpabalena ca, bhikkhave, mātugāmo samannāgato hoti, bhogabalena ca, na ca ñātibalena—**A female who has the powers of attractiveness and wealth, but not the power of relatives*";
P_HTM[6010]="*evaṃ so tenaṅgena aparipūro hoti.**is incomplete in that respect.*";
P_HTM[6011]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, mātugāmo rūpabalena ca samannāgato hoti, bhogabalena ca, ñātibalena ca—**But when she has the powers of attractiveness, wealth, and relatives*";
P_HTM[6012]="*evaṃ so tenaṅgena paripūro hoti.**she’s complete in that respect.*";
P_HTM[6013]="*Rūpabalena ca, bhikkhave, mātugāmo samannāgato hoti, bhogabalena ca, ñātibalena ca, na ca puttabalena—**A female who has the powers of attractiveness, wealth, and relatives, but not the power of children*";
P_HTM[6014]="*evaṃ so tenaṅgena aparipūro hoti.**is incomplete in that respect.*";
P_HTM[6015]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, mātugāmo rūpabalena ca samannāgato hoti, bhogabalena ca, ñātibalena ca, puttabalena ca—**But when she has the powers of attractiveness, wealth, relatives, and children*";
P_HTM[6016]="*evaṃ so tenaṅgena paripūro hoti.**she’s complete in that respect.*";
P_HTM[6017]="*Rūpabalena ca, bhikkhave, mātugāmo samannāgato hoti, bhogabalena ca, ñātibalena ca, puttabalena ca, na ca sīlabalena—**A female who has the powers of attractiveness, wealth, relatives, and children, but not the power of ethical behavior*";
P_HTM[6018]="*evaṃ so tenaṅgena aparipūro hoti.**is incomplete in that respect.*";
P_HTM[6019]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, mātugāmo rūpabalena ca samannāgato hoti, bhogabalena ca, ñātibalena ca, puttabalena ca, sīlabalena ca—**But when she has the powers of attractiveness, wealth, relatives, children, and ethical behavior*";
P_HTM[6020]="*evaṃ so tenaṅgena paripūro hoti.**she’s complete in that respect.*";
P_HTM[6021]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca mātugāmassa balānī”ti.**These are the five powers of a female.”*";
P_HTM[6022]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6023]="*6. Nāsentisuttaṃ**They Send Her Away*";
P_HTM[6024]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, mātugāmassa balāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five powers of a female.*";
P_HTM[6025]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[6026]="*Rūpabalaṃ, bhogabalaṃ, ñātibalaṃ, puttabalaṃ, sīlabalaṃ.**Attractiveness, wealth, relatives, children, and ethical behavior.*";
P_HTM[6027]="*Rūpabalena ca, bhikkhave, mātugāmo samannāgato hoti, na ca sīlabalena, nāsenteva naṃ, kule na vāsenti.**If a female has the power of attractiveness but not that of ethical behavior, the family will send her away, they won’t accommodate her.*";
P_HTM[6028]="*Rūpabalena ca, bhikkhave, mātugāmo samannāgato hoti, bhogabalena ca, na ca sīlabalena, nāsenteva naṃ, kule na vāsenti.**If a female has the powers of attractiveness and wealth but not that of ethical behavior, the family will send her away, they won’t accommodate her.*";
P_HTM[6029]="*Rūpabalena ca, bhikkhave, mātugāmo samannāgato hoti, bhogabalena ca, ñātibalena ca, na ca sīlabalena, nāsenteva naṃ, kule na vāsenti.**If a female has the powers of attractiveness, wealth, and relatives, but not that of ethical behavior, the family will send her away, they won’t accommodate her.*";
P_HTM[6030]="*Rūpabalena ca, bhikkhave, mātugāmo samannāgato hoti, bhogabalena ca, ñātibalena ca, puttabalena ca, na ca sīlabalena, nāsenteva naṃ, kule na vāsenti.**If a female has the powers of attractiveness, wealth, relatives, and children, but not that of ethical behavior, the family will send her away, they won’t accommodate her.*";
P_HTM[6031]="*Sīlabalena ca, bhikkhave, mātugāmo samannāgato hoti, na ca rūpabalena, vāsenteva naṃ, kule na nāsenti.**If a female has the power of ethical behavior but not that of attractiveness, the family will accommodate her, they won’t send her away.*";
P_HTM[6032]="*Sīlabalena ca, bhikkhave, mātugāmo samannāgato hoti, na ca bhogabalena, vāsenteva naṃ, kule na nāsenti.**If a female has the power of ethical behavior but not that of wealth, the family will accommodate her, they won’t send her away.*";
P_HTM[6033]="*Sīlabalena ca, bhikkhave, mātugāmo samannāgato hoti, na ca ñātibalena, vāsenteva naṃ, kule na nāsenti.**If a female has the power of ethical behavior but not that of relatives, the family will accommodate her, they won’t send her away.*";
P_HTM[6034]="*Sīlabalena ca, bhikkhave, mātugāmo samannāgato hoti, na ca puttabalena, vāsenteva naṃ, kule na nāsenti.**If a female has the power of ethical behavior but not that of children, the family will accommodate her, they won’t send her away.*";
P_HTM[6035]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca mātugāmassa balānī”ti.**These are the five powers of a female.”*";
P_HTM[6036]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6037]="*7. Hetusuttaṃ**Cause*";
P_HTM[6038]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, mātugāmassa balāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five powers of a female.*";
P_HTM[6039]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[6040]="*Rūpabalaṃ, bhogabalaṃ, ñātibalaṃ, puttabalaṃ, sīlabalaṃ.**Attractiveness, wealth, relatives, children, and ethical behavior.*";
P_HTM[6041]="*Na, bhikkhave, mātugāmo rūpabalahetu vā bhogabalahetu vā ñātibalahetu vā puttabalahetu vā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**It is not because of the powers of attractiveness, wealth, relatives, or children that females, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[6042]="*Sīlabalahetu kho, bhikkhave, mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**It is because of the power of ethical behavior that females, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[6043]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca mātugāmassa balānī”ti.**These are the five powers of a female.”*";
P_HTM[6044]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6045]="*8. Ṭhānasuttaṃ**Things*";
P_HTM[6046]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, ṭhānāni dullabhāni akatapuññena mātugāmena.**“Mendicants, there are five things that are hard to get for females who have not made merit.*";
P_HTM[6047]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[6048]="*Patirūpe kule jāyeyyanti—**‘May I be born into a suitable family!’*";
P_HTM[6049]="*idaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamaṃ ṭhānaṃ dullabhaṃ akatapuññena mātugāmena.**This is the first thing.*";
P_HTM[6050]="*Patirūpe kule jāyitvā patirūpaṃ kulaṃ gaccheyyanti—**‘Having been born in a suitable family, may I marry into a suitable family!’*";
P_HTM[6051]="*idaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ dullabhaṃ akatapuññena mātugāmena.**This is the second thing.*";
P_HTM[6052]="*Patirūpe kule jāyitvā, patirūpaṃ kulaṃ gantvā, asapatti agāraṃ ajjhāvaseyyanti—**‘Having been born in a suitable family and married into a suitable family, may I live at home without a co-wife!’*";
P_HTM[6053]="*idaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ dullabhaṃ akatapuññena mātugāmena.**This is the third thing.*";
P_HTM[6054]="*Patirūpe kule jāyitvā, patirūpaṃ kulaṃ gantvā, asapatti agāraṃ ajjhāvasantī puttavatī assanti—**‘Having been born in a suitable family, and married into a suitable family, and living at home without a co-wife, may I have children!’*";
P_HTM[6055]="*idaṃ, bhikkhave, catutthaṃ ṭhānaṃ dullabhaṃ akatapuññena mātugāmena.**This is the fourth thing.*";
P_HTM[6056]="*Patirūpe kule jāyitvā, patirūpaṃ kulaṃ gantvā, asapatti agāraṃ ajjhāvasantī puttavatī samānā sāmikaṃ abhibhuyya vatteyyanti—**‘Having been born in a suitable family, and married into a suitable family, and living at home without a co-wife, and having had children, may I master my husband!’*";
P_HTM[6057]="*idaṃ, bhikkhave, pañcamaṃ ṭhānaṃ dullabhaṃ akatapuññena mātugāmena.**This is the fifth thing.*";
P_HTM[6058]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca ṭhānāni dullabhāni akatapuññena mātugāmenāti.**These are the five things that are hard to get for females who have not made merit.*";
P_HTM[6059]="*Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, ṭhānāni sulabhāni katapuññena mātugāmena.**There are five things that are easy to get for females who have made merit.*";
P_HTM[6060]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[6061]="*Patirūpe kule jāyeyyanti—**‘May I be born into a suitable family!’*";
P_HTM[6062]="*idaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamaṃ ṭhānaṃ sulabhaṃ katapuññena mātugāmena.**This is the first thing.*";
P_HTM[6063]="*Patirūpe kule jāyitvā patirūpaṃ kulaṃ gaccheyyanti—**‘Having been born into a suitable family, may I marry into a suitable family!’*";
P_HTM[6064]="*idaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ sulabhaṃ katapuññena mātugāmena.**This is the second thing.*";
P_HTM[6065]="*Patirūpe kule jāyitvā patirūpaṃ kulaṃ gantvā asapatti agāraṃ ajjhāvaseyyanti—**‘Having been born into a suitable family and married into a suitable family, may I live at home without a co-wife!’*";
P_HTM[6066]="*idaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ sulabhaṃ katapuññena mātugāmena.**This is the third thing.*";
P_HTM[6067]="*Patirūpe kule jāyitvā patirūpaṃ kulaṃ gantvā asapatti agāraṃ ajjhāvasantī puttavatī assanti—**‘Having been born into a suitable family, and married into a suitable family, and living at home without a co-wife, may I have children!’*";
P_HTM[6068]="*idaṃ, bhikkhave, catutthaṃ ṭhānaṃ sulabhaṃ katapuññena mātugāmena.**This is the fourth thing.*";
P_HTM[6069]="*Patirūpe kule jāyitvā patirūpaṃ kulaṃ gantvā asapatti agāraṃ ajjhāvasantī puttavatī samānā sāmikaṃ abhibhuyya vatteyyanti—**‘Having been born into a suitable family, and married into a suitable family, and living at home without a co-wife, and having had children, may I master my husband!’*";
P_HTM[6070]="*idaṃ, bhikkhave, pañcamaṃ ṭhānaṃ sulabhaṃ katapuññena mātugāmena.**This is the fifth thing.*";
P_HTM[6071]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca ṭhānāni sulabhāni katapuññena mātugāmenā”ti.**These are the five things that are easy to get for females who have made merit.”*";
P_HTM[6072]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6073]="*9. Pañcasīlavisāradasuttaṃ**Living With Self*";
P_HTM[6074]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo visārado agāraṃ ajjhāvasati.**“Mendicants, a female living at home with five qualities is self-assured.*";
P_HTM[6075]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[6076]="*Pāṇātipātā paṭivirato ca hoti, adinnādānā paṭivirato ca hoti, kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato ca hoti, musāvādā paṭivirato ca hoti, surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānā paṭivirato ca hoti—**She doesn’t kill living creatures, steal, commit sexual misconduct, lie, or consume alcoholic drinks that cause negligence.*";
P_HTM[6077]="*imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo visārado agāraṃ ajjhāvasatī”ti.**A female living at home with these five qualities is self-assured.”*";
P_HTM[6078]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6079]="*10. Vaḍḍhīsuttaṃ**Growth*";
P_HTM[6080]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, vaḍḍhīhi vaḍḍhamānā ariyasāvikā ariyāya vaḍḍhiyā vaḍḍhati sārādāyinī ca hoti varādāyinī ca kāyassa.**“Mendicants, a female noble disciple who grows in five ways grows nobly, taking on what is essential and excellent in this life.*";
P_HTM[6081]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[6082]="*Saddhāya vaḍḍhati, sīlena vaḍḍhati, sutena vaḍḍhati, cāgena vaḍḍhati, paññāya vaḍḍhati—**She grows in faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[6083]="*imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi vaḍḍhīhi vaḍḍhamānā ariyasāvikā ariyāya vaḍḍhiyā vaḍḍhati, sārādāyinī ca hoti, varādāyinī ca kāyassāti.**A female noble disciple who grows in these five ways grows nobly, taking on what is essential and excellent in this life.*";
P_HTM[6084]="*Saddhāya sīlena ca yādha vaḍḍhati,**When she grows in faith and ethics,*";
P_HTM[6085]="*Paññāya cāgena sutena cūbhayaṃ;**wisdom, and both generosity and learning—*";
P_HTM[6086]="*Sā tādisī sīlavatī upāsikā,**a virtuous laywoman such as she*";
P_HTM[6087]="*Ādīyati sāramidheva attano”ti.**takes on what is essential for herself in this life.”*";
P_HTM[6088]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6089]="*Balavaggo tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[6090]="*Visāradā pasayha abhibhuyya,* **";
P_HTM[6091]="*Ekaṃ aṅgena pañcamaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[6092]="*Nāsenti hetu ṭhānañca,* **";
P_HTM[6093]="*Visārado vaḍḍhinā dasāti.* **";
P_HTM[6094]="*Mātugāmasaṃyuttaṃ samattaṃ.**The Linked Discourses on females are complete.*";
P_HTM[6095]="*38. Jambukhādakasaṃyuttaṃ* **";
P_HTM[6096]="*1. Aniccavaggo**With Jambukhādaka*";
P_HTM[6097]="*1. Nibbānapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About Extinguishment*";
P_HTM[6098]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā sāriputto magadhesu viharati nālakagāmake.**At one time Venerable Sāriputta was staying in the land of the Magadhans near the little village of Nālaka.*";
P_HTM[6099]="*Atha kho jambukhādako paribbājako yenāyasmā sāriputto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā sāriputtena saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then the wanderer Jambukhādaka went up to Venerable Sāriputta and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[6100]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho jambukhādako paribbājako āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to Sāriputta:*";
P_HTM[6101]="*“‘Nibbānaṃ, nibbānan’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘extinguishment’.*";
P_HTM[6102]="*Katamaṃ nu kho, āvuso, nibbānan”ti?**What is extinguishment?”*";
P_HTM[6103]="*“Yo kho, āvuso, rāgakkhayo dosakkhayo mohakkhayo—**“Reverend, the ending of greed, hate, and delusion*";
P_HTM[6104]="*idaṃ vuccati nibbānan”ti.**is called extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[6105]="*“Atthi panāvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā etassa nibbānassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti?**“But, reverend, is there a path and a practice for realizing this extinguishment?”*";
P_HTM[6106]="*“Atthi kho, āvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā etassa nibbānassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti.**“There is, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[6107]="*“Katamo panāvuso, maggo katamā paṭipadā etassa nibbānassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti?**“Well, what is it?”*";
P_HTM[6108]="*“Ayameva kho, āvuso, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo etassa nibbānassa sacchikiriyāya, seyyathidaṃ—**“It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[6109]="*sammādiṭṭhi sammāsaṅkappo sammāvācā sammākammanto sammāājīvo sammāvāyāmo sammāsati sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[6110]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā etassa nibbānassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti.**This is the path, the practice, for realizing this extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[6111]="*“Bhaddako, āvuso, maggo bhaddikā paṭipadā etassa nibbānassa sacchikiriyāya.**“Reverend, this is a fine path, a fine practice, for realizing this extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[6112]="*Alañca panāvuso sāriputta, appamādāyā”ti.**Just this much is enough to be diligent.”*";
P_HTM[6113]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6114]="*2. Arahattapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About Perfection*";
P_HTM[6115]="*“‘Arahattaṃ, arahattan’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘perfection’.*";
P_HTM[6116]="*Katamaṃ nu kho, āvuso, arahattan”ti?**What is perfection?”*";
P_HTM[6117]="*“Yo kho, āvuso, rāgakkhayo dosakkhayo mohakkhayo—**“Reverend, the ending of greed, hate, and delusion*";
P_HTM[6118]="*idaṃ vuccati arahattan”ti.**is called perfection.”*";
P_HTM[6119]="*“Atthi panāvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā etassa arahattassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti?**“But, reverend, is there a path and a practice for realizing this perfection?”*";
P_HTM[6120]="*“Atthi kho, āvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā etassa arahattassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti.**“There is, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[6121]="*“Katamo panāvuso, maggo katamā paṭipadā etassa arahattassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti?**“Well, what is it?”*";
P_HTM[6122]="*“Ayameva kho, āvuso, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo etassa arahattassa sacchikiriyāya, seyyathidaṃ—**“It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[6123]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[6124]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, maggo, ayaṃ paṭipadā etassa arahattassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti.**This is the path, the practice, for realizing this perfection.”*";
P_HTM[6125]="*“Bhaddako, āvuso, maggo bhaddikā paṭipadā etassa arahattassa sacchikiriyāya.**“Reverend, this is a fine path, a fine practice, for realizing this perfection.*";
P_HTM[6126]="*Alañca panāvuso sāriputta, appamādāyā”ti.**Just this much is enough to be diligent.”*";
P_HTM[6127]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6128]="*3. Dhammavādīpañhāsuttaṃ**Principled Speech*";
P_HTM[6129]="*“Ke nu kho, āvuso sāriputta, loke dhammavādino, ke loke suppaṭipannā, ke loke sugatā”ti?**“Reverend Sāriputta, who in the world have principled speech? Who in the world practice well? Who are the Holy Ones in the world?”*";
P_HTM[6130]="*“Ye kho, āvuso, rāgappahānāya dhammaṃ desenti, dosappahānāya dhammaṃ desenti, mohappahānāya dhammaṃ desenti, te loke dhammavādino.**“Reverend, those who teach principles for giving up greed, hate, and delusion have principled speech in the world.*";
P_HTM[6131]="*Ye kho, āvuso, rāgassa pahānāya paṭipannā, dosassa pahānāya paṭipannā, mohassa pahānāya paṭipannā, te loke suppaṭipannā.**Those who practice for giving up greed, hate, and delusion are practicing well in the world.*";
P_HTM[6132]="*Yesaṃ kho, āvuso, rāgo pahīno ucchinnamūlo tālāvatthukato anabhāvaṅkato āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo, doso pahīno ucchinnamūlo tālāvatthukato anabhāvaṅkato āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo, moho pahīno ucchinnamūlo tālāvatthukato anabhāvaṅkato āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo, te loke sugatā”ti.**Those who have given up greed, hate, and delusion—so they’re cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, obliterated, and unable to arise in the future—are Holy Ones in the world.”*";
P_HTM[6133]="*“Atthi panāvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā etassa rāgassa dosassa mohassa pahānāyā”ti?**“But, reverend, is there a path and a practice for giving up that greed, hate, and delusion?”*";
P_HTM[6134]="*“Atthi kho, āvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā etassa rāgassa dosassa mohassa pahānāyā”ti.**“There is, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[6135]="*“Katamo panāvuso, maggo katamā paṭipadā etassa rāgassa dosassa mohassa pahānāyā”ti?**“Well, what is it?”*";
P_HTM[6136]="*“Ayameva kho, āvuso, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo etassa rāgassa dosassa mohassa pahānāya, seyyathidaṃ—**“It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[6137]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[6138]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā etassa rāgassa dosassa mohassa pahānāyā”ti.**This is the path, this is the practice for giving up that greed, hate, and delusion.”*";
P_HTM[6139]="*“Bhaddako, āvuso, maggo bhaddikā paṭipadā, etassa rāgassa dosassa mohassa pahānāya.**“This is a fine path, a fine practice, for giving up greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[6140]="*Alañca panāvuso sāriputta, appamādāyā”ti.**Just this much is enough to be diligent.”*";
P_HTM[6141]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6142]="*4. Kimatthiyasuttaṃ**What’s the Purpose*";
P_HTM[6143]="*“Kimatthiyaṃ, āvuso sāriputta, samaṇe gotame brahmacariyaṃ vussatī”ti?**“Reverend Sāriputta, what’s the purpose of living the spiritual life with the ascetic Gotama?”*";
P_HTM[6144]="*“Dukkhassa kho, āvuso, pariññatthaṃ bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ vussatī”ti.**“The purpose of living the spiritual life under the Buddha is to completely understand suffering.”*";
P_HTM[6145]="*“Atthi panāvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā etassa dukkhassa pariññāyā”ti?**“But, reverend, is there a path and a practice for completely understanding this suffering?”*";
P_HTM[6146]="*“Atthi kho, āvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etassa dukkhassa pariññāyā”ti?**“There is.” …*";
P_HTM[6147]="*“Katamo panāvuso, maggo katamā paṭipadā, etassa dukkhassa pariññāyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[6148]="*“Ayameva kho, āvuso, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, etassa dukkhassa pariññāya, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[6149]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.* **";
P_HTM[6150]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā etassa dukkhassa pariññāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6151]="*“Bhaddako, āvuso, maggo bhaddikā paṭipadā, etassa dukkhassa pariññāya.* **";
P_HTM[6152]="*Alañca panāvuso sāriputta, appamādāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6153]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6154]="*5. Assāsappattasuttaṃ**Solace*";
P_HTM[6155]="*“‘Assāsappatto, assāsappatto’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘gaining solace’.*";
P_HTM[6156]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, āvuso, assāsappatto hotī”ti?**At what point do you gain solace?”*";
P_HTM[6157]="*“Yato kho, āvuso, bhikkhu channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ettāvatā kho, āvuso, assāsappatto hotī”ti.**“When a mendicant truly understands the six fields of contacts’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape, at that point they’ve gained solace.”*";
P_HTM[6158]="*“Atthi panāvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etassa assāsassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti?**“But, reverend, is there a path and a practice for realizing this solace?”*";
P_HTM[6159]="*“Atthi kho, āvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etassa assāsassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti.**“There is.” …*";
P_HTM[6160]="*“Katamo panāvuso, maggo katamā paṭipadā, etassa assāsassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[6161]="*“Ayameva kho, āvuso, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo etassa assāsassa sacchikiriyāya, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[6162]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.* **";
P_HTM[6163]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā, etassa assāsassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6164]="*“Bhaddako, āvuso, maggo bhaddikā paṭipadā, etassa assāsassa sacchikiriyāya.* **";
P_HTM[6165]="*Alañca panāvuso sāriputta, appamādāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6166]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6167]="*6. Paramassāsappattasuttaṃ**Ultimate Solace*";
P_HTM[6168]="*“‘Paramassāsappatto, paramassāsappatto’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘gaining ultimate solace’.*";
P_HTM[6169]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, āvuso, paramassāsappatto hotī”ti?**At what point do you gain ultimate solace?”*";
P_HTM[6170]="*“Yato kho, āvuso, bhikkhu channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimutto hoti, ettāvatā kho, āvuso, paramassāsappatto hotī”ti.**“When a mendicant is freed by not grasping after truly understanding the six fields of contacts’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape, at that point they’ve gained ultimate solace.”*";
P_HTM[6171]="*“Atthi panāvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etassa paramassāsassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti?**“But, reverend, is there a path and a practice for realizing this ultimate solace?”*";
P_HTM[6172]="*“Atthi kho, āvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etassa paramassāsassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti.**“There is.” …*";
P_HTM[6173]="*“Katamo pana, āvuso, maggo katamā paṭipadā, etassa paramassāsassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[6174]="*“Ayameva kho, āvuso, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo etassa paramassāsassa sacchikiriyāya, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[6175]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.* **";
P_HTM[6176]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā, etassa paramassāsassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6177]="*“Bhaddako, āvuso, maggo bhaddikā paṭipadā, etassa paramassāsassa sacchikiriyāya.* **";
P_HTM[6178]="*Alañca panāvuso sāriputta, appamādāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6179]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6180]="*7. Vedanāpañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About Feeling*";
P_HTM[6181]="*“‘Vedanā, vedanā’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘feeling’.*";
P_HTM[6182]="*Katamā nu kho, āvuso, vedanā”ti?**What is feeling?”*";
P_HTM[6183]="*“Tisso imāvuso, vedanā.**“Reverend, there are three feelings.*";
P_HTM[6184]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[6185]="*Sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā—**Pleasant, painful, and neutral feeling.*";
P_HTM[6186]="*imā kho, āvuso, tisso vedanā”ti.**These are the three feelings.”*";
P_HTM[6187]="*“Atthi panāvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etāsaṃ tissannaṃ vedanānaṃ pariññāyā”ti?**“But reverend, is there a path and a practice for completely understanding these three feelings?”*";
P_HTM[6188]="*“Atthi kho, āvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etāsaṃ tissannaṃ vedanānaṃ pariññāyā”ti.**“There is.” …*";
P_HTM[6189]="*“Katamo panāvuso, maggo katamā paṭipadā, etāsaṃ tissannaṃ vedanānaṃ pariññāyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[6190]="*“Ayameva kho, āvuso, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, etāsaṃ tissannaṃ vedanānaṃ pariññāya, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[6191]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.* **";
P_HTM[6192]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā, etāsaṃ tissannaṃ vedanānaṃ pariññāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6193]="*“Bhaddako, āvuso, maggo bhaddikā paṭipadā, etāsaṃ tissannaṃ vedanānaṃ pariññāya.* **";
P_HTM[6194]="*Alañca panāvuso sāriputta, appamādāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6195]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6196]="*8. Āsavapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About Defilements*";
P_HTM[6197]="*“‘Āsavo, āsavo’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘defilement’.*";
P_HTM[6198]="*Katamo nu kho, āvuso, āsavo”ti?**What is defilement?”*";
P_HTM[6199]="*“Tayo me, āvuso, āsavā.**“Reverend, there are three defilements.*";
P_HTM[6200]="*Kāmāsavo, bhavāsavo, avijjāsavo—**The defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[6201]="*ime kho, āvuso, tayo āsavā”ti.**These are the three defilements.”*";
P_HTM[6202]="*“Atthi panāvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā etesaṃ āsavānaṃ pahānāyā”ti?**“But, reverend, is there a path and a practice for completely understanding these three defilements?”*";
P_HTM[6203]="*“Atthi kho, āvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā etesaṃ āsavānaṃ pahānāyā”ti.**“There is.” …*";
P_HTM[6204]="*“Katamo panāvuso, maggo katamā paṭipadā etesaṃ āsavānaṃ pahānāyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[6205]="*“Ayameva kho, āvuso, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo etesaṃ āsavānaṃ pahānāya, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[6206]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.* **";
P_HTM[6207]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā, etesaṃ āsavānaṃ pahānāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6208]="*“Bhaddako, āvuso, maggo bhaddikā paṭipadā, etesaṃ āsavānaṃ pahānāya.* **";
P_HTM[6209]="*Alañca panāvuso sāriputta, appamādāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6210]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6211]="*9. Avijjāpañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About Ignorance*";
P_HTM[6212]="*“‘Avijjā, avijjā’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘ignorance’.*";
P_HTM[6213]="*Katamā nu kho, āvuso, avijjā”ti?**What is ignorance?”*";
P_HTM[6214]="*“Yaṃ kho, āvuso, dukkhe aññāṇaṃ, dukkhasamudaye aññāṇaṃ, dukkhanirodhe aññāṇaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya aññāṇaṃ—**“Not knowing about suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[6215]="*ayaṃ vuccatāvuso, avijjā”ti.**This is called ignorance.”*";
P_HTM[6216]="*“Atthi panāvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etissā avijjāya pahānāyā”ti?**“But, reverend, is there a path and a practice for giving up that ignorance?”*";
P_HTM[6217]="*“Atthi kho, āvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etissā avijjāya pahānāyā”ti.**“There is.” …*";
P_HTM[6218]="*“Katamo panāvuso, maggo katamā paṭipadā, etissā avijjāya pahānāyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[6219]="*“Ayameva kho, āvuso, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, etissā avijjāya pahānāya, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[6220]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.* **";
P_HTM[6221]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā, etissā avijjāya pahānāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6222]="*“Bhaddako, āvuso, maggo bhaddikā paṭipadā, etissā avijjāya pahānāya.* **";
P_HTM[6223]="*Alañca panāvuso sāriputta, appamādāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6224]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6225]="*10. Taṇhāpañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About Craving*";
P_HTM[6226]="*“‘Taṇhā, taṇhā’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘craving’.*";
P_HTM[6227]="*Katamā nu kho, āvuso, taṇhā”ti?**What is craving?”*";
P_HTM[6228]="*“Tisso imā, āvuso, taṇhā.**“Reverend, there are these three cravings.*";
P_HTM[6229]="*Kāmataṇhā, bhavataṇhā, vibhavataṇhā—**Craving for sensual pleasures, craving to continue existence, and craving to end existence.*";
P_HTM[6230]="*imā kho, āvuso, tisso taṇhā”ti.**These are the three cravings.”*";
P_HTM[6231]="*“Atthi panāvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etāsaṃ taṇhānaṃ pahānāyā”ti?**“But, reverend, is there a path and a practice for completely understanding these cravings?”*";
P_HTM[6232]="*“Atthi kho, āvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etāsaṃ taṇhānaṃ pahānāyā”ti.**“There is.” …*";
P_HTM[6233]="*“Katamo panāvuso, maggo katamā paṭipadā, etāsaṃ taṇhānaṃ pahānāyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[6234]="*“Ayameva kho, āvuso, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, etāsaṃ taṇhānaṃ pahānāya, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[6235]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.* **";
P_HTM[6236]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā, etāsaṃ taṇhānaṃ pahānāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6237]="*“Bhaddako, āvuso, maggo bhaddikā paṭipadā, etāsaṃ taṇhānaṃ pahānāya.* **";
P_HTM[6238]="*Alañca panāvuso sāriputta, appamādāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6239]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6240]="*11. Oghapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About Floods*";
P_HTM[6241]="*“‘Ogho, ogho’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘a flood’.*";
P_HTM[6242]="*Katamo nu kho, āvuso, ogho”ti?**What is a flood?”*";
P_HTM[6243]="*“Cattārome, āvuso, oghā.**“Reverend, there are these four floods.*";
P_HTM[6244]="*Kāmogho, bhavogho, diṭṭhogho, avijjogho—**The floods of sensuality, desire to be reborn, views, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[6245]="*ime kho, āvuso, cattāro oghā”ti.**These are the four floods.”*";
P_HTM[6246]="*“Atthi panāvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etesaṃ oghānaṃ pahānāyā”ti?**“But, reverend, is there a path and a practice for completely understanding these floods?”*";
P_HTM[6247]="*“Atthi kho, āvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etesaṃ oghānaṃ pahānāyā”ti.**“There is.” …*";
P_HTM[6248]="*“Katamo panāvuso, maggo katamā paṭipadā, etesaṃ oghānaṃ pahānāyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[6249]="*“Ayameva kho, āvuso, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, etesaṃ oghānaṃ pahānāya, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[6250]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.* **";
P_HTM[6251]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā, etesaṃ oghānaṃ pahānāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6252]="*“Bhaddako, āvuso, maggo bhaddikā paṭipadā, etesaṃ oghānaṃ pahānāya.* **";
P_HTM[6253]="*Alañca panāvuso sāriputta, appamādāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6254]="*Ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6255]="*12. Upādānapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About Grasping*";
P_HTM[6256]="*“‘Upādānaṃ, upādānan’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘grasping’.*";
P_HTM[6257]="*Katamaṃ nu kho, āvuso, upādānan”ti?**What is grasping?”*";
P_HTM[6258]="*“Cattārimāni, āvuso, upādānāni.**“Reverend, there are these four kinds of grasping.*";
P_HTM[6259]="*Kāmupādānaṃ, diṭṭhupādānaṃ sīlabbatupādānaṃ, attavādupādānaṃ—**Grasping at sensual pleasures, views, precepts and observances, and theories of a self.*";
P_HTM[6260]="*imāni kho, āvuso, cattāri upādānānī”ti.**These are the four kinds of grasping.”*";
P_HTM[6261]="*“Atthi panāvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etesaṃ upādānānaṃ pahānāyā”ti?**“But, reverend, is there a path and a practice for completely understanding these four kinds of grasping?”*";
P_HTM[6262]="*“Atthi kho, āvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etesaṃ upādānānaṃ pahānāyā”ti.**“There is.” …*";
P_HTM[6263]="*“Katamo panāvuso, maggo katamā paṭipadā, etesaṃ upādānānaṃ pahānāyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[6264]="*“Ayameva kho, āvuso, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, etesaṃ upādānānaṃ pahānāya, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[6265]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.* **";
P_HTM[6266]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā, etesaṃ upādānānaṃ pahānāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6267]="*“Bhaddako, āvuso, maggo bhaddikā paṭipadā, etesaṃ upādānānaṃ pahānāya.* **";
P_HTM[6268]="*Alañca panāvuso sāriputta, appamādāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6269]="*Dvādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6270]="*13. Bhavapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About States of Existence*";
P_HTM[6271]="*“‘Bhavo, bhavo’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of these things called ‘states of existence’.*";
P_HTM[6272]="*Katamo nu kho, āvuso, bhavo”ti?**What are states of existence?”*";
P_HTM[6273]="*“Tayome, āvuso, bhavā.**“Reverend, there are these three states of existence.*";
P_HTM[6274]="*Kāmabhavo, rūpabhavo, arūpabhavo—**Existence in the sensual realm, the realm of luminous form, and the formless realm.*";
P_HTM[6275]="*ime kho, āvuso, tayo bhavā”ti.**These are the three states of existence.”*";
P_HTM[6276]="*“Atthi panāvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etesaṃ bhavānaṃ pariññāyā”ti?**“But, reverend, is there a path and a practice for completely understanding these three states of existence?”*";
P_HTM[6277]="*“Atthi kho, āvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etesaṃ bhavānaṃ pariññāyā”ti.**“There is.” …*";
P_HTM[6278]="*“Katamo, panāvuso, maggo katamā paṭipadā, etesaṃ bhavānaṃ pariññāyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[6279]="*“Ayameva kho, āvuso, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, etesaṃ bhavānaṃ pariññāya, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[6280]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.* **";
P_HTM[6281]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā, etesaṃ bhavānaṃ pariññāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6282]="*“Bhaddako, āvuso, maggo bhaddikā paṭipadā, etesaṃ bhavānaṃ pariññāya.* **";
P_HTM[6283]="*Alañca panāvuso sāriputta, appamādāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6284]="*Terasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6285]="*14. Dukkhapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About Suffering*";
P_HTM[6286]="*“‘Dukkhaṃ, dukkhan’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘suffering’.*";
P_HTM[6287]="*Katamaṃ nu kho, āvuso, dukkhan”ti?**What is suffering?”*";
P_HTM[6288]="*“Tisso imā, āvuso, dukkhatā.**“Reverend, there are these three forms of suffering.*";
P_HTM[6289]="*Dukkhadukkhatā, saṅkhāradukkhatā, vipariṇāmadukkhatā—**The suffering inherent in painful feeling; the suffering inherent in conditions; and the suffering inherent in perishing.*";
P_HTM[6290]="*imā kho, āvuso, tisso dukkhatā”ti.**These are the three forms of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[6291]="*“Atthi panāvuso maggo atthi paṭipadā, etāsaṃ dukkhatānaṃ pariññāyā”ti?**“But, reverend, is there a path and a practice for completely understanding these three forms of suffering?”*";
P_HTM[6292]="*“Atthi kho, āvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etāsaṃ dukkhatānaṃ pariññāyā”ti.**“There is.” …*";
P_HTM[6293]="*“Katamo panāvuso, maggo katamā paṭipadā, etāsaṃ dukkhatānaṃ pariññāyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[6294]="*“Ayameva kho, āvuso, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, etāsaṃ dukkhatānaṃ pariññāya, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[6295]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.* **";
P_HTM[6296]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā, etāsaṃ dukkhatānaṃ pariññāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6297]="*“Bhaddako, āvuso, maggo bhaddikā paṭipadā, etāsaṃ dukkhatānaṃ pariññāya.* **";
P_HTM[6298]="*Alañca panāvuso sāriputta, appamādāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6299]="*Cuddasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6300]="*15. Sakkāyapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About Identity*";
P_HTM[6301]="*“‘Sakkāyo, sakkāyo’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘identity’.*";
P_HTM[6302]="*Katamo nu kho, āvuso, sakkāyo”ti?**What is identity?”*";
P_HTM[6303]="*“Pañcime, āvuso, upādānakkhandhā sakkāyo vutto bhagavatā, seyyathidaṃ—**“Reverend, the Buddha said that these five grasping aggregates are identity. That is,*";
P_HTM[6304]="*rūpupādānakkhandho, vedanupādānakkhandho, saññupādānakkhandho, saṅkhārupādānakkhandho, viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[6305]="*Ime kho, āvuso, pañcupādānakkhandhā sakkāyo vutto bhagavatā”ti.**The Buddha said that these five grasping aggregates are identity.”*";
P_HTM[6306]="*“Atthi panāvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etassa sakkāyassa pariññāyā”ti?**“But, reverend, is there a path and a practice for completely understanding this identity?”*";
P_HTM[6307]="*“Atthi kho, āvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etassa sakkāyassa pariññāyā”ti.**“There is.” …*";
P_HTM[6308]="*“Katamo panāvuso, maggo katamā paṭipadā, etassa sakkāyassa pariññāyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[6309]="*“Ayameva kho, āvuso, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, etassa sakkāyassa pariññāya, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[6310]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.* **";
P_HTM[6311]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā, etassa sakkāyassa pariññāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6312]="*“Bhaddako, āvuso, maggo bhaddikā paṭipadā, etassa sakkāyassa pariññāya.* **";
P_HTM[6313]="*Alañca panāvuso sāriputta, appamādāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6314]="*Pannarasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6315]="*16. Dukkarapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About What’s Hard to Do*";
P_HTM[6316]="*“Kiṃ nu kho, āvuso sāriputta, imasmiṃ dhammavinaye dukkaran”ti?**“Reverend Sāriputta, in this teaching and training, what is hard to do?”*";
P_HTM[6317]="*“Pabbajjā kho, āvuso, imasmiṃ dhammavinaye dukkarā”ti.**“Going forth, reverend, is hard to do in this teaching and training.”*";
P_HTM[6318]="*“Pabbajitena panāvuso, kiṃ dukkaran”ti?**“But what’s hard to do for someone who has gone forth?”*";
P_HTM[6319]="*“Pabbajitena kho, āvuso, abhirati dukkarā”ti.**“When you’ve gone forth it’s hard to be satisfied.”*";
P_HTM[6320]="*“Abhiratena panāvuso, kiṃ dukkaran”ti?**“But what’s hard to do for someone who is satisfied?”*";
P_HTM[6321]="*“Abhiratena kho, āvuso, dhammānudhammappaṭipatti dukkarā”ti.**“When you’re satisfied, it’s hard to practice in line with the teaching.”*";
P_HTM[6322]="*“Kīvaciraṃ panāvuso, dhammānudhammappaṭipanno bhikkhu arahaṃ assā”ti?**“But if a mendicant practices in line with the teaching, will it take them long to become a perfected one?”*";
P_HTM[6323]="*“Naciraṃ, āvuso”ti.**“Not long, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[6324]="*Soḷasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6325]="*Jambukhādakasaṃyuttaṃ samattaṃ.**The Linked Discourses with Jambukhādaka are complete.*";
P_HTM[6326]="*Nibbānaṃ arahattañca,* **";
P_HTM[6327]="*dhammavādī kimatthiyaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[6328]="*Assāso paramassāso,* **";
P_HTM[6329]="*vedanā āsavāvijjā;* **";
P_HTM[6330]="*Taṇhā oghā upādānaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[6331]="*bhavo dukkhañca sakkāyo.* **";
P_HTM[6332]="*Imasmiṃ dhammavinaye dukkaranti.* **";
P_HTM[6333]="*39. Sāmaṇḍakasaṃyuttaṃ* **";
P_HTM[6334]="*1. Aniccavaggo**Sāmaṇḍakavagga*";
P_HTM[6335]="*1. Sāmaṇḍakasuttaṃ**1. Sāmaṇḍakasutta*";
P_HTM[6336]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā sāriputto vajjīsu viharati ukkacelāyaṃ gaṅgāya nadiyā tīre.**At one time Venerable Sāriputta was staying in the land of the Vajjis near Ukkacelā on the bank of the Ganges river.*";
P_HTM[6337]="*Atha kho sāmaṇḍako paribbājako yenāyasmā sāriputto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā sāriputtena saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then the wanderer Sāmaṇḍaka went up to Venerable Sāriputta and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[6338]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho sāmaṇḍako paribbājako āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to Sāriputta:*";
P_HTM[6339]="*“‘Nibbānaṃ, nibbānan’ti, āvuso sāriputta, vuccati.**“Reverend Sāriputta, they speak of this thing called ‘extinguishment’.*";
P_HTM[6340]="*Katamaṃ nu kho, āvuso, nibbānan”ti?**What is extinguishment?”*";
P_HTM[6341]="*“Yo kho, āvuso, rāgakkhayo dosakkhayo mohakkhayo—**“Reverend, the ending of greed, hate, and delusion*";
P_HTM[6342]="*idaṃ vuccati nibbānan”ti.**is called extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[6343]="*“Atthi panāvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etassa nibbānassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti?**“But, reverend, is there a path and a practice for realizing this extinguishment?”*";
P_HTM[6344]="*“Atthi kho, āvuso, maggo atthi paṭipadā, etassa nibbānassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti.**“There is, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[6345]="*“Katamo panāvuso, maggo katamā paṭipadā etassa nibbānassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti?**“Well, what is it?”*";
P_HTM[6346]="*“Ayameva kho, āvuso, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, etassa nibbānassa sacchikiriyāya, seyyathidaṃ—**“It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[6347]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[6348]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā, etassa nibbānassa sacchikiriyāyā”ti.**This is the path, the practice, for realizing this extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[6349]="*“Bhaddako, āvuso, maggo bhaddikā paṭipadā, etassa nibbānassa sacchikiriyāya.**“Reverend, this is a fine path, a fine practice, for realizing this extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[6350]="*Alañca panāvuso sāriputta, appamādāyā”ti.**Just this much is enough to be diligent.”*";
P_HTM[6351]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6352]="*(Yathā jambukhādakasaṃyuttaṃ, tathā vitthāretabbaṃ.)**(These should be expanded in the same way as the Linked Discourses with Jambukhādaka.)*";
P_HTM[6353]="*2. Dukkarasuttaṃ**Hard to Do*";
P_HTM[6354]="*“Kiṃ nu kho, āvuso sāriputta, imasmiṃ dhammavinaye dukkaran”ti?**“Reverend Sāriputta, in this teaching and training, what is hard to do?”*";
P_HTM[6355]="*“Pabbajjā kho, āvuso, imasmiṃ dhammavinaye dukkarā”ti.**“Going forth, reverend, is hard to do in this teaching and training.”*";
P_HTM[6356]="*“Pabbajitena panāvuso, kiṃ dukkaran”ti?**“But what’s hard to do for someone who has gone forth?”*";
P_HTM[6357]="*“Pabbajitena kho, āvuso, abhirati dukkarā”ti.**“When you’ve gone forth it’s hard to be satisfied.”*";
P_HTM[6358]="*“Abhiratena panāvuso, kiṃ dukkaran”ti?**“But what’s hard to do for someone who is satisfied?”*";
P_HTM[6359]="*“Abhiratena kho, āvuso, dhammānudhammappaṭipatti dukkarā”ti.**“When you’re satisfied, it’s hard to practice in line with the teaching.”*";
P_HTM[6360]="*“Kīvaciraṃ panāvuso, dhammānudhammappaṭipanno bhikkhu arahaṃ assā”ti?**“But if a mendicant practices in line with the teaching, will it take them long to become a perfected one?”*";
P_HTM[6361]="*“Naciraṃ, āvuso”ti.**“Not long, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[6362]="*Soḷasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6363]="*(Purimakasadisaṃ uddānaṃ.)* **";
P_HTM[6364]="*Sāmaṇḍakasaṃyuttaṃ samattaṃ.**The Linked Discourses with Sāmaṇḍaka are complete.*";
P_HTM[6365]="*40. Moggallānasaṃyuttaṃ* **";
P_HTM[6366]="*1. Aniccavaggo**By Moggallāna*";
P_HTM[6367]="*1. Paṭhamajhānapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About the First Absorption*";
P_HTM[6368]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā mahāmoggallāno sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time Venerable Mahāmoggallāna was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[6369]="*Tatra kho āyasmā mahāmoggallāno bhikkhū āmantesi:**There Venerable Mahāmoggallāna addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[6370]="*“āvuso bhikkhave”ti.**“Reverends, mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[6371]="*“Āvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato mahāmoggallānassa paccassosuṃ.**“Reverend,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[6372]="*Āyasmā mahāmoggallāno etadavoca:**Venerable Mahāmoggallāna said this:*";
P_HTM[6373]="*“Idha mayhaṃ, āvuso, rahogatassa paṭisallīnassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**“Just now, reverends, as I was in private retreat this thought came to mind:*";
P_HTM[6374]="*‘paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ, paṭhamaṃ jhānan’ti vuccati.**‘They speak of this thing called the “first absorption”.*";
P_HTM[6375]="*Katamaṃ nu kho paṭhamaṃ jhānanti?**What is the first absorption?’*";
P_HTM[6376]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, etadahosi:**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[6377]="*‘idha bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**‘It’s when a mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[6378]="*Idaṃ vuccati paṭhamaṃ jhānan’ti.**This is called the first absorption.’*";
P_HTM[6379]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**And so … I was entering and remaining in the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[6380]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, iminā vihārena viharato kāmasahagatā saññāmanasikārā samudācaranti.**While I was in that meditation, perceptions and attentions accompanied by sensual pleasures beset me.*";
P_HTM[6381]="*Atha kho maṃ, āvuso, bhagavā iddhiyā upasaṅkamitvā etadavoca:**Then the Buddha came up to me with his psychic power and said,*";
P_HTM[6382]="*‘moggallāna, moggallāna.**‘Moggallāna, Moggallāna!*";
P_HTM[6383]="*Mā, brāhmaṇa, paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ pamādo, paṭhame jhāne cittaṃ saṇṭhapehi, paṭhame jhāne cittaṃ ekodiṃ karohi, paṭhame jhāne cittaṃ samādahā’ti.**Don’t neglect the first absorption, brahmin! Settle your mind in the first absorption; unify your mind and immerse it in the first absorption.’*";
P_HTM[6384]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, aparena samayena vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja vihāsiṃ.**And so, after some time … I entered and remained in the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[6385]="*Yañhi taṃ, āvuso, sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**So if anyone should be rightly called*";
P_HTM[6386]="*‘satthārānuggahito sāvako mahābhiññataṃ patto’ti, mamaṃ taṃ sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**a disciple who attained to great direct knowledge with help from the Teacher, it’s me.”*";
P_HTM[6387]="*‘satthārānuggahito sāvako mahābhiññataṃ patto’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6388]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6389]="*2. Dutiyajhānapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About the Second Absorption*";
P_HTM[6390]="*“‘Dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ, dutiyaṃ jhānan’ti vuccati.**“They speak of this thing called the 'second absorption'.*";
P_HTM[6391]="*Katamaṃ nu kho dutiyaṃ jhānanti?**What is the second absorption?”*";
P_HTM[6392]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, etadahosi:**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[6393]="*‘idha bhikkhu vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**‘As the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, a mendicant enters and remains in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[6394]="*Idaṃ vuccati dutiyaṃ jhānan’ti.**This is called the second absorption.’*";
P_HTM[6395]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**And so … I was entering and remaining in the second absorption.*";
P_HTM[6396]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, iminā vihārena viharato vitakkasahagatā saññāmanasikārā samudācaranti.**While I was in that meditation, perceptions and attentions accompanied by placing the mind beset me.*";
P_HTM[6397]="*Atha kho maṃ, āvuso, bhagavā iddhiyā upasaṅkamitvā etadavoca:**Then the Buddha came up to me with his psychic power and said,*";
P_HTM[6398]="*‘moggallāna, moggallāna.**‘Moggallāna, Moggallāna!*";
P_HTM[6399]="*Mā, brāhmaṇa, dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ pamādo, dutiye jhāne cittaṃ saṇṭhapehi, dutiye jhāne cittaṃ ekodiṃ karohi, dutiye jhāne cittaṃ samādahā’ti.**Don’t neglect the second absorption, brahmin! Settle your mind in the second absorption; unify your mind and immerse it in the second absorption.’*";
P_HTM[6400]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, aparena samayena vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja vihāsiṃ.**And so, after some time … I entered and remained in the second absorption.*";
P_HTM[6401]="*Yañhi taṃ, āvuso, sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**So if anyone should be rightly called*";
P_HTM[6402]="*‘satthārānuggahito sāvako mahābhiññataṃ patto’ti, mamaṃ taṃ sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**a disciple who attained to great direct knowledge with help from the Teacher, it’s me.”*";
P_HTM[6403]="*‘satthārānuggahito sāvako mahābhiññataṃ patto’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6404]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6405]="*3. Tatiyajhānapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About the Third Absorption*";
P_HTM[6406]="*“‘Tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ, tatiyaṃ jhānan’ti vuccati.**“They speak of this thing called the ‘third absorption’.*";
P_HTM[6407]="*Katamaṃ nu kho tatiyaṃ jhānanti?**What is the third absorption?*";
P_HTM[6408]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, etadahosi—**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[6409]="*idha bhikkhu pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati sato ca sampajāno sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedeti, yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti: ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**‘With the fading away of rapture, a mendicant enters and remains in the third absorption, where they meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, “Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.”*";
P_HTM[6410]="*Idaṃ vuccati tatiyaṃ jhānanti.**This is called the third absorption.’*";
P_HTM[6411]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharāmi sato ca sampajāno sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedemi. Yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti: ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**And so … I was entering and remaining in the third absorption.*";
P_HTM[6412]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, iminā vihārena viharato pītisahagatā saññāmanasikārā samudācaranti.**While I was in that meditation, perceptions and attentions accompanied by rapture beset me.*";
P_HTM[6413]="*Atha kho maṃ, āvuso, bhagavā iddhiyā upasaṅkamitvā etadavoca:**Then the Buddha came up to me with his psychic power and said,*";
P_HTM[6414]="*‘moggallāna, moggallāna.**‘Moggallāna, Moggallāna!*";
P_HTM[6415]="*Mā, brāhmaṇa, tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ pamādo, tatiye jhāne cittaṃ saṇṭhapehi, tatiye jhāne cittaṃ ekodiṃ karohi, tatiye jhāne cittaṃ samādahā’ti.**Don’t neglect the third absorption, brahmin! Settle your mind in the third absorption; unify your mind and immerse it in the third absorption.’*";
P_HTM[6416]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, aparena samayena pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharāmi sato ca sampajāno sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedemi, yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti: ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja vihāsiṃ.**And so, after some time … I entered and remained in the third absorption.*";
P_HTM[6417]="*Yañhi taṃ āvuso sammā vadamāno vadeyya … pe … mahābhiññataṃ patto”ti.**So if anyone should be rightly called a disciple who attained to great direct knowledge with help from the Teacher, it’s me.”*";
P_HTM[6418]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6419]="*4. Catutthajhānapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About the Fourth Absorption*";
P_HTM[6420]="*“‘Catutthaṃ jhānaṃ, catutthaṃ jhānan’ti vuccati.**“They speak of this thing called the ‘fourth absorption’.*";
P_HTM[6421]="*Katamaṃ nu kho catutthaṃ jhānanti?**What is the fourth absorption?*";
P_HTM[6422]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, etadahosi:**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[6423]="*‘idha bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**‘It’s when, giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, a mendicant enters and remains in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[6424]="*Idaṃ vuccati catutthaṃ jhānan’ti.**This is called the fourth absorption.’*";
P_HTM[6425]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**And so … I was entering and remaining in the fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[6426]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, iminā vihārena viharato sukhasahagatā saññāmanasikārā samudācaranti.**While I was in that meditation, perceptions and attentions accompanied by pleasure beset me.*";
P_HTM[6427]="*Atha kho maṃ, āvuso, bhagavā iddhiyā upasaṅkamitvā etadavoca:**Then the Buddha came up to me with his psychic power and said,*";
P_HTM[6428]="*‘moggallāna, moggallāna.**‘Moggallāna, Moggallāna!*";
P_HTM[6429]="*Mā, brāhmaṇa, catutthaṃ jhānaṃ pamādo, catutthe jhāne cittaṃ saṇṭhapehi, catutthe jhāne cittaṃ ekodiṃ karohi, catutthe jhāne cittaṃ samādahā’ti.**Don’t neglect the fourth absorption, brahmin! Settle your mind in the fourth absorption; unify your mind and immerse it in the fourth absorption.’*";
P_HTM[6430]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, aparena samayena sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja vihāsiṃ.**And so, after some time … I entered and remained in the fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[6431]="*Yañhi taṃ, āvuso, sammā vadamāno vadeyya … pe … mahābhiññataṃ patto”ti.**So if anyone should be rightly called a disciple who attained to great direct knowledge with help from the Teacher, it’s me.”*";
P_HTM[6432]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6433]="*5. Ākāsānañcāyatanapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About the Dimension of Infinite Space*";
P_HTM[6434]="*“‘Ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ, ākāsānañcāyatanan’ti vuccati.**“They speak of this thing called the ‘dimension of infinite space’.*";
P_HTM[6435]="*Katamaṃ nu kho ākāsānañcāyatananti?**What is the dimension of infinite space?*";
P_HTM[6436]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, etadahosi:**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[6437]="*‘idha bhikkhu sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ananto ākāsoti ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**‘It’s when a mendicant—going totally beyond perceptions of form, with the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity—aware that “space is infinite”, enters and remains in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[6438]="*Idaṃ vuccati ākāsānañcāyatanan’ti.**This is called the dimension of infinite space.’*";
P_HTM[6439]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ananto ākāsoti ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**And so … I was entering and remaining in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[6440]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, iminā vihārena viharato rūpasahagatā saññāmanasikārā samudācaranti.**While I was in that meditation, perceptions and attentions accompanied by forms beset me.*";
P_HTM[6441]="*Atha kho maṃ, āvuso, bhagavā iddhiyā upasaṅkamitvā etadavoca:**Then the Buddha came up to me with his psychic power and said,*";
P_HTM[6442]="*‘moggallāna, moggallāna.**‘Moggallāna, Moggallāna!*";
P_HTM[6443]="*Mā, brāhmaṇa, ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ pamādo, ākāsānañcāyatane cittaṃ saṇṭhapehi, ākāsānañcāyatane cittaṃ ekodiṃ karohi, ākāsānañcāyatane cittaṃ samādahā’ti.**Don’t neglect the dimension of infinite space, brahmin! Settle your mind in the dimension of infinite space; unify your mind and immerse it in the dimension of infinite space.’*";
P_HTM[6444]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, aparena samayena sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ananto ākāsoti ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja vihāsiṃ.**And so, after some time … I entered and remained in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[6445]="*Yañhi taṃ, āvuso, sammā vadamāno vadeyya … pe … mahābhiññataṃ patto”ti.**So if anyone should be rightly called a disciple who attained to great direct knowledge with help from the Teacher, it’s me.”*";
P_HTM[6446]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6447]="*6. Viññāṇañcāyatanapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About the Dimension of Infinite Consciousness*";
P_HTM[6448]="*“‘Viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ, viññāṇañcāyatanan’ti vuccati.**“They speak of this thing called the ‘dimension of infinite consciousness’.*";
P_HTM[6449]="*Katamaṃ nu kho viññāṇañcāyatananti?**What is the dimension of infinite consciousness?*";
P_HTM[6450]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, etadahosi:**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[6451]="*‘idha bhikkhu sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma anantaṃ viññāṇanti viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**‘It’s when a mendicant, going totally beyond the dimension of infinite space, aware that “consciousness is infinite”, enters and remains in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[6452]="*Idaṃ vuccati viññāṇañcāyatanan’ti.**This is called the dimension of infinite consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[6453]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma anantaṃ viññāṇanti viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**And so … I was entering and remaining in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[6454]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, iminā vihārena viharato ākāsānañcāyatanasahagatā saññāmanasikārā samudācaranti.**While I was in that meditation, perceptions and attentions accompanied by the dimension of infinite space beset me.*";
P_HTM[6455]="*Atha kho maṃ, āvuso, bhagavā iddhiyā upasaṅkamitvā etadavoca:**Then the Buddha came up to me with his psychic power and said,*";
P_HTM[6456]="*‘moggallāna, moggallāna.**‘Moggallāna, Moggallāna!*";
P_HTM[6457]="*Mā, brāhmaṇa, viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ pamādo, viññāṇañcāyatane cittaṃ saṇṭhapehi, viññāṇañcāyatane cittaṃ ekodiṃ karohi, viññāṇañcāyatane cittaṃ samādahā’ti.**Don’t neglect the dimension of infinite consciousness, brahmin! Settle your mind in the dimension of infinite consciousness; unify your mind and immerse it in the dimension of infinite consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[6458]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, aparena samayena sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma anantaṃ viññāṇanti viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja vihāsiṃ.**And so, after some time … I entered and remained in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[6459]="*Yañhi taṃ, āvuso, sammā vadamāno vadeyya … pe … mahābhiññataṃ patto”ti.**So if anyone should be rightly called a disciple who attained to great direct knowledge with help from the Teacher, it’s me.”*";
P_HTM[6460]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6461]="*7. Ākiñcaññāyatanapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About the Dimension of Nothingness*";
P_HTM[6462]="*“‘Ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ, ākiñcaññāyatanan’ti vuccati.**“They speak of this thing called the ‘dimension of nothingness’.*";
P_HTM[6463]="*Katamaṃ nu kho ākiñcaññāyatananti?**What is the dimension of nothingness?*";
P_HTM[6464]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, etadahosi:**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[6465]="*‘idha bhikkhu sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma natthi kiñcīti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**‘It’s when a mendicant, going totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness, aware that “there is nothing at all”, enters and remains in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[6466]="*Idaṃ vuccati ākiñcaññāyatanan’ti.**This is called the dimension of nothingness.’*";
P_HTM[6467]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma natthi kiñcīti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**And so … I was entering and remaining in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[6468]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, iminā vihārena viharato viññāṇañcāyatanasahagatā saññāmanasikārā samudācaranti.**While I was in that meditation, perceptions and attentions accompanied by the dimension of infinite consciousness beset me.*";
P_HTM[6469]="*Atha kho maṃ, āvuso, bhagavā iddhiyā upasaṅkamitvā etadavoca:**Then the Buddha came up to me with his psychic power and said,*";
P_HTM[6470]="*‘moggallāna, moggallāna.**‘Moggallāna, Moggallāna!*";
P_HTM[6471]="*Mā, brāhmaṇa, ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ pamādo, ākiñcaññāyatane cittaṃ saṇṭhapehi, ākiñcaññāyatane cittaṃ ekodiṃ karohi, ākiñcaññāyatane cittaṃ samādahā’ti.**Don’t neglect the dimension of nothingness, brahmin! Settle your mind in the dimension of nothingness; unify your mind and immerse it in the dimension of nothingness.’*";
P_HTM[6472]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, aparena samayena sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma natthi kiñcīti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja vihāsiṃ.**And so, after some time … I entered and remained in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[6473]="*Yañhi taṃ, āvuso, sammā vadamāno vadeyya … pe … mahābhiññataṃ patto”ti.**So if anyone should be rightly called a disciple who attained to great direct knowledge with help from the Teacher, it’s me.”*";
P_HTM[6474]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6475]="*8. Nevasaññānāsaññāyatanapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About the Dimension of Neither Perception Nor Non*";
P_HTM[6476]="*“‘Nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ, nevasaññānāsaññāyatanan’ti vuccati.**“They speak of this thing called the ‘dimension of neither perception nor non-perception’.*";
P_HTM[6477]="*Katamaṃ nu kho nevasaññānāsaññāyatananti?**What is the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception?*";
P_HTM[6478]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, etadahosi:**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[6479]="*‘idha bhikkhu sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**‘It’s when a mendicant, going totally beyond the dimension of nothingness, enters and remains in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[6480]="*Idaṃ vuccati nevasaññānāsaññāyatanan’ti.**This is called the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.’*";
P_HTM[6481]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**And so … I was entering and remaining in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[6482]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, iminā vihārena viharato ākiñcaññāyatanasahagatā saññāmanasikārā samudācaranti.**While I was in that meditation, perceptions and attentions accompanied by the dimension of nothingness beset me.*";
P_HTM[6483]="*Atha kho maṃ, āvuso, bhagavā iddhiyā upasaṅkamitvā etadavoca:**Then the Buddha came up to me with his psychic power and said,*";
P_HTM[6484]="*‘moggallāna, moggallāna.**‘Moggallāna, Moggallāna!*";
P_HTM[6485]="*Mā, brāhmaṇa, nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ pamādo, nevasaññānāsaññāyatane cittaṃ saṇṭhapehi, nevasaññānāsaññāyatane cittaṃ ekodiṃ karohi, nevasaññānāsaññāyatane cittaṃ samādahā’ti.**Don’t neglect the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, brahmin! Settle your mind in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception; unify your mind and immerse it in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.’*";
P_HTM[6486]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, aparena samayena sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja vihāsiṃ.**And so, after some time … I entered and remained in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[6487]="*Yañhi taṃ, āvuso, sammā vadamāno vadeyya … pe … mahābhiññataṃ patto”ti.**So if anyone should be rightly called a disciple who attained to great direct knowledge with help from the Teacher, it’s me.”*";
P_HTM[6488]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6489]="*9. Animittapañhāsuttaṃ**A Question About the Signless*";
P_HTM[6490]="*“‘Animitto cetosamādhi, animitto cetosamādhī’ti vuccati.**“They speak of this thing called the ‘signless immersion of the heart’.*";
P_HTM[6491]="*Katamo nu kho animitto cetosamādhīti?**What is the signless immersion of the heart?*";
P_HTM[6492]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, etadahosi:**It occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[6493]="*‘idha bhikkhu sabbanimittānaṃ amanasikārā animittaṃ cetosamādhiṃ upasampajja viharati.**‘It’s when a mendicant, not focusing on any signs, enters and remains in the signless immersion of the heart.*";
P_HTM[6494]="*Ayaṃ vuccati animitto cetosamādhī’ti.**This is called the signless immersion of the heart.’*";
P_HTM[6495]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, sabbanimittānaṃ amanasikārā animittaṃ cetosamādhiṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**And so … I was entering and remaining in the signless immersion of the heart.*";
P_HTM[6496]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, āvuso, iminā vihārena viharato nimittānusāri viññāṇaṃ hoti.**While I was in that meditation, my consciousness followed after signs.*";
P_HTM[6497]="*Atha kho maṃ, āvuso, bhagavā iddhiyā upasaṅkamitvā etadavoca:**Then the Buddha came up to me with his psychic power and said,*";
P_HTM[6498]="*‘moggallāna, moggallāna.**‘Moggallāna, Moggallāna!*";
P_HTM[6499]="*Mā, brāhmaṇa, animittaṃ cetosamādhiṃ pamādo, animitte cetosamādhismiṃ cittaṃ saṇṭhapehi, animitte cetosamādhismiṃ cittaṃ ekodiṃ karohi, animitte cetosamādhismiṃ cittaṃ samādahā’ti.**Don’t neglect the signless immersion of the heart, brahmin! Settle your mind in the signless immersion of the heart; unify your mind and immerse it in the signless immersion of the heart.’*";
P_HTM[6500]="*So khvāhaṃ, āvuso, aparena samayena sabbanimittānaṃ amanasikārā animittaṃ cetosamādhiṃ upasampajja vihāsiṃ.**And so, after some time … I entered and remained in the signless immersion of the heart.*";
P_HTM[6501]="*Yañhi taṃ, āvuso, sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**So if anyone should be rightly called*";
P_HTM[6502]="*‘satthārānuggahito sāvako mahābhiññataṃ patto’ti, mamaṃ taṃ sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**a disciple who attained to great direct knowledge with help from the Teacher, it’s me.”*";
P_HTM[6503]="*‘satthārānuggahito sāvako mahābhiññataṃ patto’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6504]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6505]="*10. Sakkasuttaṃ**With Sakka*";
P_HTM[6506]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahāmoggallāno—seyyathāpi nāma balavā puriso samiñjitaṃ vā bāhaṃ pasāreyya, pasāritaṃ vā bāhaṃ samiñjeyya; evameva—jetavane antarahito devesu tāvatiṃsesu pāturahosi.**And then Venerable Mahāmoggallāna, as easily as a strong person would extend or contract their arm, vanished from Jeta’s Grove and reappeared among the gods of the Thirty-Three.*";
P_HTM[6507]="*Atha kho sakko devānamindo pañcahi devatāsatehi saddhiṃ yenāyasmā mahāmoggallāno tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ mahāmoggallānaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitaṃ kho sakkaṃ devānamindaṃ āyasmā mahāmoggallāno etadavoca:**Then Sakka, lord of gods, with five hundred deities came up to Mahāmoggallāna, bowed, and stood to one side. Mahāmoggallāna said to him:*";
P_HTM[6508]="*“Sādhu kho, devānaminda, buddhasaraṇagamanaṃ hoti.**“Lord of gods, it’s good to go for refuge to the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[6509]="*Buddhasaraṇagamanahetu kho, devānaminda, evam’idhekacce sattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjanti.**It’s the reason why some sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[6510]="*Sādhu kho, devānaminda, dhammasaraṇagamanaṃ hoti.**It’s good to go for refuge to the teaching.*";
P_HTM[6511]="*Dhammasaraṇagamanahetu kho, devānaminda, evam’idhekacce sattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjanti.**It’s the reason why some sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[6512]="*Sādhu kho, devānaminda, saṃghasaraṇagamanaṃ hoti.**It’s good to go for refuge to the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[6513]="*Saṃghasaraṇagamanahetu kho, devānaminda, evam’idhekacce sattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjantī”ti.**It’s the reason why some sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.”*";
P_HTM[6514]="*“Sādhu kho, mārisa moggallāna, buddhasaraṇagamanaṃ hoti.**“My good Moggallāna, it’s good to go for refuge to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[6515]="*Buddhasaraṇagamanahetu kho, mārisa moggallāna, evam’idhekacce sattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjanti.* **";
P_HTM[6516]="*Sādhu kho, mārisa moggallāna, dhammasaraṇagamanaṃ hoti.**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[6517]="*Dhammasaraṇagamanahetu kho, mārisa moggallāna, evam’idhekacce sattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjanti.* **";
P_HTM[6518]="*Sādhu kho, mārisa moggallāna, saṅgha … pe …**the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[6519]="*sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjantī”ti.**It’s the reason why some sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.”*";
