P_HTM[6718]="*Savitakkāvitakkañca,* **";
P_HTM[6719]="*sukhena ca upekkhako;* **";
P_HTM[6720]="*Ākāsañceva viññāṇaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[6721]="*ākiñcaṃ nevasaññinā;* **";
P_HTM[6722]="*Animitto ca sakko ca,* **";
P_HTM[6723]="*candanekādasena cāti.* **";
P_HTM[6724]="*Moggallānasaṃyuttaṃ samattaṃ.**The Linked Discourses on Moggallāna are complete.*";
P_HTM[6725]="*41. Cittasaṃyuttaṃ* **";
P_HTM[6726]="*1. Aniccavaggo**With Citta*";
P_HTM[6727]="*1. Saṃyojanasuttaṃ**The Fetter*";
P_HTM[6728]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ sambahulā therā bhikkhū macchikāsaṇḍe viharanti ambāṭakavane.**At one time several senior mendicants were staying near Macchikāsaṇḍa in the Wild Mango Grove.*";
P_HTM[6729]="*Tena kho pana samayena sambahulānaṃ therānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkantānaṃ maṇḍalamāḷe sannisinnānaṃ sannipatitānaṃ ayamantarākathā udapādi:**Now at that time, after the meal, on return from alms-round, several senior mendicants sat together in the pavilion and this discussion came up among them:*";
P_HTM[6730]="*“‘saṃyojanan’ti vā, āvuso, ‘saṃyojaniyā dhammā’ti vā ime dhammā nānatthā nānābyañjanā udāhu ekatthā byañjanameva nānan”ti?**“Reverends, the ‘fetter’ and the ‘things prone to being fettered’: do these things differ in both meaning and phrasing? Or do they mean the same thing, and differ only in the phrasing?”*";
P_HTM[6731]="*Tatrekaccehi therehi bhikkhūhi evaṃ byākataṃ hoti:**Some senior mendicants answered like this:*";
P_HTM[6732]="*“‘saṃyojanan’ti vā, āvuso, ‘saṃyojaniyā dhammā’ti vā ime dhammā nānatthā ceva nānābyañjanā cā”ti.**“Reverends, the ‘fetter’ and the ‘things prone to being fettered’: these things differ in both meaning and phrasing.”*";
P_HTM[6733]="*Ekaccehi therehi bhikkhūhi evaṃ byākataṃ hoti:**But some senior mendicants answered like this:*";
P_HTM[6734]="*“‘saṃyojanan’ti vā, āvuso, ‘saṃyojaniyā dhammā’ti vā ime dhammā ekatthā byañjanameva nānan”ti.**“Reverends, the ‘fetter’ and the ‘things prone to being fettered’ mean the same thing; they differ only in the phrasing.”*";
P_HTM[6735]="*Tena kho pana samayena citto gahapati migapathakaṃ anuppatto hoti kenacideva karaṇīyena.**Now at that time the householder Citta had arrived at Migapathaka on some business.*";
P_HTM[6736]="*Assosi kho citto gahapati sambahulānaṃ kira therānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkantānaṃ maṇḍalamāḷe sannisinnānaṃ sannipatitānaṃ ayamantarākathā udapādi:**He heard about what those senior mendicants were discussing.*";
P_HTM[6737]="*“‘saṃyojanan’ti vā, āvuso, ‘saṃyojaniyā dhammā’ti vā ime dhammā nānatthā nānābyañjanā udāhu ekatthā byañjanameva nānan”ti?* **";
P_HTM[6738]="*Tatrekaccehi therehi bhikkhūhi evaṃ byākataṃ:* **";
P_HTM[6739]="*“‘saṃyojanan’ti vā, āvuso, ‘saṃyojaniyā dhammā’ti vā ime dhammā nānatthā ceva nānābyañjanā cā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6740]="*Ekaccehi therehi bhikkhūhi evaṃ byākataṃ:* **";
P_HTM[6741]="*“‘saṃyojanan’ti vā, āvuso, ‘saṃyojaniyā dhammā’ti vā ime dhammā ekatthā byañjanameva nānan”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6742]="*Atha kho citto gahapati yena therā bhikkhū tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā there bhikkhū abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho citto gahapati there bhikkhū etadavoca:**So he went up to them, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to them,*";
P_HTM[6743]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante, sambahulānaṃ kira therānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkantānaṃ maṇḍalamāḷe sannisinnānaṃ sannipatitānaṃ ayamantarākathā udapādi:**“Sirs, I heard that you were discussing whether the ‘fetter’ and the ‘things prone to being fettered’ differ in both meaning and phrasing, or whether they mean the same thing, and differ only in the phrasing.”*";
P_HTM[6744]="*‘saṃyojanan’ti vā, āvuso, ‘saṃyojaniyā dhammā’ti vā ime dhammā nānatthā nānābyañjanā udāhu ekatthā byañjanameva nānan”ti?* **";
P_HTM[6745]="*Ekaccehi therehi bhikkhūhi evaṃ byākataṃ:* **";
P_HTM[6746]="*“‘saṃyojanan’ti vā, āvuso, ‘saṃyojaniyā dhammā’ti vā ime dhammā nānatthā ceva nānābyañjanā cā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6747]="*Ekaccehi therehi bhikkhūhi evaṃ byākataṃ “‘saṃyojanan’ti vā, āvuso, ‘saṃyojaniyā dhammā’ti vā ime dhammā ekatthā byañjanameva nānan”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6748]="*“Evaṃ, gahapatī”ti.**“That’s right, householder.”*";
P_HTM[6749]="*“‘Saṃyojanan’ti vā, bhante, ‘saṃyojaniyā dhammā’ti vā ime dhammā nānatthā ceva nānābyañjanā ca.**“Sirs, the ‘fetter’ and the ‘things prone to being fettered’: these things differ in both meaning and phrasing.*";
P_HTM[6750]="*Tena hi, bhante, upamaṃ vo karissāmi.**Well then, sirs, I shall give you a simile.*";
P_HTM[6751]="*Upamāyapidhekacce viññū purisā bhāsitassa atthaṃ ājānanti.**For by means of a simile some sensible people understand the meaning of what is said.*";
P_HTM[6752]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, kāḷo ca balībaddo odāto ca balībaddo ekena dāmena vā yottena vā saṃyuttā assu.**Suppose there was a black ox and a white ox yoked by a single harness or yoke.*";
P_HTM[6753]="*Yo nu kho evaṃ vadeyya:**Would it be right to say that*";
P_HTM[6754]="*‘kāḷo balībaddo odātassa balībaddassa saṃyojanaṃ, odāto balībaddo kāḷassa balībaddassa saṃyojanan’ti, sammā nu kho so vadamāno vadeyyā”ti?**the black ox is the yoke of the white ox, or the white ox is the yoke of the black ox?”*";
P_HTM[6755]="*“No hetaṃ, gahapati.**“No, householder.*";
P_HTM[6756]="*Na kho, gahapati, kāḷo balībaddo odātassa balībaddassa saṃyojanaṃ, napi odāto balībaddo kāḷassa balībaddassa saṃyojanaṃ;**The black ox is not the yoke of the white ox, nor is the white ox the yoke of the black ox.*";
P_HTM[6757]="*yena kho te ekena dāmena vā yottena vā saṃyuttā taṃ tattha saṃyojanan”ti.**The yoke there is the single harness or yoke that they’re yoked by.”*";
P_HTM[6758]="*“Evameva kho, bhante, na cakkhu rūpānaṃ saṃyojanaṃ, na rūpā cakkhussa saṃyojanaṃ;**“In the same way, the eye is not the fetter of sights, nor are sights the fetter of the eye.*";
P_HTM[6759]="*yañca tattha tadubhayaṃ paṭicca uppajjati chandarāgo taṃ tattha saṃyojanaṃ.**The fetter there is the desire and greed that arises from the pair of them.*";
P_HTM[6760]="*Na sotaṃ saddānaṃ …**The ear … nose … tongue … body …*";
P_HTM[6761]="*na ghānaṃ gandhānaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[6762]="*na jivhā rasānaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[6763]="*na kāyo phoṭṭhabbānaṃ saṃyojanaṃ, na phoṭṭhabbā kāyassa saṃyojanaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[6764]="*yañca tattha tadubhayaṃ paṭicca uppajjati chandarāgo taṃ tattha saṃyojanaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6765]="*Na mano dhammānaṃ saṃyojanaṃ, na dhammā manassa saṃyojanaṃ;**mind is not the fetter of thoughts, nor are thoughts the fetter of the mind.*";
P_HTM[6766]="*yañca tattha tadubhayaṃ paṭicca uppajjati chandarāgo taṃ tattha saṃyojanan”ti.**The fetter there is the desire and greed that arises from the pair of them.”*";
P_HTM[6767]="*“Lābhā te, gahapati, suladdhaṃ te, gahapati,**“You’re fortunate, householder, so very fortunate,*";
P_HTM[6768]="*yassa te gambhīre buddhavacane paññācakkhu kamatī”ti.**to traverse the Buddha’s deep teachings with the eye of wisdom.”*";
P_HTM[6769]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6770]="*2. Paṭhamaisidattasuttaṃ**Isidatta (1st)*";
P_HTM[6771]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ sambahulā therā bhikkhū macchikāsaṇḍe viharanti ambāṭakavane.**At one time several senior mendicants were staying near Macchikāsaṇḍa in the Wild Mango Grove.*";
P_HTM[6772]="*Atha kho citto gahapati yena therā bhikkhū tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā there bhikkhū abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho citto gahapati there bhikkhū etadavoca:**Then Citta the householder went up to them, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to them,*";
P_HTM[6773]="*“adhivāsentu me, bhante, therā svātanāya bhattan”ti.**“Sirs, may the senior mendicants please accept my offering of tomorrow’s meal.”*";
P_HTM[6774]="*Adhivāsesuṃ kho therā bhikkhū tuṇhībhāvena.**They consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[6775]="*Atha kho citto gahapati therānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ adhivāsanaṃ viditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā there bhikkhū abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**Knowing that the senior mendicants had consented, Citta got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled them, keeping them on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[6776]="*Atha kho therā bhikkhū tassā rattiyā accayena pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena cittassa gahapatissa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdiṃsu.**Then when the night had passed, the senior mendicants robed up in the morning and, taking their bowls and robes, went to Citta’s home, and sat down on the seats spread out.*";
P_HTM[6777]="*Atha kho citto gahapati yena therā bhikkhū tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā there bhikkhū abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho citto gahapati āyasmantaṃ theraṃ etadavoca:**Then Citta went up to them, bowed, sat down to one side, and asked the senior venerable,*";
P_HTM[6778]="*“‘dhātunānattaṃ, dhātunānattan’ti, bhante thera, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of ‘the diversity of elements’.*";
P_HTM[6779]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, dhātunānattaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā”ti?**In what way did the Buddha speak of the diversity of elements?”*";
P_HTM[6780]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā thero tuṇhī ahosi.**When he said this, the senior venerable kept silent.*";
P_HTM[6781]="*Dutiyampi kho citto gahapati āyasmantaṃ theraṃ etadavoca:**For a second time …*";
P_HTM[6782]="*“‘dhātunānattaṃ, dhātunānattan’ti, bhante thera, vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[6783]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, dhātunānattaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[6784]="*Dutiyampi kho āyasmā thero tuṇhī ahosi.* **";
P_HTM[6785]="*Tatiyampi kho citto gahapati āyasmantaṃ theraṃ etadavoca:**And for a third time, Citta asked him,*";
P_HTM[6786]="*“‘dhātunānattaṃ, dhātunānattan’ti, bhante thera, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of ‘the diversity of elements’.*";
P_HTM[6787]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, dhātunānattaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā”ti?**In what way did the Buddha speak of the diversity of elements?”*";
P_HTM[6788]="*Tatiyampi kho āyasmā thero tuṇhī ahosi.**And a second time and a third time the senior venerable kept silent.*";
P_HTM[6789]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā isidatto tasmiṃ bhikkhusaṅghe sabbanavako hoti.**Now at that time Venerable Isidatta was the most junior mendicant in that Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[6790]="*Atha kho āyasmā isidatto āyasmantaṃ theraṃ etadavoca:**He said to the senior venerable,*";
P_HTM[6791]="*“byākaromahaṃ, bhante thera, cittassa gahapatino etaṃ pañhan”ti?**“Sir, may I answer Citta’s question?”*";
P_HTM[6792]="*“Byākarohi tvaṃ, āvuso isidatta, cittassa gahapatino etaṃ pañhan”ti.**“Answer it, Reverend Isidatta.”*";
P_HTM[6793]="*“Evañhi tvaṃ, gahapati, pucchasi:**“Householder, is this your question:*";
P_HTM[6794]="*‘dhātunānattaṃ, dhātunānattanti, bhante thera, vuccati.**‘They speak of “the diversity of elements”.*";
P_HTM[6795]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, dhātunānattaṃ, vuttaṃ bhagavatā’”ti?**In what way did the Buddha speak of the diversity of elements?’”*";
P_HTM[6796]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[6797]="*“Idaṃ kho, gahapati, dhātunānattaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā—**“This is the diversity of elements spoken of by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[6798]="*cakkhudhātu, rūpadhātu, cakkhuviññāṇadhātu … pe …**The eye element, the sights element, the eye consciousness element …*";
P_HTM[6799]="*manodhātu, dhammadhātu, manoviññāṇadhātu.**The mind element, the thought element, the mind consciousness element.*";
P_HTM[6800]="*Ettāvatā kho, gahapati, dhātunānattaṃ vuttaṃ bhagavatā”ti.**This is how the Buddha spoke of the diversity of elements.”*";
P_HTM[6801]="*Atha kho citto gahapati āyasmato isidattassa bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā there bhikkhū paṇītena khādanīyena bhojanīyena sahatthā santappesi sampavāresi.**Then Citta, having approved and agreed with what Isidatta said, served and satisfied the senior mendicants with his own hands with a variety of delicious foods.*";
P_HTM[6802]="*Atha kho therā bhikkhū bhuttāvino onītapattapāṇino uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkamiṃsu.**When the senior mendicants had eaten and washed their hands and bowls, they got up from their seats and left.*";
P_HTM[6803]="*Atha kho āyasmā thero āyasmantaṃ isidattaṃ etadavoca:**Then the senior venerable said to Venerable Isidatta,*";
P_HTM[6804]="*“sādhu kho taṃ, āvuso isidatta, eso pañho paṭibhāsi, neso pañho maṃ paṭibhāsi.**“Isidatta, it’s good that you felt inspired to answer that question, because I didn’t.*";
P_HTM[6805]="*Tenahāvuso isidatta, yadā aññathāpi evarūpo pañho āgaccheyya, taññevettha paṭibhāseyyā”ti.**So when a similar question comes up, you should also answer it as you feel inspired.”*";
P_HTM[6806]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6807]="*3. Dutiyaisidattasuttaṃ**With Isidatta (2nd)*";
P_HTM[6808]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ sambahulā therā bhikkhū macchikāsaṇḍe viharanti ambāṭakavane.**At one time several senior mendicants were staying near Macchikāsaṇḍa in the Wild Mango Grove.*";
P_HTM[6809]="*Atha kho citto gahapati yena therā bhikkhū tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā there bhikkhū abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho citto gahapati there bhikkhū etadavoca:**Then Citta the householder went up to them, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to them,*";
P_HTM[6810]="*“adhivāsentu me, bhante therā, svātanāya bhattan”ti.**“Sirs, may the senior mendicants please accept my offering of tomorrow’s meal.”*";
P_HTM[6811]="*Adhivāsesuṃ kho therā bhikkhū tuṇhībhāvena.**They consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[6812]="*Atha kho citto gahapati therānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ adhivāsanaṃ viditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā there bhikkhū abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**Then, knowing that the senior mendicants had consented, Citta got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled them, keeping them on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[6813]="*Atha kho therā bhikkhū tassā rattiyā accayena pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena cittassa gahapatissa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdiṃsu.**Then when the night had passed, the senior mendicants robed up in the morning and, taking their bowls and robes, went to Citta’s home, and sat down on the seats spread out.*";
P_HTM[6814]="*Atha kho citto gahapati yena therā bhikkhū tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā there bhikkhū abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho citto gahapati āyasmantaṃ theraṃ etadavoca:**So he went up to them, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to the senior venerable:*";
P_HTM[6815]="*“yā imā, bhante thera, anekavihitā diṭṭhiyo loke uppajjanti:**“Sir, there are many different views that arise in the world. For example:*";
P_HTM[6816]="*‘sassato lokoti vā, asassato lokoti vā, antavā lokoti vā, anantavā lokoti vā, taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīranti vā, aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīranti vā, hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā, na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā, hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā, neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā.**the world is eternal, or not eternal, or finite, or infinite; the soul and the body are the same thing, or they are different things; after death, a Realized One exists, or doesn’t exist, or both exists and doesn’t exist, or neither exists nor doesn’t exist.*";
P_HTM[6817]="*Yāni cimāni dvāsaṭṭhi diṭṭhigatāni brahmajāle bhaṇitāni;**And also the sixty-two misconceptions spoken of in the Supreme Net Discourse.*";
P_HTM[6818]="*imā nu kho, bhante, diṭṭhiyo kismiṃ sati honti, kismiṃ asati na hontī”ti?**When what exists do these views come to be? When what doesn’t exist do these views not come to be?”*";
P_HTM[6819]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā thero tuṇhī ahosi.**When he said this, the senior venerable kept silent.*";
P_HTM[6820]="*Dutiyampi kho citto gahapati … pe …**For a second time …*";
P_HTM[6821]="*tatiyampi kho citto gahapati āyasmantaṃ theraṃ etadavoca:**And for a third time, Citta said to him:*";
P_HTM[6822]="*“yā imā, bhante thera, anekavihitā diṭṭhiyo loke uppajjanti—**“Sir, there are many different views that arise in the world. …*";
P_HTM[6823]="*sassato lokoti vā, asassato lokoti vā, antavā lokoti vā, anantavā lokoti vā, taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīranti vā, aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīranti vā, hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā, na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā, hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā, neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā.* **";
P_HTM[6824]="*Yāni cimāni dvāsaṭṭhi diṭṭhigatāni brahmajāle bhaṇitāni;* **";
P_HTM[6825]="*imā nu kho, bhante, diṭṭhiyo kismiṃ sati honti, kismiṃ asati na hontī”ti?**When what exists do these views come to be? When what doesn’t exist do these views not come to be?”*";
P_HTM[6826]="*Tatiyampi kho āyasmā thero tuṇhī ahosi.**And a second time and a third time the senior venerable kept silent.*";
P_HTM[6827]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā isidatto tasmiṃ bhikkhusaṅghe sabbanavako hoti.**Now at that time Venerable Isidatta was the most junior mendicant in that Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[6828]="*Atha kho āyasmā isidatto āyasmantaṃ theraṃ etadavoca:**He said to the senior venerable,*";
P_HTM[6829]="*“byākaromahaṃ, bhante thera, cittassa gahapatino etaṃ pañhan”ti?**“Sir, may I answer Citta’s question?”*";
P_HTM[6830]="*“Byākarohi tvaṃ, āvuso isidatta, cittassa gahapatino etaṃ pañhan”ti.**“Answer it, Reverend Isidatta.”*";
P_HTM[6831]="*“Evañhi tvaṃ, gahapati, pucchasi:**“Householder, is this your question:*";
P_HTM[6832]="*‘yā imā, bhante thera, anekavihitā diṭṭhiyo loke uppajjanti—**‘There are many different views that arise in the world …*";
P_HTM[6833]="*sassato lokoti vā … pe …;* **";
P_HTM[6834]="*imā nu kho, bhante, diṭṭhiyo kismiṃ sati honti, kismiṃ asati na hontī’”ti?**When what exists do these views come to be? When what doesn’t exist do these views not come to be?’’*";
P_HTM[6835]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[6836]="*“Yā imā, gahapati, anekavihitā diṭṭhiyo loke uppajjanti:**“Householder, there are many different views that arise in the world. For example:*";
P_HTM[6837]="*‘sassato lokoti vā, asassato lokoti vā, antavā lokoti vā anantavā lokoti vā, taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīranti vā, aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīranti vā, hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā, na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā, hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā, neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā.**the world is eternal, or not eternal, or finite, or infinite; the soul and the body are the same thing, or they are different things; after death, a Realized One exists, or doesn’t exist, or both exists and doesn’t exist, or neither exists nor doesn’t exist.*";
P_HTM[6838]="*Yāni cimāni dvāsaṭṭhi diṭṭhigatāni brahmajāle bhaṇitāni;**And also the sixty-two misconceptions spoken of in the Supreme Net Discourse.*";
P_HTM[6839]="*imā kho, gahapati, diṭṭhiyo sakkāyadiṭṭhiyā sati honti, sakkāyadiṭṭhiyā asati na hontī’”ti.**These views come to be when identity view exists. When identity view does not exist they do not come to be.”*";
P_HTM[6840]="*“Kathaṃ pana, bhante, sakkāyadiṭṭhi hotī”ti?**“But sir, how does identity view come about?”*";
P_HTM[6841]="*“Idha, gahapati, assutavā puthujjano ariyānaṃ adassāvī ariyadhammassa akovido ariyadhamme avinīto, sappurisānaṃ adassāvī sappurisadhammassa akovido sappurisadhamme avinīto**“It’s when an uneducated ordinary person has not seen the noble ones, and is neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve not seen good persons, and are neither skilled nor trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[6842]="*rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ, attani vā rūpaṃ, rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ;**They regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[6843]="*vedanaṃ attato samanupassati … pe …**They regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[6844]="*saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[6845]="*saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[6846]="*viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ, attani vā viññāṇaṃ, viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[6847]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapati, sakkāyadiṭṭhi hotī”ti.**That’s how identity view comes about.”*";
P_HTM[6848]="*“Kathaṃ pana, bhante, sakkāyadiṭṭhi na hotī”ti?**“But sir, how does identity view not come about?”*";
P_HTM[6849]="*“Idha, gahapati, sutavā ariyasāvako ariyānaṃ dassāvī ariyadhammassa kovido ariyadhamme suvinīto sappurisānaṃ dassāvī sappurisadhammassa kovido sappurisadhamme suvinīto**“It’s when an educated noble disciple has seen the noble ones, and is skilled and trained in the teaching of the noble ones. They’ve seen good persons, and are skilled and trained in the teaching of the good persons.*";
P_HTM[6850]="*na rūpaṃ attato samanupassati, na rūpavantaṃ vā attānaṃ, na attani vā rūpaṃ, na rūpasmiṃ vā attānaṃ;**They don’t regard form as self, self as having form, form in self, or self in form.*";
P_HTM[6851]="*na vedanaṃ …**They don’t regard feeling …*";
P_HTM[6852]="*na saññaṃ …**perception …*";
P_HTM[6853]="*na saṅkhāre …**choices …*";
P_HTM[6854]="*na viññāṇaṃ attato samanupassati, na viññāṇavantaṃ vā attānaṃ, na attani vā viññāṇaṃ, na viññāṇasmiṃ vā attānaṃ.**consciousness as self, self as having consciousness, consciousness in self, or self in consciousness.*";
P_HTM[6855]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapati, sakkāyadiṭṭhi na hotī”ti.**That’s how identity view does not come about.”*";
P_HTM[6856]="*“Kuto, bhante, ayyo isidatto āgacchatī”ti?**“Sir, where has Venerable Isidatta come from?”*";
P_HTM[6857]="*“Avantiyā kho, gahapati, āgacchāmī”ti.**“I come from Avanti, householder.”*";
P_HTM[6858]="*“Atthi, bhante, avantiyā isidatto nāma kulaputto amhākaṃ adiṭṭhasahāyo pabbajito?**“Sir, there’s a friend of mine called Isidatta who I’ve never met. He’s gone forth from a good family in Avanti.*";
P_HTM[6859]="*Diṭṭho so āyasmatā”ti?**Have you met him?”*";
P_HTM[6860]="*“Evaṃ, gahapatī”ti.**“Yes, householder.”*";
P_HTM[6861]="*“Kahaṃ nu kho so, bhante, āyasmā etarahi viharatī”ti?**“Sir, where is that venerable now staying?”*";
P_HTM[6862]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā isidatto tuṇhī ahosi.**When he said this, Isidatta kept silent.*";
P_HTM[6863]="*“Ayyo no, bhante, isidatto”ti?**“Sir, are you that Isidatta?”*";
P_HTM[6864]="*“Evaṃ, gahapatī”ti.**“Yes, householder.”*";
P_HTM[6865]="*“Abhiramatu, bhante, ayyo isidatto macchikāsaṇḍe.**“Sir, I hope Venerable Isidatta is happy here in Macchikāsaṇḍa,*";
P_HTM[6866]="*Ramaṇīyaṃ ambāṭakavanaṃ.**for the Wild Mango Grove is lovely.*";
P_HTM[6867]="*Ahaṃ ayyassa isidattassa ussukkaṃ karissāmi cīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhārānan”ti.**I’ll make sure that Venerable Isidatta is provided with robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick.”*";
P_HTM[6868]="*“Kalyāṇaṃ vuccati, gahapatī”ti.**“That’s nice of you to say, householder.”*";
P_HTM[6869]="*Atha kho citto gahapati āyasmato isidattassa bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā there bhikkhū paṇītena khādanīyena bhojanīyena sahatthā santappesi sampavāresi.**Then Citta, having approved and agreed with what Isidatta said, served and satisfied the senior mendicants with his own hands with a variety of delicious foods.*";
P_HTM[6870]="*Atha kho therā bhikkhū bhuttāvino onītapattapāṇino uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkamiṃsu.**When the senior mendicants had eaten and washed their hands and bowls, they got up from their seats and left.*";
P_HTM[6871]="*Atha kho āyasmā thero āyasmantaṃ isidattaṃ etadavoca:**Then the senior venerable said to Venerable Isidatta,*";
P_HTM[6872]="*“sādhu kho taṃ, āvuso isidatta, eso pañho paṭibhāsi.**“Isidatta, it’s good that you felt inspired to answer that question, because I didn’t.*";
P_HTM[6873]="*Neso pañho maṃ paṭibhāsi.* **";
P_HTM[6874]="*Tenahāvuso isidatta, yadā aññathāpi evarūpo pañho āgaccheyya, taññevettha paṭibhāseyyā”ti.**So when a similar question comes up, you should also answer it as you feel inspired.”*";
P_HTM[6875]="*Atha kho āyasmā isidatto senāsanaṃ saṃsāmetvā pattacīvaramādāya macchikāsaṇḍamhā pakkāmi.**But Isidatta set his lodgings in order and, taking his bowl and robe, left Macchikasaṇḍa,*";
P_HTM[6876]="*Yaṃ macchikāsaṇḍamhā pakkāmi, tathā pakkantova ahosi, na puna paccāgacchīti.**never to return.*";
P_HTM[6877]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6878]="*4. Mahakapāṭihāriyasuttaṃ**Mahaka’s Demonstration*";
P_HTM[6879]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ sambahulā therā bhikkhū macchikāsaṇḍe viharanti ambāṭakavane.**At one time several senior mendicants were staying near Macchikāsaṇḍa in the Wild Mango Grove.*";
P_HTM[6880]="*Atha kho citto gahapati yena therā bhikkhū tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā there bhikkhū abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho citto gahapati there bhikkhū etadavoca:**Then Citta the householder went up to them, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to them,*";
P_HTM[6881]="*“adhivāsentu me, bhante therā, svātanāya gokule bhattan”ti.**“Sirs, may the senior mendicants please accept my offering of tomorrow’s meal in my barn.”*";
P_HTM[6882]="*Adhivāsesuṃ kho therā bhikkhū tuṇhībhāvena.**They consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[6883]="*Atha kho citto gahapati therānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ adhivāsanaṃ viditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā there bhikkhū abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**Then, knowing that the senior mendicants had consented, Citta got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled them, keeping them on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[6884]="*Atha kho therā bhikkhū tassā rattiyā accayena pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena cittassa gahapatino gokulaṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdiṃsu.**Then when the night had passed, the senior mendicants robed up in the morning and, taking their bowls and robes, went to Citta’s barn, and sat down on the seats spread out.*";
P_HTM[6885]="*Atha kho citto gahapati there bhikkhū paṇītena sappipāyāsena sahatthā santappesi sampavāresi.**Then Citta served and satisfied the senior mendicants with his own hands with delicious milk-rice made with ghee.*";
P_HTM[6886]="*Atha kho therā bhikkhū bhuttāvino onītapattapāṇino uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkamiṃsu.**When the senior mendicants had eaten and washed their hands and bowls, they got up from their seats and left.*";
P_HTM[6887]="*Cittopi kho gahapati “sesakaṃ vissajjethā”ti vatvā there bhikkhū piṭṭhito piṭṭhito anubandhi.**Citta instructed that the remainder of the food be distributed, then followed behind the senior mendicants.*";
P_HTM[6888]="*Tena kho pana samayena uṇhaṃ hoti kuthitaṃ;**Now at that time the heat was sweltering.*";
P_HTM[6889]="*te ca therā bhikkhū paveliyamānena maññe kāyena gacchanti, yathā taṃ bhojanaṃ bhuttāvino.**And those senior mendicants walked along as if their bodies were melting, as happens after a meal.*";
P_HTM[6890]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā mahako tasmiṃ bhikkhusaṃghe sabbanavako hoti.**Now at that time Venerable Mahaka was the most junior mendicant in that Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[6891]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahako āyasmantaṃ theraṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Mahaka said to the senior venerable,*";
P_HTM[6892]="*“sādhu khvassa, bhante thera, sītako ca vāto vāyeyya, abbhasampilāpo ca assa, devo ca ekamekaṃ phusāyeyyā”ti.**“Wouldn’t it be nice, sir, if a cool wind blew, a cloud canopy formed, and a gentle rain drizzled down?”*";
P_HTM[6893]="*“Sādhu khvassa, āvuso mahaka, yaṃ sītako ca vāto vāyeyya, abbhasampilāpo ca assa, devo ca ekamekaṃ phusāyeyyā”ti.**“It would indeed be nice, Reverend Mahaka.”*";
P_HTM[6894]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahako tathārūpaṃ iddhābhisaṅkhāraṃ abhisaṅkhari yathā sītako ca vāto vāyi, abbhasampilāpo ca assa, devo ca ekamekaṃ phusi.**Then Mahaka used his psychic power to will that a cool wind would blow, a cloud canopy would form, and a gentle rain would drizzle down.*";
P_HTM[6895]="*Atha kho cittassa gahapatino etadahosi:**Then Citta thought,*";
P_HTM[6896]="*“yo kho imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṃghe sabbanavako bhikkhu tassāyaṃ evarūpo iddhānubhāvo”ti.**“The most junior mendicant in this Saṅgha has such psychic power!”*";
P_HTM[6897]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahako ārāmaṃ sampāpuṇitvā āyasmantaṃ theraṃ etadavoca:**When they reached the monastery, Mahaka said to the senior venerable,*";
P_HTM[6898]="*“alamettāvatā, bhante therā”ti?**“Sir, is that sufficient?”*";
P_HTM[6899]="*“Alamettāvatā, āvuso mahaka.**“That’s sufficient, Reverend Mahaka,*";
P_HTM[6900]="*Katamettāvatā, āvuso mahaka.**you’ve done enough*";
P_HTM[6901]="*Pūjitamettāvatā, āvuso mahakā”ti.**and offered enough.”*";
P_HTM[6902]="*Atha kho therā bhikkhū yathāvihāraṃ agamaṃsu.**Then the senior mendicants entered their dwellings,*";
P_HTM[6903]="*Āyasmāpi mahako sakaṃ vihāraṃ agamāsi.**and Mahaka entered his own dwelling.*";
P_HTM[6904]="*Atha kho citto gahapati yenāyasmā mahako tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ mahakaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho citto gahapati āyasmantaṃ mahakaṃ etadavoca:**Then Citta went up to Mahaka, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[6905]="*“sādhu me, bhante, ayyo mahako uttari manussadhammaṃ iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ dassetū”ti.**“Sir, please show me a superhuman demonstration of psychic power.”*";
P_HTM[6906]="*“Tena hi tvaṃ, gahapati, ālinde uttarāsaṅgaṃ paññapetvā tiṇakalāpaṃ okāsehī”ti.**“Well, then, householder, place your upper robe on the porch and spread a handful of grass on it.”*";
P_HTM[6907]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho citto gahapati āyasmato mahakassa paṭissutvā ālinde uttarāsaṅgaṃ paññapetvā tiṇakalāpaṃ okāsesi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Citta, and did as he was asked.*";
P_HTM[6908]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahako vihāraṃ pavisitvā sūcighaṭikaṃ datvā tathārūpaṃ iddhābhisaṅkhāraṃ abhisaṅkhari yathā tālacchiggaḷena ca aggaḷantarikāya ca acci nikkhamitvā tiṇāni jhāpesi, uttarāsaṅgaṃ na jhāpesi.**Mahaka entered his dwelling and latched the door. Then he used his psychic power to will that a flame shoot out through the keyhole and the chink in the door, and it burned up the grass but not the upper robe.*";
P_HTM[6909]="*Atha kho citto gahapati uttarāsaṅgaṃ papphoṭetvā saṃviggo lomahaṭṭhajāto ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi.**Then Citta shook out his upper robe and stood to one side, shocked and awestruck.*";
P_HTM[6910]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahako vihārā nikkhamitvā cittaṃ gahapatiṃ etadavoca:**Mahaka left his dwelling and said to Citta,*";
P_HTM[6911]="*“alamettāvatā, gahapatī”ti?**“Is that sufficient, householder?”*";
P_HTM[6912]="*“Alamettāvatā, bhante mahaka.**“That’s sufficient, sir,*";
P_HTM[6913]="*Katamettāvatā, bhante, mahaka.**you’ve done enough*";
P_HTM[6914]="*Pūjitamettāvatā, bhante mahaka.**and offered enough.*";
P_HTM[6915]="*Abhiramatu, bhante, ayyo mahako macchikāsaṇḍe.**I hope Venerable Mahaka is happy here in Macchikāsaṇḍa,*";
P_HTM[6916]="*Ramaṇīyaṃ ambāṭakavanaṃ.**for the Wild Mango Grove is lovely.*";
P_HTM[6917]="*Ahaṃ ayyassa mahakassa ussukkaṃ karissāmi cīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhārānan”ti.**I’ll make sure that Venerable Mahaka is provided with robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick.”*";
P_HTM[6918]="*“Kalyāṇaṃ vuccati, gahapatī”ti.**“That’s nice of you to say, householder.”*";
P_HTM[6919]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahako senāsanaṃ saṃsāmetvā pattacīvaramādāya macchikāsaṇḍamhā pakkāmi.**But Mahaka set his lodgings in order and, taking his bowl and robe, left Macchikasaṇḍa,*";
P_HTM[6920]="*Yaṃ macchikāsaṇḍamhā pakkāmi, tathā pakkantova ahosi;**never to return.*";
P_HTM[6921]="*na puna paccāgacchīti.* **";
P_HTM[6922]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6923]="*5. Paṭhamakāmabhūsuttaṃ**With Kāmabhū (1st)*";
P_HTM[6924]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā kāmabhū macchikāsaṇḍe viharati ambāṭakavane.**At one time Venerable Kāmabhū was staying near Macchikāsaṇḍa in the Wild Mango Grove.*";
P_HTM[6925]="*Atha kho citto gahapati yenāyasmā kāmabhū tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ kāmabhuṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho cittaṃ gahapatiṃ āyasmā kāmabhū etadavoca:**Then Citta the householder went up to Venerable Kāmabhū, bowed, and sat down to one side. Kāmabhū said to him,*";
P_HTM[6926]="*“Vuttamidaṃ, gahapati:**“Householder, there is this saying:*";
P_HTM[6927]="*‘Nelaṅgo setapacchādo,**‘With flawless wheel and white canopy,*";
P_HTM[6928]="*ekāro vattatī ratho;**the one-spoke chariot rolls on.*";
P_HTM[6929]="*Anīghaṃ passa āyantaṃ,**See it come, untroubled,*";
P_HTM[6930]="*chinnasotaṃ abandhanan’ti.**with stream cut, unbound.’*";
P_HTM[6931]="*Imassa nu kho, gahapati, saṅkhittena bhāsitassa kathaṃ vitthārena attho daṭṭhabbo”ti?**How should we see the detailed meaning of this brief statement?”*";
P_HTM[6932]="*“Kiṃ nu kho etaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā bhāsitan”ti?**“Sir, was this spoken by the Buddha?”*";
P_HTM[6933]="*“Evaṃ, gahapatī”ti.**“Yes, householder.”*";
P_HTM[6934]="*“Tena hi, bhante, muhuttaṃ āgamehi yāvassa atthaṃ pekkhāmī”ti.**“Well then, sir, please wait a moment while I consider the meaning of this.”*";
P_HTM[6935]="*Atha kho citto gahapati muhuttaṃ tuṇhī hutvā āyasmantaṃ kāmabhuṃ etadavoca:**Then after a short silence Citta said to Kāmabhū:*";
P_HTM[6936]="*“‘Nelaṅgan’ti kho, bhante, sīlānametaṃ adhivacanaṃ.**“Sir, ‘flawless wheel’ is a term for ethics.*";
P_HTM[6937]="*‘Setapacchādo’ti kho, bhante, vimuttiyā etaṃ adhivacanaṃ.**‘White canopy’ is a term for freedom.*";
P_HTM[6938]="*‘Ekāro’ti kho, bhante, satiyā etaṃ adhivacanaṃ.**‘One spoke’ is a term for mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[6939]="*‘Vattatī’ti kho, bhante, abhikkamapaṭikkamassetaṃ adhivacanaṃ.**‘Rolls on’ is a term for going forward and coming back.*";
P_HTM[6940]="*‘Ratho’ti kho, bhante, imassetaṃ cātumahābhūtikassa kāyassa adhivacanaṃ mātāpettikasambhavassa odanakummāsūpacayassa aniccucchādanaparimaddanabhedanaviddhaṃsanadhammassa.**‘Chariot’ is a term for this body made up of the four primary elements, produced by mother and father, built up from rice and porridge, liable to impermanence, to wearing away and erosion, to breaking up and destruction.*";
P_HTM[6941]="*Rāgo kho, bhante, nīgho, doso nīgho, moho nīgho.**Greed, hate, and delusion are troubles.*";
P_HTM[6942]="*Te khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno pahīnā ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.**A mendicant who has ended the defilements has given these up, cut them off at the root, made them like a palm stump, and obliterated them, so they are unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[6943]="*Tasmā khīṇāsavo bhikkhu ‘anīgho’ti vuccati.**That’s why a mendicant who has ended the defilements is called ‘untroubled’.*";
P_HTM[6944]="*‘Āyantan’ti kho, bhante, arahato etaṃ adhivacanaṃ.**‘The one who comes’ is a term for the perfected one.*";
P_HTM[6945]="*‘Soto’ti kho, bhante, taṇhāyetaṃ adhivacanaṃ.**‘Stream’ is a term for craving.*";
P_HTM[6946]="*Sā khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno pahīnā ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.**A mendicant who has ended the defilements has given this up, cut it off at the root, made it like a palm stump, and obliterated it, so it’s unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[6947]="*Tasmā khīṇāsavo bhikkhu ‘chinnasoto’ti vuccati.**That’s why a mendicant who has ended the defilements is said to have ‘cut the stream’.*";
P_HTM[6948]="*Rāgo kho, bhante, bandhanaṃ, doso bandhanaṃ, moho bandhanaṃ.**Greed, hate, and delusion are bonds.*";
P_HTM[6949]="*Te khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno pahīnā ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.**A mendicant who has ended the defilements has given these up, cut them off at the root, made them like a palm stump, and obliterated them, so they are unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[6950]="*Tasmā khīṇāsavo bhikkhu ‘abandhano’ti vuccati.**That’s why a mendicant who has ended the defilements is called ‘unbound’.*";
P_HTM[6951]="*Iti kho, bhante, yaṃ taṃ bhagavatā vuttaṃ:**So, sir, that’s how I understand the detailed meaning of what the Buddha said in brief:*";
P_HTM[6952]="*‘Nelaṅgo setapacchādo,**‘With flawless wheel and white canopy,*";
P_HTM[6953]="*ekāro vattatī ratho;**the one-spoke chariot rolls on.*";
P_HTM[6954]="*Anīghaṃ passa āyantaṃ,**See it come, untroubled,*";
P_HTM[6955]="*chinnasotaṃ abandhanan’ti.**with stream cut, unbound.’”*";
P_HTM[6956]="*Imassa kho, bhante, bhagavatā saṅkhittena bhāsitassa evaṃ vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[6957]="*“Lābhā te, gahapati, suladdhaṃ te, gahapati.**“You’re fortunate, householder, so very fortunate,*";
P_HTM[6958]="*Yassa te gambhīre buddhavacane paññācakkhu kamatī”ti.**to traverse the Buddha’s deep teachings with the eye of wisdom.”*";
P_HTM[6959]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6960]="*6. Dutiyakāmabhūsuttaṃ**With Kāmabhū (2nd)*";
P_HTM[6961]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā kāmabhū macchikāsaṇḍe viharati ambāṭakavane.**At one time Venerable Kāmabhū was staying near Macchikāsaṇḍa in the Wild Mango Grove.*";
P_HTM[6962]="*Atha kho citto gahapati yenāyasmā kāmabhū tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho citto gahapati āyasmantaṃ kāmabhuṃ etadavoca:**Then Citta the householder went up to Venerable Kāmabhū, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[6963]="*“kati nu kho, bhante, saṅkhārā”ti?**“Sir, how many processes are there?”*";
P_HTM[6964]="*“Tayo kho, gahapati, saṅkhārā—**“Householder, there are three processes.*";
P_HTM[6965]="*kāyasaṅkhāro, vacīsaṅkhāro, cittasaṅkhāro”ti.**Physical, verbal, and mental processes.”*";
P_HTM[6966]="*“Sādhu, bhante”ti kho citto gahapati āyasmato kāmabhussa bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā āyasmantaṃ kāmabhuṃ uttariṃ pañhaṃ apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir,” Citta approved and agreed with what Kāmabhū said. Then he asked another question:*";
P_HTM[6967]="*“katamo pana, bhante, kāyasaṅkhāro, katamo vacīsaṅkhāro, katamo cittasaṅkhāro”ti?**“But sir, what is the physical process? What’s the verbal process? What’s the mental process?”*";
P_HTM[6968]="*“Assāsapassāsā kho, gahapati, kāyasaṅkhāro, vitakkavicārā vacīsaṅkhāro, saññā ca vedanā ca cittasaṅkhāro”ti.**“Breathing is a physical process. Placing the mind and keeping it connected are verbal processes. Perception and feeling are mental processes.”*";
P_HTM[6969]="*“Sādhu, bhante”ti kho citto gahapati … pe … uttariṃ pañhaṃ apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir,” he asked another question:*";
P_HTM[6970]="*“kasmā pana, bhante, assāsapassāsā kāyasaṅkhāro, kasmā vitakkavicārā vacīsaṅkhāro, kasmā saññā ca vedanā ca cittasaṅkhāro”ti?**“But sir, why is breathing a physical process? Why are placing the mind and keeping it connected verbal processes? Why are perception and feeling mental processes?”*";
P_HTM[6971]="*“Assāsapassāsā kho, gahapati, kāyikā. Ete dhammā kāyappaṭibaddhā, tasmā assāsapassāsā kāyasaṅkhāro.**“Breathing is physical. It’s tied up with the body, that’s why breathing is a physical process.*";
P_HTM[6972]="*Pubbe kho, gahapati, vitakketvā vicāretvā pacchā vācaṃ bhindati, tasmā vitakkavicārā vacīsaṅkhāro.**First you place the mind and keep it connected, then you break into speech. That’s why placing the mind and keeping it connected are verbal processes.*";
P_HTM[6973]="*Saññā ca vedanā ca cetasikā. Ete dhammā cittappaṭibaddhā, tasmā saññā ca vedanā ca cittasaṅkhāro”ti.**Perception and feeling are mental. They’re tied up with the mind, that’s why perception and feeling are mental processes.”*";
P_HTM[6974]="*“Sādhu … pe … uttariṃ pañhaṃ apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir,” he asked another question:*";
P_HTM[6975]="*“kathaṃ pana, bhante, saññāvedayitanirodhasamāpatti hotī”ti?**“But sir, how does someone attain the cessation of perception and feeling?”*";
P_HTM[6976]="*“Na kho, gahapati, saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpajjantassa bhikkhuno evaṃ hoti:**“A mendicant who is entering such an attainment does not think:*";
P_HTM[6977]="*‘ahaṃ saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpajjissan’ti vā ‘ahaṃ saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpajjāmī’ti vā ‘ahaṃ saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpanno’ti vā.**‘I will enter the cessation of perception and feeling’ or ‘I am entering the cessation of perception and feeling’ or ‘I have entered the cessation of perception and feeling.’*";
P_HTM[6978]="*Atha khvassa pubbeva tathā cittaṃ bhāvitaṃ hoti yaṃ taṃ tathattāya upanetī”ti.**Rather, their mind has been previously developed so as to lead to such a state.”*";
P_HTM[6979]="*“Sādhu … pe … uttariṃ pañhaṃ apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir,” he asked another question:*";
P_HTM[6980]="*“saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpajjantassa pana, bhante, bhikkhuno katame dhammā paṭhamaṃ nirujjhanti, yadi vā kāyasaṅkhāro, yadi vā vacīsaṅkhāro, yadi vā cittasaṅkhāro”ti?**“But sir, which cease first for a mendicant who is entering the cessation of perception and feeling: physical, verbal, or mental processes?”*";
P_HTM[6981]="*“Saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpajjantassa kho, gahapati, bhikkhuno vacīsaṅkhāro paṭhamaṃ nirujjhati, tato kāyasaṅkhāro, tato cittasaṅkhāro”ti.**“Verbal processes cease first, then physical, then mental.”*";
P_HTM[6982]="*“Sādhu … pe … uttariṃ pañhaṃ apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir,” he asked another question:*";
P_HTM[6983]="*“yvāyaṃ, bhante, mato kālaṅkato, yo cāyaṃ bhikkhu saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpanno, imesaṃ kiṃ nānākaraṇan”ti?**“What’s the difference between someone who has passed away and a mendicant who has attained the cessation of perception and feeling?”*";
P_HTM[6984]="*“Yvāyaṃ, gahapati, mato kālaṅkato tassa kāyasaṅkhāro niruddho paṭippassaddho, vacīsaṅkhāro niruddho paṭippassaddho, cittasaṅkhāro niruddho paṭippassaddho, āyu parikkhīṇo, usmā vūpasantā, indriyāni viparibhinnāni.**“When someone dies, their physical, verbal, and mental processes have ceased and stilled; their vitality is spent; their warmth is dissipated; and their faculties have disintegrated.*";
P_HTM[6985]="*Yo ca khvāyaṃ, gahapati, bhikkhu saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpanno, tassapi kāyasaṅkhāro niruddho paṭippassaddho, vacīsaṅkhāro niruddho paṭippassaddho, cittasaṅkhāro niruddho paṭippassaddho, āyu aparikkhīṇo, usmā avūpasantā, indriyāni vippasannāni.**When a mendicant has attained the cessation of perception and feeling, their physical, verbal, and mental processes have ceased and stilled. But their vitality is not spent; their warmth is not dissipated; and their faculties are very clear.*";
P_HTM[6986]="*Yvāyaṃ, gahapati, mato kālaṅkato, yo cāyaṃ bhikkhu saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpanno, idaṃ nesaṃ nānākaraṇan”ti.**That’s the difference between someone who has passed away and a mendicant who has attained the cessation of perception and feeling.”*";
P_HTM[6987]="*“Sādhu … pe … uttariṃ pañhaṃ apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir,” he asked another question:*";
P_HTM[6988]="*“kathaṃ pana, bhante, saññāvedayitanirodhasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhānaṃ hotī”ti?**“But sir, how does someone emerge from the cessation of perception and feeling?”*";
P_HTM[6989]="*“Na kho, gahapati, saññāvedayitanirodhasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhahantassa bhikkhuno evaṃ hoti:**“A mendicant who is emerging from such an attainment does not think:*";
P_HTM[6990]="*‘ahaṃ saññāvedayitanirodhasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhahissan’ti vā ‘ahaṃ saññāvedayitanirodhasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhahāmī’ti vā ‘ahaṃ saññāvedayitanirodhasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhito’ti vā.**‘I will emerge from the cessation of perception and feeling’ or ‘I am emerging from the cessation of perception and feeling’ or ‘I have emerged from the cessation of perception and feeling.’*";
P_HTM[6991]="*Atha khvassa pubbeva tathā cittaṃ bhāvitaṃ hoti, yaṃ taṃ tathattāya upanetī”ti.**Rather, their mind has been previously developed so as to lead to such a state.”*";
P_HTM[6992]="*“Sādhu, bhante … pe … uttariṃ pañhaṃ apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir,” he asked another question:*";
P_HTM[6993]="*“saññāvedayitanirodhasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhahantassa pana, bhante, bhikkhuno katame dhammā paṭhamaṃ uppajjanti, yadi vā kāyasaṅkhāro, yadi vā vacīsaṅkhāro, yadi vā cittasaṅkhāro”ti?**“But sir, which arise first for a mendicant who is emerging from the cessation of perception and feeling: physical, verbal, or mental processes?”*";
P_HTM[6994]="*“Saññāvedayitanirodhasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhahantassa, gahapati, bhikkhuno cittasaṅkhāro paṭhamaṃ uppajjati, tato kāyasaṅkhāro, tato vacīsaṅkhāro”ti.**“Mental processes arise first, then physical, then verbal.”*";
P_HTM[6995]="*“Sādhu … pe … uttariṃ pañhaṃ apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir,” he asked another question:*";
P_HTM[6996]="*“saññāvedayitanirodhasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhitaṃ pana, bhante, bhikkhuṃ kati phassā phusanti”?**“But sir, when a mendicant has emerged from the attainment of the cessation of perception and feeling, how many kinds of contact do they experience?”*";
P_HTM[6997]="*“Saññāvedayitanirodhasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhitaṃ kho, gahapati, bhikkhuṃ tayo phassā phusanti—**“They experience three kinds of contact:*";
P_HTM[6998]="*suññato phasso, animitto phasso, appaṇihito phasso”ti.**emptiness, signless, and undirected contacts.”*";
P_HTM[6999]="*“Sādhu … pe … uttariṃ pañhaṃ apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir,” he asked another question:*";
P_HTM[7000]="*“saññāvedayitanirodhasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhitassa pana, bhante, bhikkhuno kiṃninnaṃ cittaṃ hoti, kiṃpoṇaṃ, kiṃpabbhāran”ti?**“But sir, when a mendicant has emerged from the attainment of the cessation of perception and feeling, what does their mind slant, slope, and incline to?”*";
P_HTM[7001]="*“Saññāvedayitanirodhasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhitassa kho, gahapati, bhikkhuno vivekaninnaṃ cittaṃ hoti vivekapoṇaṃ vivekapabbhāran”ti.**“Their mind slants, slopes, and inclines to seclusion.”*";
P_HTM[7002]="*“Sādhu, bhante”ti kho citto gahapati āyasmato kāmabhussa bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā āyasmantaṃ kāmabhuṃ uttariṃ pañhaṃ apucchi:**Saying “Good, sir,” Citta approved and agreed with what Kāmabhū said. Then he asked another question:*";
P_HTM[7003]="*“saññāvedayitanirodhasamāpattiyā pana, bhante, kati dhammā bahūpakārā”ti?**“But sir, how many things are helpful for attaining the cessation of perception and feeling?”*";
P_HTM[7004]="*“Addhā kho tvaṃ, gahapati, yaṃ paṭhamaṃ pucchitabbaṃ taṃ pucchasi.**“Well, householder, you’ve finally asked what you should have asked first!*";
P_HTM[7005]="*Api ca tyāhaṃ byākarissāmi.**Nevertheless, I will answer you.*";
P_HTM[7006]="*Saññāvedayitanirodhasamāpattiyā kho, gahapati, dve dhammā bahūpakārā—**Two things are helpful for attaining the cessation of perception and feeling:*";
P_HTM[7007]="*samatho ca vipassanā cā”ti.**serenity and discernment.”*";
P_HTM[7008]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7009]="*7. Godattasuttaṃ**With Godatta*";
P_HTM[7010]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā godatto macchikāsaṇḍe viharati ambāṭakavane.**At one time Venerable Godatta was staying near Macchikāsaṇḍa in the Wild Mango Grove.*";
P_HTM[7011]="*Atha kho citto gahapati yenāyasmā godatto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ godattaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho cittaṃ gahapatiṃ āyasmā godatto etadavoca:**Then Citta the householder went up to Venerable Godatta, bowed, and sat down to one side. Godatta said to him:*";
P_HTM[7012]="*“yā cāyaṃ, gahapati, appamāṇā cetovimutti, yā ca ākiñcaññā cetovimutti, yā ca suññatā cetovimutti, yā ca animittā cetovimutti, ime dhammā nānatthā nānābyañjanā udāhu ekatthā byañjanameva nānan”ti?**“Householder, the limitless heart’s release, and the heart’s release through nothingness, and the heart’s release through emptiness, and the signless heart’s release: do these things differ in both meaning and phrasing? Or do they mean the same thing, and differ only in the phrasing?”*";
P_HTM[7013]="*“Atthi, bhante, pariyāyo yaṃ pariyāyaṃ āgamma ime dhammā nānatthā ceva nānābyañjanā ca.**“Sir, there is a way in which these things differ in both meaning and phrasing.*";
P_HTM[7014]="*Atthi pana, bhante, pariyāyo yaṃ pariyāyaṃ āgamma ime dhammā ekatthā byañjanameva nānan”ti.**But there’s also a way in which they mean the same thing, and differ only in the phrasing.*";
P_HTM[7015]="*“Katamo ca, bhante, pariyāyo yaṃ pariyāyaṃ āgamma ime dhammā nānatthā ceva nānābyañjanā ca?**And what’s the way in which these things differ in both meaning and phrasing?*";
P_HTM[7016]="*Idha, bhante, bhikkhu mettāsahagatena cetasā ekaṃ disaṃ pharitvā viharati, tathā dutiyaṃ, tathā tatiyaṃ, tathā catutthaṃ. Iti uddhamadho tiriyaṃ sabbadhi sabbattatāya sabbāvantaṃ lokaṃ mettāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyāpajjena pharitvā viharati.**It’s when a mendicant meditates spreading a heart full of love to one direction, and to the second, and to the third, and to the fourth. In the same way above, below, across, everywhere, all around, they spread a heart full of love to the whole world—abundant, expansive, limitless, free of enmity and ill will.*";
P_HTM[7017]="*Karuṇāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**They meditate spreading a heart full of compassion …*";
P_HTM[7018]="*muditāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**They meditate spreading a heart full of rejoicing …*";
P_HTM[7019]="*upekkhāsahagatena cetasā ekaṃ disaṃ pharitvā viharati, tathā dutiyaṃ, tathā tatiyaṃ, tathā catutthaṃ. Iti uddhamadho tiriyaṃ sabbadhi sabbattatāya sabbāvantaṃ lokaṃ upekkhāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyāpajjena pharitvā viharati.**They meditate spreading a heart full of equanimity to one direction, and to the second, and to the third, and to the fourth. In the same way above, below, across, everywhere, all around, they spread a heart full of equanimity to the whole world—abundant, expansive, limitless, free of enmity and ill will.*";
P_HTM[7020]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhante, appamāṇā cetovimutti.**This is called the limitless heart’s release.*";
P_HTM[7021]="*Katamā ca, bhante, ākiñcaññā cetovimutti?**And what is the heart’s release through nothingness?*";
P_HTM[7022]="*Idha, bhante, bhikkhu sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma, ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant, going totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness, aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, enters and remains in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[7023]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhante, ākiñcaññā cetovimutti.**This is called the heart’s release through nothingness.*";
P_HTM[7024]="*Katamā ca, bhante, suññatā cetovimutti?**And what is the heart’s release through emptiness?*";
P_HTM[7025]="*Idha, bhante, bhikkhu araññagato vā rukkhamūlagato vā suññāgāragato vā iti paṭisañcikkhati:**It’s when a mendicant has gone to a wilderness, or to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, and reflects like this:*";
P_HTM[7026]="*‘suññamidaṃ attena vā attaniyena vā’ti.**‘This is empty of a self or what belongs to a self.’*";
P_HTM[7027]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhante, suññatā cetovimutti.**This is called the heart’s release through emptiness.*";
P_HTM[7028]="*Katamā ca, bhante, animittā cetovimutti?**And what is the signless heart’s release?*";
P_HTM[7029]="*Idha, bhante, bhikkhu sabbanimittānaṃ amanasikārā animittaṃ cetosamādhiṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant, not focusing on any signs, enters and remains in the signless immersion of the heart.*";
P_HTM[7030]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhante, animittā cetovimutti.**This is called the signless heart’s release.*";
P_HTM[7031]="*Ayaṃ kho, bhante, pariyāyo yaṃ pariyāyaṃ āgamma ime dhammā nānatthā ceva nānābyañjanā ca.**This is the way in which these things differ in both meaning and phrasing.*";
P_HTM[7032]="*Katamo ca, bhante, pariyāyo yaṃ pariyāyaṃ āgamma ime dhammā ekatthā byañjanameva nānaṃ?**And what’s the way in which they mean the same thing, and differ only in the phrasing?*";
P_HTM[7033]="*Rāgo, bhante, pamāṇakaraṇo, doso pamāṇakaraṇo, moho pamāṇakaraṇo.**Greed, hate, and delusion are makers of limits.*";
P_HTM[7034]="*Te khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno pahīnā ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.**A mendicant who has ended the defilements has given these up, cut them off at the root, made them like a palm stump, and obliterated them, so they are unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[7035]="*Yāvatā kho, bhante, appamāṇā cetovimuttiyo, akuppā tāsaṃ cetovimutti aggamakkhāyati.**The unshakable heart’s release is said to be the best kind of limitless heart’s release.*";
P_HTM[7036]="*Sā kho pana akuppā cetovimutti suññā rāgena, suññā dosena, suññā mohena.**That unshakable heart’s release is empty of greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[7037]="*Rāgo kho, bhante, kiñcanaṃ, doso kiñcanaṃ, moho kiñcanaṃ.**Greed is something, hate is something, and delusion is something.*";
P_HTM[7038]="*Te khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno pahīnā ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.**A mendicant who has ended the defilements has given these up, cut them off at the root, made them like a palm stump, and obliterated them, so they are unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[7039]="*Yāvatā kho, bhante, ākiñcaññā cetovimuttiyo, akuppā tāsaṃ cetovimutti aggamakkhāyati.**The unshakable heart’s release is said to be the best kind of heart’s release through nothingness.*";
P_HTM[7040]="*Sā kho pana akuppā cetovimutti suññā rāgena, suññā dosena, suññā mohena.**That unshakable heart’s release is empty of greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[7041]="*Rāgo kho, bhante, nimittakaraṇo, doso nimittakaraṇo, moho nimittakaraṇo.**Greed, hate, and delusion are makers of signs.*";
P_HTM[7042]="*Te khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno pahīnā ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.**A mendicant who has ended the defilements has given these up, cut them off at the root, made them like a palm stump, and obliterated them, so they are unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[7043]="*Yāvatā kho, bhante, animittā cetovimuttiyo, akuppā tāsaṃ cetovimutti aggamakkhāyati.**The unshakable heart’s release is said to be the best kind of signless heart’s release.*";
P_HTM[7044]="*Sā kho pana akuppā cetovimutti suññā rāgena, suññā dosena, suññā mohena.**That unshakable heart’s release is empty of greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[7045]="*Ayaṃ kho, bhante, pariyāyo yaṃ pariyāyaṃ āgamma ime dhammā ekatthā byañjanameva nānan”ti.**This is the way in which they mean the same thing, and differ only in the phrasing.”*";
P_HTM[7046]="*“Lābhā te, gahapati, suladdhaṃ te, gahapati.**“You’re fortunate, householder, so very fortunate,*";
P_HTM[7047]="*Yassa te gambhīre buddhavacane paññācakkhu kamatī”ti.**to traverse the Buddha’s deep teachings with the eye of wisdom.”*";
P_HTM[7048]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7049]="*8. Nigaṇṭhanāṭaputtasuttaṃ**Nigaṇṭha Nāṭaputta*";
P_HTM[7050]="*Tena kho pana samayena nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto macchikāsaṇḍaṃ anuppatto hoti mahatiyā nigaṇṭhaparisāya saddhiṃ.**Now at that time Nigaṇṭha Nāṭaputta had arrived at Macchikāsaṇḍa together with a large assembly of Jain ascetics.*";
P_HTM[7051]="*Assosi kho citto gahapati: “nigaṇṭho kira nāṭaputto macchikāsaṇḍaṃ anuppatto mahatiyā nigaṇṭhaparisāya saddhin”ti.**Citta the householder heard that they had arrived.*";
P_HTM[7052]="*Atha kho citto gahapati sambahulehi upāsakehi saddhiṃ yena nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā nigaṇṭhena nāṭaputtena saddhiṃ sammodi.**Together with several lay followers, he went up to Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[7053]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho cittaṃ gahapatiṃ nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side. Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta said to him,*";
P_HTM[7054]="*“saddahasi tvaṃ, gahapati, samaṇassa gotamassa—**“Householder, do you have faith in the ascetic Gotama’s claim that*";
P_HTM[7055]="*atthi avitakko avicāro samādhi, atthi vitakkavicārānaṃ nirodho”ti?**there is a state of immersion without placing the mind and keeping it connected; that there is the cessation of placing the mind and keeping it connected?”*";
P_HTM[7056]="*“Na khvāhaṃ ettha, bhante, bhagavato saddhāya gacchāmi.**“Sir, in this case I don’t rely on faith in the Buddha’s claim that*";
P_HTM[7057]="*Atthi avitakko avicāro samādhi, atthi vitakkavicārānaṃ nirodho”ti.**there is a state of immersion without placing the mind and keeping it connected; that there is the cessation of placing the mind and keeping it connected.”*";
P_HTM[7058]="*Evaṃ vutte, nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto ulloketvā etadavoca:**When he said this, Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta looked up at his assembly and said,*";
P_HTM[7059]="*“idaṃ bhavanto passantu, yāva ujuko cāyaṃ citto gahapati, yāva asaṭho cāyaṃ citto gahapati, yāva amāyāvī cāyaṃ citto gahapati, vātaṃ vā so jālena bādhetabbaṃ maññeyya, yo vitakkavicāre nirodhetabbaṃ maññeyya, sakamuṭṭhinā vā so gaṅgāya sotaṃ āvāretabbaṃ maññeyya, yo vitakkavicāre nirodhetabbaṃ maññeyyā”ti.**“See, good sirs, how straightforward this householder Citta is! He’s not devious or deceitful at all. To imagine that you can stop placing the mind and keeping it connected would be like imagining that you can catch the wind in a net, or dam the Ganges river with your own hand.”*";
P_HTM[7060]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, bhante,**“What do you think, sir?*";
P_HTM[7061]="*katamaṃ nu kho paṇītataraṃ—ñāṇaṃ vā saddhā vā”ti?**Which is better—knowledge or faith?”*";
P_HTM[7062]="*“Saddhāya kho, gahapati, ñāṇaṃyeva paṇītataran”ti.**“Knowledge is definitely better than faith, householder.”*";
P_HTM[7063]="*“Ahaṃ kho, bhante, yāvadeva ākaṅkhāmi, vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**“Well sir, whenever I want, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, I enter and remain in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[7064]="*Ahaṃ kho, bhante, yāvadeva ākaṅkhāmi, vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā … pe … dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**And whenever I want, as the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled … I enter and remain in the second absorption.*";
P_HTM[7065]="*Ahaṃ kho, bhante, yāvadeva ākaṅkhāmi, pītiyā ca virāgā … pe … tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**And whenever I want, with the fading away of rapture … I enter and remain in the third absorption.*";
P_HTM[7066]="*Ahaṃ kho, bhante, yāvadeva ākaṅkhāmi, sukhassa ca pahānā … pe … catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**And whenever I want, giving up pleasure and pain … I enter and remain in the fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[7067]="*Na so khvāhaṃ, bhante, evaṃ jānanto evaṃ passanto kassa aññassa samaṇassa vā brāhmaṇassa vā saddhāya gamissāmi?**And so, sir, since I know and see like this, why should I rely on faith in another ascetic or brahmin who claims that*";
P_HTM[7068]="*Atthi avitakko avicāro samādhi, atthi vitakkavicārānaṃ nirodho”ti.**there is a state of immersion without placing the mind and keeping it connected; that there is the cessation of placing the mind and keeping it connected?”*";
P_HTM[7069]="*Evaṃ vutte, nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto sakaṃ parisaṃ apaloketvā etadavoca:**When he said this, Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta looked askance at his own assembly and said,*";
P_HTM[7070]="*“idaṃ bhavanto passantu, yāva anujuko cāyaṃ citto gahapati, yāva saṭho cāyaṃ citto gahapati, yāva māyāvī cāyaṃ citto gahapatī”ti.**“See, good sirs, how crooked this householder Citta is! He’s so devious and deceitful!”*";
P_HTM[7071]="*“Idāneva kho te mayaṃ, bhante, bhāsitaṃ:**“Sir, just now I understood you to say:*";
P_HTM[7072]="*‘evaṃ ājānāma idaṃ bhavanto passantu, yāva ujuko cāyaṃ citto gahapati, yāva asaṭho cāyaṃ citto gahapati, yāva amāyāvī cāyaṃ citto gahapatī’ti.**‘See, good sirs, how straightforward this householder Citta is! He’s not devious or deceitful at all.’*";
P_HTM[7073]="*Idāneva ca pana mayaṃ, bhante, bhāsitaṃ:**But then I understood you to say:*";
P_HTM[7074]="*‘evaṃ ājānāma idaṃ bhavanto passantu, yāva anujuko cāyaṃ citto gahapati, yāva saṭho cāyaṃ citto gahapati, yāva māyāvī cāyaṃ citto gahapatī’ti.**‘See, good sirs, how crooked this householder Citta is! He’s so devious and deceitful!’*";
P_HTM[7075]="*Sace te, bhante, purimaṃ saccaṃ, pacchimaṃ te micchā.**If your first statement is true, the second is wrong.*";
P_HTM[7076]="*Sace pana te, bhante, purimaṃ micchā, pacchimaṃ te saccaṃ.**If your first statement is wrong, the second is true.*";
P_HTM[7077]="*Ime kho pana, bhante, dasa sahadhammikā pañhā āgacchanti.**And also, sir, these ten legitimate questions are relevant.*";
P_HTM[7078]="*Yadā nesaṃ atthaṃ ājāneyyāsi, atha maṃ paṭihareyyāsi saddhiṃ nigaṇṭhaparisāya.**When you understand what they mean, then, together with your assembly of Jain ascetics, you can rebut me.*";
P_HTM[7079]="*Eko pañho, eko uddeso, ekaṃ veyyākaraṇaṃ.**‘One thing: question, summary, and answer. Two … three … four … five … six … seven … eight … nine … ten things: question, summary, and answer.’”*";
P_HTM[7080]="*Dve pañhā, dve uddesā, dve veyyākaraṇāni.* **";
P_HTM[7081]="*Tayo pañhā, tayo uddesā, tīṇi veyyākaraṇāni.* **";
P_HTM[7082]="*Cattāro pañhā, cattāro uddesā, cattāri veyyākaraṇāni.* **";
P_HTM[7083]="*Pañca pañhā, pañca uddesā, pañca veyyākaraṇāni.* **";
P_HTM[7084]="*Cha pañhā, cha uddesā, cha veyyākaraṇāni.* **";
P_HTM[7085]="*Satta pañhā, satta uddesā, satta veyyākaraṇāni.* **";
P_HTM[7086]="*Aṭṭha pañhā, aṭṭha uddesā, aṭṭha veyyākaraṇāni.* **";
P_HTM[7087]="*Nava pañhā, nava uddesā, nava veyyākaraṇāni.* **";
P_HTM[7088]="*Dasa pañhā, dasa uddesā, dasa veyyākaraṇānī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7089]="*Atha kho citto gahapati nigaṇṭhaṃ nāṭaputtaṃ ime dasa sahadhammike pañhe āpucchitvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkāmīti.**Then Citta got up from his seat and left without asking Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta these ten legitimate questions.*";
P_HTM[7090]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7091]="*9. Acelakassapasuttaṃ**With Kassapa, the Naked Ascetic*";
P_HTM[7092]="*Tena kho pana samayena acelo kassapo macchikāsaṇḍaṃ anuppatto hoti cittassa gahapatino purāṇagihisahāyo.**Now at that time the naked ascetic Kassapa, who in lay life was an old friend of Citta, had arrived at Macchikāsaṇḍa.*";
P_HTM[7093]="*Assosi kho citto gahapati: “acelo kira kassapo macchikāsaṇḍaṃ anuppatto amhākaṃ purāṇagihisahāyo”ti.**Citta the householder heard that he had arrived.*";
P_HTM[7094]="*Atha kho citto gahapati yena acelo kassapo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā acelena kassapena saddhiṃ sammodi.**So he went up to him, and they exchanged greetings.*";
P_HTM[7095]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho citto gahapati acelaṃ kassapaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to the naked ascetic Kassapa,*";
P_HTM[7096]="*“kīvaciraṃ pabbajitassa, bhante kassapā”ti?**“Sir, Kassapa, how long has it been since you went forth?”*";
P_HTM[7097]="*“Tiṃsamattāni kho me, gahapati, vassāni pabbajitassā”ti.**“It’s been thirty years, householder.”*";
P_HTM[7098]="*“Imehi pana te, bhante, tiṃsamattehi vassehi atthi koci uttari manussadhammā alamariyañāṇadassanaviseso adhigato phāsuvihāro”ti?**“But sir, in these thirty years have you achieved any superhuman distinction in knowledge and vision worthy of the noble ones, a meditation at ease?”*";
P_HTM[7099]="*“Imehi kho me, gahapati, tiṃsamattehi vassehi pabbajitassa natthi koci uttari manussadhammā alamariyañāṇadassanaviseso adhigato phāsuvihāro, aññatra naggeyyā ca muṇḍeyyā ca pāvaḷanipphoṭanāya cā”ti.**“I have no such achievement, householder, only nakedness, baldness, and pokes in the buttocks.”*";
P_HTM[7100]="*Evaṃ vutte, citto gahapati acelaṃ kassapaṃ etadavoca:**Citta said to him,*";
P_HTM[7101]="*“acchariyaṃ vata, bho, abbhutaṃ vata, bho.**“It’s incredible, it’s amazing,*";
P_HTM[7102]="*Dhammassa svākkhātatā yatra hi nāma tiṃsamattehi vassehi na koci uttari manussadhammā alamariyañāṇadassanaviseso adhigato abhavissa phāsuvihāro, aññatra naggeyyā ca muṇḍeyyā ca pāvaḷanipphoṭanāya cā”ti.**how well explained the teaching is. For in thirty years you have achieved no superhuman distinction in knowledge and vision worthy of the noble ones, no meditation at ease, only nakedness, baldness, and pokes in the buttocks.”*";
P_HTM[7103]="*“Tuyhaṃ pana, gahapati, kīvaciraṃ upāsakattaṃ upagatassā”ti?**“But householder, how long have you been a lay follower?”*";
P_HTM[7104]="*“Mayhampi kho pana, bhante, tiṃsamattāni vassāni upāsakattaṃ upagatassā”ti.**“It’s been thirty years, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7105]="*“Imehi pana te, gahapati, tiṃsamattehi vassehi atthi koci uttari manussadhammā alamariyañāṇadassanaviseso adhigato phāsuvihāro”ti?**“But householder, in these thirty years have you achieved any superhuman distinction in knowledge and vision worthy of the noble ones, a meditation at ease?”*";
P_HTM[7106]="*“Gihinopi siyā, bhante.**“How, sir, could I not?*";
P_HTM[7107]="*Ahañhi, bhante, yāvadeva ākaṅkhāmi, vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**For whenever I want, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, I enter and remain in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[7108]="*Ahañhi, bhante, yāvadeva ākaṅkhāmi, vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā … dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**And whenever I want, as the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled … I enter and remain in the second absorption.*";
P_HTM[7109]="*Ahañhi, bhante, yāvadeva ākaṅkhāmi, pītiyā ca virāgā … pe … tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**And whenever I want, with the fading away of rapture … I enter and remain in the third absorption.*";
P_HTM[7110]="*Ahañhi, bhante, yāvadeva ākaṅkhāmi, sukhassa ca pahānā … pe … catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharāmi.**And whenever I want, giving up pleasure and pain … I enter and remain in the fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[7111]="*Sace kho panāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato paṭhamataraṃ kālaṃ kareyyaṃ, anacchariyaṃ kho panetaṃ yaṃ maṃ bhagavā evaṃ byākareyya:**If I pass away before the Buddha, it wouldn’t be surprising if the Buddha declares of me:*";
P_HTM[7112]="*‘natthi taṃ saṃyojanaṃ yena saṃyojanena saṃyutto citto gahapati puna imaṃ lokaṃ āgaccheyyā’”ti.**‘The householder Citta is bound by no fetter that might return him to this world.’”*";
P_HTM[7113]="*Evaṃ vutte, acelo kassapo cittaṃ gahapatiṃ etadavoca:**When this was said, Kassapa said to Citta,*";
P_HTM[7114]="*“acchariyaṃ vata bho, abbhutaṃ vata bho.**“It’s incredible, it’s amazing,*";
P_HTM[7115]="*Dhammassa svākkhātatā, yatra hi nāma gihī odātavasano evarūpaṃ uttari manussadhammā alamariyañāṇadassanavisesaṃ adhigamissati phāsuvihāraṃ.**how well explained the teaching is. For a white-clothed layperson can achieve such a superhuman distinction in knowledge and vision worthy of the noble ones, a meditation at ease.*";
P_HTM[7116]="*Labheyyāhaṃ, gahapati, imasmiṃ dhammavinaye pabbajjaṃ, labheyyaṃ upasampadan”ti.**Sir, may I receive the going forth, the ordination in the Buddha’s presence?”*";
P_HTM[7117]="*Atha kho citto gahapati acelaṃ kassapaṃ ādāya yena therā bhikkhū tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā there bhikkhū etadavoca:**Then Citta the householder took the naked ascetic Kassapa to see the senior mendicants, and said to them:*";
P_HTM[7118]="*“ayaṃ, bhante, acelo kassapo amhākaṃ purāṇagihisahāyo.**“Sirs, this is the naked ascetic Kassapa, who in lay life was an old friend of mine.*";
P_HTM[7119]="*Imaṃ therā pabbājentu upasampādentu.**May the senior monks give him the going forth, the ordination.*";
P_HTM[7120]="*Ahamassa ussukkaṃ karissāmi cīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhārānan”ti.**I’ll make sure that he’s provided with robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick.”*";
P_HTM[7121]="*Alattha kho acelo kassapo imasmiṃ dhammavinaye pabbajjaṃ, alattha upasampadaṃ.**And the naked ascetic Kassapa received the going forth, the ordination in this teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[7122]="*Acirūpasampanno ca panāyasmā kassapo eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto nacirasseva—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihāsi.**Not long after his ordination, Venerable Kassapa, living alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute, soon realized the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life. He lived having achieved with his own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[7123]="*“Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti abbhaññāsi.**He understood: “Rebirth is ended; the spiritual journey has been completed; what had to be done has been done; there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[7124]="*Aññataro ca panāyasmā kassapo arahataṃ ahosīti.**And Venerable Kassapa became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[7125]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7126]="*10. Gilānadassanasuttaṃ**Seeing the Sick*";
P_HTM[7127]="*Tena kho pana samayena citto gahapati ābādhiko hoti dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**Now at that time the householder Citta was sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[7128]="*Atha kho sambahulā ārāmadevatā vanadevatā rukkhadevatā osadhitiṇavanappatīsu adhivatthā devatā saṅgamma samāgamma cittaṃ gahapatiṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then several deities of the parks, forests, trees, and those who haunt the herbs, grass, and big trees came together and said to Citta,*";
P_HTM[7129]="*“paṇidhehi, gahapati, anāgatamaddhānaṃ rājā assaṃ cakkavattī”ti.**“Householder, make a wish to become a wheel-turning monarch in the future!”*";
P_HTM[7130]="*Evaṃ vutte, citto gahapati tā ārāmadevatā vanadevatā rukkhadevatā osadhitiṇavanappatīsu adhivatthā devatā etadavoca:**When they said this, Citta said to them,*";
P_HTM[7131]="*“tampi aniccaṃ, tampi addhuvaṃ, tampi pahāya gamanīyan”ti.**“That too is impermanent! That too will pass! That too will be left behind!”*";
P_HTM[7132]="*Evaṃ vutte, cittassa gahapatino mittāmaccā ñātisālohitā cittaṃ gahapatiṃ etadavocuṃ:**When he said this, his friends and colleagues, relatives and family members said,*";
P_HTM[7133]="*“satiṃ, ayyaputta, upaṭṭhapehi, mā vippalapī”ti.**“Be mindful, lord! Don’t babble.”*";
P_HTM[7134]="*“Kiṃ tāhaṃ vadāmi yaṃ maṃ tumhe evaṃ vadetha:**“What have I said that makes you say that?”*";
P_HTM[7135]="*‘satiṃ, ayyaputta, upaṭṭhapehi, mā vippalapī’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7136]="*“Evaṃ kho tvaṃ, ayyaputta, vadesi:**“It’s because you said:*";
P_HTM[7137]="*‘tampi aniccaṃ, tampi addhuvaṃ, tampi pahāya gamanīyan’”ti.**‘That too is impermanent! That too will pass! That too will be left behind!’”*";
P_HTM[7138]="*“Tathā hi pana maṃ ārāmadevatā vanadevatā rukkhadevatā osadhitiṇavanappatīsu adhivatthā devatā evamāhaṃsu:**“Oh, well, that’s because the deities of the parks, forests, trees, and those who haunt the herbs, grass, and big trees said to me:*";
P_HTM[7139]="*‘paṇidhehi, gahapati, anāgatamaddhānaṃ rājā assaṃ cakkavattī’ti.**‘Householder, make a wish to become a wheel-turning monarch in the future!’*";
P_HTM[7140]="*Tāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:**So I said to them:*";
P_HTM[7141]="*‘tampi aniccaṃ … pe … tampi pahāya gamanīyan’”ti.**‘That too is impermanent! That too will pass! That too will be left behind!’”*";
P_HTM[7142]="*“Kiṃ pana tā, ayyaputta, ārāmadevatā vanadevatā rukkhadevatā osadhitiṇavanappatīsu adhivatthā devatā atthavasaṃ sampassamānā evamāhaṃsu:**“But what reason do they see for saying that to you?”*";
P_HTM[7143]="*‘paṇidhehi, gahapati, anāgatamaddhānaṃ rājā assaṃ cakkavattī’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7144]="*“Tāsaṃ kho ārāmadevatānaṃ vanadevatānaṃ rukkhadevatānaṃ osadhitiṇavanappatīsu adhivatthānaṃ devatānaṃ evaṃ hoti:**“They think:*";
P_HTM[7145]="*‘ayaṃ kho citto gahapati, sīlavā kalyāṇadhammo.**‘This householder Citta is ethical, of good character.*";
P_HTM[7146]="*Sace paṇidahissati—**If he makes a wish to*";
P_HTM[7147]="*anāgatamaddhānaṃ rājā assaṃ cakkavattī’ti, ‘tassa kho ayaṃ ijjhissati, sīlavato cetopaṇidhi visuddhattā dhammiko dhammikaṃ phalaṃ anupassatī’ti.**become a wheel-turning monarch in the future, his heart’s wish will succeed because of the purity of his ethics. And then as a proper, principled king he will provide proper spirit-offerings.’*";
P_HTM[7148]="*Imaṃ kho tā ārāmadevatā vanadevatā rukkhadevatā osadhitiṇavanappatīsu adhivatthā devatā atthavasaṃ sampassamānā evamāhaṃsu:**That’s the reason they see for saying to me:*";
P_HTM[7149]="*‘paṇidhehi, gahapati, anāgatamaddhānaṃ rājā assaṃ cakkavattī’ti.**‘Householder, make a wish to become a wheel-turning monarch in the future!’*";
P_HTM[7150]="*Tāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:**So I said to them:*";
P_HTM[7151]="*‘tampi aniccaṃ, tampi addhuvaṃ, tampi pahāya gamanīyan’”ti.**‘That too is impermanent! That too will pass! That too will be left behind!’”*";
P_HTM[7152]="*“Tena hi, ayyaputta, amhepi ovadāhī”ti.**“Then, lord, advise us!”*";
P_HTM[7153]="*“Tasmā hi vo evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ—**“So you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[7154]="*buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgatā bhavissāma:**We will have experiential confidence in the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[7155]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[7156]="*Dhamme aveccappasādena samannāgatā bhavissāma:**We will have experiential confidence in the teaching:*";
P_HTM[7157]="*‘svākkhāto bhagavatā dhammo sandiṭṭhiko akāliko ehipassiko opaneyyiko paccattaṃ veditabbo viññūhī’ti.**‘The teaching is well explained by the Buddha—visible in this very life, immediately effective, inviting inspection, relevant, so that sensible people can know it for themselves.’*";
P_HTM[7158]="*Saṅghe aveccappasādena samannāgatā bhavissāma:**We will have experiential confidence in the Saṅgha:*";
P_HTM[7159]="*‘suppaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho, ujuppaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho, ñāyappaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho, sāmīcippaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho, yadidaṃ cattāri purisayugāni aṭṭha purisapuggalā esa bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho āhuneyyo pāhuneyyo dakkhiṇeyyo añjalikaraṇīyo anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassā’ti.**‘The Saṅgha of the Buddha’s disciples is practicing the way that’s good, straightforward, methodical, and proper. It consists of the four pairs, the eight individuals. This is the Saṅgha of the Buddha’s disciples that is worthy of offerings dedicated to the gods, worthy of hospitality, worthy of a religious donation, worthy of greeting with joined palms, and is the supreme field of merit for the world.’*";
P_HTM[7160]="*Yaṃ kho pana kiñci kule deyyadhammaṃ sabbaṃ taṃ appaṭivibhattaṃ bhavissati sīlavantehi kalyāṇadhammehīti evañhi vo sikkhitabban”ti.**And we will share without reservation all the gifts available to give in our family with those who are ethical and of good character.”*";
P_HTM[7161]="*Atha kho citto gahapati mittāmacce ñātisālohite buddhe ca dhamme ca saṅghe ca cāge ca samādapetvā kālamakāsīti.**Then, after Citta had encouraged his friends and colleagues, relatives and family members in the Buddha, the teaching, the Saṅgha, and generosity, he passed away.*";
P_HTM[7162]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7163]="*Cittavaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[7164]="*Saṃyojanaṃ dve isidattā,* **";
P_HTM[7165]="*Mahako kāmabhūpi ca;* **";
P_HTM[7166]="*Godatto ca nigaṇṭho ca,* **";
P_HTM[7167]="*Acelena gilānadassananti.* **";
P_HTM[7168]="*Cittasaṃyuttaṃ samattaṃ.**The Linked Discourses on Citta the Householder are complete.*";
P_HTM[7169]="*42. Gāmaṇisaṃyuttaṃ* **";
P_HTM[7170]="*1. Aniccavaggo**Chiefs*";
P_HTM[7171]="*1. Caṇḍasuttaṃ**Vicious*";
P_HTM[7172]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[7173]="*Atha kho caṇḍo gāmaṇi yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho caṇḍo gāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then the chief named Fury went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[7174]="*“ko nu kho, bhante, hetu, ko paccayo yena midhekacco caṇḍo caṇḍotveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**“What is the cause, sir, what is the reason why some people are regarded as furious,*";
P_HTM[7175]="*Ko pana, bhante, hetu, ko paccayo yena midhekacco sorato soratotveva saṅkhaṃ gacchatī”ti?**while others are regarded as sweet-natured?”*";
P_HTM[7176]="*“Idha, gāmaṇi, ekaccassa rāgo appahīno hoti.**“Take someone who hasn’t given up greed.*";
P_HTM[7177]="*Rāgassa appahīnattā pare kopenti, parehi kopiyamāno kopaṃ pātukaroti.**So they get annoyed by others, and they show it.*";
P_HTM[7178]="*So caṇḍotveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**They’re regarded as furious.*";
P_HTM[7179]="*Doso appahīno hoti.**They haven’t given up hate.*";
P_HTM[7180]="*Dosassa appahīnattā pare kopenti, parehi kopiyamāno kopaṃ pātukaroti.**So they get annoyed by others, and they show it.*";
P_HTM[7181]="*So caṇḍotveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**They’re regarded as furious.*";
P_HTM[7182]="*Moho appahīno hoti.**They haven’t given up delusion.*";
P_HTM[7183]="*Mohassa appahīnattā pare kopenti, parehi kopiyamāno kopaṃ pātukaroti.**So they get annoyed by others, and they show it.*";
P_HTM[7184]="*So caṇḍotveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**They’re regarded as furious.*";
P_HTM[7185]="*Ayaṃ kho, gāmaṇi, hetu, ayaṃ paccayo yena midhekacco caṇḍo caṇḍotveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**This is the cause, this is the reason why some people are regarded as furious.*";
P_HTM[7186]="*Idha pana, gāmaṇi, ekaccassa rāgo pahīno hoti.**But take someone who has given up greed.*";
P_HTM[7187]="*Rāgassa pahīnattā pare na kopenti, parehi kopiyamāno kopaṃ na pātukaroti.**So they don’t get annoyed by others, and don’t show it.*";
P_HTM[7188]="*So soratotveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**They’re regarded as sweet-natured.*";
P_HTM[7189]="*Doso pahīno hoti.**They’ve given up hate.*";
P_HTM[7190]="*Dosassa pahīnattā pare na kopenti, parehi kopiyamāno kopaṃ na pātukaroti.**So they don’t get annoyed by others, and don’t show it.*";
P_HTM[7191]="*So soratotveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**They’re regarded as sweet-natured.*";
P_HTM[7192]="*Moho pahīno hoti.**They’ve given up delusion.*";
P_HTM[7193]="*Mohassa pahīnattā pare na kopenti, parehi kopiyamāno kopaṃ na pātukaroti.**So they don’t get annoyed by others, and don’t show it.*";
P_HTM[7194]="*So soratotveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**They’re regarded as sweet-natured.*";
P_HTM[7195]="*Ayaṃ kho, gāmaṇi, hetu ayaṃ paccayo yena midhekacco sorato soratotveva saṅkhaṃ gacchatī”ti.**This is the cause, this is the reason why some people are regarded as sweet-natured.”*";
P_HTM[7196]="*Evaṃ vutte, caṇḍo gāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, the chief named Fury said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[7197]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bhante, abhikkantaṃ, bhante.**“Excellent, sir! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[7198]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhagavatā anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, the Buddha has made the teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[7199]="*Esāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṅghañca.**I go for refuge to the Buddha, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[7200]="*Upāsakaṃ maṃ bhagavā dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may the Buddha remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[7201]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7202]="*2. Tālapuṭasuttaṃ**With Tāḷapuṭa*";
P_HTM[7203]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[7204]="*Atha kho tālapuṭo naṭagāmaṇi yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho tālapuṭo naṭagāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Tāḷapuṭa the dancing master came up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[7205]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante, pubbakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ naṭānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ:**“Sir, I have heard that the dancers of the past who were teachers of teachers said:*";
P_HTM[7206]="*‘yo so naṭo raṅgamajjhe samajjamajjhe saccālikena janaṃ hāseti rameti, so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā pahāsānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjatī’ti.**‘Suppose a dancer entertains and amuses people on a stage or at a festival with truth and lies. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in the company of laughing gods.’*";
P_HTM[7207]="*Idha bhagavā kimāhā”ti?**What does the Buddha say about this?”*";
P_HTM[7208]="*“Alaṃ, gāmaṇi, tiṭṭhatetaṃ. Mā maṃ etaṃ pucchī”ti.**“Enough, chief, let it be. Don’t ask me that.”*";
P_HTM[7209]="*Dutiyampi kho tālapuṭo naṭagāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**For a second time …*";
P_HTM[7210]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante, pubbakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ naṭānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7211]="*‘yo so naṭo raṅgamajjhe samajjamajjhe saccālikena janaṃ hāseti rameti, so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā pahāsānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7212]="*Idha bhagavā kimāhā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7213]="*“Alaṃ, gāmaṇi, tiṭṭhatetaṃ. Mā maṃ etaṃ pucchī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7214]="*Tatiyampi kho tālapuṭo naṭagāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**And for a third time Tāḷapuṭa said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[7215]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante, pubbakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ naṭānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ:**“Sir, I have heard that the dancers of the past who were teachers of teachers said:*";
P_HTM[7216]="*‘yo so naṭo raṅgamajjhe samajjamajjhe saccālikena janaṃ hāseti rameti, so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā pahāsānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjatī’ti.**‘Suppose a dancer entertains and amuses people on a stage or at a festival with truth and lies. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in the company of laughing gods.’*";
P_HTM[7217]="*Idha bhagavā kimāhā”ti?**What does the Buddha say about this?”*";
P_HTM[7218]="*“Addhā kho tyāhaṃ, gāmaṇi, na labhāmi:**“Clearly, chief, I’m not getting through to you when I say:*";
P_HTM[7219]="*‘alaṃ, gāmaṇi, tiṭṭhatetaṃ,**‘Enough, chief, let it be.*";
P_HTM[7220]="*mā maṃ etaṃ pucchī’ti.**Don’t ask me that.’*";
P_HTM[7221]="*Api ca tyāhaṃ byākarissāmi.**Nevertheless, I will answer you.*";
P_HTM[7222]="*Pubbe kho, gāmaṇi, sattā avītarāgā rāgabandhanabaddhā.**When sentient beings are still not free of greed, and are still bound by greed,*";
P_HTM[7223]="*Tesaṃ naṭo raṅgamajjhe samajjamajjhe ye dhammā rajanīyā te upasaṃharati bhiyyoso mattāya.**a dancer in a stage or festival presents them with even more arousing things.*";
P_HTM[7224]="*Pubbe kho, gāmaṇi, sattā avītadosā dosabandhanabaddhā.**When sentient beings are still not free of hate, and are still bound by hate,*";
P_HTM[7225]="*Tesaṃ naṭo raṅgamajjhe samajjamajjhe ye dhammā dosanīyā te upasaṃharati bhiyyoso mattāya.**a dancer in a stage or festival presents them with even more hateful things.*";
P_HTM[7226]="*Pubbe kho, gāmaṇi, sattā avītamohā mohabandhanabaddhā.**When sentient beings are still not free of delusion, and are still bound by delusion,*";
P_HTM[7227]="*Tesaṃ naṭo raṅgamajjhe samajjamajjhe ye dhammā mohanīyā te upasaṃharati bhiyyoso mattāya.**a dancer in a stage or festival presents them with even more delusory things.*";
P_HTM[7228]="*So attanā matto pamatto pare madetvā pamādetvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā pahāso nāma nirayo tattha upapajjati.**And so, being heedless and negligent themselves, they’ve encouraged others to be heedless and negligent. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in the hell called ‘Laughter’.*";
P_HTM[7229]="*Sace kho panassa evaṃdiṭṭhi hoti:**But if you have such a view:*";
P_HTM[7230]="*‘yo so naṭo raṅgamajjhe samajjamajjhe saccālikena janaṃ hāseti rameti, so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā pahāsānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjatī’ti, sāssa hoti micchādiṭṭhi.**‘Suppose a dancer entertains and amuses people on a stage or at a festival with truth and lies. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in the company of laughing gods.’ This is your wrong view.*";
P_HTM[7231]="*Micchādiṭṭhikassa kho panāhaṃ, gāmaṇi, purisapuggalassa dvinnaṃ gatīnaṃ aññataraṃ gatiṃ vadāmi—**An individual with wrong view is reborn in one of two places, I say:*";
P_HTM[7232]="*nirayaṃ vā tiracchānayoniṃ vā”ti.**hell or the animal realm.”*";
P_HTM[7233]="*Evaṃ vutte, tālapuṭo naṭagāmaṇi parodi assūni pavattesi.**When he said this, Tāḷapuṭa cried and burst out in tears.*";
P_HTM[7234]="*“Etaṃ kho tyāhaṃ, gāmaṇi, nālatthaṃ:**“This is what I didn’t get through to you when I said:*";
P_HTM[7235]="*‘alaṃ, gāmaṇi, tiṭṭhatetaṃ; mā maṃ etaṃ pucchī’”ti.**‘Enough, chief, let it be. Don’t ask me that.’”*";
P_HTM[7236]="*“Nāhaṃ, bhante, etaṃ rodāmi yaṃ maṃ bhagavā evamāha;**“Sir, I’m not crying because of what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[7237]="*api cāhaṃ, bhante, pubbakehi ācariyapācariyehi naṭehi dīgharattaṃ nikato vañcito paluddho:**But sir, for a long time I’ve been cheated, tricked, and deceived by the dancers of the past who were teachers of teachers, who said:*";
P_HTM[7238]="*‘yo so naṭo raṅgamajjhe samajjamajjhe saccālikena janaṃ hāseti rameti so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā pahāsānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjatī’”ti.**‘Suppose a dancer entertains and amuses people on a stage or at a festival with truth and lies. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in the company of laughing gods.’*";
P_HTM[7239]="*“Abhikkantaṃ, bhante, abhikkantaṃ, bhante.**Excellent, sir! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[7240]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhagavatā anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, the Buddha has made the teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[7241]="*Esāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṅghañca.**I go for refuge to the Buddha, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[7242]="*Labheyyāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato santike pabbajjaṃ, labheyyaṃ upasampadan”ti.**Sir, may I receive the going forth, the ordination in the Buddha’s presence?”*";
P_HTM[7243]="*Alattha kho tālapuṭo naṭagāmaṇi bhagavato santike pabbajjaṃ, alattha upasampadaṃ.**And the dancing master Tāḷapuṭa received the going forth, the ordination in the Buddha’s presence.*";
P_HTM[7244]="*Acirūpasampanno ca panāyasmā tālapuṭo … pe …**Not long after his ordination, Venerable Tāḷapuṭa*";
P_HTM[7245]="*arahataṃ ahosīti.**became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[7246]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7247]="*3. Yodhājīvasuttaṃ**A Warrior*";
P_HTM[7248]="*Atha kho yodhājīvo gāmaṇi yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho yodhājīvo gāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Dustin the warrior chief went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[7249]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante, pubbakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ yodhājīvānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ:**“Sir, I have heard that the warriors of the past who were teachers of teachers said:*";
P_HTM[7250]="*‘yo so yodhājīvo saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati, tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare hananti pariyāpādenti, so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā parajitānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjatī’ti.**‘Suppose a warrior, while striving and struggling in battle, is killed and finished off by his foes. When his body breaks up, after death, he’s reborn in the company of the gods of the fallen.’*";
P_HTM[7251]="*Idha bhagavā kimāhā”ti?**What does the Buddha say about this?”*";
P_HTM[7252]="*“Alaṃ, gāmaṇi, tiṭṭhatetaṃ; mā maṃ etaṃ pucchī”ti.**“Enough, chief, let it be. Don’t ask me that.”*";
P_HTM[7253]="*Dutiyampi kho … pe …**For a second time …*";
P_HTM[7254]="*tatiyampi kho yodhājīvo gāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**And for a third time the warrior chief said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[7255]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante, pubbakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ yodhājīvānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ:**“Sir, I have heard that the warriors of the past who were teachers of teachers said:*";
P_HTM[7256]="*‘yo so yodhājīvo saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati, tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare hananti pariyāpādenti, so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā parajitānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjatī’ti.**‘Suppose a warrior, while striving and struggling in battle, is killed and finished off by his foes. When his body breaks up, after death, he’s reborn in the company of the gods of the fallen.’*";
P_HTM[7257]="*Idha bhagavā kimāhā”ti?**What does the Buddha say about this?”*";
P_HTM[7258]="*“Addhā kho tyāhaṃ, gāmaṇi, na labhāmi:**“Clearly, chief, I’m not getting through to you when I say:*";
P_HTM[7259]="*‘alaṃ, gāmaṇi, tiṭṭhatetaṃ; mā maṃ etaṃ pucchī’ti.**‘Enough, chief, let it be. Don’t ask me that.’*";
P_HTM[7260]="*Api ca tyāhaṃ byākarissāmi.**Nevertheless, I will answer you.*";
P_HTM[7261]="*Yo so, gāmaṇi, yodhājīvo saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati, tassa taṃ cittaṃ pubbe gahitaṃ dukkaṭaṃ duppaṇihitaṃ:**When a warrior strives and struggles in battle, their mind is already low, degraded, and misdirected as they think:*";
P_HTM[7262]="*‘ime sattā haññantu vā bajjhantu vā ucchijjantu vā vinassantu vā mā vā ahesuṃ iti vā’ti.**‘May these sentient beings be killed, slaughtered, slain, destroyed, or annihilated!’*";
P_HTM[7263]="*Tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare hananti pariyāpādenti;**His foes kill him and finish him off, and*";
P_HTM[7264]="*so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā parajito nāma nirayo tattha upapajjatīti.**when his body breaks up, after death, he’s reborn in the hell called ‘The Fallen’.*";
P_HTM[7265]="*Sace kho panassa evaṃ diṭṭhi hoti:**But if you have such a view:*";
P_HTM[7266]="*‘yo so yodhājīvo saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare hananti pariyāpādenti, so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā parajitānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjatī’ti, sāssa hoti micchādiṭṭhi.**‘Suppose a warrior, while striving and struggling in battle, is killed and finished off by his foes. When his body breaks up, after death, he’s reborn in the company of the gods of the fallen.’ This is your wrong view.*";
P_HTM[7267]="*Micchādiṭṭhikassa kho panāhaṃ, gāmaṇi, purisapuggalassa dvinnaṃ gatīnaṃ aññataraṃ gatiṃ vadāmi—**An individual with wrong view is reborn in one of two places, I say:*";
P_HTM[7268]="*nirayaṃ vā tiracchānayoniṃ vā”ti.**hell or the animal realm.”*";
P_HTM[7269]="*Evaṃ vutte, yodhājīvo gāmaṇi parodi, assūni pavattesi.**When he said this, Dustin the warrior chief cried and burst out in tears.*";
P_HTM[7270]="*“Etaṃ kho tyāhaṃ, gāmaṇi, nālatthaṃ:**“This is what I didn’t get through to you when I said:*";
P_HTM[7271]="*‘alaṃ, gāmaṇi, tiṭṭhatetaṃ; mā maṃ etaṃ pucchī’”ti.**‘Enough, chief, let it be. Don’t ask me that.’”*";
P_HTM[7272]="*“Nāhaṃ, bhante, etaṃ rodāmi yaṃ maṃ bhagavā evamāha;**“Sir, I’m not crying because of what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[7273]="*api cāhaṃ, bhante, pubbakehi ācariyapācariyehi yodhājīvehi dīgharattaṃ nikato vañcito paluddho:**But sir, for a long time I’ve been cheated, tricked, and deceived by the warriors of the past who were teachers of teachers, who said:*";
P_HTM[7274]="*‘yo so yodhājīvo saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati, tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare hananti pariyāpādenti, so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā parajitānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjatī’”ti.**‘Suppose a warrior, while striving and struggling in battle, is killed and finished off by his foes. When his body breaks up, after death, he’s reborn in the company of the gods of the fallen.’*";
P_HTM[7275]="*“Abhikkantaṃ, bhante … pe …**Excellent, sir! Excellent! …*";
P_HTM[7276]="*ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may the Buddha remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[7277]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7278]="*4. Hatthārohasuttaṃ**An Elephant Warrior*";
P_HTM[7279]="*Atha kho hatthāroho gāmaṇi yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā … pe …**Then an elephant warrior chief went up to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7280]="*ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatanti.**“From this day forth, may the Buddha remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[7281]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7282]="*5. Assārohasuttaṃ**A Cavalryman*";
P_HTM[7283]="*Atha kho assāroho gāmaṇi yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho assāroho gāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a cavalry chief went up to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7284]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante, pubbakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ assārohānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7285]="*‘yo so assāroho saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati, tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare hananti pariyāpādenti, so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā parajitānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7286]="*Idha bhagavā kimāhā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7287]="*“Alaṃ, gāmaṇi, tiṭṭhatetaṃ; mā maṃ etaṃ pucchī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7288]="*Dutiyampi kho … pe …* **";
P_HTM[7289]="*tatiyampi kho assāroho gāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[7290]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante, pubbakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ assārohānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7291]="*‘yo so assāroho saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati, tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare hananti pariyāpādenti, so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā parajitānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7292]="*Idha bhagavā kimāhā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[7293]="*“Addhā kho tyāhaṃ, gāmaṇi, na labhāmi:* **";
P_HTM[7294]="*‘alaṃ, gāmaṇi, tiṭṭhatetaṃ; mā maṃ etaṃ pucchī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7295]="*Api ca kho tyāhaṃ byākarissāmi.* **";
P_HTM[7296]="*Yo so, gāmaṇi, assāroho saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati tassa taṃ cittaṃ pubbe gahitaṃ dukkaṭaṃ duppaṇihitaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7297]="*‘ime sattā haññantu vā bajjhantu vā ucchijjantu vā vinassantu vā mā ahesuṃ iti vā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7298]="*Tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare hananti pariyāpādenti, so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā parajito nāma nirayo tattha upapajjati.* **";
P_HTM[7299]="*Sace kho panassa evaṃ diṭṭhi hoti:* **";
P_HTM[7300]="*‘yo so assāroho saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati, tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare hananti pariyāpādenti, so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā parajitānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjatī’ti, sāssa hoti micchādiṭṭhi.* **";
P_HTM[7301]="*Micchādiṭṭhikassa kho panāhaṃ, gāmaṇi, purisapuggalassa dvinnaṃ gatīnaṃ aññataraṃ gatiṃ vadāmi—* **";
P_HTM[7302]="*nirayaṃ vā tiracchānayoniṃ vā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7303]="*Evaṃ vutte, assāroho gāmaṇi parodi, assūni pavattesi.* **";
P_HTM[7304]="*“Etaṃ kho tyāhaṃ, gāmaṇi, nālatthaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7305]="*‘alaṃ, gāmaṇi, tiṭṭhatetaṃ; mā maṃ etaṃ pucchī’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7306]="*“Nāhaṃ, bhante, etaṃ rodāmi yaṃ maṃ bhagavā evamāha.* **";
P_HTM[7307]="*Api cāhaṃ, bhante, pubbakehi ācariyapācariyehi assārohehi dīgharattaṃ nikato vañcito paluddho:* **";
P_HTM[7308]="*‘yo so assāroho saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati, tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare hananti pariyāpādenti, so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā parajitānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjatī’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7309]="*“Abhikkantaṃ, bhante … pe …* **";
P_HTM[7310]="*ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**“From this day forth, may the Buddha remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[7311]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7312]="*6. Asibandhakaputtasuttaṃ**With Asibandhaka’s Son*";
P_HTM[7313]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā nāḷandāyaṃ viharati pāvārikambavane.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Nālandā in Pāvārika’s mango grove.*";
P_HTM[7314]="*Atha kho asibandhakaputto gāmaṇi yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho asibandhakaputto gāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Asibandhaka’s son the chief went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[7315]="*“brāhmaṇā, bhante, pacchā bhūmakā kāmaṇḍalukā sevālamālikā udakorohakā aggiparicārakā.**“Sir, there are western brahmins draped with moss who carry pitchers, immerse themselves in water, and serve the sacred flame.*";
P_HTM[7316]="*Te mataṃ kālaṅkataṃ uyyāpenti nāma saññāpenti nāma saggaṃ nāma okkāmenti.**When someone has passed away, they truly lift them up, raise them up, and guide them along to heaven.*";
P_HTM[7317]="*Bhagavā pana, bhante, arahaṃ sammāsambuddho pahoti tathā kātuṃ yathā sabbo loko kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjeyyā”ti?**But what about the Blessed One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha: is he able to ensure that the whole world will be reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm when their body breaks up, after death?”*";
P_HTM[7318]="*“Tena hi, gāmaṇi, taññevettha paṭipucchissāmi. Yathā te khameyya tathā naṃ byākareyyāsīti.**“Well then, chief, I’ll ask you about this in return, and you can answer as you like.*";
P_HTM[7319]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi,**What do you think, chief?*";
P_HTM[7320]="*idhassa puriso pāṇātipātī adinnādāyī kāmesumicchācārī musāvādī pisuṇavāco pharusavāco samphappalāpī abhijjhālu byāpannacitto micchādiṭṭhiko.**Take a person who kills living creatures, steals, and commits sexual misconduct. They use speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical. And they’re covetous, malicious, and have wrong view.*";
P_HTM[7321]="*Tamenaṃ mahājanakāyo saṅgamma samāgamma āyāceyya thomeyya pañjaliko anuparisakkeyya:**And a large crowd comes together to offer up prayers and praise, circumambulating them with joined palms and saying:*";
P_HTM[7322]="*‘ayaṃ puriso kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjatū’ti.**‘When this person’s body breaks up, after death, may they be reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm!’*";
P_HTM[7323]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi,**What do you think, chief?*";
P_HTM[7324]="*api nu so puriso mahato janakāyassa āyācanahetu vā thomanahetu vā pañjalikā anuparisakkanahetu vā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjeyyā”ti?**Would that person be reborn in heaven because of their prayers?”*";
P_HTM[7325]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7326]="*“Seyyathāpi, gāmaṇi, puriso mahatiṃ puthusilaṃ gambhīre udakarahade pakkhipeyya.**“Chief, suppose a person were to throw a broad rock into a deep lake.*";
P_HTM[7327]="*Tamenaṃ mahā janakāyo saṅgamma samāgamma āyāceyya thomeyya pañjaliko anuparisakkeyya:**And a large crowd was to come together to offer up prayers and praise, circumambulating it with joined palms, and saying:*";
P_HTM[7328]="*‘ummujja, bho puthusile, uplava, bho puthusile, thalamuplava, bho puthusile’ti.**‘Rise, good rock! Float, good rock! Float to shore, good rock!’*";
P_HTM[7329]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi,**What do you think, chief?*";
P_HTM[7330]="*api nu sā puthusilā mahato janakāyassa āyācanahetu vā thomanahetu vā pañjalikā anuparisakkanahetu vā ummujjeyya vā uplaveyya vā thalaṃ vā uplaveyyā”ti?**Would that broad rock rise up or float because of their prayers?”*";
P_HTM[7331]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7332]="*“Evameva kho, gāmaṇi, yo so puriso pāṇātipātī adinnādāyī kāmesumicchācārī musāvādī pisuṇavāco pharusavāco samphappalāpī abhijjhālu byāpannacitto micchādiṭṭhiko.**“In the same way, take a person who kills living creatures, steals, and commits sexual misconduct. They use speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical. And they’re covetous, malicious, and have wrong view.*";
P_HTM[7333]="*Kiñcāpi taṃ mahā janakāyo saṅgamma samāgamma āyāceyya thomeyya pañjaliko anuparisakkeyya:**Even though a large crowd comes together to offer up prayers and praise …*";
P_HTM[7334]="*‘ayaṃ puriso kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjatū’ti, atha kho so puriso kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjeyya.**when their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[7335]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi,**What do you think, chief?*";
P_HTM[7336]="*idhassa puriso pāṇātipātā paṭivirato adinnādānā paṭivirato kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato musāvādā paṭivirato pisuṇāya vācāya paṭivirato pharusāya vācāya paṭivirato samphappalāpā paṭivirato anabhijjhālu abyāpannacitto sammādiṭṭhiko.**Take a person who doesn’t kill living creatures, steal, or commit sexual misconduct. They don’t use speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical. And they’re contented, kind-hearted, and have right view.*";
P_HTM[7337]="*Tamenaṃ mahā janakāyo saṅgamma samāgamma āyāceyya thomeyya pañjaliko anuparisakkeyya:**And a large crowd comes together to offer up prayers and praise, circumambulating them with joined palms and saying:*";
P_HTM[7338]="*‘ayaṃ puriso kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjatū’ti.**‘When this person’s body breaks up, after death, may they be reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell!’*";
P_HTM[7339]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi,**What do you think, chief?*";
P_HTM[7340]="*api nu so puriso mahato janakāyassa āyācanahetu vā thomanahetu vā pañjalikā anuparisakkanahetu vā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjeyyā”ti?**Would that person be reborn in hell because of their prayers?”*";
P_HTM[7341]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7342]="*“Seyyathāpi, gāmaṇi, puriso sappikumbhaṃ vā telakumbhaṃ vā gambhīre udakarahade ogāhetvā bhindeyya. Tatra yāssa sakkharā vā kaṭhalā vā sā adhogāmī assa; yañca khvassa tatra sappi vā telaṃ vā taṃ uddhaṃ gāmi assa.**“Chief, suppose a person were to sink a pot of ghee or oil into a deep lake and break it open. Its shards and chips would sink down, while the ghee or oil in it would rise up.*";
P_HTM[7343]="*Tamenaṃ mahā janakāyo saṅgamma samāgamma āyāceyya thomeyya pañjaliko anuparisakkeyya:**And a large crowd was to come together to offer up prayers and praise, circumambulating it with joined palms and saying:*";
P_HTM[7344]="*‘osīda, bho sappitela, saṃsīda, bho sappitela, adho gaccha, bho sappitelā’ti.**‘Sink, good ghee or oil! Descend, good ghee or oil! Go down, good ghee or oil!”*";
P_HTM[7345]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi,**What do you think, chief?*";
P_HTM[7346]="*api nu taṃ sappitelaṃ mahato janakāyassa āyācanahetu vā thomanahetu vā pañjalikā anuparisakkanahetu vā osīdeyya vā saṃsīdeyya vā adho vā gaccheyyā”ti?**Would that ghee or oil sink and descend because of their prayers?”*";
P_HTM[7347]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7348]="*“Evameva kho, gāmaṇi, yo so puriso pāṇātipātā paṭivirato, adinnādānā paṭivirato, kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato, musāvādā paṭivirato, pisuṇāya vācāya paṭivirato, pharusāya vācāya paṭivirato, samphappalāpā paṭivirato, anabhijjhālu, abyāpannacitto, sammādiṭṭhiko,**“In the same way, take a person who doesn’t kill living creatures, steal, or commit sexual misconduct. They don’t use speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical. And they’re contented, kind-hearted, and have right view.*";
P_HTM[7349]="*kiñcāpi taṃ mahā janakāyo saṅgamma samāgamma āyāceyya thomeyya pañjaliko anuparisakkeyya:**Even though a large crowd comes together to offer up prayers and praise …*";
P_HTM[7350]="*‘ayaṃ puriso kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjatū’ti, atha kho so puriso kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjeyyā”ti.**when their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.”*";
P_HTM[7351]="*Evaṃ vutte, asibandhakaputto gāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Asibandhaka’s son the chief said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[7352]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bhante … pe …**“Excellent, sir! …*";
P_HTM[7353]="*ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may the Buddha remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[7354]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7355]="*7. Khettūpamasuttaṃ**The Simile of the Field*";
P_HTM[7356]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā nāḷandāyaṃ viharati pāvārikambavane.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Nālandā in Pāvārika’s mango grove.*";
P_HTM[7357]="*Atha kho asibandhakaputto gāmaṇi yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho asibandhakaputto gāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Asibandhaka’s son the chief went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[7358]="*“nanu, bhante, bhagavā sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī viharatī”ti?**“Sir, doesn’t the Buddha live full of compassion for all living beings?”*";
P_HTM[7359]="*“Evaṃ, gāmaṇi, tathāgato sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī viharatī”ti.**“Yes, chief.”*";
P_HTM[7360]="*“Atha kiñcarahi, bhante, bhagavā ekaccānaṃ sakkaccaṃ dhammaṃ deseti, ekaccānaṃ no tathā sakkaccaṃ dhammaṃ desetī”ti?**“Well, sir, why exactly do you teach some people thoroughly and others less thoroughly?”*";
P_HTM[7361]="*“Tena hi, gāmaṇi, taññevettha paṭipucchissāmi. Yathā te khameyya tathā naṃ byākareyyāsi.**“Well then, chief, I’ll ask you about this in return, and you can answer as you like.*";
P_HTM[7362]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi, idhassu kassakassa gahapatino tīṇi khettāni—ekaṃ khettaṃ aggaṃ, ekaṃ khettaṃ majjhimaṃ, ekaṃ khettaṃ hīnaṃ jaṅgalaṃ ūsaraṃ pāpabhūmi.**What do you think? Suppose a farmer has three fields: one’s good, one’s average, and one’s poor—bad ground of sand and salt.*";
P_HTM[7363]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi, asu kassako gahapati bījāni patiṭṭhāpetukāmo kattha paṭhamaṃ patiṭṭhāpeyya, yaṃ vā aduṃ khettaṃ aggaṃ, yaṃ vā aduṃ khettaṃ majjhimaṃ, yaṃ vā aduṃ khettaṃ hīnaṃ jaṅgalaṃ ūsaraṃ pāpabhūmī”ti?**What do you think? When that farmer wants to plant seeds, where would he plant them first: the good field, the average one, or the poor one?”*";
P_HTM[7364]="*“Asu, bhante, kassako gahapati bījāni patiṭṭhāpetukāmo yaṃ aduṃ khettaṃ aggaṃ tattha patiṭṭhāpeyya. Tattha patiṭṭhāpetvā yaṃ aduṃ khettaṃ majjhimaṃ tattha patiṭṭhāpeyya. Tattha patiṭṭhāpetvā yaṃ aduṃ khettaṃ hīnaṃ jaṅgalaṃ ūsaraṃ pāpabhūmi tattha patiṭṭhāpeyyapi, nopi patiṭṭhāpeyya.**“Sir, he’d plant them first in the good field, then the average, then he may or may not plant seed in the poor field.*";
P_HTM[7365]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[7366]="*Antamaso gobhattampi bhavissatī”ti.**Because at least it can be fodder for the cattle.”*";
P_HTM[7367]="*“Seyyathāpi, gāmaṇi, yaṃ aduṃ khettaṃ aggaṃ; evameva mayhaṃ bhikkhubhikkhuniyo.**“To me, the monks and nuns are like the good field.*";
P_HTM[7368]="*Tesāhaṃ dhammaṃ desemi—ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ, sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāsemi.**I teach them the Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And I reveal a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[7369]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[7370]="*Ete hi, gāmaṇi, maṃdīpā maṃleṇā maṃtāṇā maṃsaraṇā viharanti.**Because they live with me as their island, protection, shelter, and refuge.*";
P_HTM[7371]="*Seyyathāpi, gāmaṇi, yaṃ aduṃ khettaṃ majjhimaṃ; evameva mayhaṃ upāsakaupāsikāyo.**To me, the laymen and laywomen are like the average field.*";
P_HTM[7372]="*Tesaṃ pāhaṃ dhammaṃ desemi—ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ, sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāsemi.**I also teach them the Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And I reveal a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[7373]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[7374]="*Ete hi, gāmaṇi, maṃdīpā maṃleṇā maṃtāṇā maṃsaraṇā viharanti.**Because they live with me as their island, protection, shelter, and refuge.*";
P_HTM[7375]="*Seyyathāpi, gāmaṇi, yaṃ aduṃ khettaṃ hīnaṃ jaṅgalaṃ ūsaraṃ pāpabhūmi; evameva mayhaṃ aññatitthiyā samaṇabrāhmaṇaparibbājakā.**To me, the ascetics, brahmins, and wanderers who follow other paths are like the poor field, the bad ground of sand and salt.*";
P_HTM[7376]="*Tesaṃ pāhaṃ dhammaṃ desemi—ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ, kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāsemi.**I also teach them the Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And I reveal a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[7377]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[7378]="*Appeva nāma ekaṃ padampi ājāneyyuṃ taṃ nesaṃ assa dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyāti.**Hopefully they might understand even a single sentence, which would be for their lasting welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[7379]="*Seyyathāpi, gāmaṇi, purisassa tayo udakamaṇikā—eko udakamaṇiko acchiddo ahārī aparihārī, eko udakamaṇiko acchiddo hārī parihārī, eko udakamaṇiko chiddo hārī parihārī.**Suppose a person had three water jars: one that’s uncracked and nonporous; one that’s uncracked but porous; and one that’s cracked and porous.*";
P_HTM[7380]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi, asu puriso udakaṃ nikkhipitukāmo kattha paṭhamaṃ nikkhipeyya, yo vā so udakamaṇiko acchiddo ahārī aparihārī, yo vā so udakamaṇiko acchiddo hārī parihārī, yo vā so udakamaṇiko chiddo hārī parihārī”ti?**What do you think? When that person wants to store water, where would they store it first: in the jar that’s uncracked and nonporous, the one that’s uncracked but porous, or the one that’s cracked and porous?”*";
P_HTM[7381]="*“Asu, bhante, puriso udakaṃ nikkhipitukāmo, yo so udakamaṇiko acchiddo ahārī aparihārī tattha nikkhipeyya, tattha nikkhipitvā, yo so udakamaṇiko acchiddo hārī parihārī tattha nikkhipeyya, tattha nikkhipitvā, yo so udakamaṇiko chiddo hārī parihārī tattha nikkhipeyyapi, nopi nikkhipeyya.**“Sir, they’d store water first in the jar that’s uncracked and nonporous, then the one that’s uncracked but porous, then they may or may not store water in the one that’s cracked and porous.*";
P_HTM[7382]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[7383]="*Antamaso bhaṇḍadhovanampi bhavissatī”ti.**Because at least it can be used for washing the dishes.”*";
P_HTM[7384]="*“Seyyathāpi, gāmaṇi, yo so udakamaṇiko acchiddo ahārī aparihārī; evameva mayhaṃ bhikkhubhikkhuniyo.**“To me, the monks and nuns are like the water jar that’s uncracked and nonporous.*";
P_HTM[7385]="*Tesāhaṃ dhammaṃ desemi—ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ, kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāsemi.**I teach them the Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And I reveal a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[7386]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[7387]="*Ete hi, gāmaṇi, maṃdīpā maṃleṇā maṃtāṇā maṃsaraṇā viharanti.**Because they live with me as their island, protection, shelter, and refuge.*";
P_HTM[7388]="*Seyyathāpi, gāmaṇi, yo so udakamaṇiko acchiddo hārī parihārī; evameva mayhaṃ upāsakaupāsikāyo.**To me, the laymen and laywomen are like the water jar that’s uncracked but porous.*";
P_HTM[7389]="*Tesāhaṃ dhammaṃ desemi—ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ, kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāsemi.**I teach them the Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And I reveal a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[7390]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[7391]="*Ete hi, gāmaṇi, maṃdīpā maṃleṇā maṃtāṇā maṃsaraṇā viharanti.**Because they live with me as their island, protection, shelter, and refuge.*";
P_HTM[7392]="*Seyyathāpi, gāmaṇi, yo so udakamaṇiko chiddo hārī parihārī; evameva mayhaṃ aññatitthiyā samaṇabrāhmaṇaparibbājakā.**To me, the ascetics, brahmins, and wanderers who follow other paths are like the water jar that’s cracked and porous.*";
P_HTM[7393]="*Tesāhaṃ dhammaṃ desemi—ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāsemi.**I also teach them the Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And I reveal a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[7394]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[7395]="*Appeva nāma ekaṃ padampi ājāneyyuṃ, taṃ nesaṃ assa dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā”ti.**Hopefully they might understand even a single sentence, which would be for their lasting welfare and happiness.”*";
P_HTM[7396]="*Evaṃ vutte, asibandhakaputto gāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Asibandhaka’s son the chief said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[7397]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bhante, abhikkantaṃ, bhante … pe …**“Excellent, sir! Excellent! …*";
P_HTM[7398]="*upāsakaṃ maṃ bhagavā dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may the Buddha remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[7399]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7400]="*8. Saṅkhadhamasuttaṃ**A Horn Blower*";
P_HTM[7401]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā nāḷandāyaṃ viharati pāvārikambavane.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Nālandā in Pāvārika’s mango grove.*";
P_HTM[7402]="*Atha kho asibandhakaputto gāmaṇi nigaṇṭhasāvako yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho asibandhakaputtaṃ gāmaṇiṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**Then Asibandhaka’s son the chief, who was a disciple of the Jains, went up to the Buddha, and sat down to one side. The Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[7403]="*“kathaṃ nu kho, gāmaṇi, nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto sāvakānaṃ dhammaṃ desetī”ti?**“Chief, how does Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta teach his disciples?”*";
P_HTM[7404]="*“Evaṃ kho, bhante, nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto sāvakānaṃ dhammaṃ deseti:**“Sir, this is how Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta teaches his disciples:*";
P_HTM[7405]="*‘yo koci pāṇaṃ atipāteti, sabbo so āpāyiko nerayiko, yo koci adinnaṃ ādiyati, sabbo so āpāyiko nerayiko, yo koci kāmesu micchā carati, sabbo so āpāyiko nerayiko, yo koci musā bhaṇati sabbo, so āpāyiko nerayiko.**‘Everyone who kills a living creature, steal, commits sexual misconduct, or lies goes to a place of loss, to hell.*";
P_HTM[7406]="*Yaṃbahulaṃ yaṃbahulaṃ viharati, tena tena nīyatī’ti.**You’re led on by what you usually live by.’*";
P_HTM[7407]="*Evaṃ kho, bhante, nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto sāvakānaṃ dhammaṃ desetī”ti.**This is how Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta teaches his disciples.”*";
P_HTM[7408]="*“‘Yaṃbahulaṃ yaṃbahulañca, gāmaṇi, viharati, tena tena nīyati’, evaṃ sante na koci āpāyiko nerayiko bhavissati, yathā nigaṇṭhassa nāṭaputtassa vacanaṃ.**“‘You’re led on by what you usually live by’: if this were true, then, according to what Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta says, no-one would go to a place of loss, to hell.*";
P_HTM[7409]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi,**What do you think, chief?*";
P_HTM[7410]="*yo so puriso pāṇātipātī rattiyā vā divasassa vā samayāsamayaṃ upādāya, katamo bahutaro samayo, yaṃ vā so pāṇamatipāteti, yaṃ vā so pāṇaṃ nātipātetī”ti?**Take a person who kills living creatures. If we compare periods of time during the day and night, which is more frequent: the occasions when they’re killing or when they’re not killing?”*";
P_HTM[7411]="*“Yo so, bhante, puriso pāṇātipātī rattiyā vā divasassa vā samayāsamayaṃ upādāya, appataro so samayo yaṃ so pāṇamatipāteti, atha kho sveva bahutaro samayo yaṃ so pāṇaṃ nātipātetī”ti.**“The occasions when they’re killing are less frequent, while the occasions when they’re not killing are more frequent.”*";
P_HTM[7412]="*“‘Yaṃbahulaṃ yaṃbahulañca, gāmaṇi, viharati tena tena nīyatī’ti, evaṃ sante na koci āpāyiko nerayiko bhavissati, yathā nigaṇṭhassa nāṭaputtassa vacanaṃ.**“‘You’re led on by what you usually live by’: if this were true, then, according to what Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta says, no-one would go to a place of loss, to hell.*";
P_HTM[7413]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi,**What do you think, chief?*";
P_HTM[7414]="*yo so puriso adinnādāyī rattiyā vā divasassa vā samayāsamayaṃ upādāya, katamo bahutaro samayo, yaṃ vā so adinnaṃ ādiyati, yaṃ vā so adinnaṃ nādiyatī”ti.**Take a person who steals …*";
P_HTM[7415]="*“Yo so, bhante, puriso adinnādāyī rattiyā vā divasassa vā samayāsamayaṃ upādāya appataro so samayo, yaṃ so adinnaṃ ādiyati, atha kho sveva bahutaro samayo, yaṃ so adinnaṃ nādiyatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7416]="*“‘Yaṃbahulaṃ yaṃbahulañca, gāmaṇi, viharati tena tena nīyatī’ti, evaṃ sante na koci āpāyiko nerayiko bhavissati, yathā nigaṇṭhassa nāṭaputtassa vacanaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7417]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi, yo so puriso kāmesumicchācārī rattiyā vā divasassa vā samayāsamayaṃ upādāya, katamo bahutaro samayo, yaṃ vā so kāmesu micchā carati, yaṃ vā so kāmesu micchā na caratī”ti?**Take a person who commits sexual misconduct …*";
P_HTM[7418]="*“Yo so, bhante, puriso kāmesumicchācārī rattiyā vā divasassa vā samayāsamayaṃ upādāya, appataro so samayo yaṃ so kāmesu micchā carati, atha kho sveva bahutaro samayo, yaṃ so kāmesu micchā na caratī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7419]="*“‘Yaṃbahulaṃ yaṃbahulañca, gāmaṇi, viharati tena tena nīyatī’ti, evaṃ sante na koci āpāyiko nerayiko bhavissati, yathā nigaṇṭhassa nāṭaputtassa vacanaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7420]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi, yo so puriso musāvādī rattiyā vā divasassa vā samayāsamayaṃ upādāya, katamo bahutaro samayo, yaṃ vā so musā bhaṇati, yaṃ vā so musā na bhaṇatī”ti?**Take a person who lies. If we compare periods of time during the day and night, which is more frequent: the occasions when they’re lying or when they’re not lying?”*";
P_HTM[7421]="*“Yo so, bhante, puriso musāvādī rattiyā vā divasassa vā samayāsamayaṃ upādāya, appataro so samayo, yaṃ so musā bhaṇati, atha kho sveva bahutaro samayo, yaṃ so musā na bhaṇatī”ti.**“The occasions when they’re lying are less frequent, while the occasions when they’re not lying are more frequent.”*";
P_HTM[7422]="*“‘Yaṃbahulaṃ yaṃbahulañca, gāmaṇi, viharati tena tena nīyatī’ti, evaṃ sante na koci āpāyiko nerayiko bhavissati, yathā nigaṇṭhassa nāṭaputtassa vacanaṃ.**“‘You’re led on by what you usually live by’: if this were true, then, according to what Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta says, no-one would go to a place of loss, to hell.*";
P_HTM[7423]="*Idha, gāmaṇi, ekacco satthā evaṃvādī hoti evaṃdiṭṭhi:**Take some teacher who has this doctrine and view:*";
P_HTM[7424]="*‘yo koci pāṇamatipāteti, sabbo so āpāyiko nerayiko, yo koci adinnaṃ ādiyati, sabbo so āpāyiko nerayiko, yo koci kāmesu micchā carati, sabbo so āpāyiko nerayiko, yo koci musā bhaṇati, sabbo so āpāyiko nerayiko’ti.**‘Everyone who kills a living creature, steals, commits sexual misconduct, or lies goes to a place of loss, to hell.’*";
P_HTM[7425]="*Tasmiṃ kho pana, gāmaṇi, satthari sāvako abhippasanno hoti.**And there’s a disciple who is devoted to that teacher.*";
P_HTM[7426]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[7427]="*‘mayhaṃ kho satthā evaṃvādī evaṃdiṭṭhi—**‘My teacher has this doctrine and view:*";
P_HTM[7428]="*yo koci pāṇamatipāteti, sabbo so āpāyiko nerayikoti.**‘Everyone who kills a living creature, steals, commits sexual misconduct, or lies goes to a place of loss, to hell.’*";
P_HTM[7429]="*Atthi kho pana mayā pāṇo atipātito, ahampamhi āpāyiko nerayikoti diṭṭhiṃ paṭilabhati.**But I’ve killed living creatures …*";
P_HTM[7430]="*Taṃ, gāmaṇi, vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā yathābhataṃ nikkhitto evaṃ niraye.* **";
P_HTM[7431]="*Mayhaṃ kho satthā evaṃvādī evaṃdiṭṭhi—* **";
P_HTM[7432]="*yo koci adinnaṃ ādiyati, sabbo so āpāyiko nerayikoti.* **";
P_HTM[7433]="*Atthi kho pana mayā adinnaṃ ādinnaṃ ahampamhi āpāyiko nerayikoti diṭṭhiṃ paṭilabhati.**stolen …*";
P_HTM[7434]="*Taṃ, gāmaṇi, vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā yathābhataṃ nikkhitto evaṃ niraye.* **";
P_HTM[7435]="*Mayhaṃ kho satthā evaṃvādī evaṃdiṭṭhi—* **";
P_HTM[7436]="*yo koci kāmesu micchā carati, sabbo so āpāyiko nerayiko’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7437]="*Atthi kho pana mayā kāmesu micchā ciṇṇaṃ.**committed sexual misconduct …*";
P_HTM[7438]="*‘Ahampamhi āpāyiko nerayiko’ti diṭṭhiṃ paṭilabhati.* **";
P_HTM[7439]="*Taṃ, gāmaṇi, vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā yathābhataṃ nikkhitto evaṃ niraye.* **";
P_HTM[7440]="*Mayhaṃ kho satthā evaṃvādī evaṃdiṭṭhi—* **";
P_HTM[7441]="*yo koci musā bhaṇati, sabbo so āpāyiko nerayikoti.* **";
P_HTM[7442]="*Atthi kho pana mayā musā bhaṇitaṃ.**or lied.*";
P_HTM[7443]="*‘Ahampamhi āpāyiko nerayiko’ti diṭṭhiṃ paṭilabhati.**They get the view: ‘I too am going to a place of loss, to hell.’*";
P_HTM[7444]="*Taṃ, gāmaṇi, vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā yathābhataṃ nikkhitto evaṃ niraye.**Unless they give up that speech and thought, and let go of that view, they will be cast down to hell.*";
P_HTM[7445]="*Idha pana, gāmaṇi, tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā.**But consider when a Realized One arises in the world, perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.*";
P_HTM[7446]="*So anekapariyāyena pāṇātipātaṃ garahati vigarahati, ‘pāṇātipātā viramathā’ti cāha.**In many ways he criticizes and denounces killing living creatures, saying: ‘Stop killing living creatures!’*";
P_HTM[7447]="*Adinnādānaṃ garahati vigarahati, ‘adinnādānā viramathā’ti cāha.**He criticizes and denounces stealing …*";
P_HTM[7448]="*Kāmesumicchācāraṃ garahati, vigarahati ‘kāmesumicchācārā viramathā’ti cāha.**sexual misconduct …*";
P_HTM[7449]="*Musāvādaṃ garahati vigarahati ‘musāvādā viramathā’ti cāha.**lying, saying: ‘Stop lying!’*";
P_HTM[7450]="*Tasmiṃ kho pana, gāmaṇi, satthari sāvako abhippasanno hoti.**And there’s a disciple who is devoted to that teacher.*";
P_HTM[7451]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:**Then they reflect:*";
P_HTM[7452]="*‘bhagavā kho anekapariyāyena pāṇātipātaṃ garahati vigarahati, pāṇātipātā viramathāti cāha.**‘In many ways the Buddha criticizes and denounces killing living creatures, saying: “Stop killing living creatures!”*";
P_HTM[7453]="*Atthi kho pana mayā pāṇo atipātito yāvatako vā tāvatako vā.**But I have killed living creatures to a certain extent.*";
P_HTM[7454]="*Yo kho pana mayā pāṇo atipātito yāvatako vā tāvatako vā, taṃ na suṭṭhu, taṃ na sādhu.**That’s not right, it’s not good,*";
P_HTM[7455]="*Ahañceva kho pana tappaccayā vippaṭisārī assaṃ.**and I feel remorseful because of it.*";
P_HTM[7456]="*Na metaṃ pāpaṃ kammaṃ akataṃ bhavissatī’ti.**But I can’t undo what I have done.’*";
P_HTM[7457]="*So iti paṭisaṅkhāya tañceva pāṇātipātaṃ pajahati.**Reflecting like this, they give up killing living creatures,*";
P_HTM[7458]="*Āyatiñca pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti.**and in future they don’t kill living creatures.*";
P_HTM[7459]="*Evametassa pāpassa kammassa pahānaṃ hoti.**That’s how to give up this bad deed*";
P_HTM[7460]="*Evametassa pāpassa kammassa samatikkamo hoti.**and get past it.*";
P_HTM[7461]="*‘Bhagavā kho anekapariyāyena adinnādānaṃ garahati vigarahati, adinnādānā viramathāti cāha.**‘In many ways the Buddha criticizes and denounces stealing …*";
P_HTM[7462]="*Atthi kho pana mayā adinnaṃ ādinnaṃ yāvatakaṃ vā tāvatakaṃ vā.* **";
P_HTM[7463]="*Yaṃ kho pana mayā adinnaṃ ādinnaṃ yāvatakaṃ vā tāvatakaṃ vā taṃ na suṭṭhu, taṃ na sādhu.* **";
P_HTM[7464]="*Ahañceva kho pana tappaccayā vippaṭisārī assaṃ, na metaṃ pāpaṃ kammaṃ akataṃ bhavissatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7465]="*So iti paṭisaṅkhāya tañceva adinnādānaṃ pajahati.* **";
P_HTM[7466]="*Āyatiñca adinnādānā paṭivirato hoti.* **";
P_HTM[7467]="*Evametassa pāpassa kammassa pahānaṃ hoti.* **";
P_HTM[7468]="*Evametassa pāpassa kammassa samatikkamo hoti.* **";
P_HTM[7469]="*‘Bhagavā kho pana anekapariyāyena kāmesumicchācāraṃ garahati vigarahati, kāmesumicchācārā viramathāti cāha.**‘In many ways the Buddha criticizes and denounces sexual misconduct …*";
P_HTM[7470]="*Atthi kho pana mayā kāmesu micchā ciṇṇaṃ yāvatakaṃ vā tāvatakaṃ vā.* **";
P_HTM[7471]="*Yaṃ kho pana mayā kāmesu micchā ciṇṇaṃ yāvatakaṃ vā tāvatakaṃ vā taṃ na suṭṭhu, taṃ na sādhu.* **";
P_HTM[7472]="*Ahañceva kho pana tappaccayā vippaṭisārī assaṃ, na metaṃ pāpaṃ kammaṃ akataṃ bhavissatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7473]="*So iti paṭisaṅkhāya tañceva kāmesumicchācāraṃ pajahati, āyatiñca kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato hoti.* **";
P_HTM[7474]="*Evametassa pāpassa kammassa pahānaṃ hoti.* **";
P_HTM[7475]="*Evametassa pāpassa kammassa samatikkamo hoti.* **";
P_HTM[7476]="*‘Bhagavā kho pana anekapariyāyena musāvādaṃ garahati vigarahati, musāvādā viramathāti cāha.**‘In many ways the Buddha criticizes and denounces lying, saying: “Stop lying!”*";
P_HTM[7477]="*Atthi kho pana mayā musā bhaṇitaṃ yāvatakaṃ vā tāvatakaṃ vā.**But I have lied to a certain extent.*";
P_HTM[7478]="*Yaṃ kho pana mayā musā bhaṇitaṃ yāvatakaṃ vā tāvatakaṃ vā taṃ na suṭṭhu, taṃ na sādhu. Ahañceva kho pana tappaccayā vippaṭisārī assaṃ, na metaṃ pāpaṃ kammaṃ akataṃ bhavissatī’ti.**That’s not right, it’s not good, and I feel remorseful because of it. But I can’t undo what I have done.’*";
P_HTM[7479]="*So iti paṭisaṅkhāya tañceva musāvādaṃ pajahati, āyatiñca musāvādā paṭivirato hoti.**Reflecting like this, they give up lying, and in future they refrain from lying.*";
P_HTM[7480]="*Evametassa pāpassa kammassa pahānaṃ hoti. Evametassa pāpassa kammassa samatikkamo hoti.**That’s how to give up this bad deed and get past it.*";
P_HTM[7481]="*So pāṇātipātaṃ pahāya pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti.**They give up killing living creatures.*";
P_HTM[7482]="*Adinnādānaṃ pahāya adinnādānā paṭivirato hoti.**They give up stealing.*";
P_HTM[7483]="*Kāmesumicchācāraṃ pahāya kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato hoti.**They give up sexual misconduct.*";
P_HTM[7484]="*Musāvādaṃ pahāya musāvādā paṭivirato hoti.**They give up lying.*";
P_HTM[7485]="*Pisuṇaṃ vācaṃ pahāya pisuṇāya vācāya paṭivirato hoti.**They give up divisive speech.*";
P_HTM[7486]="*Pharusaṃ vācaṃ pahāya pharusāya vācāya paṭivirato hoti.**They give up harsh speech.*";
P_HTM[7487]="*Samphappalāpaṃ pahāya samphappalāpā paṭivirato hoti.**They give up talking nonsense.*";
P_HTM[7488]="*Abhijjhaṃ pahāya anabhijjhālu hoti.**They give up covetousness.*";
P_HTM[7489]="*Byāpādappadosaṃ pahāya abyāpannacitto hoti.**They give up ill will and malevolence.*";
P_HTM[7490]="*Micchādiṭṭhiṃ pahāya sammādiṭṭhiko hoti.**They give up wrong view and have right view.*";
P_HTM[7491]="*Sa kho so, gāmaṇi, ariyasāvako evaṃ vigatābhijjho vigatabyāpādo asammūḷho sampajāno paṭissato mettāsahagatena cetasā ekaṃ disaṃ pharitvā viharati, tathā dutiyaṃ, tathā tatiyaṃ, tathā catutthaṃ. Iti uddhamadho tiriyaṃ sabbadhi sabbattatāya sabbāvantaṃ lokaṃ mettāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyāpajjena pharitvā viharati.**That noble disciple is rid of desire, rid of ill will, unconfused, aware, and mindful. They meditate spreading a heart full of love to one direction, and to the second, and to the third, and to the fourth. In the same way above, below, across, everywhere, all around, they spread a heart full of love to the whole world—abundant, expansive, limitless, free of enmity and ill will.*";
P_HTM[7492]="*Seyyathāpi, gāmaṇi, balavā saṅkhadhamo appakasireneva catuddisā viññāpeyya;**Suppose there was a powerful horn blower. They’d easily make themselves heard in the four directions.*";
P_HTM[7493]="*evameva kho, gāmaṇi, evaṃ bhāvitāya mettāya cetovimuttiyā evaṃ bahulīkatāya yaṃ pamāṇakataṃ kammaṃ, na taṃ tatrāvasissati, na taṃ tatrāvatiṭṭhati.**In the same way, when the heart’s release by love has been developed and cultivated like this, any limited deeds they’ve done don’t remain or persist there.*";
P_HTM[7494]="*Sa kho so, gāmaṇi, ariyasāvako evaṃ vigatābhijjho vigatabyāpādo asammūḷho sampajāno paṭissato karuṇāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**Then that noble disciple is rid of desire, rid of ill will, unconfused, aware, and mindful. They meditate spreading a heart full of compassion …*";
P_HTM[7495]="*muditāsahagatena cetasā … pe ….**They meditate spreading a heart full of rejoicing …*";
P_HTM[7496]="*Upekkhāsahagatena cetasā ekaṃ disaṃ pharitvā viharati, tathā dutiyaṃ, tathā tatiyaṃ, tathā catutthaṃ. Iti uddhamadho tiriyaṃ sabbadhi sabbattatāya sabbāvantaṃ lokaṃ upekkhāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyāpajjena pharitvā viharati.**They meditate spreading a heart full of equanimity to one direction, and to the second, and to the third, and to the fourth. In the same way above, below, across, everywhere, all around, they spread a heart full of equanimity to the whole world—abundant, expansive, limitless, free of enmity and ill will.*";
P_HTM[7497]="*Seyyathāpi, gāmaṇi, balavā saṅkhadhamo appakasireneva catuddisā viññāpeyya;**Suppose there was a powerful horn blower. They’d easily make themselves heard in the four directions.*";
P_HTM[7498]="*evameva kho, gāmaṇi, evaṃ bhāvitāya upekkhāya cetovimuttiyā evaṃ bahulīkatāya yaṃ pamāṇakataṃ kammaṃ na taṃ tatrāvasissati, na taṃ tatrāvatiṭṭhatī”ti.**In the same way, when the heart’s release by equanimity has been developed and cultivated like this, any limited deeds they’ve done don’t remain or persist there.”*";
P_HTM[7499]="*Evaṃ vutte, asibandhakaputto gāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Asibandhaka’s son the chief said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[7500]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bhante, abhikkantaṃ, bhante … pe …**“Excellent, sir! Excellent! …*";
P_HTM[7501]="*upāsakaṃ maṃ bhagavā dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may the Buddha remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[7502]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7503]="*9. Kulasuttaṃ**Families*";
P_HTM[7504]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kosalesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ yena nāḷandā tadavasari.**At one time the Buddha was wandering in the land of the Kosalans together with a large Saṅgha of mendicants when he arrived at Nāḷandā.*";
P_HTM[7505]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā nāḷandāyaṃ viharati pāvārikambavane.**There he stayed near Nālandā in Pāvārika’s mango grove.*";
P_HTM[7506]="*Tena kho pana samayena nāḷandā dubbhikkhā hoti dvīhitikā setaṭṭhikā salākāvuttā.**Now that was a time of famine and scarcity in Nāḷandā, with blighted crops turned to straw.*";
P_HTM[7507]="*Tena kho pana samayena nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto nāḷandāyaṃ paṭivasati mahatiyā nigaṇṭhaparisāya saddhiṃ.**At that time Nigaṇṭha Nāṭaputta was residing at Nāḷandā together with a large assembly of Jain ascetics.*";
P_HTM[7508]="*Atha kho asibandhakaputto gāmaṇi nigaṇṭhasāvako yena nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā nigaṇṭhaṃ nāṭaputtaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho asibandhakaputtaṃ gāmaṇiṃ nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto etadavoca:**Then Asibandhaka’s son the chief, who was a disciple of the Jains, went up to Nigaṇṭha Nāṭaputta, bowed, and sat down to one side. Nigaṇṭha Nāṭaputta said to him:*";
P_HTM[7509]="*“ehi tvaṃ, gāmaṇi, samaṇassa gotamassa vādaṃ āropehi.**“Come, chief, refute the ascetic Gotama’s doctrine.*";
P_HTM[7510]="*Evaṃ te kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggacchissati:**Then you will get a good reputation:*";
P_HTM[7511]="*‘asibandhakaputtena gāmaṇinā samaṇassa gotamassa evaṃmahiddhikassa evaṃmahānubhāvassa vādo āropito’”ti.**‘Asibandhaka’s son the chief refuted the doctrine of the ascetic Gotama, so mighty and powerful!’”*";
P_HTM[7512]="*“Kathaṃ panāhaṃ, bhante, samaṇassa gotamassa evaṃmahiddhikassa evaṃmahānubhāvassa vādaṃ āropessāmī”ti?**“But sir, how am I to do this?”*";
P_HTM[7513]="*“Ehi tvaṃ, gāmaṇi, yena samaṇo gotamo tenupasaṅkama; upasaṅkamitvā samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ evaṃ vadehi:**“Here, brahmin, go to the ascetic Gotama and say to him:*";
P_HTM[7514]="*‘nanu, bhante, bhagavā anekapariyāyena kulānaṃ anuddayaṃ vaṇṇeti, anurakkhaṃ vaṇṇeti, anukampaṃ vaṇṇetī’ti?**‘Sir, don’t you in many ways praise kindness, protection, and compassion for families?’*";
P_HTM[7515]="*Sace kho, gāmaṇi, samaṇo gotamo evaṃ puṭṭho evaṃ byākaroti:**When he’s asked this, if he answers:*";
P_HTM[7516]="*‘evaṃ, gāmaṇi, tathāgato anekapariyāyena kulānaṃ anuddayaṃ vaṇṇeti, anurakkhaṃ vaṇṇeti, anukampaṃ vaṇṇetī’ti, tamenaṃ tvaṃ evaṃ vadeyyāsi:**‘Indeed I do, chief,’ say this to him:*";
P_HTM[7517]="*‘atha kiñcarahi, bhante, bhagavā dubbhikkhe dvīhitike setaṭṭhike salākāvutte mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ cārikaṃ carati?**‘So what exactly are you doing, wandering together with this large Saṅgha of mendicants during a time of famine and scarcity, with blighted crops turned to straw?*";
P_HTM[7518]="*Ucchedāya bhagavā kulānaṃ paṭipanno, anayāya bhagavā kulānaṃ paṭipanno, upaghātāya bhagavā kulānaṃ paṭipanno’ti.**The Buddha is practicing to annihilate, collapse, and ruin families!’*";
P_HTM[7519]="*Imaṃ kho te, gāmaṇi, samaṇo gotamo ubhatokoṭikaṃ pañhaṃ puṭṭho neva sakkhati uggilituṃ, neva sakkhati ogilitun”ti.**When you put this dilemma to him, the Buddha won’t be able to either spit it out or swallow it down.”*";
P_HTM[7520]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho asibandhakaputto gāmaṇi nigaṇṭhassa nāṭaputtassa paṭissutvā uṭṭhāyāsanā nigaṇṭhaṃ nāṭaputtaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho asibandhakaputto gāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, sir,” replied Asibandhaka’s son. He got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled Nigaṇṭha Nāṭaputta, keeping him on his right. Then he went to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[7521]="*“Nanu, bhante, bhagavā anekapariyāyena kulānaṃ anuddayaṃ vaṇṇeti, anurakkhaṃ vaṇṇeti, anukampaṃ vaṇṇetī”ti?**“Sir, don’t you in many ways praise kindness, protection, and compassion for families?”*";
P_HTM[7522]="*“Evaṃ, gāmaṇi, tathāgato anekapariyāyena kulānaṃ anuddayaṃ vaṇṇeti, anurakkhaṃ vaṇṇeti, anukampaṃ vaṇṇetī”ti.**“Indeed I do, chief.”*";
P_HTM[7523]="*“Atha kiñcarahi, bhante, bhagavā dubbhikkhe dvīhitike setaṭṭhike salākāvutte mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ cārikaṃ carati?**“So what exactly are you doing, wandering together with this large Saṅgha of mendicants during a time of famine and scarcity, with blighted crops turned to straw?*";
P_HTM[7524]="*Ucchedāya bhagavā kulānaṃ paṭipanno, anayāya bhagavā kulānaṃ paṭipanno, upaghātāya bhagavā kulānaṃ paṭipanno”ti.**The Buddha is practicing to annihilate, collapse, and ruin families!”*";
P_HTM[7525]="*“Ito so, gāmaṇi, ekanavutikappe yamahaṃ anussarāmi, nābhijānāmi kiñci kulaṃ pakkabhikkhānuppadānamattena upahatapubbaṃ.**“Well, chief, I recollect ninety eons back but I’m not aware of any family that’s been ruined merely by offering some cooked alms-food.*";
P_HTM[7526]="*Atha kho yāni tāni kulāni aḍḍhāni mahaddhanāni mahābhogāni pahūtajātarūparajatāni pahūtavittūpakaraṇāni pahūtadhanadhaññāni, sabbāni tāni dānasambhūtāni ceva saccasambhūtāni ca sāmaññasambhūtāni ca.**Rather, rich, affluent, and wealthy families—with lots of gold and silver, lots of property and assets, and lots of money and grain—all acquired their wealth because of generosity, truth, and restraint.*";
P_HTM[7527]="*Aṭṭha kho, gāmaṇi, hetū, aṭṭha paccayā kulānaṃ upaghātāya.**Chief, there are eight causes and conditions for the ruin of families.*";
P_HTM[7528]="*Rājato vā kulāni upaghātaṃ gacchanti, corato vā kulāni upaghātaṃ gacchanti, aggito vā kulāni upaghātaṃ gacchanti, udakato vā kulāni upaghātaṃ gacchanti, nihitaṃ vā ṭhānā vigacchati, duppayuttā vā kammantā vipajjanti, kule vā kulaṅgāroti uppajjati, yo te bhoge vikirati vidhamati viddhaṃseti, aniccatāyeva aṭṭhamīti.**Their ruin stems from rulers, bandits, fire, or flood. Or their savings vanish. Or their business fails due to not applying themselves to work. Or a wastrel is born into the family who squanders and fritters away their wealth. And impermanence is the eighth.*";
P_HTM[7529]="*Ime kho, gāmaṇi, aṭṭha hetū, aṭṭha paccayā kulānaṃ upaghātāya.**These are the eight causes and conditions for the ruin of families.*";
P_HTM[7530]="*Imesu kho, gāmaṇi, aṭṭhasu hetūsu, aṭṭhasu paccayesu saṃvijjamānesu yo maṃ evaṃ vadeyya:**Given that these eight reasons are found, suppose someone says this:*";
P_HTM[7531]="*‘ucchedāya bhagavā kulānaṃ paṭipanno, anayāya bhagavā kulānaṃ paṭipanno, upaghātāya bhagavā kulānaṃ paṭipanno’ti,**‘The Buddha is practicing to annihilate, collapse, and ruin families!’*";
P_HTM[7532]="*taṃ, gāmaṇi, vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā yathābhataṃ nikkhitto evaṃ niraye”ti.**Unless they give up that speech and thought, and let go of that view, they will be cast down to hell.”*";
P_HTM[7533]="*Evaṃ vutte, asibandhakaputto gāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Asibandhaka’s son the chief said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[7534]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bhante, abhikkantaṃ, bhante … pe …**“Excellent, sir! Excellent! …*";
P_HTM[7535]="*upāsakaṃ maṃ bhagavā dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may the Buddha remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[7536]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7537]="*10. Maṇicūḷakasuttaṃ**With Maṇicūḷaka*";
P_HTM[7538]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[7539]="*Tena kho pana samayena rājantepure rājaparisāya sannisinnānaṃ sannipatitānaṃ ayamantarākathā udapādi:**Now at that time while the king’s retinue was sitting together in the royal compound this discussion came up among them,*";
P_HTM[7540]="*“kappati samaṇānaṃ sakyaputtiyānaṃ jātarūparajataṃ, sādiyanti samaṇā sakyaputtiyā jātarūparajataṃ, paṭiggaṇhanti samaṇā sakyaputtiyā jātarūparajatan”ti.**“Gold and money are proper for Sakyan ascetics. They accept and receive gold and money.”*";
P_HTM[7541]="*Tena kho pana samayena maṇicūḷako gāmaṇi tassaṃ parisāyaṃ nisinno hoti.**Now at that time the chief Maṇicūḷaka was sitting in that assembly.*";
P_HTM[7542]="*Atha kho maṇicūḷako gāmaṇi taṃ parisaṃ etadavoca:**He said to that retinue,*";
P_HTM[7543]="*“mā ayyo evaṃ avacuttha.**“Good sirs, don’t say that.*";
P_HTM[7544]="*Na kappati samaṇānaṃ sakyaputtiyānaṃ jātarūparajataṃ, na sādiyanti samaṇā sakyaputtiyā jātarūparajataṃ, nappaṭiggaṇhanti samaṇā sakyaputtiyā jātarūparajataṃ, nikkhittamaṇisuvaṇṇā samaṇā sakyaputtiyā apetajātarūparajatā”ti.**Gold and money are not proper for Sakyan ascetics. They neither accept nor receive gold and money. They have set aside gems and gold, and rejected gold and money.”*";
P_HTM[7545]="*Asakkhi kho maṇicūḷako gāmaṇi taṃ parisaṃ saññāpetuṃ.**He was able to persuade that assembly.*";
P_HTM[7546]="*Atha kho maṇicūḷako gāmaṇi yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho maṇicūḷako gāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Maṇicūḷaka went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and told him what had happened. He then said,*";
P_HTM[7547]="*“idha, bhante, rājantepure rājaparisāya sannisinnānaṃ sannipatitānaṃ ayamantarākathā udapādi:* **";
P_HTM[7548]="*‘kappati samaṇānaṃ sakyaputtiyānaṃ jātarūparajataṃ, sādiyanti samaṇā sakyaputtiyā jātarūparajataṃ, paṭiggaṇhanti samaṇā sakyaputtiyā jātarūparajatan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7549]="*Evaṃ vutte, ahaṃ, bhante, taṃ parisaṃ etadavocaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7550]="*‘mā ayyo evaṃ avacuttha.* **";
P_HTM[7551]="*Na kappati samaṇānaṃ sakyaputtiyānaṃ jātarūparajataṃ, na sādiyanti samaṇā sakyaputtiyā jātarūparajataṃ, nappaṭiggaṇhanti samaṇā sakyaputtiyā jātarūparajataṃ, nikkhittamaṇisuvaṇṇā samaṇā sakyaputtiyā apetajātarūparajatā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7552]="*Asakkhiṃ khvāhaṃ, bhante, taṃ parisaṃ saññāpetuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7553]="*Kaccāhaṃ, bhante, evaṃ byākaramāno vuttavādī ceva bhagavato homi, na ca bhagavantaṃ abhūtena abbhācikkhāmi, dhammassa cānudhammaṃ byākaromi, na ca koci sahadhammiko vādānuvādo gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgacchatī”ti?**“Answering this way, I trust that I repeat what the Buddha has said, and don’t misrepresent him with an untruth. I trust my explanation is in line with the teaching, and that there are no legitimate grounds for rebuke or criticism.”*";
P_HTM[7554]="*“Taggha tvaṃ, gāmaṇi, evaṃ byākaramāno vuttavādī ceva me hosi, na ca maṃ abhūtena abbhācikkhasi, dhammassa cānudhammaṃ byākarosi, na ca koci sahadhammiko vādānuvādo gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgacchati.**“Indeed, in answering this way you repeat what I’ve said, and don’t misrepresent me with an untruth. Your explanation is in line with the teaching, and there are no legitimate grounds for rebuke or criticism.*";
P_HTM[7555]="*Na hi, gāmaṇi, kappati samaṇānaṃ sakyaputtiyānaṃ jātarūparajataṃ, na sādiyanti samaṇā sakyaputtiyā jātarūparajataṃ, nappaṭiggaṇhanti samaṇā sakyaputtiyā jātarūparajataṃ, nikkhittamaṇisuvaṇṇā samaṇā sakyaputtiyā apetajātarūparajatā.**Gold and money are not proper for Sakyan ascetics. They neither accept nor receive gold and money. They have set aside gems and gold, and rejected gold and money.*";
P_HTM[7556]="*Yassa kho, gāmaṇi, jātarūparajataṃ kappati, pañcapi tassa kāmaguṇā kappanti.**If gold and money were proper for them, then the five kinds of sensual stimulation would also be proper.*";
P_HTM[7557]="*Yassa pañca kāmaguṇā kappanti (), ekaṃsenetaṃ, gāmaṇi, dhāreyyāsi assamaṇadhammo asakyaputtiyadhammoti.**And if the five kinds of sensual stimulation are proper for them, you should definitely regard them as not having the qualities of an ascetic or a follower of the Sakyan.*";
P_HTM[7558]="*Api cāhaṃ, gāmaṇi, evaṃ vadāmi—**Rather, chief, I say this:*";
P_HTM[7559]="*tiṇaṃ tiṇatthikena pariyesitabbaṃ, dāru dārutthikena pariyesitabbaṃ, sakaṭaṃ sakaṭatthikena pariyesitabbaṃ, puriso purisatthikena pariyesitabbo.**Straw may be looked for by one needing straw; wood may be looked for by one needing wood; a cart may be looked for by one needing a cart; a workman may be looked for by one needing a workman.*";
P_HTM[7560]="*Na tvevāhaṃ, gāmaṇi, kenaci pariyāyena ‘jātarūparajataṃ sāditabbaṃ pariyesitabban’ti vadāmī”ti.**But I say that there is no way they can accept or look for gold and money.”*";
P_HTM[7561]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7562]="*11. Bhadrakasuttaṃ**With Bhadraka*";
P_HTM[7563]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā mallesu viharati uruvelakappaṃ nāma mallānaṃ nigamo.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Mallas, near the Mallian town called Uruvelakappa.*";
P_HTM[7564]="*Atha kho bhadrako gāmaṇi yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho bhadrako gāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Bhadraka the village chief went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[7565]="*“sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā dukkhassa samudayañca atthaṅgamañca desetū”ti.**“Please, sir, teach me the origin and cessation of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[7566]="*“Ahañce te, gāmaṇi, atītamaddhānaṃ ārabbha dukkhassa samudayañca atthaṅgamañca deseyyaṃ:**“Chief, if I were to teach you about the origin and ending of suffering in the past, saying*";
P_HTM[7567]="*‘evaṃ ahosi atītamaddhānan’ti, tatra te siyā kaṅkhā, siyā vimati.**‘this is how it was in the past,’ you might have doubts or uncertainties about that.*";
P_HTM[7568]="*Ahañce te, gāmaṇi, anāgatamaddhānaṃ ārabbha dukkhassa samudayañca atthaṅgamañca deseyyaṃ:**If I were to teach you about the origin and ending of suffering in the future, saying*";
P_HTM[7569]="*‘evaṃ bhavissati anāgatamaddhānan’ti, tatrāpi te siyā kaṅkhā, siyā vimati.**‘this is how it will be in the future,’ you might have doubts or uncertainties about that.*";
P_HTM[7570]="*Api cāhaṃ, gāmaṇi, idheva nisinno ettheva te nisinnassa dukkhassa samudayañca atthaṅgamañca desessāmi.**Rather, chief, I will teach you about the origin and ending of suffering as I am sitting right here and you are sitting right there.*";
P_HTM[7571]="*Taṃ suṇāhi, sādhukaṃ manasi karohi; bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[7572]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho bhadrako gāmaṇi bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Bhadraka replied.*";
P_HTM[7573]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[7574]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi,**“What do you think, chief?*";
P_HTM[7575]="*atthi te uruvelakappe manussā yesaṃ te vadhena vā bandhena vā jāniyā vā garahāya vā uppajjeyyuṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā”ti?**Are there any people here in Uruvelakappa who, if they were executed, imprisoned, fined, or condemned, it would cause you sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress?”*";
P_HTM[7576]="*“Atthi me, bhante, uruvelakappe manussā yesaṃ me vadhena vā bandhena vā jāniyā vā garahāya vā uppajjeyyuṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā”ti.**“There are, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7577]="*“Atthi pana te, gāmaṇi, uruvelakappe manussā yesaṃ te vadhena vā bandhena vā jāniyā vā garahāya vā nuppajjeyyuṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā”ti?**“But are there any people here in Uruvelakappa who, if they were executed, imprisoned, fined, or condemned, it would not cause you sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress?”*";
P_HTM[7578]="*“Atthi me, bhante, uruvelakappe manussā yesaṃ me vadhena vā bandhena vā jāniyā vā garahāya vā nuppajjeyyuṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā”ti.**“There are, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7579]="*“Ko nu kho, gāmaṇi, hetu, ko paccayo yena te ekaccānaṃ uruvelakappiyānaṃ manussānaṃ vadhena vā bandhena vā jāniyā vā garahāya vā uppajjeyyuṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā”ti?**“What’s the cause, chief, what’s the reason why, if this was to happen to some people it could cause you sorrow, while if it happens to others it does not?”*";
P_HTM[7580]="*“Yesaṃ me, bhante, uruvelakappiyānaṃ manussānaṃ vadhena vā bandhena vā jāniyā vā garahāya vā uppajjeyyuṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā, atthi me tesu chandarāgo.**“The people regarding whom this would give rise to sorrow are those I desire and love.*";
P_HTM[7581]="*Yesaṃ pana, bhante, uruvelakappiyānaṃ manussānaṃ vadhena vā bandhena vā jāniyā vā garahāya vā nuppajjeyyuṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā, natthi me tesu chandarāgo”ti.**The people regarding whom this would not give rise to sorrow are those I don’t desire and love.”*";
P_HTM[7582]="*“Iminā tvaṃ, gāmaṇi, dhammena diṭṭhena viditena akālikena pattena pariyogāḷhena atītānāgate nayaṃ nehi:**“With this present phenomenon that is seen, known, immediate, attained, and fathomed, you may infer to the past and future:*";
P_HTM[7583]="*‘yaṃ kho kiñci atītamaddhānaṃ dukkhaṃ uppajjamānaṃ uppajji sabbaṃ taṃ chandamūlakaṃ chandanidānaṃ.**‘All the suffering that arose in the past was rooted and sourced in desire.*";
P_HTM[7584]="*Chando hi mūlaṃ dukkhassa.**For desire is the root of suffering.*";
P_HTM[7585]="*Yampi hi kiñci anāgatamaddhānaṃ dukkhaṃ uppajjamānaṃ uppajjissati, sabbaṃ taṃ chandamūlakaṃ chandanidānaṃ.**All the suffering that will arise in the future will be rooted and sourced in desire.*";
P_HTM[7586]="*Chando hi mūlaṃ dukkhassā’”ti.**For desire is the root of suffering.’”*";
P_HTM[7587]="*“Acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante.**“It’s incredible, sir, it’s amazing!*";
P_HTM[7588]="*Yāva subhāsitañcidaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā:**How well said this was by the Buddha!*";
P_HTM[7589]="*‘yaṃ kiñci dukkhaṃ uppajjamānaṃ uppajjati, sabbaṃ taṃ chandamūlakaṃ chandanidānaṃ.**‘All the suffering that arises is rooted and sourced in desire.*";
P_HTM[7590]="*Chando hi mūlaṃ dukkhassā’ti.**For desire is the root of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[7591]="*Atthi me, bhante, ciravāsī nāma kumāro bahi āvasathe paṭivasati.**I have a boy called Ciravāsi, who resides in a house away from here.*";
P_HTM[7592]="*So khvāhaṃ, bhante, kālasseva vuṭṭhāya purisaṃ uyyojemi:**I rise early and send someone, saying:*";
P_HTM[7593]="*‘gaccha, bhaṇe, ciravāsiṃ kumāraṃ jānāhī’ti.**‘Go, my man, and check on my boy Ciravāsi.’*";
P_HTM[7594]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhante, so puriso nāgacchati, tassa me hoteva aññathattaṃ:**Until they get back I worry:*";
P_HTM[7595]="*‘mā heva ciravāsissa kumārassa kiñci ābādhayitthā’”ti.**‘I hope nothing’s wrong with Ciravāsi!’”*";
P_HTM[7596]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi,**“What do you think, chief?*";
P_HTM[7597]="*ciravāsissa kumārassa vadhena vā bandhena vā jāniyā vā garahāya vā uppajjeyyuṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā”ti?**If Ciravāsi was executed, imprisoned, fined, or condemned, would it cause you sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress?”*";
P_HTM[7598]="*“Ciravāsissa me, bhante, kumārassa vadhena vā bandhena vā jāniyā vā garahāya vā jīvitassapi siyā aññathattaṃ, kiṃ pana me nuppajjissanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā”ti.**“How could it not, sir?”*";
P_HTM[7599]="*“Imināpi kho etaṃ, gāmaṇi, pariyāyena veditabbaṃ:**“This too is a way to understand:*";
P_HTM[7600]="*‘yaṃ kiñci dukkhaṃ uppajjamānaṃ uppajjati, sabbaṃ taṃ chandamūlakaṃ chandanidānaṃ.**‘All the suffering that arises is rooted and sourced in desire.*";
P_HTM[7601]="*Chando hi mūlaṃ dukkhassā’ti.**For desire is the root of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[7602]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi,**What do you think, chief?*";
P_HTM[7603]="*yadā te ciravāsimātā adiṭṭhā ahosi, assutā ahosi, te ciravāsimātuyā chando vā rāgo vā pemaṃ vā”ti?**Before you’d seen or heard of Ciravāsi’s mother, did you have any desire or love or fondness for her?”*";
P_HTM[7604]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7605]="*“Dassanaṃ vā te, gāmaṇi, āgamma savanaṃ vā evaṃ te ahosi:**“Then was it because you saw or heard of her that you had*";
P_HTM[7606]="*‘ciravāsimātuyā chando vā rāgo vā pemaṃ vā’”ti?**desire or love or fondness for her?”*";
P_HTM[7607]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7608]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, gāmaṇi,**“What do you think, chief?*";
P_HTM[7609]="*ciravāsimātuyā te vadhena vā bandhena vā jāniyā vā garahāya vā uppajjeyyuṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā”ti?**If Ciravāsi’s mother was executed, imprisoned, fined, or condemned, would it cause you sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress?”*";
P_HTM[7610]="*“Ciravāsimātuyā me, bhante, vadhena vā bandhena vā jāniyā vā garahāya vā jīvitassapi siyā aññathattaṃ, kiṃ pana me nuppajjissanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā”ti.**“How could it not, sir?”*";
P_HTM[7611]="*“Imināpi kho etaṃ, gāmaṇi, pariyāyena veditabbaṃ:**“This too is a way to understand:*";
P_HTM[7612]="*‘yaṃ kiñci dukkhaṃ uppajjamānaṃ uppajjati, sabbaṃ taṃ chandamūlakaṃ chandanidānaṃ.**‘All the suffering that arises is rooted and sourced in desire.*";
P_HTM[7613]="*Chando hi mūlaṃ dukkhassā’”ti.**For desire is the root of suffering.’”*";
P_HTM[7614]="*Ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7615]="*12. Rāsiyasuttaṃ**With Rāsiya*";
P_HTM[7616]="*Atha kho rāsiyo gāmaṇi yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho rāsiyo gāmaṇi bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Rāsiya the chief went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[7617]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante, ‘samaṇo gotamo sabbaṃ tapaṃ garahati, sabbaṃ tapassiṃ lūkhajīviṃ ekaṃsena upavadati upakkosatī’ti.**“Sir, I have heard this: ‘The ascetic Gotama criticizes all forms of mortification. He categorically condemns and denounces those self-mortifiers who live rough.’*";
P_HTM[7618]="*Ye te, bhante, evamāhaṃsu: ‘samaṇo gotamo sabbaṃ tapaṃ garahati, sabbaṃ tapassiṃ lūkhajīviṃ ekaṃsena upavadati upakkosatī’ti, kacci te, bhante, bhagavato vuttavādino, na ca bhagavantaṃ abhūtena abbhācikkhanti, dhammassa cānudhammaṃ byākaronti, na ca koci sahadhammiko vādānuvādo gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgacchatī”ti?**Do those who say this repeat what the Buddha has said, and not misrepresent him with an untruth? Is their explanation in line with the teaching? Are there any legitimate grounds for rebuke and criticism?”*";
P_HTM[7619]="*“Ye te, gāmaṇi, evamāhaṃsu: ‘samaṇo gotamo sabbaṃ tapaṃ garahati, sabbaṃ tapassiṃ lūkhajīviṃ ekaṃsena upavadati upakkosatī’ti, na me te vuttavādino, abbhācikkhanti ca pana maṃ te asatā tucchā abhūtena.**“Chief, those who say this do not repeat what I have said. They misrepresent me with what is false, hollow, and untrue.*";
P_HTM[7620]="*Dveme, gāmaṇi, antā pabbajitena na sevitabbā—**These two extremes should not be cultivated by one who has gone forth.*";
P_HTM[7621]="*yo cāyaṃ kāmesu kāmasukhallikānuyogo hīno gammo pothujjaniko anariyo anatthasaṃhito, yo cāyaṃ attakilamathānuyogo dukkho anariyo anatthasaṃhito.**Indulgence in sensual pleasures, which is low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless. And indulgence in self-mortification, which is painful, ignoble, and pointless.*";
P_HTM[7622]="*Ete te, gāmaṇi, ubho ante anupagamma majjhimā paṭipadā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā—cakkhukaraṇī ñāṇakaraṇī upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati.**Avoiding these two extremes, the Realized One woke up by understanding the middle way, which gives vision and knowledge, and leads to peace, direct knowledge, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[7623]="*Katamā ca sā, gāmaṇi, majjhimā paṭipadā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā—cakkhukaraṇī ñāṇakaraṇī upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati?**And what is that middle way?*";
P_HTM[7624]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, seyyathidaṃ—**It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[7625]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[7626]="*Ayaṃ kho sā, gāmaṇi, majjhimā paṭipadā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā—cakkhukaraṇī ñāṇakaraṇī upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati.**This, chief, is the middle way, woken up to by the Realized One, which gives vision and knowledge, and leads to peace, direct knowledge, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[7627]="*Tayo kho me, gāmaṇi, kāmabhogino santo saṃvijjamānā lokasmiṃ.**There are these three kinds of pleasure seekers in the world.*";
P_HTM[7628]="*Katame tayo?**What three?*";
P_HTM[7629]="*Idha, gāmaṇi, ekacco kāmabhogī adhammena bhoge pariyesati, sāhasena adhammena bhoge pariyesitvā sāhasena na attānaṃ sukheti na pīṇeti na saṃvibhajati na puññāni karoti.**Take a pleasure seeker who seeks wealth using illegitimate, coercive means, and who doesn’t make themselves happy and pleased, or share it and make merit.*";
P_HTM[7630]="*Idha pana, gāmaṇi, ekacco kāmabhogī adhammena bhoge pariyesati sāhasena.**Next, a pleasure seeker seeks wealth using illegitimate, coercive means.*";
P_HTM[7631]="*Adhammena bhoge pariyesitvā sāhasena attānaṃ sukheti pīṇeti, na saṃvibhajati na puññāni karoti.**They make themselves happy and pleased, but don’t share it and make merit.*";
P_HTM[7632]="*Idha pana, gāmaṇi, ekacco kāmabhogī adhammena bhoge pariyesati sāhasena.**Next, a pleasure seeker seeks wealth using illegitimate, coercive means.*";
P_HTM[7633]="*Adhammena bhoge pariyesitvā sāhasena attānaṃ sukheti pīṇeti saṃvibhajati puññāni karoti. (1–3.)**They make themselves happy and pleased, and they share it and make merit.*";
P_HTM[7634]="*Idha pana, gāmaṇi, ekacco kāmabhogī dhammādhammena bhoge pariyesati sāhasenapi asāhasenapi.**Next, a pleasure seeker seeks wealth using means both legitimate and illegitimate, and coercive and non-coercive.*";
P_HTM[7635]="*Dhammādhammena bhoge pariyesitvā sāhasenapi asāhasenapi na attānaṃ sukheti, na pīṇeti, na saṃvibhajati, na puññāni karoti.**They don’t make themselves happy and pleased, or share it and make merit.*";
P_HTM[7636]="*Idha pana, gāmaṇi, ekacco kāmabhogī dhammādhammena bhoge pariyesati sāhasenapi asāhasenapi.**Next, a pleasure seeker seeks wealth using means both legitimate and illegitimate, and coercive and non-coercive.*";
P_HTM[7637]="*Dhammādhammena bhoge pariyesitvā sāhasenapi asāhasenapi attānaṃ sukheti pīṇeti, na saṃvibhajati, na puññāni karoti.**They don’t make themselves happy and pleased, or share it and make merit.*";
P_HTM[7638]="*Idha pana, gāmaṇi, ekacco kāmabhogī dhammādhammena bhoge pariyesati, sāhasenapi asāhasenapi.**Next, a pleasure seeker seeks wealth using means both legitimate and illegitimate, and coercive and non-coercive.*";
P_HTM[7639]="*Dhammādhammena bhoge pariyesitvā sāhasenapi asāhasenapi attānaṃ sukheti pīṇeti saṃvibhajati puññāni karoti. (4–6.)**They make themselves happy and pleased, and they share it and make merit.*";
P_HTM[7640]="*Idha pana, gāmaṇi, ekacco kāmabhogī dhammena bhoge pariyesati asāhasena.**Next, a pleasure seeker seeks wealth using legitimate, non-coercive means.*";
P_HTM[7641]="*Dhammena bhoge pariyesitvā asāhasena na attānaṃ sukheti, na pīṇeti, na saṃvibhajati, na puññāni karoti.**They don’t make themselves happy and pleased, or share it and make merit.*";
P_HTM[7642]="*Idha pana, gāmaṇi, ekacco kāmabhogī dhammena bhoge pariyesati asāhasena.**Next, a pleasure seeker seeks wealth using legitimate, non-coercive means.*";
P_HTM[7643]="*Dhammena bhoge pariyesitvā asāhasena attānaṃ sukheti pīṇeti, na saṃvibhajati, na puññāni karoti.**They make themselves happy and pleased, but don’t share it and make merit.*";
P_HTM[7644]="*Idha pana, gāmaṇi, ekacco kāmabhogī dhammena bhoge pariyesati asāhasena.**Next, a pleasure seeker seeks wealth using legitimate, non-coercive means.*";
P_HTM[7645]="*Dhammena bhoge pariyesitvā asāhasena attānaṃ sukheti pīṇeti saṃvibhajati puññāni karoti.**They make themselves happy and pleased, and they share it and make merit.*";
P_HTM[7646]="*Te ca bhoge gadhito mucchito ajjhopanno anādīnavadassāvī anissaraṇapañño paribhuñjati.**They enjoy that wealth tied, infatuated, attached, blind to the drawbacks, and not understanding the escape.*";
P_HTM[7647]="*Idha pana, gāmaṇi, ekacco kāmabhogī dhammena bhoge pariyesati asāhasena.**Next, a pleasure seeker seeks wealth using legitimate, non-coercive means.*";
P_HTM[7648]="*Dhammena bhoge pariyesitvā asāhasena attānaṃ sukheti pīṇeti saṃvibhajati puññāni karoti.**They make themselves happy and pleased, and they share it and make merit.*";
P_HTM[7649]="*Te ca bhoge agadhito amucchito anajjhopanno ādīnavadassāvī nissaraṇapañño paribhuñjati. (7–9.)**And they enjoy that wealth untied, uninfatuated, unattached, seeing the drawbacks, and understanding the escape.*";
P_HTM[7650]="*Tatra, gāmaṇi, yvāyaṃ kāmabhogī adhammena bhoge pariyesati sāhasena, adhammena bhoge pariyesitvā sāhasena na attānaṃ sukheti, na pīṇeti, na saṃvibhajati, na puññāni karoti.**Now, consider the pleasure seeker who seeks wealth using illegitimate, coercive means, and who doesn’t make themselves happy and pleased, or share it and make merit.*";
P_HTM[7651]="*Ayaṃ, gāmaṇi, kāmabhogī tīhi ṭhānehi gārayho.**They may be criticized on three grounds.*";
P_HTM[7652]="*Katamehi tīhi ṭhānehi gārayho?**What three?*";
P_HTM[7653]="*Adhammena bhoge pariyesati sāhasenāti, iminā paṭhamena ṭhānena gārayho.**They seek wealth using illegitimate, coercive means. This is the first ground for criticism.*";
P_HTM[7654]="*Na attānaṃ sukheti na pīṇetīti, iminā dutiyena ṭhānena gārayho.**They don’t make themselves happy and pleased. This is the second ground for criticism.*";
P_HTM[7655]="*Na saṃvibhajati, na puññāni karotīti, iminā tatiyena ṭhānena gārayho.**They don’t share it and make merit. This is the third ground for criticism.*";
P_HTM[7656]="*Ayaṃ, gāmaṇi, kāmabhogī imehi tīhi ṭhānehi gārayho.**This pleasure seeker may be criticized on these three grounds.*";
P_HTM[7657]="*Tatra, gāmaṇi, yvāyaṃ kāmabhogī adhammena bhoge pariyesati sāhasena, adhammena bhoge pariyesitvā sāhasena attānaṃ sukheti pīṇeti, na saṃvibhajati, na puññāni karoti.**Now, consider the pleasure seeker who seeks wealth using illegitimate, coercive means, and who makes themselves happy and pleased, but doesn’t share it and make merit.*";
P_HTM[7658]="*Ayaṃ, gāmaṇi, kāmabhogī dvīhi ṭhānehi gārayho, ekena ṭhānena pāsaṃso.**This pleasure seeker may be criticized on two grounds, and praised on one.*";
P_HTM[7659]="*Katamehi dvīhi ṭhānehi gārayho?**What are the two grounds for criticism?*";
P_HTM[7660]="*Adhammena bhoge pariyesati sāhasenāti, iminā paṭhamena ṭhānena gārayho.**They seek wealth using illegitimate, coercive means. This is the first ground for criticism.*";
P_HTM[7661]="*Na saṃvibhajati, na puññāni karotīti, iminā dutiyena ṭhānena gārayho.**They don’t share it and make merit. This is the second ground for criticism.*";
P_HTM[7662]="*Katamena ekena ṭhānena pāsaṃso?**What is the one ground for praise?*";
P_HTM[7663]="*Attānaṃ sukheti pīṇetīti, iminā ekena ṭhānena pāsaṃso.**They make themselves happy and pleased. This is the one ground for praise.*";
P_HTM[7664]="*Ayaṃ, gāmaṇi, kāmabhogī imehi dvīhi ṭhānehi gārayho, iminā ekena ṭhānena pāsaṃso. (2)**This pleasure seeker may be criticized on these two grounds, and praised on this one.*";
P_HTM[7665]="*Tatra, gāmaṇi, yvāyaṃ kāmabhogī adhammena bhoge pariyesati sāhasena, adhammena bhoge pariyesitvā sāhasena attānaṃ sukheti pīṇeti saṃvibhajati puññāni karoti.**Now, consider the pleasure seeker who seeks wealth using illegitimate, coercive means, and who makes themselves happy and pleased, and shares it and makes merit.*";
P_HTM[7666]="*Ayaṃ, gāmaṇi, kāmabhogī ekena ṭhānena gārayho, dvīhi ṭhānehi pāsaṃso.**This pleasure seeker may be criticized on one ground, and praised on two.*";
P_HTM[7667]="*Katamena ekena ṭhānena gārayho?**What is the one ground for criticism?*";
P_HTM[7668]="*Adhammena bhoge pariyesati sāhasenāti, iminā ekena ṭhānena gārayho.**They seek wealth using illegitimate, coercive means. This is the one ground for criticism.*";
P_HTM[7669]="*Katamehi dvīhi ṭhānehi pāsaṃso?**What are the two grounds for praise?*";
P_HTM[7670]="*Attānaṃ sukheti pīṇetīti, iminā paṭhamena ṭhānena pāsaṃso.**They make themselves happy and pleased. This is the first ground for praise.*";
P_HTM[7671]="*Saṃvibhajati puññāni karotīti, iminā dutiyena ṭhānena pāsaṃso.**They share it and make merit. This is the second ground for praise.*";
